<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7732 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFE     05-23 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIORS FEELING HEAT FOR DEFEAT OF CROSSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - An angry Cardinals fan called the team's Tempe offices
last Wednesday and said he had planned to purchase a new truck from
a Mesa car dealership but was backing out of the deal because of
the city's overwhelming defeat of the Rio Salado Crossing
convention center and stadium project.
</P>
<P>
   A Cardinals coach was so upset by the lopsided vote and the
rudeness with which he was treated by senior citizen voters at a
polling place that he wondered aloud whether he would ever spend
another dime in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   You're blaming the wrong folks, fellas. The Mesa business
community supported the project from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Bashing Mesa's older crowd also became a sport last week on talk
radio, almost a feeding frenzy. Grandma didn't just oppose a
quarter-cent sales tax increase. She showed up at the polls,
according to the callers, wearing an oxygen mask and brandishing a
cane, a vigilante willing to use force to protect her right to
oppose schools, libraries, mass transit and, heaven forbid, a new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The issue became so emotional that Cardinals officials have
endorsed a cooling-off period. But it won't lessen their desire to
get a new stadium, and they aren't going to wait around forever.
Without plans for one in the Valley by the end of next season, the
team could begin to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have a strong ally in their quest for a new
stadium _ the Fiesta Bowl, which has begun to make its message loud
and clear that it has serious doubts about remaining a top-tier
bowl if it has to continue to play in Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Those same Valley politicians who are reluctant to stick their
necks out to try to get a stadium for Cardinals owner  &UR; Bill Bidwill
also don't want to be in office if the Fiesta Bowl drops down to
the status of the Cotton Bowl or Independence Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Mayor  &UR; Neil Giuliano thinks he can make both happy by
spending $200 million to refurbish Sun Devil Stadium. Forget about
it. You're wasting your time trying to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't going to be the only team in pro sports to
continue to play in a college stadium. They don't want their fans
to continue to have to sit in the hot sun. Plus, they don't get any
revenue streams from playing there.
</P>
<P>
   Atop the Cardinals' wish list would be a domed stadium near the
intersection of highways 101 and 202, where Tempe, Mesa and
Scottsdale meet. But they're willing to listen to potential sites
in other parts of town, including the west side.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a minute that they're going to agree to any
facility that is without some public funding. They're not going to
play in a stadium built strictly by private money when the Suns,
Diamondbacks and Coyotes all could have new facilities that include
some public dollars.
</P>
<P>
   One Cardinals official said the next few months will show what
kind of leadership the Valley has, whether anyone, including  &UR; Gov.
Jane
 &UR; Hull, is strong enough to get all the parties together and get a
deal done.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the sports community will be the big loser. There
will be no Super Bowls, no Final Fours. The nation's No. 1 sport
will be gone, not to return until a fancy and more expensive new
stadium is built.
</P>
<P>
   That won't matter to some, including those seniors who showed up
in buses last week and shouted, ``Hell, no,'' as they stood in line
to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senior citizens are an inherent part of the process,'' said
 &UR; Rick
 &UR; Horrow, the NFL's stadium consultant. ``Every community has a
sizable senior influence. The question is whether the majority of
them believe in the infrastructure to build for future
generations.'' &QL; 
Trouble in Motor City &QL; 
Sometime in the next couple of weeks, Detroit Lions Coach  &UR; Bobby
Ross should know whether future Hall of Fame running back  &UR; Barry
Sanders will retire after 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has been trying to reach Sanders for nearly four months by
phone, fax and e-mail. But Sanders' agent,  &UR; David Ware, said late
last week that he expects the coach and player to talk soon.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has said he wants to know by June 1 whether Sanders plans
to retire because if Sanders isn't coming back, the Lions want to
acquire another running back.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' father,  &UR; William, continues to criticize Ross' offense,
saying, ``If they don't change (it), he won't be with the Lions in
August. . . . They can clean Barry's locker out.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how important it is for Sanders to break  &UR; Walter Payton's
rushing record of 16,726 yards, Sanders' father said, ``He can do
just like  &UR; Jim Brown did in '65 _ walk away from the game and never
let it faze him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has rushed for 15,269 yards, 1,458 behind Payton. &QL; 
Little patience &QL; 
First-year Philadelphia Eagles Coach  &UR; Andy Reid, whose team opens
the regular season against the Cardinals, would like for
first-round pick &UR; Donovan McNabb to sit on the bench early in the
year and watch starter
 &UR; Doug Pederson play.
</P>
<P>
   But Pederson has struggled in the team's minicamps, and McNabb
said he plans to report to training camp focused on winning the
starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here to sit,'' McNabb said.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting deadlines &QL; 
 &UR; James McAlister, the former UCLA running back who is Arizona
cornerback  &UR; Chris McAlister's father, knows that agent  &UR; Eugene
Parker isn't afraid to hold his client out of training camp to get
the best rookie contract.
</P>
<P>
   Parker clients  &UR; Peter Boulware, Bryant Westbrook and  &UR; Walter
Jones in 1997 and the Cardinals'  &UR; Andre Wadsworth last year were
long holdouts. In fact, Wadsworth didn't sign with the Cardinals
until the eve of the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   But McAlister's dad said he will push Parker to get the deal
done with the Baltimore Ravens, who picked McAlister 10th overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first met Eugene, the first words out of Chris' mouth
were, `I don't want to be a holdout,' '' the elder McAlister said.
``The most important thing for our son is to be in camp that first
day with everybody else. He wants to pay his dues and earn
everything he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray we can get that done. But money becomes an issue.
We'll follow Eugene's lead on this. He knows what he is doing.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at (602) 444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
