<HEADLINE>
PITCHING INJURIES CAUSES MINOR-LEAGUE WORRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER - A twinge?
</P>
<P>
   ``A twinge is good. If it's a sharp pain, like a knife, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the words of Diamondbacks interim pitching coach  &UR; Gil
 &UR; Patterson after watching closer  &UR; Gregg Olson throw in the bullpen
Saturday while testing the abdominal muscle he pulled in the ninth
inning of Friday night's 8-7, 11-inning loss to the Colorado
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Club officials were determining whether to place the
right-hander on the disabled list. Olson convinced them he could
pitch through the problem, so they decided to option infielder
 &UR; Hanley Frias to Triple-A Tucson and recall right-hander  &UR; Bobby
Chouinard from Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The club will keep 12 pitchers on the roster, at least for the
immediate future, given Olson's status and the fact that
right-handed reliever  &UR; Darren Holmes came up with stiffness in his
back and is day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Olson said he had abdominal difficulty while throwing in the
bullpen about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You adjust and pitch through it (discomfort),'' he said. ``You
sort of know what to expect. This time, you had no idea it was
coming. That makes it different in a game situation. Now that I
know what I'm dealing with, I think I can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard was available immediately. He last pitched for Tucson
on Wednesday, throwing 80 pitches. He has pitched in two games for
the Diamondbacks this season, getting credit for a 7-6 victory over
Los Angeles on April 13 at Bank One Ballpark in 16 innings, the
longest game in club history. &QL; 
Bell takes kid to school &QL; 
Second baseman  &UR; Jay Bell walked down the clubhouse hallway before
Saturday's game, mixing coffee by pouring it back and forth into
plastic foam cups.
</P>
<P>
   A mad chemist?
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to love chemistry in school,'' he said. ``You've got to
mix science and math together.''
</P>
<P>
   During the game, he mixed the science of hitting with math,
hitting a three-run homer off right-hander  &UR; David Lee in his major
league debut. Lee had been called up on Thursday from Double-A.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 26, is from Pittsburgh and went with his father to watch
the Pirates, for whom Bell played from 1990-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what (kind of pitches) he had, but it is still a
difficult at-bat when you haven't faced him,'' Bell said. ``He left
(a fastball) up and over the plate, but he seems to have a very
good idea of where he wants to throw the ball. The Rockies have a
good pitcher. He's going to be something special.'' &QL; 
Anderson presses on &QL; 
Left-hander  &UR; Brian Anderson was not overjoyed with his start on
Friday night, the first after being recalled from Tucson and the
first since Sept. 26. He gave up seven runs on nine hits in 4
innings but was not charged with the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because physically, I feel the best I've
felt, my arm feels great,'' Anderson said. ``Stuff-wise, it's the
best I've had. I won several games last season with way worse
(stuff).
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was back. I was moving the ball in and out . . .
I don't know, when a pitcher adds 2 or 3 mph to his fastball and
has more break on his slider and gets worse, something's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Because right-hander  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre is on the disabled list
for a minimum of four to six weeks, Anderson is expected to be in
the rotation at least that long, so he'll have more chances to turn
things around. His next scheduled start is Wednesday night at Bank
One Ballpark against San Diego in the finale of a three-game
series. &QL; 
Pitcher to Dodgers &QL; 
The Diamondbacks have traded left-hander  &UR; Neil Weber, an expansion
draft pick from Montreal, to the Los Angeles Dodgers for future
considerations. Weber had been with Triple-A Tucson. In 1998, he
pitched in four games for the Diamondbacks (2 innings) with an
11.57 ERA and 0-0 record. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
