<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON ACING TEST  
 ASTROS' STAFF LACKS NO. 1 BUT FLOURISHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once  &UR; Randy Johnson departed for the Arizona riches and  &UR; Moises
Alou went down for the year with a torn-up knee, the two-time
defending National League Central champion Houston Astros were
supposed to be very catchable by their divisional foes.
</P>
<P>
   One quarter of the way into the season, though, reveals the
opposite is true.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros entered their weekend series in San Francisco with
the second-largest lead of any division leader. They are getting
the kind of pitching that makes other clubs green with envy, and
they took it personally when just about everyone in baseball
anointed Atlanta, Arizona and Los Angeles with the best pitching
staffs in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick and tired of hearing that,'' Houston General Manager
 &UR; Gerry Hunsicker said. ``Statistically, we have the best pitching
staff in the National League, and it's an insult to the pitchers we
have when people keep saying that we need an ace. Well, we had one
(Randy Johnson) last year, and we didn't get past the first round
of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many Number 1's are out there? Probably four or five.
Would I like to have one of those five? Sure. But I like the guys
we have, too, and I like the challenge of competing without the
high-profile guy that everyone says we are lacking. That makes it
extra satisfying when we quietly keep winning while everyone else
is debating what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than  &UR; Jose Lima, acquired a few years ago from
Detroit as part of the trade that sent  &UR; Brian Hunter and  &UR; Todd
Jones to the Tigers, for the leader of this Houston staff.
</P>
<P>
   He's definitely eccentric, but Lima is emerging as one of the
top pitchers in the game. His 7-1 record with a 2.98 ERA is proof
enough that he has the goods. Couple him with fellow starters  &UR; Mike
Hampton (5-1, 2.61) and  &UR; Shane Reynolds (6-3, 4.06), and the Astros
have themselves quite a top three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't ask for anything more from those guys,'' Astros
Manager  &UR; Larry Dierker said. ``Then again, those guys have been
doing it for a while now, so we can realistically expect them to
keep pitching this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they really think of themselves as Number 1
starters, and in a way, that's good. I think that creates some
internal competition, but at the same time none of them has to
carry the burden of being the Number 1 guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Throwing in  &UR; Sean Bergman, a 12-game winner last season, and the
fact that  &UR; Mike Holt (0-6, 5.80 after Saturday) has managed to hold
off the oncoming  &UR; Scott Elarton (2-1, 1.50 in 15 relief
appearances) speaks volumes about the depth this staff has.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's detractors are quick to point to his automatic-pilot
style of managing. That he rarely makes moves worth noting and
that, despite winning 139 games during a 13-year major league
career, he didn't have the necessary grooming because he had been a
broadcaster in the years leading to his being named manager before
the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a solid club, top to bottom,'' St. Louis Manager  &UR; Tony
 &UR; La Russa said. ``They have few holes.'' &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
Of the 30 major league managers, name the only two who accumulated
at least 2,000 hits during their major league careers. As a bonus,
more juicy information will be included with the answer. &QL; 
Bird droppings &QL; 
Will the mess in Baltimore ever end?
</P>
<P>
   With each passing week the Orioles seem to write a new chapter
to further make everyone conclude they truly are the most
dysfunctional ballclub in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   The latest centers on the three high-profile figures in
management _ owner  &UR; Peter Angelos, General Manager  &UR; Frank Wren and
Manager  &UR; Ray Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Angelos, unwilling to admit he made a mistake in letting  &UR; Davey
 &UR; Johnson go in favor of Miller after the successful 1997 season,
will not act on Wren's request to fire Miller. The mere appearance
that the three have an ongoing poor relationship caused Miller to
try to clear the record last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of this is I wanted to tell you I have a
relationship with Peter Angelos that requires me, when I signed the
contract, to fill him in two or three times a week,'' Miller said.
`That's all I do. . . . I can say that any decision that has been
made as far as releasing someone or sending someone out are mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank has the final say-so because he's the general manager.
There's absolutely nothing subversive, nothing hidden. I've
probably got the best relationship with the general manager that
I've ever had in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   If true, then Miller has had some awful relationships with GMs
in the past. It was Miller, club sources said, who persuaded
Angelos to release reliever  &UR; Heathcliff Slocumb a few weeks back, a
move that went against the wishes of Wren.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is also trying to get the club to let go of pitchers
 &UR; Scott
 &UR; Kamieniecki and  &UR; Mike Fetters. Angelos, however, is balking at
those moves so far. Wren, a rookie GM, offers very little these
days. Read between the lines, however, and it's powerful stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been involved in every decision,'' Wren said. ``I can't
say I've agreed with every decision.'' &QL; 
Strangest of 'em all &QL; 
With all the hoopla surrounding  &UR; Luis Gonzalez's recent 30-game
hitting streak, San Diego Manager  &UR; Bruce Bochy was reminded of
then-Padres catcher  &UR; John Flaherty's 26-game streak in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say all you want about
 &UR; Joe DiMaggio and all the other great hitting streaks,'' Bochy said.
``To me, John's was the most amazing of them all. He's probably the
slowest player in the majors. For him to hit safely in 26 games in
a row is a minor miracle. The guy's got no legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while Gonzalez legged out an infield hit or two during
his streak, Flaherty had to rely on clean hits to the outfield to
continue his streak. &QL; 
A voice from above &QL; 
The sputtering Anaheim Angels, who look like world-beaters one week
in sweeping New York at Yankee Stadium, and then like dregs the
next in losing two of three to Tampa Bay, apparently didn't listen
closely enough to their new leader after the surprising sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can look back on a series like this and remember this is
how it's supposed to be,'' first baseman  &UR; Mo Vaughn said. ``This
team is notorious for playing the Yankees well and everyone else
like crap. That's got to stop. I don't want to see any letdowns.
Let's continue to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels entered the weekend series stuck in last place in the
American League West. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Yankees skipper  &UR; Joe Torre had 2,342 hits during his distinguished
playing career, during which he won the National League's Most
Valuable Player award in 1971. The only other manager to reach at
least 2,000 hits is Montreal Manager  &UR; Felipe Alou, who had 2,101
big-league hits.
</P>
<P>
   Other notables with at least 1,000 hits are: San Francisco's
 &UR; Dusty
 &UR; Baker (1,981), Detroit's  &UR; Larry Parrish (1,789) Toronto's  &UR; Jim
Fregosi (1,726), Seattle's  &UR; Lou Piniella (1,705), Cleveland's  &UR; Mike
Hargrove (1,614), Milwaukee's  &UR; Phil Garner (1,594) and Los Angeles'
 &UR; Davey
 &UR; Johnson (1,252).
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the scale was Boston Manager  &UR; Jimy
Williams, who totaled three hits in his big-league career. Chicago
White Sox skipper  &UR; Jerry Manuel had 23, Minnesota's  &UR; Tom Kelly had
23, St. Louis'
 &UR; Tony La Russa had 35 and Pittsburgh's  &UR; Gene Lamont had 37.
</P>
<P>
   Three managers were pitchers, and six never made it to the
majors, including the Diamondbacks' Buck Showalter. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Just think, if they sell them out, they can
 &UR; cover Kevn Brown's yearly salary: The Dodgers are hoping to
complete construction for next season on 35 to 40 luxury suites
that will be leased for $370,000 to $390,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Further proof that Rickey is in a class all by
 &UR; himself: Cleveland's  &UR; Kenny Lofton last week slammed a home run to
lead off a game for the 14th time in his career. He now trails the
career record holder,  &UR; Rickey Henderson, by a mere 59.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Dick Drago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why weren't they thinking of this five years ago?: Texas
believed  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro's swing better fit the club's home
ballpark better than the now-departed  &UR; Will Clark, who tends to hit
into the left-center field gap. Palmeiro has eight home runs in 74
home at-bats. The most home runs Clark hit in Texas in a
single-season was 11.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Conclusive proof that he really played in the
 &UR; majors: Exhaustive research by  &UR; Jim Henzler of Stats Inc. revealed
that KGME-AM (550) radio host  &UR; Jim Traber ranked as the ninth-worst
hitter ever when it came to hitting a triple. Traber had none in
819 career at-bats. Of the eight players in front of him, half were
pitchers. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the 14 clubs that have joined as expansion clubs since 1961,
only the Padres and Pilots/Brewers have had a player with a hitting
streak longer than  &UR; Luis Gonzalez's 30.  &UR; Paul Molitor had a 39-game
streak for the Brewers and  &UR; Benito Santiago reached 34. Both took
place in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Texas catcher  &UR; Ivan Rodriguez last week committed his first
error in 57 games. Cleveland catcher  &UR; Sandy Alomar recently had
this to say about Pudge: ``Nobody else is going to win the Gold
Glove. They should have the Gold Glove and the Silver Glove. Pudge
would get the Gold Glove, and the rest of us would go for the
Silver Glove.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles GM  &UR; Kevin Malone is so infuriated that
 &UR; Chan Ho Park's agent, who also happens to be his uncle, seems to be
negotiating a contract extension in the newspapers that he has
broken off negotiations until the season is over.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay first baseman  &UR; Fred McGriff, who is having himself a
nice season, hit a home run in his 35th different ballpark last
week, two more than anyone else. He can add Baltimore's Camden
Yards and Seattle's Safeco Field later this season, as well as any
of the four others scheduled to open next season.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's  &UR; David Justice entered the weekend series against
Detroit batting .391 (25 for 64) with nine home runs and an
astonishing 27 RBIs in only 16 games. Since the month began,
Justice's average has skyrocketed from .208 to .313.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Jeff Juden, now with the Yankees' Triple-A affiliate in
Columbus (Ohio) and someone with a long history of having bad
confrontations, got into one with his manager,  &UR; Trey Hillman, and
teammate and former Diamondback  &UR; Andy Stankiewicz, one of the
kindest souls in the game at any level. Juden's consistently poor
behavior appears unchanged. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bruce Chen has been called up to take  &UR; John
 &UR; Smoltz's spot in Atlanta's rotation for two starts. If he does
well, expect the Braves to keep Chen and send  &UR; Odalis Perez, who
seems to have some bizarre excuse every time he pitches poorly, to
the minors. Atlanta has scored at least nine runs three times for
Perez, who has only one win in those starts.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle came close to sending outfielder  &UR; Butch
 &UR; Huskey to Boston last week. The Mariners gave the Red Sox a list of
five players, any one of whom would have been acceptable to secure
the deal. Boston GM  &UR; Dan Duquette was unwilling to lose any of the
five.
</P>
<P>
   Try as he may, Philadelphia reliever  &UR; Jeff Brantley may not be
able to nurse his sore shoulder through the remaining 4{ months of
the season. It's more than likely that Brantley will wind up on the
DL and probably undergo season-ending surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore starter  &UR; Scott Kamieniecki may be down to his final
chance with the Orioles. He will make three starts at Triple-A
Rochester. Unless some form of progress is shown, he may wind up
with his walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle and Texas might be interested in Pittsburgh starter
 &UR; Pete Schourek, who is 2-3 with a 5.27 ERA in his first eight
starts. The Mariners scouted his last start. One possible holdup is
the two-year, $4 million contract Schourek signed last winter.
</P>
<P>
   With  &UR; Midre Cummings signed to a minor league deal, there is
growing belief in Minnesota that first baseman  &UR; Marty Cordova could
be gone soon. Cordova was recently placed on waivers far earlier
than normal. The Twins' hope might be for someone to claim the
former Rookie of the Year and take them off the hook for his $3
million salary. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Cleveland &UR; Manny Ramirez has not gone more than two games without
an RBI.  &QL; 
2. HoustonFront office maintains the pitching staff is the best in
the majors.  &QL; 
3. Atlanta &UR; Tom Glavine, who has won three of his past four starts,
appears to be back.  &QL; 
4. BostonStarter  &UR; Pedro Martinez is on pace to strike out a record
391 batters.  &QL; 
5. NY Yankees &UR; Scott Brosius slamming a bat to pieces offers a sign
of frustration.  &QL; 
6. ArizonaWent to the city by the Bay and flexed its muscle in
winning two of three.  &QL; 
7. San Francisco &UR; Barry Bonds may be slightly ahead of schedule to
return in early June.  &QL; 
8. TexasRookie  &UR; Ryan Glynn takes over  &UR; John Burkett's spot in the
rotation.  &QL; 
9. NY MetsImagine if they had any kind of production from their
outfielders? &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. FloridaCloser Matt Mantei is experiencing lower back pain.  &QL; 
29. MontrealNew signee Mel Rojas' first assignment is to lose
weight.  &QL; 
28. MinnesotaStarting pitchers not named  &UR; Brad Radke are 3-19 with
a 8.45 ERA.  &QL; 
27. Baltimore &UR; Cal Ripken finally got rid of that awkward-looking
batting stance.  &QL; 
26. DetroitTigers brass is battling with  &UR; Justin Thompson to alter
his delivery.  &QL; 
25. San DiegoThe dreadful offense is sputtering big time.  &QL; 
24. ColoradoEight of the 15 smallest crowds in Coors Field history
have been in 1999.  &QL; 
23. TorontoStarter  &UR; Joey Hamilton should be back in the rotation
this week.  &QL; 
22. AnaheimWhere have you gone,  &UR; Darin Erstad? The Halos' lonely
eyes are searching. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Chicago Cubs: Even with eight pitchers having spent some time on
the disabled list, the Cubs have not raised the white flag.  &UR; Sammy
 &UR; Sosa looks like he has his home run swing back and the Cubs have
regained some of that lost swagger.  &UR; Kevin Tapani is pitching like
one of the game's elite and  &UR; Mark Grace is among league leaders in
hitting. Maybe there is something to that old Cubs magic. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Chicago White Sox: While things are looking up on the north side,
they aren't so glib on the south side. The White Sox thought they
were going to have a litmus test of sorts by facing first-place
Cleveland last week. If so, Chicago remains separated by a wide gap
with the best in the division. The Indians scored 13 runs in each
of their three games against the White Sox. Starter  &UR; Jaime Navarro
blasted the umpires after he gave up nine runs in 1 innings. Fellow
starter
 &UR; Jim Parque took his beating like a man, admitting he was terrible. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Cincinnati first baseman  &UR; Sean Casey after the 24-12 victory over
Colorado at Coors Field on Wednesday afternoon: ``That was like a
summer league softball game and we won the keg of beer. I was on
base seven straight times? I didn't realize that. I scored five
runs? Don't think I ever did that because I can't run and steal
bases.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
Yes, we know this space is reserved for young major leaguers worth
noting. This week we offer left-handed pitcher  &UR; Rick Ankiel, who
was promoted from St. Louis' Double-A club in Arkansas to Triple-A
Memphis. Ankiel, 19, was 6-0 with an 0.91 ERA at Arkansas. If he
continues on his pace, expect Ankiel to be a part of the Cardinals
rotation by the middle of June. ``I wouldn't bet against him if I
was going to go to the window,'' St. Louis Manager  &UR; Tony La Russa
said. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
