r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOTTERY-SUNS-AZR &LR;      05-23 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOTTERY-SUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS' GET NINTH PICK, BUT HORNETS PULL OFF MIRACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been that kind of year for the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Luck scorned them Saturday in the NBA draft lottery,
smiling on the Charlotte Hornets instead.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets owned only five four-number combinations out of the
1,000 possibilities in Saturday's lottery. One of those
combinations was drawn third, giving the Hornets the No. 3 pick in
the June 30 draft. The Hornets had less than a 1 percent chance to
get the pick.
</P>
<P>
   And because Charlotte moved into the top three, by lottery
rules, every team below Vancouver, the Los Angeles Clippers and
Chicago were bumped down one spot.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Suns, who had the eighth-most combinations because
they own the Dallas Mavericks' first-round pick, dropped down one
spot to No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you travel this far with very small odds of winning it,
you hope at least to hold your position,'' downcast Suns General
Manager Bryan Colangelo said. ``Because of Charlotte's good luck,
everybody else slipped a spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, conspiracy theories will abound after the Chicago
Bulls won the lottery and got the first pick. But forget the Bulls.
They had a 15.7 percent shot at the No. 1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   But how about the Hornets? Michael Jordan had been negotiating
to purchase the club from George Shinn until talks recently broke
off. What better way to rekindle Jordan's interest than for
Charlotte to have one of the top three picks?
</P>
<P>
   As for the Suns, it has been a tough year. They saw their
rebuilding plan blown up last summer when the NBA locked out its
players, and a new collective bargaining agreement changed the
rules that would have helped the Suns attract several top free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Then they went through a disappointing 27-23 season and were
bumped from the playoffs in the first round for the fourth
consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   With only 37 of the possible 1,000 number combinations in the
lottery, the Suns were a long shot to get into the top three. Now
they'll have to make due with No. 9, which still is the club's
highest pick since their last trip to the lottery in 1988. They
selected Tim Perry with the No. 7 choice that season.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns also own the 16th pick unless they decide Monday to
pass it on to the Chicago Bulls to complete the Luc Longley trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it seriously alter our draft plans?'' Colangelo asked.
``If we had jumped from Number 8 to one of the top three picks, it
would have made a big difference. But there isn't a decided shift
from eight to nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll start zeroing in on the person, or persons, we think
will be there. The draft is deeper than most people will lead you
to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   But Colangelo agrees with observers who have said that few
players, if any, in the draft this season will turn a team into an
instant contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you pick 1 or 9, the person selected is unlikely to
have an immediate impact,'' Colangelo said. ``The people who are
looked upon as the top picks are going to need a year or two to
have an impact because of their age, experience and the acclimation
period that all players go through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns could seek to move up in the draft by keeping the 16th
pick and packaging the two if that will move them up to get a
player they want. They also could make a pick for another team,
then complete a trade later.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could trade either or both picks for established players
in an attempt to get a player who will make an immediate
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means are we married to the pick,'' Colangelo said.
``We've had people approach us about the possibility of packaging
the picks, and we'll look at all scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some way, we'll add a player with the ninth pick who will
help us address one of our weaknesses.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
