<HEADLINE>
MILLER WANTS TOUGHNESS IN POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Cheryl Miller had a scowl on her face and a message
for her team Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Get attitude down low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day they step on the floor, I want them coming in here
with a bad attitude,'' the Mercury coach-general manager said.
``And to be hungry, and to get after it and be passionate and push
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition we have in the guards is ferocious. We don't
have that in the post. I don't like them being nice in the post.
Post players aren't supposed to be nice. Some of our toughest
players are on the perimeter, and that's got to change.''
</P>
<P>
   With Miller at training camp for just the second time in nine
days because of her broadcasting obligations, the Mercury is
without centers Maria Stepanova and Marlies Askamp, playing at the
European Championships, May 28-June 6.
</P>
<P>
   The absences are no excuse for a lack of intensity, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to step up to the challenge,'' she said. ``I'm not
going to ask Merle or Jenny to do something that physically they're
not capable of, but you can always play more aggressively. You can
be more active on the boards. There are a lot of things they can do
that hasn't been done consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Merlelynn Lange-Harris, a 6-foot-6 former Canadian Olympian, and
Jenny Crouse, a 6-3 pro rookie from the University of North Dakota,
are the main camp competition for veterans Jennifer Gillom and Toni
Foster. Trisha Stafford, a top-10 career scorer and rebounder at
the University of California who has American Basketball League and
overseas experience, joined the group Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The battles are more intense on the perimeter because starting
jobs at shooting guard and small forward are at stake. And Lisa
Harrison, Andrea Kuklova and Umeki Webb seemingly are in a
competition for the final two roster spots unless someone begins
the season on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix will play the first of two preseason games against the
Charlotte Sting at 7 p.m. Wednesday at America West Arena. The
rematch is June 4 in Charlotte. The Mercury opens its 32-game
regular season at Sacramento on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Miller will be on the bench Wednesday but is uncertain when she
will join the team full time. She hopes to be back after the
Portland-Utah NBA series is finished. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
