<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--SPURS-HNS &LR;      05-23 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Spurs take 3-0 lead
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ All season long, the Los Angeles Lakers have
been the story in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But now they're on the verge of becoming yesterday's news.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs took a commanding 3-0 lead in the
best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals series with their
103-91 victory over the Lakers on Saturday before 17,505 at the
Great Western Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were on television practically every week, were
pictured on just about every magazine cover and were supposed to
pick up the league's banner in the post-Michael Jordan NBA.
</P>
<P>
   They are on the verge of getting dumped, and the Spurs, former
playoff fodder themselves, are doing the dumping. They scored the
final 13 points of the game to put the Lake Show on the verge of
cancellation entering Game 4, which is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``These Spurs are something special,'' said Spurs point guard
Avery Johnson. ``We're not losing these types of games. We just
keep on pounding away and keep on playing mentally tough. And if we
keep making our free throws, we're really going to be a tough
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Too tough for the Lakers, who must attempt to win four straight
games from the league's hottest team, a pretty tall order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation for them, there's no question about
it,'' said the Spurs' David Robinson. ``But it's a basketball game,
and when you play a basketball game anybody can win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be ready for (today). We really have to come out
and get going early and try to take some of this momentum into
(today's) game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Spurs are necessarily looking for the sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not important at all,'' Robinson said. ``For us, we just
need to work on getting better night in and night out. I don't
think we're even close to where we need to be on the whole, overall
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out there thinking about a sweep, you've got your
mind on the wrong stuff. You have to think about getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to imagine the Spurs playing much better than they
are now.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, heroes were everywhere for the Spurs in this game _ Tim
Duncan pounded away inside to finish with a monster 37-point,
14-rebound game, and Jaren Jackson fired away from the outside for
22 points, including a huge 3-pointer with 1:40 to play.
</P>
<P>
   And after scoring just two points in the first three quarters,
Johnson scored six in the final 5:13, making all three of his shots
to help the Spurs put away the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Duncan was the key, not only scoring 24 of his points in the
first half, but hitting 19 of 23 foul shots in his 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy never ceases to amaze me,'' said the Spurs' Mario
Elie. ``Tim is my Most Valuable Player, man. I've been hearing
whispers that Karl Malone is going to get it (the MVP award), and
that's not fair. Give it to the best player in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? After all, the Lakers gave him just about everything
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They might give, but the Lakers are getting little in return.
The stars have definitely not been aligned for the Lakers, and
we're not talking about celestial bodies here.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Big Three of Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and
Glen Rice have not meshed against the defense-minded Spurs, one big
reason for their predicament _ or three big reasons, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Rice finished with a team-high 24 points, but hit just six of
his 19 shots. Bryant made just seven of his 18, and O'Neal was left
to pick up the scraps, getting only 14 attempts, making eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very frustrated,'' said O'Neal, who finished with 22
points and 15 rebounds. ``Down 2-0 (entering Saturday's game), I
felt we weren't in a hole. But down 3-0, I know we're in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a game (today), so we just have to come out with a lot
more effort than we did (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in the final two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry hit a 3-pointer with 1:55 left to put the Lakers up
by a point, but Jackson began the Spurs' closing run by taking a
pass out of the post from Duncan and nailing a 3-pointer just 15
seconds after Horry's bomb, putting the Spurs up 93-91 and
appearing to break the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big shot, a big shot _ a very big shot,'' Jackson
said of his 3-pointer. ``It was late in the game, and I knew I had
to be very aggressive. All my teammates were supporting me, telling
me that when they doubled (Duncan) inside, to just take my shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the house knew how they were rotating (on
defense), so I just made sure I stepped up and took the shot.
That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   As in that's all for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   After a Derek Fisher miss, Johnson scored on a 19-foot jumper to
give San Antonio a four-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing went right for the Lakers after that. Unable to make a
shot (making just seven of their 20 fourth-quarter field-goal
attempts for 35 percent), they were forced to foul the Spurs, who
stepped to the line and drilled their last six foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little disappointed,'' said Bryant, who had 20 points.
``We didn't play like we wanted to play. We didn't come out with a
lot of energy and passion, like we should have at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're an explosive team. I think that if anybody can do it
(come back from the 3-0 deficit), it's us. We have a lot of
dynamite on this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but it's blowing up in their faces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
