<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-Caminiti-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Caminiti can't avoid going on disabled list
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ As much as he wanted to believe otherwise, Ken
Caminiti knew his strained right calf wasn't going to get much
better over the course of a few days.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Caminiti, considered by many to be baseball's
ultimate gamer, offered no resistance when general manager Gerry
Hunsicker told him he was going on the 15-day disabled list before
Saturday's game against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti has a history of fighting such decisions, of ignoring
the pain and finding a way to get back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could say was, `That's fine,''' he said. ``I know how
bad it hurts. I can barely walk. I've never felt anything like this
before, and I've felt some pretty (bad) stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Daryle Ward was recalled from Class AAA New
Orleans to take Caminiti's spot on the roster. Ward, 23, will join
the Astros today. Caminiti joins Moises Alou, Ricky Gutierrez,
Mitch Meluskey, and Doug Henry on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said Caminti's recovery time could be anywhere from a
week to a month. Caminiti will be eligible to come off the disabled
list June 7, when the Astros open a three-game series against the
White Sox in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he can do is rest and get therapy,'' Hunsicker said.
``With any muscle pull or strain, you can't rush it. We're just
hoping for the best. We hope he'll be ready when he's eligible to
come back. With injuries like this, we pencil it in for a week to
10 days minimum; it could go anywhere up to a month.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred in the third inning of Friday's game against
the Giants. After delivering a two-out, RBI single off Mark
Gardner, Caminiti strained his calf in the process of stealing
second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took one step and I felt it,'' Caminiti said. ``I thought
someone had thrown something from the stands and hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's game, Hunsicker termed Caminiti's status as
day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspected this (after Friday's game),'' Hunsicker said.
``But we wanted to give it the benefit of the doubt. His calf is
extremely sore, and it's not likely he's going to get over this
very quickly. Rather than go (a player) short for another day, we
decided to bring up Daryle Ward.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward was hitting .339 with a Pacific Coast League-leading 15
homers and 41 RBIs in 42 games at New Orleans. This will be the
second stint in the big leagues for Ward, who was called up when
Jeff Bagwell went on the DL last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daryle's basically going to be a bat off the bench,''
Hunsicker said. ``I usually don't like to have a young player come
up here and sit _ especially a player like Ward _ but for the role
we were looking at, he was the best choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Villalobos (New Orleans) and Chris Truby (Class AA
Jackson) are the top third-base prospects in the organization, but
the Astros are well covered at third on the major-league roster
with Bill Spiers, Jack Howell and Russ Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti was struggling at the time of his injury (1-for-19) but
is hitting .292 with two homers and 17 RBIs in 36 games. This is
the third year in a row Caminiti has been disabled, and he believes
he has gained the reputation of a player who is always injured _ a
label he hardly appreciates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played hard in my career and I've paid the price,'' said
Caminiti, who missed 21 games during a stint on the disabled list
in 1998. ``It just seems like lately, people think I'm always
getting hurt. I handled my own contract negotiations this time, and
I heard what they had to say (about health concerns).
</P>
<P>
   ``It (ticked) me off, and now I'm dealing with it. I can
understand why they had concerns. I've had surgeries the last two
years. I'm sure they're like, `Who knows what we're going to get?'
That's not the way I like it, and that's not the way I want it.
This is a hard game to play, and I've played it hard. Things
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7754 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAPE-AZR &LR;      05-23 2471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS OF RAPE MUST ENDURE POORLY EQUIPPED MEDICAL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER  
 and SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rape victims are being shuffled from hospital to hospital
throughout metropolitan Phoenix, their care delayed for hours by
overcrowded emergency rooms and doctors reluctant to examine them.
</P>
<P>
   Women who were at the mercy of their attackers have found
themselves at the mercy of a broken-down system that is supposed to
provide physical exams that are critical for police investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Even the basics _ rape-exam kits, for example _ aren't always
available. Last month, a woman at Maryvale Hospital Medical Center
had to wait for a kit to be delivered via taxi from Thunderbird
Samaritan Medical Center in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Flores, a Valley mother who was beaten and raped, was
driven to three hospitals last year before she could get an exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like, `What the hell do they have hospitals for?' ''
she said. ``Regardless if I've been raped or haven't been raped,
I'm hurting. Isn't that what you go to hospitals for?''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, some women get help; some don't; some
give up and go home.
</P>
<P>
   Victims' advocates say a lack of communication and a maze of
contradictory rules and services create confusion that can
retraumatize victims and set rapists free.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Assaulted women sometimes go from hospital to hospital before
they find someone who will see them, or wait for hours in crowded
emergency rooms. During this time, they can't clean up and are
supposed to urinate as little as possible so they don't destroy
evidence. As they wait, physical evidence of the attack fades while
their emotional trauma builds.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency-room physicians acknowledge they are increasingly
reluctant to examine victims, largely because of a concern about
having to testify in court.
</P>
<P>
   Police say they routinely bypass nearby hospitals and take
victims to Mesa's Center Against Family Violence because they
consider it the best place for treatment and evidence collection.
Two other Valley centers are planned but won't open for months,
which means police officers in cities as far away as Glendale will
travel to Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most ERs right now are so helter-skelter, with people in and
out,'' said Chandler police Sgt. Kenny Thatcher, who oversees the
crimes against persons unit. ``If a sexual assault victim hasn't
been injured, they're very low on the priority list.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just sit and sit and sit. They may sit for three or four
hours before they to see the doctor.'' &QL; 
THE SECOND ORDEAL
</P>
<P>
   After Flores had been held hostage, raped and beaten, she
escaped and called police _ and then began another ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Avondale police Det. Kelly Shore drove her to St. Joseph's
Hospital and Medical Center and Good Samaritan Regional Medical
Center, but was turned away at both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of upsetting. We're trying to work a case, we're
trying to gather evidence, and she needs help and we just got
turned away,'' Shore said.
</P>
<P>
   Good Samaritan officials said they have no record of Flores
coming to the hospital. If she had no physical injuries, she could
have been sent elsewhere for a forensic exam, said Bill Byron, Good
Samaritan spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Helander, who was St. Joseph's emergency-department
manager at the time, said the hospital didn't have a record of
Flores, either. He added that what happened would have been an
``aberration'' from the hospital's policy.
</P>
<P>
   Frazzled, Shore and Flores eventually arrived at Maricopa
Medical Center, the county hospital, took a seat and waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was embarrassed,'' Flores said. ``My shirt was torn. I was
walking in with no shoes. . . . Just imagine what people were
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like everyone knew I was raped.''
</P>
<P>
   After two hours she was led into an exam room. Then she waited
2{ hours more before she was released. After being shuffled around
and made to wait for a doctor, Flores felt unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   The system isn't supposed to treat people that way.
</P>
<P>
   And the Maricopa County Attorney's Office is lobbying for
change. &QL; 
A `SANE' APPROACH
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors want to adopt a system used across the country in
which specially trained nurses conduct sexual assault exams on
adults. The nurses would work from victim advocacy centers, like
the one in Mesa, and would collect evidence, provide emotional
support and then testify in court when needed.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the perfect solution, advocates and others say. But
there never has been a perfect solution, they add, noting that the
current system is riddled with defects.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the victims' fates depend largely on their choice of
emergency rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals such as Phoenix Regional Medical Center and
Thunderbird Samaritan Medical Center will likely send patients
elsewhere for exams. Others, like Mesa Lutheran hospitals, say they
offer patients the option of staying there or going someplace else.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's two John C. Lincoln hospitals and Phoenix Memorial
Hospital say they will do the exams if requested. Others, like
Desert Samaritan Medical Center in Mesa, expect the police to bring
their own kits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be years ago that you could take a victim to
whatever hospital was closest,'' said Chris Parks, victim services
coordinator for the Phoenix Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   But now, she said, ``It's hard. You prepare a victim: `This is
where we're going, this is what's going to happen, these people are
going to treat you very nicely.' And then you walk in and they say,
`Sorry we can't treat you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you turn around (to the victim) and say, `OK, this is
really what's going to happen.' '' &QL; 
DOCTORS RELUCTANT
</P>
<P>
   The problem lies in part with doctors' reluctance to perform
rape exams. When it comes to treating victims, doctors can be a
little ``schizophrenic,'' said Dr. Kent Layton, business manager &UR; of
Tempe Emergency Physicians Group, which provides services at Tempe
St. Luke's Hospital and St. Luke's Medical Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, we are sympathetic and supportive. . . . We
are outraged that something like this would happen,'' he said.
``But like a lot of people in society, we don't want to get
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to go into that (examining) room because we
don't want to go to court.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying in court can mean taking days off without pay or
throwing stretched-thin staffing schedules out of whack. It's
especially frustrating when cases are constantly rescheduled,
doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize it's my civic duty . . . but what bothers physicians
is the lack of coordination in court,'' said Dr. Todd Taylor, a
Good Samaritan emergency-room physician. ``Like most people,
doctors don't enjoy rearranging their lives around court schedules
and then seeing nothing come of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike expert witnesses, doctors are not paid for their time
in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't even have to pay for parking,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, doctors can refuse to do the exams, although hospitals
are required to screen and stabilize anyone who comes into the
emergency department. But it shouldn't be an option, said Dr.
Charles Pollack, who runs Maricopa Medical Center's emergency
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no sympathy for doctors who don't want to perform the
exams,'' he said. ``These people are their patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Deputy County Attorney Joe Heilman, who prosecuted sex
crimes cases for eight years and called doctors as witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about seeing a patient and writing a
prescription,'' he said. ``I think it goes deeper than that.
There's an obligation to the patient.'' &QL; 
CROWDED EMERGENCY ROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is emergency rooms. They have become crowded in
part because of an influx of uninsured patients who wait until
their symptoms become severe, then seek treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Rape victims often wait until medical personnel work their way
through cases considered more of a threat to people's lives than
sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   Victims can feel increasingly vulnerable amid a waiting room
full of strangers. At times, police have to interview them in
whispers. Or victims must repeat their story to various hospital
staffers.
</P>
<P>
   They may, or may not, sit in anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Cindi Nannetti, who heads the county attorney's sexual assault
unit, recalls once when an emergency-department staffer came out
into the waiting room and asked, ``Who's the rape victim?''
</P>
<P>
   When a friend of Kathleen Ferraro was raped a month ago, the
emergency room seemed the logical place to go.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Actually, it wasn't the right place at all, said Dr. Andrea
Stone, Desert Samaritan's manager of business operations for the
emergency department. Desert Samaritan's ER is over &UR; capacity these
days. It's never been designated as a sexual assault center and
police should have known that, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But no one told that to Ferraro, her friend, or the Phoenix
officer on the case as they waited 3{ hours at Desert Samaritan.
They only found out when a hospital social worker led them into a
small waiting room and told them the hospital didn't have rape
kits. The victim, Ferraro said, exploded at the social worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know that I have been waiting for hours? Why didn't you
tell me that at the beginning?''
</P>
<P>
   But there was no good explanation, and the three drove to the
Mesa center.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, an associate professor of women's studies at Arizona
State University, can't believe such poor treatment still exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had resolved this,'' she said. ``I didn't think
things like this happened anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Flores.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after being turned away twice, she didn't want to take
her chances at a third hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I just wanted to give up and go home,'' she said.
``But the detective told me he couldn't do that. He wanted me to
get the exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just giving up hope, like nobody cares.''
</P>
<P>
   EASIER TO STAY SILENT
</P>
<P>
   Victim advocates wonder what happens to women who don't have
Flores' tenacity. National experts say that only 10 percent of
assaults are reported; the current chaos invites assaulted women to
remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 10 of the Valley's hospitals entered into loose
contracts with the county to provide exams. The County Attorney's
Office must pay for sexual assault exams when the victim wants to
prosecute and with the contracts, it could set a fixed fee and
control costs, Nannetti said.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the contracts only complicated services for
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals that once did the exams shied away, fearing they would
get victims from all across the Valley. Meanwhile, police and
advocates were confused about where to take victims, because some
hospitals without contracts intermittently offered to do the exams.
Others with contracts later dropped off the list.
</P>
<P>
   A notable no-show was Samaritan Health Systems, which had four
hospitals at the time. Taylor, of Good Samaritan, said doctors
talked with hospital administrators, explaining that the exams
could take hours and that staffers could spend days in court. Also,
the county was barely covering the exams' costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals that agreed to do the exams started seeing their
emergency rooms fill up with sexual assault victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were seeing people being brought from across town, and we
didn't think that was in the patients' best interests,'' said
Helander, of St. Joe's. Eventually, St. Joe's dropped out of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arrowhead Community Hospital, which had been doing
the exams for many West Valley communities, decided not to enter
into an agreement with the county. Officials feared that their
emergency room would be filled with sexual assault patients, said
Susie Melendez, a nurse and emergency room director.
</P>
<P>
   When Arrowhead dropped out, that left an even larger void in the
West Valley, where there are few hospitals. &QL; 
MESA CENTER A MODEL
</P>
<P>
   Today, nearly 20 hospitals around the Valley say they will do
the exams. Parks, the victim services coordinator for Phoenix
police, isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're telling you they do (the exams)?'' she said. ``I sure
hope they're following through with it, because it's certainly not
what we're seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   She and others say they can usually count on St. Luke's,
Maricopa Medical and the Mesa advocacy center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been turned away from the majority of the other ones,''
Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa center, opened by the Police Department in 1996, is
seen as a model for victim advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mesa police have seen an enormous change in three years: Rape
prosecutions have increased from 50 percent to 91 percent, said
Mesa police Sgt. Jon Terpay.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, police from as far away as Glendale and Peoria prefer
the Mesa center, regardless of the drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drive is nothing compared to what (problems) you can
create by walking into an ER,'' said Sgt. Bill Copeland, who heads
Glendale's sex crimes and family violence unit.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale police opened their own center last year. Police
detectives have already moved in, but the exam room isn't ready
yet. Phoenix officials will open their version of the Mesa center
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Once the centers are open, victims won't go to emergency rooms
unless they are injured, under the proposal by the County
Attorney's Office. Their exams will be done by a specially trained
sexual assault nurse examiner _ SANE.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale Health System already has 10 nurses trained under the
SANE program. It was the only group to bid on the county's contract
to provide sexual assault exams. Even if it doesn't receive the
contract, Scottsdale's Osborn Road and Shea Boulevard hospitals
would become other designated centers.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates and police welcome the centers, but wonder if there
are enough to serve the entire Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, about 1,360 women and men got exams at hospital
emergency rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern with the county's proposal: getting the word out
to police and hospital staffers _ a challenge given how poor
communications are now.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a new system _ even one with possible flaws _ is long
overdue, police officers and advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police Lt. Joe Yonner, who heads the sex crimes unit,
wants to get victims into advocacy centers for both the exam and
police interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victim who gets the runaround, they're pretty worn out. We
lose information that way,'' Yonner said.
</P>
<P>
   How victims react to their attack runs the gamut of emotions,
said Dr. Emily Pollack, one of two doctors at the Mesa center, who
recently treated a teenager who said she had to wait eight hours at
Chandler Regional Hospital for an exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be depressed and sad and angry at their
perpetrators,'' she said. ``(But) they are not angry at the system,
and they have a perfect right to be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
