<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED COYOTE MAKES BIG SAVE IN CHILDBIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember  &UR; Darcy Wakaluk, the former backup goalie for the
Coyotes whose career was cut short two years ago because of knee
problems?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the recently retired puck stopper, who now runs a rock and
gravel company in Alberta, came up with the biggest save of his
life a couple of weeks ago. He had just left home to take his
children out for an afternoon of putt-putt golf when he got a call
on his cellular phone from his pregnant wife,  &UR; Dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Wakaluk made a U-turn and a beeline back to his mother-in-law's
house, where Dawn had called from. She had gone into labor. There
was no time to rush to the hospital. The baby was coming, and
someone had to deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   Dad did the honors, after a few frantic moments on the phone
with a 911 operator. The conversation went a little something like
this, according to family friends:
</P>
<P>
   Wakaluk: ``My wife's having a baby! . . . The head's coming out!
What do I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``The head's coming out?''
</P>
<P>
   Wakaluk: ``Yeah. . . . Wait a minute, it's out! What do I do
now?
</P>
<P>
   Operator: ``You have to tie off the cord.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakaluk: ``Tie it up with what?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he used the shoestrings from his boots and, luckily
for Dawn, Darcy kept his focus and made the glove save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came out so fast,'' he said later, ``I'm surprised I didn't
lose it through my five hole.''
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, little  &UR; Brock Wakaluk was welcomed into the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Darcy) did real well,'' Dawn Wakaluk said. ``He was a
little shaken up. . . . His hair was standing on end there for a
while. He was a basket case. But he did real well, and I'm very,
very proud of him.'' &QL; 
Meltdown in Motown
</P>
<P>
   Don't kid yourself. Detroit's elimination in the second round of
the playoffs by Colorado was as difficult for the two-time
defending Stanley Cup champions as it was for their legion of
die-hard fans, many of whom reside in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the middle of May, and we're done,'' forward  &UR; Martin
Lapointe said. ``But we're not machines, we're human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   All too human, it turns out, allowing the Avalanche to win four
straight to capture the series in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of empty and humbling,'' captain  &UR; Steve Yzerman
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Joe Nieuwendyk of the Dallas Stars had to rub it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing a much better team (in Colorado instead of
Detroit), in my mind,'' he said. ``They proved that in the last
series, and now we've got to go out and beat this team. After what
they did to Detroit, I don't think anybody's worried about Detroit
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   And now there's the  &UR; Scotty Bowman Watch. Will the NHL's career
winningest coach decide he's finally had enough of the game and
retire? Detroit General Manager  &UR; Ken Holland said he was
``optimistic'' that Bowman, 65, will come back for at least one
more season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly hope Scotty will be back,'' Avalanche Coach  &UR; Bob
Hartley said. ``By coming back next year, Scotty would be starting
his fifth decade as a coach, and I don't think that ever will be
repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Red Wings center  &UR; Sergei Fedorov to lose any sleep
of Bowman bows out. Fedorov openly grumbled about his role and
supposed lack of ice time after the Red Wings were ousted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a new feeling,'' Fedorov said. ``I feel like, all the
potential I have, I didn't have a chance to use it all the way.'' &QL; 
4x4 rally
</P>
<P>
   Is it a coincidence, or is there something a lot more to the
fact that four of the NHL's very best goalies are the final four
left in the postseason?
</P>
<P>
   In the Eastern Conference Finals, it's Buffalo's  &UR; Dominik Hasek
against Toronto's  &UR; Curtis Joseph, and in the Western Conference,
it's Colorado's  &UR; Patrick Roy against Dallas'  &UR; Eddie Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it shows just how important goaltending is to hockey
teams,'' Colorado's  &UR; Joe Sakic said. ``Obviously, we feel we have
the best one in the game right now. Especially this time of year.
But I don't think it's a coincidence that the four best goalies in
the game are in the (conference) finals right now. That's what it
takes to win championships.''
</P>
<P>
   All four have super credentials and incredible stats, but many
NHL experts pick Roy as the best of the bunch right now. &QL; 
The rumor mill
</P>
<P>
   With the Coyotes, it's hard to predict anything. But the
whispers around the organization are that Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld
will be back next season, possibly with a one- or two-year contract
extension. An announcement of some sort should come down by
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The team will be closing its offices in north Scottsdale for six
straight days beginning Thursday, and it's doubtful General Manager
 &UR; Bobby Smith will want another full week of coaching rumors to
persist. Besides, it's time to pull the trigger, one way or the
other, and stop letting Schoenfeld twist in the wind. Unless, of
course, they've already privately told him he's coming back. Maybe
that's why Schoenfeld won't grant any interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   If the Coyotes lose assistant coach  &UR; John Tortorella to another
NHL team _ his contract expires this summer along with fellow
assistant  &UR; Gordie Roberts _ one potential candidate might be
 &UR; Claude
 &UR; Julian, head coach of the Hull Olympiques, a Canadian junior team.
According to NHL sources, Smith likes the guy a lot.
</P>
<P>
   According to other sources, Tortorella is a candidate for jobs
in Los Angeles, New York, Atlanta and Vancouver. Roberts,
meanwhile, will take a group of 10 Phoenix prospects to Helsinki,
Finland, later this summer for a two-week training camp with the
Jokerit club. They wouldn't send him without a new contract, so
expect him to return next season with Schoenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   The word is out that free-agent-to-be  &UR; Mark Tinordi, a veteran
defenseman with the Washington Capitals, has purchased a home in
the Valley. Is it the first step to signing with the Coyotes this
summer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Newsday'' has reported that the New York Islanders, co-owned
by former Coyotes Owner  &UR; Steven Gluckstern, have an agreement to
build a new $300 million arena and that the deal is ``97 percent''
completed. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at (602) 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
