<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7757 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-     05-23 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVER STATE'S TREASURES FOR MEMORIAL DAY HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Longtime residents of Arizona usually have their favorite
Memorial Day weekend retreats. They know the state. They know what
they have to do to assure a place at a favorite recreational site.
</P>
<P>
   I've been in Arizona for 22 years, most of it exploring Arizona.
Anyone who has lived here that long is almost a native. I see
bumper stickers that proclaim the driver is a ``Native.'' I demand
one that says ``Alien.'' We ``aliens'' far exceed the natives in
numbers, and that disparity will continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Just because I wasn't born here and didn't understand the desert
when I first arrived, doesn't mean I haven't come to love it as
much as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   I would like to help recent arrivals, newcomers to the desert,
come to know it better so they can love it and protect it, too.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so here's the deal: You have talked to co-workers and
friends since you moved to Arizona. You've heard of the White
Mountains, the Mogollon Rim, the Grand Canyon, Oak Creek Canyon,
high-rolling, status cities such as Sedona, weird but charming old
mining towns such as Bisbee and wonder about something special for
Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   First, you must know that many accommodations in hot spots such
as Oak Creek near Sedona have been booked for at least a year. The
lodges are among the best anywhere. They'll cost upwards of $300 a
night. I'm not interested. Unless I can weasel a room on my expense
account, I can't afford it. My boss wouldn't allow that often.
</P>
<P>
   But for short-time residents of Phoenix, I can provide some
places that should be good even if no reservations have been made.
We'll do a couple of distant treasures, and the rest closer in.
</P>
<P>
   The first would be the North Kaibab Plateau that borders Utah to
the north. This is the north side of the Grand Canyon's North Rim.
You must understand that the North Rim is 1,000 feet higher than
the more popular and easier-to-reach South Rim. The views from the
north are unsurpassed. Fewer visitors, too. But reaching the North
from the Valley of the Sun takes longer than getting to the South.
It's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   You take Interstate 17 north to Flagstaff, join U.S. 89 there
and head north through the Navajo Reservation on U.S. 89. Then,
near Page, you take U.S. 89A, pass over the Colorado River at Lees
Ferry and continue to the top of the plateau. It's a journey from
desert to alpine country. The drive is at least five hours from
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The crossroads is at Jacob Lake. There isn't much of a lake, but
there's a motel, restaurant, campgrounds and other services. Great
place about 8,000 feet above sea level. From there, you can go
south toward the North Rim.
</P>
<P>
   The country is outstanding, full of evergreens and wonderful
beauty. No fire restrictions have been imposed there yet. The
sparse campgrounds are wonderful, but dispersed camping is allowed
in certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   Now at the other end of the state, in southeastern Arizona near
the New Mexico border, lies the Chiricahua Mountains and Chiricahua
National Monument. The rock formations, trails and camping areas
make it among the best in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   This is a grasslands area with the mountains rising above it. It
is spectacular, normal stuff for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Its isolation from urban areas makes this a prime place. Take
Interstate 10 from Phoenix through Tucson and on southeast to
Willcox, where you'll turn off toward the monument. Willcox has
plenty of motels. You can go through the monument, pass over the
mountains to Portal on the eastern side. This is absolutely
wonderful country _ probably a little warm during the day but cool
at night. It is four or more hours from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one of my favorite spots in Arizona, if you're willing to
hike 3.5 miles one way, is Fossil Creek Springs on the Mogollon
Rim. It is so desirable that I hiked into it twice in one day.
</P>
<P>
   The springs are located near Strawberry, which also is one my
favorite places because of the Strawberry Lodge, which offers rooms
without TVs and excellent food. The cost in reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is several hours from Phoenix and can be reached two
different ways. From northern Phoenix, take Interstate 17 north to
Camp Verde and take Gen. Crook Highway (State Route 260) to the top
of the Mogollon Rim and back down to Strawberry. The same trip can
be taken on State Route 87 off the Beeline Highway.
</P>
<P>
   Turn off the highway at the Strawberry Inn on Fossil Creek Road
and head east down the road to Fossil Creek. There are two
entrances to the spring. An upper parking lot takes you to a trail
head that goes down. At the bottom of the canyon, there is a
trailhead that goes up on a road to the springs.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same distance to the springs from either trailhead. The
lower one is easier, but I prefer the top one. It's tough, but the
view is outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The springs put out about a million gallons an hour. Part is
used for power generation, but that's downstream from the springs.
There are great pools to swim in, including ropes hung to trees
that allow swings out over the water. There are fire restrictions
in the area but plenty of pull-offs for camping.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I hiked in there was during the week. The pools
were so great I skinny-dipped in them, thinking no one was around.
On the way out that day, I met Boy Scout troops and hordes of other
individuals. I didn't know that. With luck, I never embarrassed
myself.
</P>
<P>
   No campfires, please.
</P>
<P>
   Stay in Payson and take a great drive. It's called Rim Road and
offers some of the best views off the Mogollon Rim anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Motels will be crowded so start calling now. Besides Payson,
Kohl's Ranch, various places in Christopher Creek and a motel in
Forest Lakes are fine places.
</P>
<P>
   From Payson, take State Route 260 northeast toward the Mogollon
Rim past Kohl's Ranch and Christopher Creek and up to the top of
the Rim. It's a beautiful drive.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the Rim, you'll see a left-hand turn to Woods
Canyon Lake. That's the Rim Road. A short stretch is paved. The
rest isn't.
</P>
<P>
   It'll take you past the lake and on a trip that gives you
spectacular views. It may be the prettiest drive in the Arizona
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   It ultimately takes you out at State Route 87 north of
Strawberry, where you can go south to Payson.
</P>
<P>
   This should be a newcomers heaven. Enjoy it. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
