r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUNG-TRANSPLANT-LADN     05-23 0275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNG-TRANSPLANT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNUSUAL TYPE OF SURGERY SAVES CYSTIC FIBROSIS PATIENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Suffering from cystic fibrosis, Misty Laird
faced a bleak future earlier this year because of her rapidly
deteriorating lungs.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to an unusual type of surgery, officials at USC
University Hospital say her future now looks bright.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old Oregon woman received lung lobes from both of
her parents in a dramatic three-way surgery last month at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Laird was one of about 250 people who attended the first
Cardiothoracic Transplant Fair sponsored by the hospital Saturday
at the Red Lion Inn in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   The unique event offered heart and lung transplant patients,
prospective candidates and their families an informal setting in
which to learn more about opportunities available to them and meet
with an array of transplant surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speaker, Dr. Vaughn Starnes, chairman of the USC
department of cardiothoracic transplants, was the physician who
performed Laird's surgery.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the surgery, Laird is looking forward to
returning home to attend her high school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia Schenkel, senior transplant coordinator for USC
University Hospital, said transplant surgery ``is a good
alternative for people with end-stage heart and lung disease.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of innovations in transplants that the
public may not know about,'' Schenkel said. ``The word transplant
might cause fear in some people, but the survival rate is really
very good.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
