<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7765 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      05-23 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros extend Holt's bad luck
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After yet another loss and round of questions
about his frustrating start to the season, Chris Holt slipped into
the hallway for a chat with San Francisco Giants pitcher Russ
Ortiz, a young righthander for whom everything has fallen into
place in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonder Holt hasn't fallen apart.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 3-1 loss was void of his usual first-inning drama,
but with Holt's luck, you almost knew something else would stand
between him and his first win since Aug. 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That something happened to be a someone _ Ortiz, who made the
best-hitting lineup in the National League look like one of the
worst. Ortiz, who owns a league-leading 2.25 earned-run average to
go with his 6-2 record, limited the Astros to just three hits in 6
innings and left them feeling like they never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kid pitched a great game,'' said Astros first baseman
Jeff Bagwell, who was 0-for-3. ``He just doesn't make mistakes. His
pitches are either on the black (corners of the plate) or on your
hands. It's pretty tough to beat a guy who's doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has good composure, and he doesn't get rattled. Of course,
we didn't do much to rattle him. To be honest, I don't even think
we hit a ball hard against him.''
</P>
<P>
   There has long been a belief in baseball that facing an elite
pitcher can throw off a hitter's timing at the plate for the next
few days. There may be something to that theory.
</P>
<P>
   Since being shut down by Dodgers ace Kevin Brown on Wednesday in
Los Angeles, the Astros are hitting .142 and they are averaging a
mere 2.7 runs per game. They only have 17 hits during that stretch,
and they've struck out 25 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to score runs, and it just hasn't happened in the
last three games,'' Bagwell said. ``But I'll tell you what; this
was the best-pitched game we've seen in the last three days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros wasted a well-pitched game by Holt, who has lost 12
of his last 13 decisions dating to 1997. The high-powered Astros
offense has only averaged 3.3 runs for Holt in those 12 losses. The
hard-luck righthander allowed three runs (two earned) on six hits
in six innings Saturday, but he moved no closer to the winner's
circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot I can say,'' Holt said. ``It gets old. I'm
tired of losing. I know the guys are busting their butts trying to
score some runs for me, and I know it's going to happen. It's just
one of those unlucky things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to shake it off. I know this team will score some
runs. There's only so long you can keep having bad things happen to
you. Unfortunately, my spot in the rotation has just been
unlucky.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros need a victory today to break even on the six-game
road trip, and they will send their more prosperous pitcher, Jose
Lima, to the mound. But even Lima would have had trouble sneaking
out of 3Com Park with a win Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Holt (0-6) escaped the first inning without allowing a run to
score, but he missed out on his first 1-2-3 first inning when
Armando Rios worked him for a two-out walk. Only three of the first
nine batters reached base against Holt, who didn't encounter his
first sign of trouble until the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   With third baseman Bill Spiers playing on the grass in
anticipation of a bunt, Giants leadoff hitter Melvin Benard goosed
a single past Spiers' diving reach.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like an insignificant occurrence until Benard went to
third on Bill Mueller's double and scored on a groundout by Rios.
Jeff Kent drove in another run with a sacrifice fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holt had good stuff again,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said. ``He made a few mistakes, but you can usually get away with
that with our offense. He gave up two runs in (the third), and in a
low-scoring game, two runs is a big inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller's wild throw to first after a grounder to third by Tim
Bogar set up the Astros' only run of the game. Bogar wound up at
second base on the play and scored on Craig Biggio's single to left
in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The first of Bogar's two errors in the game helped the Giants
increase their lead to two in the fifth. Rios reached first safely
on a routine grounder bobbled by Bogar, whose throw to first was
close, but not in time according to first-base umpire Jerry
Crawford. J.T. Snow doubled Rios home.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros only had one other legitimate scoring opportunity,
and that came in the seventh inning. Carl Everett led off with a
single, and Ortiz issued back-to-back two-out walks to Tony Eusebio
and Bogar.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker summoned lefthanded-hitting Jack Howell to pinch hit for
relief pitcher Trever Miller, prompting Giants manager Dusty Baker
to call lefty Alan Embree from the bullpen. Dierker switched to
Russ Johnson, who struck out to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a pretty good situation there,'' Dierker
said. ``Johnson has a tendency to draw some walks and Embree has a
tendency to walk people. I thought we might get a run and get
Biggio to the plate, but it didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, not much did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
