<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7766 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-T     05-23 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE STEAL HOME-ICE ADVANTAGE FROM STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dallas Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher has seen this
look in Colorado goalie Patrick Roy's eyes before, a twinkling that
he gets when he's playing game-stealingly good.
</P>
<P>
   He had that look while winning two Stanley Cups in Montreal,
while winning a Cup in Colorado in 1996 and again while helping the
Avalanche to a 2-1 victory against the Stars in Game 1 of the
Western Conference finals Saturday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played really well,'' Hatcher said, ``but both goalies gave
their teams a chance to win. They took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy finished with 30 saves, and Stars goalie Ed Belfour had 26.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour had save No. 27 sitting before him with less than six
minutes remaining in a 1-1 game. He went to pounce just as
Avalanche winger Valeri Kamensky began poking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went up in the air and Mo tried to hit it in the corner,''
Belfour explained. ``It was one of those reaction plays, and it
ended up in our net.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It went off my stick,'' Stars center Mike Modano confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Kamensky's game-winning goal went in with 5:58 remaining,
finishing the Avalanche's come-from-behind effort and extending
their road record in the playoffs to 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   His game-winning goal helped to ease Kamensky's anger after he
had an apparent second-period goal disallowed, touching off a
mini-maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 15 minutes to save the integrity of the game!''
Avalanche general manager Pierre Lacroix screamed to NHL off-ice
official Wally Harris between the second and third periods.
</P>
<P>
   Harris had ruled the puck didn't cross the goal line. Avalanche
officials argued the puck didn't cross the goal line because it was
stopped by the padding that surrounds the bottom of the net.
</P>
<P>
   When the announcement was made that the goal had been
disallowed, Avalanche winger Claude Lemieux banged his stick
against the glass where the goal judge sits.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different Colorado team from that point on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they had a goal. They probably did,'' Stars
defenseman Craig Ludwig said.''I'm sure that got them fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche center Peter Forsberg scored almost 10 minutes later
to tie the game at 1-1. He poked a rebound past Belfour with 5:53
remaining in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   An Avalanche goal looked to be just a matter of time, Stars
players said. They said they felt the game slipping away before
that. The Avalanche was skating well, generating a lot of chances.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the first period where the Stars looked to
be in firm control. They outshot the Avalanche 14-9 in the first
period and left with a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was the typical Dallas goal of late _ hardworking and
from the stick of Modano.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado defenseman Adam Foote attempted to reverse puck, and
Modano intercepted along the boards. Roy had been heading behind
the net to get the puck and found himself in no man's land.
</P>
<P>
   A flick of Modano's wrist and a simple tap by Brett Hull
standing alone in front of the net and the Stars had a lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we have to do some of the same things to generate
some type of offensive production,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chances were plentiful, especially late, for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Stars players peppered Roy with 31 shots in all.
</P>
<P>
   No. 29 was by Jamie Langenbrunner with less than 60 seconds
remaining and Roy just barely pushed it wide. No. 30 was a rebound
by Benoit Hogue cradled in Roy's pads.
</P>
<P>
   He had that look going. He was feeling it, ready to steal
another series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let a goaltender beat us,'' Stars defenseman Darryl
Sydor said.
</P>
<P>
   So how exactly do they beat him in Game 2?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, more shots, I guess,'' Sydor said. ``I guess we had
opportunities. We had chances. We had our chances. We just didn't
have second and third chances. That's what it is going to take.''
</P>
<P>
   They get another chance Monday night. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
