<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      05-23 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAINING CATS AND . . . MORE CATS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A woman named Mary Reed is on my answering machine saying she
has a son with cancer and needs help. In a wavering voice, she
appeals not only to my news judgment, but to my hu manity. She's
frightened. Broken-hearted. Grasping at straws.
</P>
<P>
   I have no choice but to give her the brushoff.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, I'll call her back.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen wondrous results when news organizations publicize the
plight of par ents with ill or injured children. Miracles are
possible.
</P>
<P>
   But only when the timing's right.
</P>
<P>
   And near as I can tell, it's all wrong for Mary. The local news
has featured a suc cession of stories lately about ailing young
people and their families.
</P>
<P>
   And, while we pretend to care about each and every needy child,
the truth is, the sad stories wear us down. We can't deal with a
new one every day. So I con tact Mary with the idea of listening to
what she has to say, then politely declin ing to write about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newspaper has done some won derful things for people in
need,'' she says. ``There are so many good people out there willing
to help other people. That's what I'm looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Is money a problem? she is asked.
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance troubles?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Is her employer being uncooperative? Are the doctors giving her
the runaround? Has the hospital treated her badly? Does her son
need an organ do nor?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all the support I need from my work and my family,''
Mary says. ``The doctors are great. The insurance company has done
its job. It's nothing like that. All I need help with are my pets _
my cats.'' &QL; 
WORLD UPSIDE DOWN
</P>
<P>
   A few months back, Mary's 18-year-old son, Kris Ridlon, came
home com plaining of a backache. He worked at a restaurant and
thought he'd injured him self lifting a box of frozen pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   Many uncomfortable tests later, Mary and her husband, Rick, were
told Kris had a rare form of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our world was turned upside down,'' Mary says. ``Everything,
now, is focused on making Kris well. And for that, we must find
homes for the cats.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, Mary's grandson brought home a stray. Her
daughter is al lergic to cats, though, so Mary took it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how we got Samson,'' she says. Who was followed,
shortly after wards, by Delilah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never my intention to become someone who rescues
strays,'' Mary says. ``But if they come your way, and you be lieve
in preserving life, and you want to put those beliefs into
practice, what do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   You take in Hersey and Harvey. And Leo and Cleo. And Cody and
Jerry and Juliet. And three-legged Mickey.
</P>
<P>
   Until the number of humans living in your house is three, and
the number of cats is 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' Mary says, ``things changed because Kris' immune
system has been depleted by chemotherapy and radiation, making him
at risk for infection. So we've decided to find homes for most of
the cats.'' &QL; 
`EACH ONE IS LOVED'
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't want to take them to a shelter, if she can help it.
Almost all of them have been spayed or neutered, she says. Most
have had their shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one,'' Mary says, ``is loved.''
</P>
<P>
   She's spent the past three weeks at Kris' bedside at Good
Samaritan Regional Medical Center, where he's undergoing treatment.
Because of that, she asks anyone inter ested in adopting one of the
cats to con tact her through the pager she wears at all times. The
number is 613-7562.
</P>
<P>
   What if no one calls? she is asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have faith,'' she says. ``You've got to believe
in people. You've got to cherish life and count on the possi bility
of good things happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Like her cats getting adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Like her son getting well.
</P>
<P>
   Like a guy who wasn't interested in doing another ``sick kid''
story getting snookered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
