</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD WORK IS SECRET TO COLORADO'S SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
DALLAS _ An ugly word applies:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Outworked.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a label that hung from Stars necks last night as Game 1
of the NHL's Western Conference finals took a frantic third-period
tilt toward Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Score tied, game on the line, and the Avalanche shifted into a
forechecking frenzy that caught the Stars with anvils on their
skates and sticks. Or so it looked.
</P>
<P>
   No, Colorado wasn't on repeated power plays. It just seemed that
way.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Belfour survived a couple of rough waves, but finally saw
the puck sweep past him and into the strings. With just under six
minutes remaining, the Avalanche had earned _ emphasize earned'' _
another large playoff road win, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   And with it, goes all the momentum relocation that occurs when
home-ice advantage is lost in the first game of a series. Monday
night's Game 2 at Reunion just became double pressurized for the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Also add an additional worry for the local lads. They were
beaten last night at their own game _ discipline, patience and
forcing turnovers in the other end _ which is what the third-period
goal by Valeri Kamensky was all about. Assists on the game winner
should have gone to all four Colorado lines, and each set of
defensemen. All helped it happen by wearing down the Stars during a
five-minute third-period surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept working at keeping the puck deep on them,'' said
Colorado's Peter Forsberg, who continued his playoff blitz by tying
the game in the second period. ``The little things are going to win
this series,'' he added. ``That means pressure like we had \Rin the
third period\S, plus not turning over the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded like one of Ken Hitchcock's constant sermons. The
first period had gone by Hitchcock's script, as Dallas was the
dominant team and had a 1-0 lead to show for it. The second period
was a repeat of the St. Louis series, with a full-blown controversy
thrown in. But the Avalanche won the 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Dallas appeared to have the jump in the third
period, but...
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the puck was being dumped in on Belfour, and it took
forever to leave the zone. Beginning at the 10-minute mark,
Avalanche sharp-shooters pounded away on three different shifts,
and finally, Kamensky took a belt-high swing at his own rebound
which had bounced in the air off Belfour. This time he didn't miss.
</P>
<P>
   With desperation creeping in, the Stars created that same kind
of forechecking storm in the final five minutes. Patrick Roy,
however, was sensational, and the Colorado road record in the
postseason climbed to a very serious 7-zip.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, this conference finals opener provided outstanding
entertainment, along with the expected Belfour-Roy duel. And to top
off the hockey portion of the evening, the Reunion press box also
had fireworks, centering around a controversial no-goal ruling on a
Kamensky deflection past Belfour in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Play stopped as the Avalanche celebrated on the ice, except the
goal light never came on. (In case anyone asks, the goal judges
were from Phoenix, and obviously the guy on that one end was not
named Roenick.) The referees went upstairs to the replay judge, who
finally ruled ``no goal,'' shocking the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   The puck appeared to graze the post, hit the bumper padding that
sits on the ice inside the goal, and bounce out. For one thing, the
padding had been placed too close to the post, and was cut back
after the second period.
</P>
<P>
   But between periods, Avalanche general manager Pierre Lacroix
tried unsuccessfully to storm the off-limits replay booth, and then
collared the league's supervisor of officials, Wally Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix apparently thought he had discovered another
grassy-knoll conspiracy theory in Dallas. He demanded the right to
speak immediately with NHL commissioner Gary Bettman, and
repeatedly ordered Harris to get Bettman on the phone. ``The
integrity of the game is at stake,'' Lacroix yelled at Harris.
``We've got 15 minutes \Rthe time between periods\S to save the
integrity of the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   As those two exchanged heated words, here came Stars general
manager Bob Gainey, looking like he might want to take Lacroix hard
into the boards. ``Wally, this area is off-limits,'' Gainey told
Harris, harshly.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Gainey wanted Lacroix moved away from the replay
booth _ like right now. And with Gainey in no mood to be debated,
Lacroix meekly moved, although in the end, he got his justice, and
Kamensky got his goal.
</P>
<P>
   The team that worked the hardest in the third period was the
team that won.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
