r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-ROY-TEX     05-23 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-ROY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER ONE LAPSE, ROY PROVIDES STONE WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
DALLAS _ Patrick Roy, the Avalanche's all-world goalie, can stop
shots from all angles and at all speeds when he's between the
pipes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He did it last night, turning aside 30 Stars shots.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to make a save when you stray, and that's how the
Stars scored their only goal.
</P>
<P>
   Roy, who has a tendency to liven up the proceedings by straying
from his crease to play the puck, allowed a goal in the first
period because he wasn't anywhere near the goal.
</P>
<P>
   He went behind it, anticipating that the puck was coming around
the boards, but it never got there. Mike Modano intercepted it, and
with Roy out of position, threw it in front to Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Hull had one of the easiest goals of his career, throwing it
into an empty net from point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad play by me,'' said Roy, who allowed a
first-period goal for the first time since Game 3 of the conference
semifinals against the Detroit Red Wings. ``I had no business being
behind my net. I just wanted to help back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy could chuckle about it after the game because when he stayed
where he was supposed to be, he was his usual brilliant self.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped 17 shots after the first period, including some tough
chances in the final two minutes when the Stars desperately tried
to get the equalizer. Overall, he stopped 30 of 31 shots, his sixth
consecutive game with at least 30 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great,'' Roy said. ``I was moving very well in my
net.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy said he was motivated by the first-period gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really mad at myself, and it gave me a boost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a continuation of his work in the Red Wings series, when
he was a big factor as Colorado came back from a 0-2 deficit to win
four consecutive games. Roy had a .954 save percentage and 1.75
goals-against average in those victories.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a weakness in his game, it was a failure to control
rebounds. Several times he would rush a shot and the puck would
tantalizingly sit in front of his crease, but the Avalanche defense
was able to clear the pucks before the Stars could get to them.
</P>
<P>
   Roy continued to increase his teammates' blood pressure by doing
his imitation of the Avalanche's fancy, puck-handling forwards.
</P>
<P>
   He was trapped behind the net by Pat Verbeek late in the second
period, but the Stars couldn't get a shot off this time, and did it
again in the third period with traffic buzzing around.
</P>
<P>
   Roy said he had to continue to do it because the Stars continued
to play dump and chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're dumping soft, and it's a tough building to play in
because the glass is so soft,'' he said. ``I felt I could help my
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy helped more when he stayed put, and he did that enough to
let his team win.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
