<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS OUTSLUG SLUGGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The folks came to see Mark McGwire put on a home
run show. He did. Big Mac hit two homers, including one out of
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was the main attraction, but the Los Angeles Dodgers'
bats put on quite a display themselves. The Dodgers wracked up 14
hits and beat the St. Louis Cardinals 10-7 in front of a
season-high 54,179 on Saturday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth homered for the first time in more than a
year and Raul Mondesi added to his National League lead with his
16th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   You figure it had to be this type of game since Darren Dreifort
started for the Dodgers. When the right-hander is on the mound runs
are scored. Not necessarily against Dreifort, but rather on his
behalf. He had the eighth-best run-support of any pitcher in the
National League, and nothing happened Saturday to change that.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's first homer was a towering shot to left-center field,
but his two-run blast in the top of the eighth inning to
left-center dwarfed it.
</P>
<P>
   The 484-foot homer off Jamie Arnold cleared the roof of the
bleachers, the third player to accomplish the feat. Willie Stargell
did it twice and Mike Piazza, who did it Sept. 21, 1997, are the
other two. It was McGwire's 12th homer of the season and the 55th
time in his career he's hit two in one game.
</P>
<P>
   It brought the Cardinals within 9-7, but Mondesi homered with
one out in the eighth to push the Dodgers lead to 10-7.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (5-2) was neither dazzling nor disastrous, but he did
provide six innings in which he allowed five runs on six hits.
Dreifort walked three and struck out six in tying Kevin Brown for
the team lead in wins.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Jeff Shaw, who blew his last two saves, walked a
tightrope in the ninth. He allowed a two-out single and walked
McGwire to bring Ray Lankford to the plate. Lankford homered in the
ninth to beat the Dodgers on Sunday in St. Louis, but Shaw got his
ninth save when Lankford lined out to first to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored for Dreifort. Each member of the starting
lineup had at least one hit and by scoring nine runs in the first
five innings increased his run-support to nearly one run per inning
he's pitched. The Dodgers have scored 41 runs in the 47 innings
Dreifort has thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Long called a pitcher's park, the first two months of the season
have gone a long way in ruining the reputation of Chavez Ravine.
During the last three seasons there were 1.6 homers hit per game at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the second game of the series with the Cardinals, the
Dodgers and their opponents had hit 67 homers in 22 games, more
than three per game.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire made sure the new-fangled trend continued when he hit a
towering homer to left-center field in the top of the first to put
St. Louis ahead 1-0. It was the first time McGwire homered at
Dodger Stadium, though too much has been made of that. McGwire
missed last year's series in Los Angeles with an injury and was
playing here for the fifth time.
</P>
<P>
   It was McGwire's 11th homer of the season, and it leaves
Cincinnati's Cinergy Field the lone major-league ballpark at which
McGwire hasn't homered.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' lead was short-lived behind the lackluster
pitching of starter and loser Clint Sodowsky (0-1), who allowed the
Dodgers to score five times in the bottom of the inning. The
initial blow came via Hollandsworth, making his first career start
at first base. He hit a two-run homer to right to give the Dodgers
a 2-1 lead, his first homer since May 8, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp Cromer added an infield single with the bases loaded and
Dreifort contributed a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added a run in the second on an RBI single from Dave
Hansen to go ahead 6-1, but St. Louis went back to the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Renteria and McGwire singled to begin the fourth inning
and Lankford doubled in a run. Fernando Tatis, who hit a pair of
grand slams in the same inning during his last visit to Los
Angeles, then smacked his 13th homer of the season. The three-run
shot was his fifth homer of the season against the Dodgers. It
pulled St. Louis within 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi tripled in a run in the fourth and then scored on Todd
Hundley's single to make it 8-5. Devon White scored on a wild pitch
in the fifth inning to give the Dodgers a 9-5 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
