r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-LADN     05-23 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ONE LOSS FROM ELIMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It started, as it always does, with the
little things. A stupid foul here, a rushed shot there, a pass that
should have been made. And it ended, as it usually does, with a
complete meltdown _ the result of too many mistakes strung together
at exactly the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the Los Angeles Lakers frittered away Game 3 of the
conference semifinals Saturday, allowing the San Antonio Spurs to
take a 103-91 victory at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the Lakers, all talent and bravado but still short
on wisdom, find themselves down 0-3 in a series for the second
straight postseason.
</P>
<P>
   No one had to remind them that no team in NBA history has come
back from such a deficit. They know all too well because they have
lived the statistic.
</P>
<P>
   And somehow haven't learned from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have played with our lives on the line,'' Rick Fox
said, ``and I don't think we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Lakers played like the team that squandered leads
in Games 1 and 2 at the Alamodome. Same inconsistency, same lapses,
same results.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio's Tim Duncan went unchecked for 37 points. Jaren
Jackson scored a career playoff-high 22 off the bench. And yet the
Lakers still had a one-point lead with less than two minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
   But a 91-90 lead became a four-point deficit when the Spurs
scored five straight. Then the panicky Lakers abandoned their
offense in a rush to get it all back at once _ and instead got
nothing. San Antonio scored the last 13 points of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said it never should have come to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being at home doesn't guarantee you a win,'' he said. ``They
came in obviously up 2-0, loose, free, confident. And we came out
and didn't match that and played as if we were up 2-0....
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you let it come to a situation where they have a
chance to win that game at the end.... I think we all in this
locker room make enough money to go down fighting. You don't wait
to Game 4 to go down fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the second straight May, that's what it's come down to
for the Lakers. Only this time, they didn't wait for the conference
finals to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, they simply enticed and teased, showing signs of
their immense talent before conceding to the opponent's superior
poise and intellect.
</P>
<P>
   A Kobe Bryant 3-pointer staked the Lakers to an 81-77 lead with
6:52 to go, on a play that showed them at their best. Glen Rice
drove baseline, then kicked the ball out to Robert Horry, who swung
it to Bryant for the open shot.
</P>
<P>
   But Horry's flagrant foul on David Robinson let the Spurs come
back and tie the game at 81-81, and the Lakers began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   They took their last lead at 91-90, on an Horry 3-pointer with
1:55 remaining. They never scored again. A slow defensive rotation
let Jackson hit a 3-pointer, Avery Johnson followed with a 19-foot
jumper, and with 1:10 left, down 95-91, the Lakers lost their poise
for good.
</P>
<P>
   A Rice 3-point try bounced over the backboard with less than a
minute to go, but the Lakers had one last chance to recover. It
ended when Bryant drove too hard toward the baseline, trying to
turn the corner on Jackson, and instead lost his balance and the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of beating ourselves,'' said O'Neal, who scored
22 points but was upset after getting just two shots in the fourth.
``We always talk about it, but we've gotta get the ball in the
hands of the right people, and we've gotta take smart shots, and
we're just not doing it. I'm very frustrated. It's a shame that
we're down 0-3 in this series. It's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again the Lakers played several stretches at their highest
level. Rice, Bryant and O'Neal all scored 20 points or more, and
Derek Fisher steadily guided the offense with 9 assists and 13
points. But the offensive precision was lost in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``On several occasions, for periods of the game, we did some
things very nicely out there,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``But
turnovers once again killed us. Some quick shots hurt us throughout
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A near-empty locker room said more than any Laker could, and
most chose to say nothing at all. The talkative Fisher pushed
silently by reporters. J.R. Reid and Robert Horry left quickly. Fox
had to be enticed to come back to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Those who spoke tried desperately not to concede the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of fight left in us,'' Rice vowed. A comeback
from 0-3? ``It seems impossible, but it's not. We've got all the
motivation in the world. We lose, it's gonna be a long summer.
Teams don't like being swept, and that's another reason we
definitely should be motivated to put something together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
