r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-23 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY COACH, IT'S NOT OUR FAULT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Finally, a Los Angeles Lakers coach has
identified the problem, the reason the team is failing yet again to
meet expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Us guys. The writers. The Media.
</P>
<P>
   How did he find out?
</P>
<P>
   It's true, before the season, the newspaper guys held a
writers-only meeting. The topic: new ways to make the Lakers
miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about if we don't allow them to grow?'' somebody said, six
beers into the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worked before,'' somebody else said through a mouthful of
pretzel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's resolve: Warning signs of growth are to be shared with
the group so that said growth may be headed off,'' suggested a man
in a plaid jacket, banging a hotel-logo ballpoint pen on the table
like a gavel. ``Everybody in?''
</P>
<P>
   And so the plan was agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   How could we have known it would work so well?
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, still making the mistakes that once threatened to
keep them out of the NBA playoffs entirely, are a game from being
swept from the postseason a round earlier than last year after
their 103-91 loss to the San Antonio Spurs on Saturday at the
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, his interim head-coaching job looking more ``interim''
by the day, didn't wait for the game to be played before pleading
for leniency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys have to understand,'' he said during a pregame news
conference, responding to a writer's question about Glen Rice and
ball movement. ``It's a very hard point to get across to you guys
that the development process of a team does not happen overnight.
Without practice time, it's hard to make sure that everybody ... is
best utilized in the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar theme: The Lakers' starting lineup has played only 17
games together. Glen Rice and J.R. Reid joined the team in
mid-March. The compressed schedule allowed less practice time....
</P>
<P>
   Rambis used the tight-knit Indiana Pacers as examples of how
you'd like it to work. When Mark Jackson drives the lane, he can
flip a blind pass to Reggie Miller because he knows where Reggie
will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team hasn't developed into that yet. We will at some point
in time,'' Rambis said. ``But because we are in such a tremendous
media spotlight, you guys are not allowing us to grow and develop,
you're assuming that all of this stuff (just happens)....''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis conceded high expectations are ``not necessarily unique''
to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But ``nobody's following the Pistons or the Bulls or the Rockets
while they're growing into champions,'' he said, obviously not
having spent long in Detroit, Chicago and Houston. ``Nobody's
putting pressure on them to do that, or analyzing them and
dissecting all the little things that they (do), because no one's
expecting them to get to that level....
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of pressures and expectations for the
Houston Rockets, too. But they, like us, realize it's not easy to
do those things, to bring in a superstar ballplayer and _ voila _
everything works. It doesn't happen that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this year, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   As for the original question, about Rice's repeated criticism of
the Lakers offense: ``You guys prod him (to complain),'' Rambis
contended. ``You guys !ital!do!off!. It's part of your process that
you guys do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So who prodded Rambis to complain?
</P>
<P>
   Why did he think whining about ``expectations'' would help him
or his team?
</P>
<P>
   Was Rambis trying to whip up an us-against-them mentality for
his players? If so, it isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers guard Derek Harper said after Saturday's defeat the
expectations are ``not necessarily'' unfair: ``There are
expectations for this team because it's a good basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Rambis trying to win sympathy from fans? If so, does he
expect anybody to feel sorry for the franchise with the best
combination of talent (Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant, etc.), brains
(Jerry West) and money (Jerry Buss) in pro basketball?
</P>
<P>
   If high expectations come from anywhere in particular, it's not
the press room. It's the Forum wall that bears the Lakers'
championship banners, and it's the front office that's impatient
for a title after a decade-long drought.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters have gotten used to Rambis' sarcasm. It was refreshing
at first. People want to root for the old Lakers cult hero. Poor
guy, thrown into a situation like this, to deal with Dennis Rodman
and a major trade and a truncated schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, as he grows weary of his role as team spokesman, his
sarcasm sounds bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Writer (recently): ``With the playoffs coming up ... are you
concerned about Shaq's free-throwing?''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis (reading more into the question than was intended): ``OK,
I won't play him anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on that day to complain ``you guys'' are going to overdo
the Shaq's-free-throws angle.
</P>
<P>
   Most head coaches stay on the job for more than 45 games before
souring.
</P>
<P>
   Today is No. 46 for Rambis. That might be all he gets.
</P>
<P>
   Because if this is the way a coach reacts to simple questions
from reporters in the pregame peace and quiet of a locker room,
it's no surprise he can't find the answers in a sideline huddle
with fans screaming and a season at stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
