<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC IS CLEAR: L.A. FAILS IN FINAL MINUTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK 
and STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ As per tradition, dejected Los Angeles
Lakers fans left in droves long before the final buzzer Saturday.
But Magic Johnson stayed in his courtside seat until the bitter
end, then gave his bitter assessment of the Lakers' latest playoff
collapse _ a 103-91 loss to San Antonio that left them down 0-3 in
the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played dumb in the last two minutes of the last two
games. I've never seen us do that before,'' said the leader of the
Lakers' ``Showtime'' era, now a part-owner. ``What happens the last
couple minutes with us? We take an ill-advised 3-pointer, then
mistakes, mistakes, mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing in San Antonio (in Game 2). We gotta get
together. We gotta get together mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear which errant 3-point try Johnson referred to _
Derek Fisher's with 1:30 left or the three 3-point misses by Glen
Rice in the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson was absolutely clear in his feelings about Robert
Horry's costly flagrant foul on David Robinson with 6:30 to go. The
Lakers were up 81-77 when Horry punched Robinson in the chest as
they battled for position. Robinson made both free throws, the
Spurs retained possession, and Robinson dunked to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up, we've got all the momentum going, and what do we do?
A flagrant foul,'' Johnson said. ``Why do we do that? Why? We've
got the game, and then (throw it away). That's a four-point play,
you know what I'm saying?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything, we just compounded. We do something good, we turn
around and do something bad. We do something good, we turn around
and do something bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Johnson turned to get into his limo, but first exchanged
consoling words with a season-ticket holder. ``I know,'' Johnson
told him, ``I'm as sick as you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's bad bounce: For the second straight game Kobe Bryant
had a chance to save the Lakers but faltered. In Game 2 it was two
missed free throws. On Saturday, it was his turnover with 33.2
seconds left, the Lakers down by four.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant tried to drive to the baseline to beat Jaren Jackson but
lost his balance and the ball, effectively killing the Lakers' last
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinking too far ahead, that's all,'' he said. ``When I drive,
I can kind of visualize a picture of what's gonna happen before it
happens.... Sometimes you kind of run ahead of yourself....
Sometimes when that happens, you lose the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's miscue wasn't the only one, just the last in a series
for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of inexperience and not executing our
sets,'' he said. ``That goes back to the start of the season,
working at execution and being efficient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
