<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7785 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-23 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BOUND TO BE OUT AT THIS RATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The good news is there's a remedy for what
ails the Los Angeles Lakers. The bad news is there's no way the
players can complete an Outward Bound course before today's
must-win game against the San Antonio Spurs in their best-of-seven
Western Conference semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Damn, those NBA schedule-makers. You can bet they'll be
Shaquille O'Neal's next target, once he tires of whining about the
officiating and his lack of touches in crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Shaq: Your teammates will give you the ball in the final
moments of a close game as soon as they can trust you at the
free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   At this point they'd sooner hop in a raft in O'Neal and roar
down a raging rapid than look to him to bail them out at the foul
line.
</P>
<P>
   There's no getting around the trust issue. It's like the
elephant on the court that everyone pretends not to see.
</P>
<P>
   Trust, not the Spurs' terrific tag-team of David Robinson and
Tim Duncan, was the difference Saturday in Game 3 of the
best-of-seven series. San Antonio had it, the Lakers did not, and
that basically tells the story of the Spurs' 103-91 win in front of
a Forum sellout crowd of 17,505.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again in the fourth quarter the Spurs showed complete
faith in the perimeter shooting of Avery Johnson and Jaren Jackson,
never mind that they had combined for five points in the first
half. Pressed into prominence because of the Lakers' doubling and
tripling of Duncan (his 24 points in the opening 24 minutes got
their attention), Jackson contributed 13 points in the final 12
minutes. Johnson added six more to underscore the glaring
difference between the No. 1-seeded Spurs and the fourth-seeded
Lakers:
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have complete confidence in one another while every
Laker has utter confidence in himself.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder the Lakers look like a band of mercenaries
fighting an efficient army? Glen Rice and J.R. Reid, two-fifths of
the Lakers' starting lineup, joined the team in mid-March. That was
time enough for a little over two dozen games and oh, about a week
of productive practices thanks to the shortened season's
spandex-tight schedule.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Duncan's two years on the Spurs qualify him as an
old-timer. If he seems mature beyond his 23 years, perhaps it's
because he arrived in San Antonio via Wake Forest, where he stayed
long enough to earn a psychology degree.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' youngest starter, 20-year-old Kobe Bryant, would be
a junior in college if he hadn't decided to go straight from high
school to the NBA. Bryant is like the math genius who can't balance
his checkbook; he has the ability to make the ridiculously
difficult play look effortless and yet the simple concepts trip him
up.
</P>
<P>
   Little things such as passing the ball when you're triple-teamed
instead of taking the shot. Bryant was guilty of that late in the
third quarter, with the Lakers leading 56-54, and the Spurs got the
ball and a piece of the lead when the Spurs' Jackson drained one of
his jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of playing within yourself. Bryant
committed three of his four turnovers in the fourth quarter. Twice
in the final six minutes he tried to turn a simple play into a
spectacular one. Both times a basket would have brought the Lakers
to within two of the Spurs. Both times he turned the ball over and
the Spurs padded their lead at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   The last of Bryant's turnovers was a comeback killer as the
Lakers were down to their final 32.8 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking too far ahead,'' Bryant said of his turnovers.
``My mind was ahead of my body.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's problem has always been the opposite. His basketball
mind has yet to catch up to his body. Try as he might, he can't see
that sometimes the Lakers would be better off if he'd take pride in
something other than scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Oh what it were if coach Kurt Rambis had been the one to say,
``He understands you make double teams pay by involving your
teammates and he's willing to do that. That helps a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, that was Spurs coach Gregg Popovich talking about Duncan,
who finished with four assists on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And O'Neal? He has two assists in the three games.
</P>
<P>
   Say this about O'Neal; his free-throw shooting showed some
improvement. After making 20 percent of his foul shots in Game 2,
he converted 57 percent on Saturday. Only three of O'Neal's seven
foul shots in the fourth quarter fell. That's why as long as the
Spurs have a player with a foul to give in crunch time, O'Neal, his
wondrous size notwithstanding, is a liability.
</P>
<P>
   Take away their obvious go-to guy and the Lakers look lost.
Indeed, you'd have to go to a comedy club to find more
improvisation than the Lakers provided in the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In one particularly ugly sequence, Rice reached in on Duncan _ a
really silly foul _ and atoned for it by making a bad pass at the
other end. He also missed a couple of shots in the final minute (he
was 2 for 8 in the quarter) and was victimized on defense a couple
of times by Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry passed up shots he made without thinking during his
championship run with Houston in 1994 and 1995. He made the only
shot he took in the final 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And Bryant was 2 for 4 with those three turnovers. Veteran point
guard Derek Harper, who sat the entire fourth quarter, said,
``We're so talented, we sometimes try to do things that are
difficult instead of keeping it simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Lakers don't need to spend four days roughing it in
the Rocky Mountains to learn the finer points of teamwork and group
decision-making. Maybe their Outward Bound experience is taking
place right here, right now, with the Spurs serving as the
instructors.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they make a few forward strides today, the Lakers have
wandered so deep into the wilderness you have to wonder how long
it's going to take them to find their way to daylight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
