<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAUSE HITS BULL'S-EYE IN LOTTERY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECAUCUS, N.J. _ Flash! The Chicago Bulls have won the 1999 NBA
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   A breathless NBA awaits their move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the slightest idea what Jerry Krause is going to
do,'' says Vancouver coach Brian Hill, whose team will be picking
directly behind the Bulls at the June 30 draft. ``It might be some
guy from Bolivia, for all I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the man known as The Sleuth did employ a Hungarian (Kornel
David) this year, and no one has ever done that before. Surely a
Bolivian or a Mongolian or a guy from Sierra Leone is a possibility
when the ever-secretive Krause is involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Sleuth likes to maintain a dignified public posture, but he
couldn't suppress his glee when NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik
opened the No. 2 envelope Saturday and pulled out a Vancouver
Grizzlies logo. The rotund GM pumped his fists a few times and
bounded out of his chair. It wasn't quite the Roberto Benigni-like
display put on by Philadelphia owner Pat Croce three years ago, but
for The Sleuth it was pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had also won the lottery during a TV rehearsal
conducted about 45 minutes prior to the lottery. `` `Doggone it,' I
was saying,'' beamed Krause. ``I didn't want to win the
rehearsal.''
</P>
<P>
   They're now sitting at No. 1, but a strong case can be made that
the Bulls were only the second biggest winners at the 15th annual
lottery. That honor could easily be given to Charlotte, which
entered the proceedings 13th, and last, with a laughable 0.5
percent chance of winning the lottery, and wound up third.
</P>
<P>
   It's been quite a run for Charlotte coach Paul Silas. He gets a
job for a handsome salary. He finishes third in the lottery when he
could easily have finished 13th. And now if he could only get some
dumb sucker to take Derrick Coleman off his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five chances in a thousand,'' said Silas. ``I thought there
was no way we'd ever wind up in the top three.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did anyone else. And it is enough to make people in the East
very nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Charlotte was a playoff team that didn't make the
playoffs,'' observed Boston general manager Chris Wallace, who was
quite content to finish eighth and then hand it over to Cleveland
as part of the Vitaly Potapenko deal. ``Look at the way they came
on down the stretch. They really responded to Silas. They might be
able to go for a need.''
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver ought to know the drill by now. Since 1996 the
Grizzlies have drafted third (Shareef Abdur-Rahim), fourth (Antonio
Daniels), second (Mike Bibby) and, now, second again. They could
write the lottery manual. Anyway, they have had two hits and a miss
in that time, with Daniels being a major flopperoo.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so let's assume Chicago chooses not to risk an international
incident by raiding the Bolivian League. What is out there for
them?
</P>
<P>
   If you follow the college game, you already know the answer.
Lamar Odom. Steve Francis. Elton Brand. Richard Hamilton. Wally
Szczerbiak. Baron Davis. Excited yet?
</P>
<P>
   Neither is anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, the versatile 6-foot-10-inch kid who hung out in Kingston,
Rhode Island, for a year and change, is the consensus top pick. He
has legitimate guard skills, but he is not yet ready to be a lead
guard in the pros. He needs to firm up his outside shot. He needs
to become more assertive. He has amazing skill and he has a good
heart. But he needs time to develop. In a better world, he'd be
spending at least one more year in college.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, we don't live in that world. We live in a very messy
athletic world. The only one of the above six who is truly ready
for the NBA is Szczerbiak, who, naturally, is the only senior in
the bunch. You can make a passable case for Hamilton's readiness.
The rest are all-too-typical of the unfinished products who are
infesting the world's greatest basketball league.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing we do know is where the ball is now. It's
in Chicago, and it will be Jerry Krause's serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen all the obvious people,'' he said. ``But I haven't
met any of them. We've seen them play. Now comes the hard part.''
</P>
<P>
   Krause is a huge believer in personal contact. Starting Monday,
the Bulls will be bringing in waves of players, owing in large
measure to the fact that in addition to now owning the top pick the
Bulls also have the 32d.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to look a player in the eye,'' said Krause.
``And it's really important for us to work players out because he
must fit into our system. We need intelligent players who are
capable of playing in the triple post. We are committed to the
triple post. And we believe in character people.''
</P>
<P>
   The cynics are already accusing Krause of duplicity. ``You
telling me he doesn't know who he's taking?'' smirked one Windy
City Krause-watcher. ``Look how excited he was.''
</P>
<P>
   I think he was excited because he now has options, and there is
nothing more exciting to a GM in a situation like this than
options. ``A trade?'' smiled Krause. ``Nothing is ever out of the
question. If I've learned one thing in this business, it's that
nothing is ever out of the question. You keep your ears open and
you listen. You never close your eyes and your ears.''
</P>
<P>
   That goes for all you other NBA teams. If you hear about some
little round guy booking a Chicago-to-La Paz flight, you might want
to tag along. The Sleuth might know something you don't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
