<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7788 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-B     05-23 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS VALENTIN'S DAY 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As long as there is a Fenway Park, there will be the
``green light.'' Hitters love to be at the plate with a 3-and-0
count. Fans anticipate something spectacular, and often they are
right.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened Saturday when Red Sox third baseman John
Valentin stroked a grand slam in the third inning to spark Boston
to a 6-4 victory over the Toronto Blue Jays. Valentin got the green
light from manager Jimy Williams and never gave it a second
thought. The pitch by righthander Chris Carpenter was in his zone
and his bat did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy has the confidence in me to have me swing on a 3-and-0
count,'' said Valentin, whose bat has come to life in May. ``He
gives it to me a high percentage of the time, both last year and
this year. I'm glad he has that confidence in me. It's just a
matter of being aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the pitcher didn't want to go to 3-and-0 on me. He
wanted me to swing at a bad pitch. But in that situation, I was
able to be a combination of things. Patient and aggressive. It all
comes out a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are on quite a roll. They won two of three from the
Yankees, and thus far in this series twice have fallen behind the
Blue Jays but rallied to win.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is 4-1 on the current homestand and 14-8 for the season
at Fenway. Saturday's victory was its 13th in the last 16 games.
Over that same period, the club has rapped out 10 hits or more 14
times.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin's home run was one of his four hits. That's the same
number as rookie Trot Nixon had, a career best. And let's not
forget that knuckleballer Tim Wakefield had lost four of six starts
before pitching 8 1/3 strong innings to claim the victory Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have good hitters,'' said Williams. ``Guys who make
contact and put good swings on the ball. We've been patient, too.
We've gotten key walks in situations that have helped us. We've
gotten good starting pitching. It all goes back to them, because
they set the tone. Coming out of the bullpen we've pitched good
when we had to. Today, we just played a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield gave up an unearned run in the first inning and it was
anybody's guess as to how he would react. He bore down, using his
fastball and curveball to supplement the floater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mental approach is to keep battling,'' said Wakefield.
``(You say), `I've given up one run and that's all they're going to
get.' It worked out that way today. I was able to throw my
knuckleball with more confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have that kind of attitude, it's easier to throw mostly
curveballs and fastballs and try to get ahead in the count.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Darren Lewis reached on an error, and singles by
Nixon and Jose Offerman loaded the bases. Valentin teed off on
Carpenter to send the crowd of 32,088 into a frenzy. Boston scored
an insurance run with two out on a double by Troy O'Leary and a
single by Mike Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Nixon picked up his fourth hit and scored the
sixth Boston run. Toronto scored three in the ninth before Tom
Gordon earned his sixth save by getting Mark Dalesandro to fly out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it all came back to that green light. The great hitters
in Fenway history never have been afraid to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing for a long time,'' said Valentin. ``I know
what pitch I like and what is my strength. I'd probably swing every
time. I'm not saying I'm going to hit a home run every time. But I
know if it's there I'm going to hit it hard someplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is team that works hard on hitting. If guys like myself
are struggling, you've got find out what's wrong. You've got to be
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you also remember it's a long year and you really can't
get too high or too low.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
