<SLUG> BC-BKN-IVERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVERSON MORE THAN QUICK STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The coach was full of answers and quips. A crowd
had gathered where he was standing Saturday, near the quiet arena's
baseline. There were questions from a group of reporters and
subsequent responses from coach Larry Bird. But there was only one
question he couldn't answer. It was regarding The Answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sure goes baseline a lot,'' someone said to Bird, referring
to Allen ``The Answer'' Iverson. Bird shrugged. Yes, he is the
coach of the Pacers, but there is nothing he or anyone else can do
about the 76ers' Iverson dribbling the basketball, twirling the
basketball, and then blurring your vision of the basketball before
deciding to take it and himself along the lines and to the hoop.
You know it's going to happen a few times a night. Bird knows it.
Iverson knows it. It's still tough to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so quick,'' marveled Bird. ``You know, it's a lot harder
to defend him when he's not handling the ball than it is when he
has it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how most people now talk about the NBA's skinniest and
shortest (6 feet) shooting guard. There is less of a focus on his
cornrowed mane and more on his rapidly developing game. Bird and
his coaching staff have thought a lot about the unpredictable guard
during the past week. They know that one man can help extend this
best-of-seven Eastern Conference semifinal series _ which the
Pacers lead, three games to none _ beyond Sunday's Game 4. It is
Iverson, who is averaging nearly 30 points per game against the
Pacers. Forget his hairstyle; they want to know how to stop this
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do,'' Bird said. ``You really want to get him
underneath the basket. You can sorta tell whether he wants to shoot
or if he's looking for somebody. When he's not looking to shoot,
you can really clamp down on him under the hoop and make him throw
a pass out over the defense. But he's so quick . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's speed is not new. He was quick at Georgetown. He was
quick at his Virginia high school, where he also quarterbacked the
football team. He was quick during his first year in the NBA, 1996,
when the Sixers told the world that they were going to rebuild
around him. The difference now is that people are talking about
what Iverson does on the court rather than what he does off it.
Bird recently commented about Iverson's unselfishness. You didn't
hear comments like that before this season.
</P>
<P>
   But those around Iverson will tell you that a lot of what you
hear, read or, in some cases, think, is inaccurate. Local fans
still can't believe that one of his best friends is Bruce Hornsby.
He has begun to change his dressing style, becoming less of a jeans
man and more of a two-piece suit type. The hair? It is often
braided into neat strips atop his head. But sometimes he'll unbraid
it and display a 1970s-style, classic ABA afro.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Saturday. He is generally receptive to
speaking with the media. But he noticed a headline in a local
paper. His picture was next to the screaming headline, which read,
``Near Death Experience.'' What a switch. The day before, a
headline read, ``Go Sixers.'' Iverson didn't like that. His
teammate, Eric Snow, noticed that it bothered him. So Snow teased a
little. He spotted a writer from that paper and said to Iverson,
``You know he writes the headlines, right?''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't true. But Iverson didn't feel like talking. He left
the practice site without talking to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not doing everything perfect. But where he's come from
and the respect that he's shown is impressive,'' Sixers coach Larry
Brown said. ``I like the things he says. You know, a lot of times
kids can say all the right things _ because Allen is bright as hell
_ and I don't get caught up in it. But some of the things he says
mean a lot to me. Like, he said, `I'm not anything special for
Indiana; they played against Michael (Jordan).' And I think that's
a great way for the kid to show respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes on time now. He's dressing the right way. He's
starting to do all the things that you hope a young kid does when
he grows up and begins to understand. I've got one big guy on my
team, he'll tell you anything he thinks you want to hear. He has
his own agenda. But there is nothing phony about Allen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixers owner Pat Croce found that out in '96, when he first met
Iverson at an Embassy Suites near the Philadelphia airport. Croce
wanted to interview Iverson. They talked about Iverson's youth,
when he was jailed for allegedly inciting a riot. L. Douglas
Wilder, the former Virginia governor, eventually cleared Iverson's
name. What matters to Brown is that his team finds a way to play
better defense Sunday. It needs to rebound better, too. Matt Geiger
didn't grab a single rebound in 27 minutes Friday night. That has
to change. But if it doesn't, at least Brown has learned about his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always look around and see how guys in this league handle
losing,'' Brown said. ``I've learned a lot about some of the guys
on the Celtics. I mean, their talent is just incredible. But they
have five guys who want to score and we have one (Iverson).''
</P>
<P>
   That one man will have to perform like he hasn't before to keep
the 76ers from joining the Celtics and other teams who are now
watching the playoffs. Croce has a cross-country biking trip
planned for June.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll postpone my trip if we make it to the Finals,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers aren't that talented yet. If they happen to make it
that far, the man wearing jersey No. 3 will have to take them
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
