<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA FOUND IT TOUGH DRIVING CARR 
</HEADLINE>
 LA HOYA-CARR-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oba Carr predicted he would be buoyed by God's hand
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night and for 10 rounds it appeared he was because
something had to be holding him up the way he was getting hit by
Oscar De La Hoya. Unfortunately, no one told God this was a
12-round fight.
</P>
<P>
   After getting up off the floor in the first round and being
rocked a half-dozen times by similar left hooks as the fight
progressed, a weary Carr came out for the 11th round and had one
more big left hook slam into his face. This time God's hand was
gone and Carr soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   Carr spun halfway around as he rocked backward, collapsing on
his face before De La Hoya could get close enough to land another
blow. As it turned out, none were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Although Carr got up at the count of five, he was a man adrift,
staggering sideways and then back as referee Richard Steele closely
watched. De La Hoya charged forward but Steele pushed him back to
the neutral corner. What Steele saw on Carr's face was the
expression of a game man saying ``Enough'' without moving his lips.
</P>
<P>
   Steele waved his hands, ending the bout 55 seconds into the 11th
round, giving De La Hoya his 31st win without a loss and Carr his
third unhappy ending to a world title quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, I got tired at the end,'' Carr (48-3-1) said.
``I really should have been quicker. Oscar was very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Carr's weariness was probably the all-too-often
presence of De La Hoya's left hook. That hook, plus a stinging jab,
rocked Carr midway through the first round before finally dropping
him.
</P>
<P>
   Carr remained upright until the end but the damage he accepted
was considerable, a testament to his gameness but also his lack of
speed when compared to De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can take a punch,'' De La Hoya (31-0, 25 KO's) said. ``He
was rough and ready. But I put the pressure on.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya later claimed that pressure came despite what he
described cryptically as ``a personal problem'' that arose after
the second round. No one was sure what he was talking about but
Tony Daly, the Los Angeles Lakers' team physician, was dispatched
to De La Hoya's locker room after the fight, causing speculation he
might have injured his left hand, which remained gloved even after
the right glove was removed.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, it didn't stop him from consistently rocking
Carr, although Carr would have enough moments of his own to keep
the crowd of 11,528 at the Mandalay Bay Events Center screaming
much of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Carr's God barely had time to react before the fighter hit the
floor the first time, the victim of a big left hook with just over
90 seconds to go in the first round. Over the next four rounds,
Carr became well acquainted with that left, twice being rocked by a
left jab, and when it turned into a hook, it quite often left him
reeling.
</P>
<P>
   Carr kept his feet thereafter, but also kept getting hit far too
often for anyone whose intention was to win a portion of the
welterweight title. Carr occasionally landed some stiff lead right
hands of his own, and, from time to time, landed some with his
head.
</P>
<P>
   In Round 7, Carr slammed the side of his head into De La Hoya's
exposed left cheek, splitting it open. Steele immediately deducted
a point from Carr, whom he already warned about such un-Christian
behavior. Before the round was done, he had deducted a second point
for a low blow, which he also had been warned about.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as one-sided as the fight was, it was far more entertaining
than De La Hoya's battle with highly-regarded Ike Quartey in his
last outing because both De La Hoya and Carr were more often on the
offensive and intent on doing damage to each other.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, God knows Oscar De La Hoya did more of that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Mayweather craves exposure but he got more of it than he
anticipated Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The World Boxing Council super featherweight champion was
expecting a short night against challenger Justin Juuko, who was a
last-minute replacement for Goyo Vargas (flu), but Juuko refused to
cooperate. Or at least his chin did.
</P>
<P>
   Juuko absorbed some powerful right hands from the young champion
early in the fight and by Rounds 7 and 8 began to land some of his
own, several of which seemed to catch Mayweather's attention.
Although Mayweather wasn't hurt, his ego was by the ninth round,
when Juuko came out quickly and landed a flurry of punches that had
the crowd roaring.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for him, it also caught Mayweather's attention and
within seconds he nailed Juuko with an overhand right that stunned
the challenger. Juuko reeled backward and Mayweather stalked him,
landing a second, crisper right to the ear that sent Juuko to the
floor. Referee Mitch Halpern counted him out at 1:20 of the round.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad fight to
hit a snag. Less than 48 hours after promoters Bob Arum and Don
King reached an agreement that would put the two welterweight
champions in the ring at Mandalay Bay Resort Sept. 18, Trinidad's
lawyer declared the $11 million offer was ``unacceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
