</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LAST INDY GO-ROUND, LUYENDYK CAPTURES POLE 
</HEADLINE>
 500-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ One last time, Arie Luyendyk carefully rolled his
sleek Indy car out of the pits at Indianapolis Motor Speedway. He
was given a rousing ovation Saturday as he set out on his four-lap,
10-mile, qualifying attempt for his 15th and final Indianapolis
500.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the pits, 2 minutes 25.179 seconds later,
the Dashing Dutchman was greeted with a conquering hero's welcome.
Luyendyk completed his qualifying tour of the fabled Brickyard in
an average of 225.179 miles per hour, good enough to win the pole
for the 83d Indianapolis 500 a week from Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Normally a calm, cool, and collected customer, Luyendyk admitted
to ``being a little nervous,'' just before his run because he knew
``I was going to have to drive the car on the limit and that's not
a comfortable place to be,'' referring to the windy and cool
conditions that played havoc with qualifying. So, after holding the
throttle of his G-Force Aurora wide open for four laps, including a
blistering 225.643 m.p.h. on his second go-round, Luyendyk returned
to the pits, where he allowed the adulation to wash over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy Pole Day,'' said Luyendyk, a two-time Indy 500
winner and three-time pole-sitter. ``Everyone is really tense,
there's a lot of electricity in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't until he heard the cheers and saw the
enthusiastic thumbs-up from his competitors up and down pit row
that it really hit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think the thing that struck me the most was that I
didn't wake up this morning saying this is going to be my last
qualifying day or my last this or that,'' said Luyendyk. ``When I
completed the run, I was really moved by the enthusiastic crowd all
around the racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when a record 33 drivers qualified _ the first time the
field has been filled on the first day _ Luyendyk took center
stage, stealing the spotlight from Team Menard driver Greg Ray, who
was a heavy favorite to win the pole. Ray, however, wound up
qualifying second with a four-lap average of 225.073 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk withstood one last challenge from Robby Gordon with a
half-hour remaining before the track's closing. The CART driver,
behind the wheel of Ray's backup car that posted a hot lap of
227.192 during practice Thursday, qualified in 223.066.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk will be joined on the front row by Ray and Billy Boat,
last year's pole-sitter who rebounded from a crash on his initial
qualifying attempt to make the field with a four-lap run of 223.469
in his backup car.
</P>
<P>
   Ray seemed poised to wrest the pole away from Luyendyk when he
came smoking out of the barrel with a first lap of 225.643, which
was as fast as Luyendyk's second qualifying lap. Ray slowed a tick,
dropping off the pace for the pole when his speed dipped to 224.439
on his final lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very, very close,'' said Ray, who had hoped to deliver
the pole as a birthday gift to his 6-year-old son, Winston. ``I
drove all four laps exactly the same. We were close. My crew chief
(Thomas Knapp) said on the last lap, `We need a little more here,'
and I said, `That's all there is.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Eddie Cheever Jr. was the first to make a
qualifying attempt and appeared to make the field solidly when he
took the checkered flag on a four-lap run of 221.438. However,
Cheever's crew inexplicably waved off the run, nullifying the
results. Cheever waved off a second attempt, before he finally
qualified in his third and final try in his primary car in 221.314,
good for a spot in the middle of Row 5.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart, who was on the tightest of schedules Saturday, was
the first to make the field when he qualified in 220.653. Stewart
then made a mad dash to the airport, where he took a private jet
belonging to his NASCAR Winston Cup owner, Joe Gibbs, to Charlotte,
N.C., where he competed in the Winston Open qualifying race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to go quicker, obviously,'' said Stewart, whose
plans seemed to be jeopardized by a one-hour rain delay, ``but we
were flat-out the whole way around. That's all the car had today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
