<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-OSCAR-LADN     05-23 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OSCAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WALKOVER FOR DE LA HOYA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ This wasn't the statement Oscar De La Hoya wanted to
make.
</P>
<P>
   He did one thing he said he'd do against Oba Carr on Saturday at
the Mandalay Bay Events Center. He fought aggressively, although he
did it more in spurts than on a consistent basis.
</P>
<P>
   However, he ran into two significant problems: 1) An injured
left hand in the second round that he said hindered him the rest of
the fight and, 2) a game Carr.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger, not the pushover many believed he'd be, not only
stood up to De La Hoya's best advances for most of the fight, he
did some damage himself until the champion finally put him down and
hurt him with a single left hook in the 11th round.
</P>
<P>
   Carr wobbled to his feet but referee Richard Steele had seen
enough. He stopped it at 55 seconds and no one complained.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which allowed De La Hoya to keep his WBC
welterweight championship, sets up a bout against Felix Trinidad
here on Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Or does it?
</P>
<P>
   There are two !ital!more!off! problems: The injured hand _
possibly a sprain, according to De La Hoya's doctor, Tony Daly _
and the fact Trinidad's handlers said Saturday that the deal hasn't
been finalized, which leave the long-awaited matchup in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the second, I couldn't do the things I wanted to do,''
said De La Hoya, who wouldn't reveal the injury in interviews
immediately after the fight. ``It's kind of personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``... If the personal problem hadn't occurred, he would've been
out (earlier).''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya (31-0 with 25 knockouts) almost ended the fight in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   He stormed out of his corner and, about halfway through the
fight, landed a straight left and follow-up short left that sent
Carr (48-3-1, 28 KOs) to one knee. The challenger from Detroit
survived the round but seemed vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   However, De La Hoya couldn't follow up. He told Daly he hurt the
hand throwing a jab early in the next round and he delivered few
punches the rest of the three-minute period. That allowed Carr to
regain his senses and build some confidence.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was a fight.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, who had said he planned to revert to the
knockout-minded fighter he was immediately after the 1992 Olympics,
engaged Carr in repeated toe-to-toe exchanges but hardly
overpowered him between the first and final knockdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Neither fighter landed a significant number of pain-inducing
punches during the flurries and neither was seriously hurt.
According to computer statistics, they landed a comparable number
of power punches _ 137 for the champion, 108 for Carr.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, De La Hoya won the fight by outboxing Carr.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, a very good boxer, landed a miserable 49 of 442 jabs and
only 157 of 759 total punches thrown, an indication that the
champion was at his elusive best. De La Hoya landed 103 of 249 jabs
even though that punch caused him the greatest pain after the
injury and connected on 240 of 518 total punches.
</P>
<P>
   After the fight, Carr was asked to compare Trinidad, who knocked
him out in eight rounds in 1994, with De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``De La Hoya is more evasive,'' said Carr, who wouldn't predict
a winner. Later he added: ``And Oscar can take a better punch.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya was well ahead on points after the 10th round.
</P>
<P>
   The judges had it 96-91, 95-92 and 97-90 while the Daily News
scored it 97-90 in favor of De La Hoya. The scoring was lopsided
partly because of two points taken from Carr for butting and low
blows in the seventh round.
</P>
<P>
   However, to his delight, De la Hoya didn't leave anything to
chance. The end came when Carr attempted to throw a left and De La
Hoya instantly responded with his best punch _ the left hook _
hitting Carr flush on his cheek and sending him face first to the
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   He got up immediately but couldn't go on. As Steele waved him
off, De La Hoya raised his fists in the air and then climbed onto
the shoulders of his trainer, Robert Alcazar, and strutted around
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the ring announcer proclaimed him the winner,
De La Hoya let out a cry of ``WHOOO! WHOOO!''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, he was overjoyed that he was able to do what he'd set
out to do _ knock out Carr _ in spite of the injury.
</P>
<P>
   And, even though the Trinidad bout _ which would be the biggest
in his career _ could be in jeopardy, he couldn't resist striking
the first blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna get you,'' he said, referring to Trinidad. ``He
finally signed. We're gonna do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be the fight of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya missed the postfight news conference to have X-rays
taken on his injured hand.
</P>
<P>
   In another championship bout, Floyd Mayweather knocked out
Justin Juuko to retain his WBC super featherweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Mayweather (21-0, 16 KOs) dominated the fight because of his
exceptional skill and quickness but had trouble. He didn't hurt
Juuko (33-3-1, 25 KOs) until he put him down and out with a
straight right at 1:20 of the ninth round.
</P>
<P>
   Juuko was a last-minute replacement for Goyo Vargas, who said he
pulled out the fight because he is ill.
</P>
<P>
   After the bout, Mayweather's grandmother, Bernice Mayweather,
collapsed in the ring as her family celebrated the victory. After a
few minutes, she walked out of the ring and appeared to be OK.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a scheduled eight-round heavyweight bout, unbeaten Lamon
Brewster (21-0, 19 KOs) of Los Angeles stopped Mario Cawley (21-3,
16 KOs) at 1:20 of the second round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
