<HEADLINE>
GEORGE IN LOSING BATTLE FIGHTING MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ As much as Tony George has made the motorsports
media out to be the Phantom Menace, we do not represent any Evil
Empire. What we really represent _ and this is what George, the
misguided president of Indianapolis Motor Speedway and founder of
the Indy Racing League, has trouble grasping _ is a necessary evil.
</P>
<P>
   So, Tony, you're just going to have to deal with us.
</P>
<P>
   George came to that realization Thursday when he backed off his
ill-conceived decision to revoke the credential ``privileges'' of
Sports Illustrated writer Ed Hinton for the Indy 500. After the
Chicago Tribune pulled its writer, and several other papers,
including the Globe, contemplated following suit, George came to
his senses and realized that he was in jeopardy of making the
Greatest Spectacle in Racing into merely a spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   At an impromptu press conference in the Speedway's media center
Thursday, George said, ``The decision to not extend the privilege
of credentials to Ed Hinton at Indianapolis Motor Speedway was
based on a feeling that he's dangerous to himself and to the sport
that he's assigned to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   You're wrong, Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Hinton is not the menace to motorsports. He's just the
messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you are the one who's dangerous to yourself and the
sport we are assigned to cover.
</P>
<P>
   There have been suspicions that George was behaving in an
irrational manner since he founded the IRL, an all-oval, open-wheel
series aimed at competing against the Championship Auto Racing
Teams circuit. Why would he ruin a good thing like the Indianapolis
500 by tinkering with its time-honored traditions? He put Indy at
risk by taking all of his cars and his track and forming his own
series because the guys at CART refused to play ball with him.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicions were confirmed this past week. The man is
vengeful and carries grudges, so don't hold your breath waiting for
a reconciliation in the lingering feud between CART and IRL that
has done irreparable harm to open-wheel racing.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to revoke Hinton's credential, which George made
against the counsel of his own publicity people, seemed largely the
result of a personal vendetta. George was put off by Hinton's
critical story on the IRL following the death of three spectators
at the VisionAire 500 May 1 at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Charlotte,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``His comments in a recent article following a tragedy in
Charlotte where he seems to pontificate and be knowledgeable on
design engineering and construction again proves that he really
doesn't have much of a feel for the sport and is trying to make a
name for himself,'' George said, taking a swipe at Hinton before
reluctantly reinstating his credential. ``I felt it was extremely
in poor taste for Sports Illustrated to run his article with the AP
photograph, which I understand was available to others, and just
shows me that whoever's in charge of publishing that magazine
doesn't use very good judgment in how they place their ads. They
are insensitive and are treating motorsports tabloidal.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, that may be the case. You may take umbrage at that, too, but
that's their prerogative, Tony. You cannot dictate who can and
cannot be assigned to cover your race. It smacks of censorship.
</P>
<P>
   The ad that George was upset about was a Valvoline layout that
depicted five men working underneath the hood of a car with the
caption: ``You're born. You die. In between you work on cars. We
should all be so lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The gall they had to apologize to the advertisers for running
it next to the article, but not to the families of the victims, was
just beyond me,'' George said. ``It just shows a lack of
responsibility and poor judgment, and that's what I question.''
</P>
<P>
   You have that right, Tony. It's your track. It's your property.
And if, as you say, ``a credential isn't a constitutional right,
it's a privilege,'' then you have every right to hold the Greatest
Spectacle in Racing in a media vacuum. That's your ``privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   George claimed, ``It's my job to move the sport forward and not
be a party to its demise,'' but he very nearly was a party to its
demise himself by alienating the national media. And that would
have been a grave mistake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR driver Tony Stewart had his hands full this weekend,
shuttling between Indianapolis and Charlotte to qualify for both
the Indy 500 and Coca-Cola 600. Stewart made matters difficult for
himself Thursday at Indy when he slammed the wall between Turns 3
and 4 while practicing in his primary car. ``I'm just disgusted
with myself for making a stupid mistake as a driver and creating a
lot of extra work for my team that didn't deserve to have to work
this hard,'' Stewart said. `They've done everything perfect up to
this point.'' . . . McCormack Motorsports announced a week ago that
it had signed Jimmy Kite to pilot its No. 30 TransWorld
Racing/G-Force Oldsmobile for the Indy 500. Kite, 23, who was 11th
in last year's Indy 500, fills the vacancy left by the departure of
veteran Raul Boesel. He will be paired with Indy 500 rookie Nick
Firestone, the 33-year-old great-grandson of tire pioneer Harvey S.
Firestone. ``We are excited about it,'' said team owner Dennis
McCormack. ``Things happen for a reason, and everyone here at the
shop is really excited about having Jimmy on the team.'' McCormack
was not worried about a lack of preparation time before the time
trials. ``It is one of the reasons that we picked Jimmy,'' he said.
``He is a veteran here and ran very competitive times here last
year. Jimmy is the right person for the job.'' . . . FedEx-CART
rookie driver Juan Montoya continues to burn up the circuit,
winning his third race in a row in last Saturday's Rio 200.
Montoya, who previously won back-to-back races at Long Beach and
Nazareth, will go for four in a row in the Motorola 300 at Gateway
International Raceway next Saturday . . . For the record, Hinton
was greeted with lusty boos from his peers when he arrived in the
press room Friday morning at Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
