<HEADLINE>
CELTICS LACK LUCK, LIKELY TO LOSE PICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECAUCUS, N.J. _ No miracles for the Celtics. And no regrets,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vitaly Potapenko is, in essence, our No. 1 pick this year,''
declared Celtics general manager Chris Wallace, whose team wound up
in the eighth spot in Saturday's NBA draft lottery. That pick
likely will be scooped up by the Cleveland Cavaliers as part of the
trade that brought the 6-foot-10-inch, 250-pound center to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Celtics' will hold the 37th pick, the eighth
selection of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would make that trade again and again,'' insisted Wallace.
``We needed a center. There are no franchise-type centers in this
year's draft, or in the next couple of drafts. Unless someone is
coming out of the foreign ranks, I don't know where the next Tim
Duncan or Shaquille O'Neal is coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   The first pick went to the Chicago Bulls, who, with a 13-37
record, had gone into the lottery with a 15.7 percent chance of
winning. Vancouver was second and the Charlotte Hornets, with a
microscopic .5 percent chance of winning, came up a surprising
third.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics had a 3.7 percent chance of winning the lottery.
Toward that end, Wallace toted along such good luck charms as a
lock of hair from his young son Truman's latest haircut; a Notre
Dame ID card, courtesy of (Rick's son) Michael Pitino; a
15-year-old Celtics business card from trainer Ed Lacerte; a Red
Auerbach suit jacket worn by Celtics aide Jeff Noyes (``not
cleaned, so as to retain all the luck,'' said Wallace); and a
leprechaun figurine.
</P>
<P>
   It worked _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, they moved down from 7 to 8,'' reasoned Wallace. ``That
alone makes it a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace also pointed out fans had somewhat of a misconception
about what the Celtics were risking by tacking their 1999
first-round pick to Andrew DeClercq when they traded for Potapenko.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were protected against Nos. 1, 2, and 3 from the trade,''
he said. ``But we were also protected on 4, 5, and 6 by league
rules. So the risk was even better than people thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The simple truth is that this is regarded as a woefully thin
draft that couldn't begin to address the Celtics' needs, even at 1,
2, and 3. They would rather have Potapenko.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are much more comfortable with him than trying to be lucky
with the eighth pick,'' Wallace said. ``He's now played 200 NBA
games. He's been in the playoffs. We start off next year with a
center who does not have to be introduced to the NBA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
