u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXINGNOTEBOOK-BO     05-23 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS SPITES HAND THAT COULD FEED HIM 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The face of jealousy is never a pretty thing, even
if it's worn by a pretty face.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vargas is a good-looking fighter and a good-looking
kid, perhaps the best of the young 154-pound champions now ruling
the junior middleweight division. He wears the International Boxing
Federation belt despite having fought professionally only 16 times,
having defeated a tough Mexican warrior named Yory Boy Campas to
claim it, and is now preparing to defend it this summer against a
former champion on the downside, Raul Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing in front of Vargas but blue skies because he
fights in a division with few challengers but also a former Olympic
teammate named David Reid with whom he could earn some money one
day if he plays his cards right. Reid holds the World Boxing
Association title despite having only 12 professional fights
himself and is the only gold-medal winner from the 1996 US team in
Atlanta, so there is a natural rivalry that any promoter worth his
salt easily could exploit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Vargas has seemed an unhappy young man since the day in
Atlanta when he failed to do what Oscar De La Hoya had done four
years before him. De La Hoya became boxing's Golden Boy when he
seized his moment in Barcelona and won the gold medal, and he has
made millions off that experience.
</P>
<P>
   It transformed De La Hoya from a barrio kid in East Los Angeles
into a Hollywood star and he has become a boxing phenomenon: a
cover boy, a teen idol, a company pitchman, a money machine in
short pants.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, De La Hoya already has won four world titles in four
weight classes and earned some of the biggest purses in boxing
history for a nonheavyweight. As he said this past week, ``I feel
I'm carrying boxing on my shoulders. It is a burden, but I enjoy
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Vargas doesn't enjoy watching it.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his Olympic days, Vargas has taunted and criticized
De La Hoya, his Southern California rival, claiming De La Hoya lost
his roots after he got rich. He has claimed time and again that he
wanted nothing more than to get in the ring with De La Hoya and
show who the better fighter is, insisting that the true Mexican
boxing fan had no use for De La Hoya despite his apparent
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas continued his verbal assaults last week, telling writers
around the country that De La Hoya was ducking him. How a 147-pound
champion can be ducking a 154-pound champion is beyond me,
especially when the 147-pound champion is in no hurry to move up
now that he stands to make $16 million-$20 million for a Sept. 18
fight with Felix Trinidad in a unification fight for the
welterweight title.
</P>
<P>
   While De La Hoya fights for millions in one of the sport's most
glamorous divisions, young Vargas fights for peanuts in a division
cobbled together by boxing's three crime families as a way to
extract more sanction fees from more fighters who can't or won't
make either 147 or 160. That Vargas is jealous of all De La Hoya
has, which includes millions in endorsement contracts and millions
more in a long-term deal with HBO, has been obvious for a long
time. What is sad to see is his effort to turn it into a publicity
campaign that is absurd on its face.
</P>
<P>
   One of Vargas's three managers, Rolando Arellano, was amusing
when he pointed out the depth of the rivalry by announcing that
Vargas was about to sign an endorsement deal with Miller Lite, a
rival of one of De La Hoya's longtime sponsors, Budweiser. But when
the two droned on at length about how De La Hoya had ``been running
his mouth'' while he was ``avoiding'' Vargas, their position became
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas is the one who chose to fight at 154 rather than 147,
which has been De La Hoya's weight class for some time. It is
Vargas who needs De La Hoya a lot more than De La Hoya needs him,
which, at this point is not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Arellano says, ``We think he's scared to fight Fernando.
That's why his PR people keep telling him to say he won't fight us.
He shouldn't go after weaker champions. He should go to the one who
will give him the trouble and prove his point.''
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Rolando: He did. He went to Trinidad, who is considered by
many fight fans to be De La Hoya's welterweight equal. He did that
after he first went to Pernell Whitaker and then Ike Quartey. Your
man, on the other hand, went to Raul Marquez, who's a nice kid with
slow hands and a mug that's starting to get dented from taking too
many punches.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya tired of his young critic and said last week, ``I'll
never give Vargas an opportunity. He has no respect. He's very
disrespectful. He does not deserve an opportunity. I respect most
fighters but I don't respect him. I'll lose a fortune before I'd
fight him. I see David Reid in my future, not Vargas.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly that galled Vargas, because even in his impetuous youth
he understands that De La Hoya calls the shots on such matters. Yet
the fact is he got what he's been asking for. He has been taunting
De La Hoya since he was a teenager and now he needs him to make a
payday. What he doesn't seem to understand is that when you're
begging someone for a favor _ and a job _ it's not wise to insult
him in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the two will fight in a year or two, but only if Vargas
forces the issue with his hands and not his mouth. If he wants a
shot at De La Hoya, he needs to worry about his own business, which
should be lining up all the 154-pound champions and beating them so
that when De La Hoya does move up in weight, there is no place to
go but to him.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Vargas will remain to De La Hoya like a gnat at a
picnic, a buzzing nuisance to be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rumor around Vegas all week was that wily old trainer Gil
Clancy would work his final fight with De La Hoya Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
But De La Hoya told HBO on camera Friday night in a prefight taping
that Clancy will remain with him even after he begins a promised
housecleaning of his organization. De La Hoya had been talking
recently about changing much of his operation once Saturday's fight
with Oba Carr was over and he was critical last week of the parade
of trainers he'd added and subtracted in the past few years. He
will, for example, no longer serve as a co-promoter with Bob Arum
for future fights, something he had insisted on earlier in the
year. He also told a Los Angeles Daily News reporter that Clancy
was out, saying, ``This is his last fight. Like I said, it's gonna
be me, (head trainer) Robert (Alcazar), and (cutman) Chuck (Bodek).
Robert's my trainer and that's it. Gil is a excellent motivator.
He's a person with a lot of knowledge in boxing. It's nothing
against him. That's just the team I want.'' If true, that's news to
Clancy and would run counter to what De La Hoya told HBO's Larry
Merchant Friday night. As for Clancy, he said Saturday, ``I'm on a
fight-by-fight (basis) with Oscar, so he can make a change whenever
he wants, but he hasn't said anything to me. I don't know how these
things get started.'' In this case, apparently by his boss . . .
Word is Tony Ayala may return to the ring July 31 in San Antonio on
the undercard of World Boxing Council super bantamweight champion
Erik Morales's next title defense if details can be ironed out with
Morales's promoter, Arum. It appears that San Antonio promoter
Lester Bedford has signed Ayala to a three-fight deal worth
$600,000 with an option for three more fights. However, Arum said
Friday, ``We've got no deal with them. We might do the show in
Tijuana, and what does Ayala mean there? What does he mean on
pay-per-view? The guy hasn't fought in 17 years! Those people
(Ayala's handlers) are crazy. If Ayala means anything, it's in San
Antonio (his hometown), but we don't know if that's where we're
going.'' Ayala was one of the hottest fighters in the country in
1982 before he was convicted of a violent rape for which he served
the past 17 years in a New Jersey prison. During his incarceration,
Ayala underwent intense psychotherapy and claims to have become a
new man. He served nearly half his term as a prison counselor and
had an exemplary record . . . Roberto Duran recently went to Brazil
to fight for $100,000. He was paid $20,000 up front but the check
for the $80,000 balance he collected after the fight allegedly
bounced. Now Duran wants to sue. He's got a better chance of
beating Roy Jones than beating the Brazilian promoter in a
Brazilian court . . . Lou Duva sent a strongly worded letter to IBF
president Bob Lee asking why North American Boxing Federation
welterweight champion Vernon Forrest (28-0, 22 KOs) wasn't
considered to replace Vincent Pettay next Saturday night against
Trinidad (Pettway pulled out with a detached retina). Duva argued
that Forrest had faced much better opposition than either Hugo
Pineda or Raul Frank, the two welterweights ranked above him by the
IBF, and has been around since the 1992 Olympics. Pineda got the
shot anyway, in part because he is promoted by Cedric Kushner, who
has done several last-minute favors for HBO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
