</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTON WILL BE SPENDING IDOL TIME AT FLEETCENTER 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ No one had to ask Bill Walton more than once if he
might be interested in attending this week's Bill Russell tribute.
That'd be like asking Dennis Rodman if he wanted an extra ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Russell is my absolute favorite,'' Walton said. ``He was
my idol growing up, my hero, my role model. I absolutely love that
guy. I'm so happy that they're having another day for him. But as
far as I'm concerned, every day is Bill Russell Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton's first television memories of the NBA, formed while
growing up in San Diego, are of watching the Celtics and Russell.
He saw what a difference one man could make by being the consummate
team player, by focusing on the little things, and by starting the
fast break.
</P>
<P>
   He considers Russell to be the best player in the history of
basketball. He patterned his athletic life after Russell's book,
``Go Up For Glory.'' He liked the fact that Russell's only valued
statistic was number of championships won, that Russell considered
defense to be the most important part of the game, and that Russell
competed so fiercely.
</P>
<P>
   When Walton enrolled at UCLA, the number he wanted _ 33, which
he had worn in high school _ was unavailable because his West Coast
idol, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, had worn it. So he chose 32.
</P>
<P>
   When he got to Boston in 1985, Walton wanted the No. 32 he had
worn at UCLA and with the Portland Trail Blazers. Unfortunately,
Kevin McHale had the number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have played Kevin for it, because I would have had it
then and there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he chose No. 5, one less than the No. 6 that was worn by
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose that number for Bill Russell,'' said Walton. ``I knew
No. 6 wasn't available. As far as I'm concerned, No. 6 should be
retired on a league-wide basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton is elated to have been chosen to play a part in
Wednesday's gala at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be such a special event,'' he said. ``The way
Bill Russell played, and the way he lived his life, to me are one
and the same. He's a model for a whole generation that followed him
and tried to compete against him, and it all culminated with Larry
and Magic. Then it became a game of stats and numbers for players
on losing teams, and that whole focus has been lost. That's why
he's so special.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you think ousted Knicks GM Ernie Grunfeld is enjoying his
former team's romp through the playoffs? He must be saying, ``Where
have you guys been all season?'' Grunfeld, of course, tried to
reshape the Knicks into a younger, more athletic team. It looked
like a sound strategy. But when the team was struggling, Latrell
Sprewell was moaning about roles, and the players were lamenting
the losses of Charles Oakley and John Starks, the Knicks jettisoned
Grunfeld. But as the playoffs proceed, they continue to amaze. This
is a team that was a hideous 8-17 on the road this season. They are
4-1 on the road in the playoffs. Sprewell lit up the Hawks for 31
points in both games in Atlanta. What's really come across is
Sprewell's incredible quickness as well as his stamina. The guy
doesn't get tired. If he's making his outside shot, he's almost
unstoppable. Meanwhile, the NBA Players Association this past week
(in between Games 1 and 2 of the series) filed a grievance
regarding the ridiculous $25,000 fine the Knicks levied against
Sprewell for statements made by the player's agent. The union is
hoping to resolve this with Madison Square Garden president Dave
Checketts, but if it can't, it'll go through the grievance
procedure . . . USA Basketball will announce the final three
players this week (probably Wednesday) for its team competing in
the July zone qualifier in San Juan. Nine NBA players already are
on board. The other three will be ex-collegians; look for Elton
Brand, Wally Szczerbiak, and Richard Hamilton to make the cut. The
NBA contingent is guard-heavy. The US needs to finish first or
second in the tournament to qualify for the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney. The team will meet early in July in Florida for a week's
worth of training camp. Houston's Rudy Tomjanovich is still the
head coach (and will be in Sydney, as well). Lenny Currier, of
Newburyport and the 76ers, is the team's trainer . . . As if things
aren't tough enough for Denver nowadays (its first-round pick is
owned by Toronto), Nuggets fans are being reminded at this time of
year of what they had and what they don't have. Just tune into any
playoff series. In the East, there's Dikembe Mutombo and Jalen Rose
playing, with LaPhonso Ellis sitting and watching. Out West, they
can see Avery Johnson, who was cut on Christmas Eve in 1990.
Meanwhile, the status of head coach Mike D'Antoni, who has a
three-year deal, is still up in the air with new ownership on hand.
D'Antoni, GM Dan Issel, and owner Bill Laurie were to meet last
week but put everything on hold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was great to see America's Team, the Sacramento Kings, extend
Utah. Had Vlade Divac made one simple rotation on the
pick-and-roll, John Stockton never would have gotten off his
game-winning shot in Game 4. And there wasn't enough time to make a
pass. Also, what in the world was coach Rick Adelman thinking in
Game 5 by leaving so many key guys on the bench for so long while
leaving the defensively challenged Peja Stojakovic on the floor?
And while we're on the subject, where was Lenny Wilkens's mind when
he allowed the Knicks to simply walk the ball up the floor in the
final two minutes of Game 2 with Atlanta trailing by 6? Couldn't he
at least have tried a trap or press to induce a turnover or two? .
. . Things are souring again between Penny Hardaway and the Magic.
Penny took more than a few potshots at the organization the day
after Orlando was eliminated by the 76ers. Where once he said he
owed it to his teammates to stick around, Hardaway is now saying he
might play elsewhere. He sounded a lot like Shaq when he talked
about having to bear all the pressure _ the big fish/little pond
syndrome. The comments didn't sit well with Magic owner Rich DeVos.
In an interview with the Orlando Sentinel's Tim Povtak, DeVos said
Hardaway's comments ``were not appropriate'' and that if Hardaway
wants to play elsewhere, ``We'll help him to do that.'' DeVos also
said he's getting a little tired of the same old rant. ``It just
seems like we can't please him. I don't even know who he's mad at.
I used to think he was just a young kid trying to grow up. But this
has gone on for quite a while now.'' Hardaway can exercise an
``out'' clause in his contract and become a free agent. If he does,
Orlando would be eligible to re-sign him for $85 million over seven
years. (He has three years and $26.7 million left on his existing
deal.) Orlando had the third-highest payroll in the league at $43
million this season and, according to DeVos, will lose money for
the second year in a row . . . Then there's the Golden State
Warriors. They've announced they won't raise ticket prices, and
this came after they made the second-biggest improvement in the
league (after Toronto) and increased their attendance. ``We're
going in the right direction,'' said GM Garry St. Jean. ``We've got
more assets than we did at this time last year. But we still need a
couple stars. We've got solid guys. We need stars.'' Toward that
end, don't be surprised if the Warriors make a serious run at the
disgruntled Gary Payton, an Oakland native (Skyline High School,
where he was a teammate of Greg Foster). Golden State dearly wants
a point guard, and Payton would be perfect because he is also
undeniably a star. Whether Seattle would give him up for anything
the Warriors have is another matter entirely . . . Dino Radja came
up big for Panathinaikos in the Greek playoffs, leading his team to
a victory in the deciding fifth game over Olympiakos. Radja had 12
points and 13 rebounds. He averaged 17.6 points and 10.8 rebounds
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the Nets apparently offering everything but a rest stop on
the New Jersey Turnpike to Phil Jackson, does that mean the rumors
about Jim Calhoun can stop? Then again, maybe Calhoun would take
the job just to be able _ again _ to do what John Calipari
couldn't. But Jackson seems like the logical choice given his ties
to the general area and the lefty leanings of the owners. If he
does say no, there's no reason not to give Don Casey the reins . .
. The Celtics had hoped to have Ben Pepper, their second-round pick
in 1997, available for some summer league fun, but the Aussie had
ankle surgery and the team isn't sure he will recover in time. For
the first time in (non-lockout) years, there won't be the
conventional four-day free agent/rookie camp at Brandeis (or
anywhere else, for that matter). With two summer leagues on the
agenda (Los Angeles and Boston), the Celtics will likely have a
couple of practice sessions before each venture. There is no need
to bring in a lot of players. They already have 11 NBA players
under contract for next season, 12 if you include Pervis Ellison.
They also have to decide on Bruce Bowen, who is still likely to
draw interest from Miami and maybe a couple of other teams . . .
Speaking of the Heat, Pat Riley told Miami reporters after their
crushing Game 5 loss to the Knicks that he won't panic and back up
the truck after ``one bounce of the ball.'' He added, ``Heads are
not rolling, unless it's mine.'' Hmmm. But with the way Jamal
Mashburn disappeared in the Knicks series, you have to think Riles
will at least explore trade options with the Celtics for Rick
Pitino's all-time favorite player . . . Dale Davis spent much of
last summer and fall working with a free throw teacher, and it paid
off. Now his agent, Steve Kauffman, is doing the same thing for
client Ben Wallace, a poor man's Davis. Everyone loves Wallace
except for the fact that he is an utter liability at the line. If
he can improve that part of his game, he could be a very valuable
commodity next summer as a free agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
