<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTOM LINE ON BRUINS: BOSTON GOT MONEY'S WORHT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Not to be accused of being the CEO of Blue Skies Inc.,
but I don't think I was alone in feeling impressed by what the
Bruins did this season. No one around here really felt they were a
Cup contender _ did they? _ and, for a budget operation, they truly
got a lot of bang for their buck.
</P>
<P>
   It may be difficult to reckon with the Vault's prices and think
of the on-ice product as a budget operation. For some, it's as rank
as thinking of the Celtics as an expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But profit first, last, and foremost is the stated mandate of
both the owner and the Bruins' management team. That's nothing new.
In fact, it has been that way for more than 20 years. If you're
just getting to that now, then wake up and smell the $150,000
luxury boxes. And let's not forget, there are a lot of ol' time
Yankees here in the Hub of the Universe, just now switching to
their spring Harris Tweeds, who count Jeremy Jacobs as a soulmate
and dream of hooking up with him in an Internet chat session.
</P>
<P>
   Can't you imagine it?
</P>
<P>
   CHAD09: Hey, Jerry, how's biz?
</P>
<P>
   JJ$$: Can't talk now, time is money, you know. Uh, that'll be 55
cents.
</P>
<P>
   It's a business. So what. Can't we all get over it?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the budget ballyhoo gets all the louder when salaries
are spiraling, ticket prices follow in lockstep, and the local NHL
entry won't go out and pay for a bona fide competitor. It's true
what Harry Sinden says, that spending won't guarantee a winner. But
the unspoken truth that we never hear around here is that not
spending provides a 99.99 percent guarantee that a team won't be
able to marshal a true Cup run.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here then, folks, is a novelty item, a niche
franchise. The Bruins are fun to watch and they began to blossom
this year with a touch of personality _ a gregarious, talented
goalie in Byron Dafoe, a possible star in the making in Joe
Thornton, and Anson Carter, who keeps getting better, has an
infectious enthusiasm for his work, and is winning over an audience
that isn't, shall we say, accustomed to seeing a black kid do
things with a flourish in a hockey uniform. On top of all that, if
you haven't long appreciated Ray Bourque's work, then I imagine
you're not reading this anyway.
</P>
<P>
   When we heard the trash-talking, cash-talking Sinden again
Tuesday night, moments after his team got dumped from the playoffs,
it sadly took some of the luster off a decent season. He drove a
stake through Dmitri Khristich and Jason Allison, which for the
night made the veteran president/GM a .500 hitter. Rolling those
two names off the tongue is like ordering corned-beef hash and
filet mignon from the same menu. Bringing up player performance and
linking it to player payroll has become a very, very tired act.
</P>
<P>
   Can't all of us _ management, players, fans, and media _ just
get beyond the money around here? Everyone _ and I mean everyone _
knows that player salaries are ridiculous in every sport. If I'm
right, every NBA player works under a six-year, $72 million deal.
I'm just so numb to it all now. What they make is what they make.
My feeling is, good luck to 'em, and now let's watch the game. As
fans _ and for the most part media _ isn't that where we all
entered the equation in the first place? It was meant to be fun, an
escape, not an hour-by-hour assault of our economic sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden should know better by now. His soliloquies immediately
following his club's playoff elimination games have become
legendary. Beat writers from around North America leave their homes
in the middle of the night, like old-country vets attending to
horses in foal, and rush to their offices to read Sinden's comments
on the AP wire when his Bruins get bounced. They fantasize over
where to place the exclamation points, which expletives to delete.
</P>
<P>
   But, clearly, it's counterproductive, on so many levels, and it
was especially so this time. If this had been, say, the great,
prolific '71 Bruins team that folded shop, a championship team
snuffed out by Ken Dryden's glove and stick and blocker, then OK,
let 'em have it. But no one in their right minds saw the 1998-99
Bruins as being anything close to championship fodder. Sinden was
kicking his own dead horse.
</P>
<P>
   It is what it is, and it will remain what it will remain: just
another NHL club, a for-profit business that can provide some
decent entertainment and maybe win a round or two.
</P>
<P>
   If you're OK with that, then please shut up and enjoy the game,
no matter where you fit in the
owner-management-fan-player-agent-media equation. If you're not,
then I suggest you leave, while the gettin's still good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An update on Shayne Stevenson, the former Bruin first-round pick
(No. 17 in '89) who ran afoul of the law in early March when he and
a teammate hijacked a cab _ the driver was off-duty, eating at the
Waffle House _ in an early-morning attempt to drive back to their
hotel in Bossier City, La.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stevenson, reached at home in Aurora, Ontario, the
entire affair was a prank gone wrong. Leaving the Waffle House
early one morning with his teammate on the San Angelo (Texas)
Outlaws, Kevin McKinnon, Stevenson said the two were prepared to
walk back to their hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were drinking,'' said Stevenson. ``We were both juiced.''
</P>
<P>
   When McKinnon spotted the keys in the cab's ignition, Stevenson
said he dared his pal to get in and drive them home. They were on
their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us probably 45 seconds to get out of the parking lot,
because we couldn't find the main entrance,'' said the 28-year-old
Stevenson, who hasn't missed playing a season _ be it in North
America or Europe _ since last playing in the NHL for Tampa in
1992-93. ``We could see the driver looking at us through the Waffle
House window, and he was with some cops. No one seemed to care. He
knew where we were going, because we asked him to take us to the
hotel, but he said he was off-duty. We figured the cops probably
would give him a ride later to the hotel and he'd just get his cab
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, Stevenson said, he was on the taxi's CB, talking
to the dispatcher (could Jack Nicholson play this part or what?),
who didn't like what she was hearing. The dispatcher called the
cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw about a dozen cruisers flying down the other side of
the highway,'' recalled Stevenson. ``I remember saying, `I wonder
where they're going?' Then I realized, they were after us.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief visit to the local lock-up, Stevenson eventually
paid a $500 fine and said he has been assured that he won't carry a
permanent record. McKinnon, he said, also paid a $500 fine and got
tagged with a DUI charge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stevenson is back home, planning to get in shape for
another season. He said he earned $1,500 a week with the Outlaws
and finished with 30 goals in 45 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 10 times the player I was than when I was in Boston,''
said Stevenson. ``I just wasn't mature. But, hey, as soon as you're
branded, you're all done. I blew that opportunity, right out the
window. I should be worth millions, but I'm not. But I could make
that Boston team right now, I know I could. But, hey, everyone's
got a story, and that's mine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet one more confirmation that everything in New York is
overpriced and the money is mind-boggling: the deal Brian Leetch is
about to sign _ perhaps as early as Monday _ that will bring him
some $35 million over four years. It makes Leetch the highest-paid
blue liner in NHL history. The truth is, Leetch, scheduled to
become an unrestricted free agent July 1, would have gotten
something close to that in the open market. After losing Mark
Messier (free agent to Vancouver) and Wayne Gretzky (retirement),
the Rangers couldn't have afforded another PR hit, especially after
missing out on the playoffs for two straight seasons . . . Dafoe
doesn't have true free agency as a weapon, but he has an arsenal of
eye-popping statistics, which is why he should reap a hefty award
in arbitration. Remember when we all thought Bill Ranford would
have a slam dunk at the arbitration table in the summer of '96 when
he was on the Boston payroll? Instead, he failed miserably, and
arbitrator Claude Foisy pointed to the goalie's mediocre statistics
in rendering that lowball decision. All signs point to arbitration
now for Dafoe, and the Bruins undoubtedly choosing a one-year
award. Based on his numbers, and comparisons to other netminders
with similar statistics (remember, Foisy emphasized current
numbers, not past performance), Dafoe easily can ask for $4 million
or more a year and expect to get it . . . The Hurricanes are
contemplating retiring the late Steve Chiasson's No. 3 or having a
street named after him next to their new arena (opening in October)
in Raleigh, N.C. Chiasson was very drunk (his blood-alcohol reading
was .27, more than triple the legal limit of .08 in North Carolina)
and was traveling at 74 m.p.h in a 55 m.p.h zone, without a seat
belt, when he smashed his truck . . . What a collapse by the Red
Wings, who folded up like the Dead Wings of old after taking a 2-0
lead over the Avalanche. Among the most troubling signs, looking
ahead: Chris Chelios was a minus-8 for the series. The Wings gave
up two first-rounders to bring in the 37-year-old Chelios and
quickly agreed to extend his existing contract by two years. Not
that Chelios was alone in his futility. Brendan Shanahan, Sergei
Fedorov, and Darren McCarty also went bust . . . The Oilers have
decided they won't offer Joe Hulbig, ex- of St. Sebastian's, a new
deal. The 13th pick in the '92 draft, the 6-foot-3-inch Hulbig is a
decent banger (Edmonton has lots of those) who made less than
$300,000 last season. For that kind of dough, he could be a Boston
pickup, provided the Islanders don't get to him first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't you love the circus in New Jersey? Now Devils owner John
McMullen is joining hands with Cablevision, owner of the Knicks,
Rangers, and Madison Square Garden, in hopes of building a new home
for the hockey team over the rail station in Hoboken. Only four
years ago, McMullen squeezed another $5 million per year out of the
state when he threatened to move the Devils to Nashville. That's no
longer enough, and it's off to Hoboken, where McMullen and friends
want to build a $206 million facility with, oh, $30 million in
state aid (think they'll toss in one of them de-luxe
Foxborough-like off-ramps?) . . . Don't look for Miroslav Satan,
the Sabres' 40-goal scorer, to be in the lineup for the start of
the Buffalo-Toronto series. However, his bruised ankle (compliments
of an Alexei Zhitnik slapper) is improving and he could be back
mid-series . . . Alexei Kovalev may be streaky, but he plays in
pain. Pittsburgh's skilled Russian winger played the last
Penguins-Leafs game with a broken foot and refused to take
pain-killers . . . Look for the Flyers to buy out the last year of
Ron Hextall's deal. He's due just over $1.1 million, and they'll
save one-third of it. Brian Boucher, ex- of Woonsocket and Mount
St. Charles, is the heir apparent as John Vanbiesbrouck's backup .
. . The Penguins might be in the same mood to buy out Tom Barrasso,
in line to earn $2.717 million next season. They'll need some of
that $900,000 savings to pay free agents Martin Straka and Jiri
Slegr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
