<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT LAKE CITY GETS A LITTLE CASH FLOW 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Though the budget trim list keeps growing _ no lunches
for volunteers, fewer free tickets for International Olympic
Committee members, less outdoor seating at venues _ the Salt Lake
organizers are seeing more cash flowing in.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC recently signed three local sponsors (the first since the
December corruption scandal) for more than $25 million, and last
week's mascot unveiling boosted merchandising sales that are
supposed to provide at least $40 million of the $1.4 billion
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake had planned on trotting out its mascot trio _ a
yet-unnamed snowshoe hare, coyote, and black bear _ in February,
but the scandal fallout kept them on the shelf. The trend toward
multiple mascots _ Sydney has a platypus (Syd), an echidna
(Millie), and a kookaburra (Oly) _ is entirely souvenir-driven. Why
sell one pin, one T-shirt, one stuffed animal when you can sell
three?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While SLOC looks to chop costs, its Games keep growing. If the
IOC decides to add men's and women's skeleton sledding, women's
bobsledding, and men's and women's cross-country sprints, the 2002
program will have 75 medal events, nearly a third more than a
decade ago and seven more than 1998. Extra cost: $650,000 . . .
First it was Utah's lenient gun laws that had the Lords of the
Rings arching their brows. Now it's the sticky Mormon-inspired
rules on alcohol. Among the IOC coordination commission's concerns
during last week's visit to Salt Lake was whether media members
will be able to belly up to their customary bar inside the main
press center at the Salt Palace. SLOC promised to ask the state for
an exemption to the liquor laws so the scribes won't have to carry
concealed flasks . . . The International Ice Hockey Federation will
scrap its controversial two-game final for next year's world men's
championships and return to the one-for-the-gold format. Even the
Czechs, who won their second title in four years last weekend,
conceded that the two-game concept (also used for the semifinals)
was goofy. The Czechs had to beat Canada in a shootout after they
split their semis, then took the Finns in overtime after they split
their finals. ``It's a very weird system, but it worked for us,''
shrugged forward Martin Rucinsky. Commendable showing, meanwhile,
by the Americans, who ended up sixth after having to survive a
relegation tournament to stay in the A pool. Former Bruin Ted
Donato led the squad with 8 points in six games . . . No accident
that the International Skating Union assigned Michelle Kwan to the
two Grand Prix events closest to home for next season: Skate
America and Skate Canada. The ISU knows Kwan is entering UCLA in
the fall and figures she'd never skate the Grand Prix if she were
sent to Japan or Russia. Kwan, though, won't make up her mind until
the summer after she has conferred with coach Frank Carroll and
seen her class schedule. Sarah Hughes, the 13-year-old skater who
finished a startling seventh at the world championships, will
compete in Skate America and Trophy Lalique in France. Still stuck
on the junior circuit is 13-year-old Naomi Nari Nam, who was second
to Kwan at the US nationals but couldn't compete at Worlds. ``There
wasn't that much downside this year, but next year worries me much
more because it starts setting up for Olympics and Naomi won't have
any senior exposure,'' says John A.W. Nicks, Nam's coach. ``The
junior and senior levels are judged very differently. You can excel
at the junior level, but you're still not accepted at the senior
level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Splitsville after 14 years (and three world crowns and two
Olympic silvers) for figure skater Elvis Stojko and coach Doug
Leigh. Different directions and all that. Stojko, who broke his
collarbone in a practice tumble while skating backwards earlier
this month, says he'll decide this fall whether to turn pro or stay
eligible for the 2002 Games . . . Back on the sled is three-time
Olympic luger Duncan Kennedy, who retired before the last Games
with brain-stem bleeding that was making him dizzy. Though
neurologists have cleared him to slide again, Kennedy will have to
survive a summer conditioning test and an autumn raceoff to get
back on the US team. Off the sled for good is Somerville's Erin
Warren, who is calling it a career at 27 to finish college at
Northeastern. ``It's time to do other things,'' says Warren, who
competed in two Olympics and was sixth at Nagano. ``I'll be home
for Thanksgiving for the first time in 10 years.'' . . . The first
batch of US oarsfolk for this summer's World Rowing Championships
in Ontario will emerge Sunday and Monday from the sculling trials
in Aiken, S.C. Favored are former world champ Jamie Koven and Julia
Chilicki in the men's and women's single, Lisa Schlenker in the
women's lightweight single, and Steve Tucker-Conal Groom in the
men's lightweight double . . . Slow ticket sales for this summer's
quadrennial Pan American Games in Winnipeg. Barely two months
before the opening ceremonies, only a third of the projected
600,000 tickets have been sold, though 60 percent of Manitobans
told pollsters they'll be attending . . . The US women's water polo
team can earn its Olympic ticket this week by finishing ahead of
the Canadians in the World Cup in Winnipeg. The two top teams from
the Americas and Europe (probably Italy) plus the host Australians
will qualify for the six-team field. The rest will have another
shot next May . . . Amateur boxing's switch to shorter bouts (from
nine minutes to eight) and more rounds (from three to four) will
stand for next year's Olympics. Doctors had pushed for the change,
saying the old format caused boxers to wear down in the final
minute and made them more vulnerable to injury . . . If women's
boxing were added to the Olympic program, the US would win a
fistful of medals. The Americans dominated the first-ever
international tournament in Finland last weekend, winning five of
the nine weight classes plus three other medals . . . Juicy _ and
embarrassing _ reading in those personal dossiers that Australia's
Phil Coles compiled on his IOC colleagues and sent to the Salt Lake
bidders. Venezuela's Flor Isava, confided one note written by
Coles's girlfriend, ``loves men, especially good looking, attentive
ones. They keep her young.'' Isava, who is 78, is steaming and says
she might boycott the Sydney Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 0240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
