r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN     05-23 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG, PURSLEY WINNERS AT IRWINDALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Darren Young and Greg Pursley made their
Irwindale Speedway victories look easy Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Young pulled away from Ron Peterson and Frank Steiner to win the
51-lap Speed Truck Challenge main event and Pursley took advantage
of a broken rear end to win the 50-lap Super Late Model race before
a crowd of 3,666 people.
</P>
<P>
   However, both drivers say Saturday night's victories were
anything but easy.
</P>
<P>
   `The car was a little loose, said Young, from Gilbert, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Young said the spec truck ran fine once he got running, but four
caution flags made the race troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   `Those restarts were hard, he said. `The car ran loose, but once
we got a long run, it ran great. It was hard to hold those other
guys off the first couple of laps after the restarts.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Barron led the first 27 laps in Super Late Model, closely
pursued by Pursley. But Barron dropped a rear end and Pursley
pulled ahead and eventually pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   `It was anything but easy, said Pursley, who was involved in a
first-lap crash last week. `I just had to get back in the car,
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Newhall resident was racing with a sore neck and back after
the wreck took out all but the rear end and sent him to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   `The team worked its rear off to get the car here, he said. `The
car was flawless.
</P>
<P>
   In another main event, Jim Warden of Anaheim won the 40-lap MSRA
Pro-4 race, pulling away from the field to win by half a track
length. The race was marred by a four-car crash on the final lap,
which Warden almost ran into on the victory lap. No one was hurt in
the crash and all four cars left the track under their own power.
</P>
<P>
   In Street Stock, top qualifier Albert Sallie of Tujunga rallied
from last to win the 12-lap main event and Mike Peace of El Cajon
won the 24-lap Allison Legacy main event.
</P>
<P>
   Pole sitter Tony Green of Oak Hills led the Speed Trucks until
Young, Steiner, of Crestline, and Peterson, of San Bernardino,
caught him on the yellows. Young got the lead, but Steiner nearly
got by him on the restarts. Peterson finally got by Steiner with
less than 10 laps to go, but when both drivers thought the race was
over and were pulling off the track, they hit, knocking Peterson
into fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   Barron, from Corona, seemed to have the upper hand in Super Late
Model. Pursley, who won the Southwest Featherlite Irwindale 100
last week before crashing in Super Late Model, finally caught him
on Lap 28. They ran side-by-side for six laps before Pursley took
the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   `Brian Barron ran really good, Pursley said. `He's getting a lot
closer.
</P>
<P>
   Barron said he just wanted to stay close to Pursley after the
rear end went out.
</P>
<P>
   `It ran really good until it started going, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
