<HEADLINE>
WHEELS CONTINUE TO SPIN IN LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The PGA Tour sometimes just doesn't get it. It's one
thing to escalate purses to lofty levels, quite another to
virtually phase out longstanding tournaments such as the one at
Pleasant Valley. Then there is the Tiger Woods/David Duval
made-for-TV extravaganza on a Monday night in Los Angeles in August
that clearly will sabotage the Greater Hartford Open.
</P>
<P>
   Duval had a sponsor's exemption at the GHO before he earned his
Tour card, and Woods had great success playing in junior events
underwritten by tournament sponsor Canon. But instead of playing
there, they will be in a match-play event on the West Coast, with
the winner taking home $1.1 million, the loser $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the Casey Martin case, now on appeal. Last
year, the PGA Tour banned Martin from using a cart during events,
even though he has a rare genetic disorder that affects the
circulation in his right leg. Martin had to go to court to win the
right to use a cart.
</P>
<P>
   He played in the GHO, the US Open, and three other official
events, with $37,221 in official earnings. He's back on the Nike
Tour this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the PGA Tour has appealed the court ruling, making an
appearance in the 9th US Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco
May 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walking rule is a substantial rule, expressly designed to
inject stress and fatigue and impact the outcome of the game,''
argued PGA attorney Andrew Hurwitz in court. ``In an elite athletic
competition, certain rules must apply equally to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a position endorsed by Jack Nicklaus, but following hip
replacement surgery this year, Nicklaus suggested that he might use
a cart on the PGA Senior Tour since it was within the rules.
</P>
<P>
   In the Martin case, the PGA Tour could have just relented, but
instead it has brought a lot of bad publicity on itself.
</P>
<P>
   Now this past week comes news that a federal judge in South
Bend, Ind., has denied a request by Ford Olinger, who has a
degenerative hip disorder, for an injuction against the US Golf
Association that would have allowed him to use a cart in a local
qualifier for the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   Olinger, like Martin, sued under the Americans With Disabilities
Act, but Judge Robert Miller wrote in his ruling that athletic
competition is different from work in a normal place of employment.
Stay tuned. Martin could still be history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recent observations from a springtime spent at Irish golf
courses: The Connemara GC in the village of Ballyconneely, located
in the wild west of County Galway, is about to expand with nine new
holes that will rival any in Ireland. The first two border the
Atlantic Ocean, and the second is a par-3 measuring 240 yards into
the prevailing wind. Plans eventually are to incorporate this nine
with the back nine on the present 18 to create a true championship
course. ``This nine should really put Connemara on the world
stage,'' said John McLaughlin, the club's secretary/manager. ``We
would hope to be available for any of the major tournaments that
come around. We'll be making a big play for them. We're going to
play the three nines, and we would hope to build another nine and
have a 36-hole complex.'' Plans are to make life memberships
available to Americans for 5,000 pounds. ``We hope to go to America
this fall to promote it,'' said McLaughlin. ``It's a pretty good
deal.'' The new nine at Connemara features pot bunkers, fresh water
hazards, and a spectacular ocean view. It has been 17 years in the
making, because original architect Eddie Hackett and successor Tom
Craddock died during construction. The new nine will provide ``18
championship holes we should genuflect to,'' said board member John
McWilliams, who runs the vastly expanded general store in
Ballyconneely . . . Then there is the Old Course at Ballybunion GC,
one of the game's great courses, located at the mouth of the river
Shannon in Kerry. It requested Ryder Cup consideration for 2005,
but money prevailed, and the Ryder Cup went to the K Club west of
Dublin, which isn't even a links course. Ballybunion may be
somewhat isolated, but no place could have been more difficult to
get to than Valderrama in the last Ryder Cup two years ago. ``We
possibly did not have a chance to get it,'' said Ballybunion GC
secretary/manager Jim McKenna. ``It's good for the country, and
that's the good thing about it. The whole country will benefit as a
result. We're pleased for the K Club. It will be a fabulous event,
and it was a great coup to get it.'' Tom Watson has made some
improvements at Ballybunion, and he will be the club captain in the
millennial year. That is a rare tribute, and Watson wasted little
time in accepting the honor when it was extended to him at
Christmas time. Last year, Ballybunion attracted Watson, Woods,
Ernie Els, Mark O'Meara, Payne Stewart, Ben Crenshaw, Andrew Magee,
and Jim Furyk _ on the same day _ as they were en route to the
British Open. . . . West Coast Links has attractive packages to
Connemara, Carne Golf Links, Inniscrone GC, County Sligo GC at
Rosses Point, Murvagh, and Ballyliffin. For information, contact
your golf tour operator or Michael Burke in Oranmore, County
Galway, at 011-353-91-794500 . . . Europeans who are critical of
Boston prices for the Ryder Cup should note that a two-bedroom pad
in Carnoustie for the British Open this July is 3,000 pounds, with
a 500-pound refundable deposit. This is more expensive than a
three-bedroom townhouse was at Valderrama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
