<HEADLINE>
INCENTIVES ARE THERE FOR PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hungry players or angry players?
</P>
<P>
   Either might be a good thing for the Patriots as a prelude to
the 1999 season, a season that is critical to the future of the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Several key players will be entering the final year of their
contracts. Those who excel will earn either an extension on their
careers or a ``dream'' contract.
</P>
<P>
   Some players will be consumed by the pressure of the situation.
And some with no firm future commitment from the team could look at
the situation as hopeless, which could lead to bad feelings.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are counting on players being hungry enough to
perform at high levels _ not only the ones whose contracts are up,
but also the ones such as Willie McGinest, Chris Slade, Ted
Johnson, Terry Glenn, Max Lane, and Vincent Brisby who have a
chance to jump-start their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a good thing,'' said vice president of player
personnel Bobby Grier. ``You could see players playing harder than
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   It could all work out very well, or it could be a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was very frustrating,'' said All-Pro cornerback Ty
Law. ``We had so many guys out that it felt like we were swimming
uphill all year. I wanted so badly to do more than I did. I wish I
could have touched the ball more. The way I was feeling, I wanted
to play every position.''
</P>
<P>
   Law heads the list of players whose contracts are ending. He,
defensive backfield mates Willie Clay, Lawyer Milloy, and Steve
Israel, plus receivers Shawn Jefferson and Troy Brown, linebacker
Tedy Bruschi, defensive lineman Chris Sullivan, and offensive
lineman Heath Irwin, are all entering the final year of their
contracts before unrestricted free agency.
</P>
<P>
   This is a significant group of players, one that could have a
huge say in whether the team goes deep into the playoffs or
continues to languish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we'll be together,'' said Law, who is hoping
to break the bank. ``I'd like to play with these guys in the same
backfield for the rest of my career. But I know that's not
realistic in today's NFL. I'm sure some of us will be back and some
won't. Or maybe they'll clear everyone out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little tough not knowing what the future is going to
be, but if this is our last dance together, we might as well go out
and win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to be a great defense because we've been
together a few years now,'' he said. ``We're used to the system,
and now we can build on that. We have good players on this team.
There's no reason we can't be one of the best. Sure, all of us are
a little uneasy about the future. We all want to continue playing.
All of us would like to stay in one place and not have to move from
team to team. Hopefully things will work out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt Law will be the top priority. At some point,
the Patriots will clear out the roster to pay him, and that could
mean sacrificing Clay and Israel. Milloy is probably the second
priority, and the Patriots have options, such as making him the
franchise player to take him off the free agent market. Many
believe that signing both players to long-term deals is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson would like to remain a Patriot, and because of his
durability and help with the younger receivers, he deserves the
right to a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is another underappreciated player. Oddly, the Patriots
reworked Brisby's deal even though he has missed a lot of playing
time the past three years, but they haven't rewarded Brown for his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bruschi, who has been used as a nickel-type linebacker, will
compete with rookie Andy Katzenmoyer for a starting job. His energy
on the field is important, but this will be the season in which
Bruschi proves that he's either an every-down player deserving of a
big contract or expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Israel added stability to the secondary once he finally got
healthy. Now his time is almost up.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, the Patriots have paid out big money to
McGinest, Slade, Johnson, Bruce Armstrong, Todd Rucci, and Max Lane
and gotten little in return, mostly because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Those commitments have made the Patriots salary-cap poor. It is
a predicament in which many teams find themselves. With the $17.6
billion television deal came outstretched hands from All-Pro type
players who are absorbing huge percentages of salary caps, leaving
little room for the average to above-average veterans who in past
years served as important backups or spot starters. Now those spots
are being taken up by younger players.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots have failed in one area this offseason, it is in
getting more experience. Grier asserted after the season that they
needed more veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet first-round draft pick Damien Woody will replace five-year
man Dave Wohlabaugh at center, and Katzenmoyer may well replace
six-year veteran Todd Collins. The Patriots have added veteran
Lamont Warren to the running back corps, and before all is said and
done, they will also add Terry Allen or Harold Green to that mix
and hope to get a veteran for a defensive line that is getting
younger and younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a chance to acquire veteran players at certain
positions,'' said Grier. ``There's always the chance you can get a
veteran who sacrifices a bit of salary and says, `I'll play for you
for a year on an incentive-type contract.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But a steady veteran such as Zefross Moss will likely be the
player who is dumped to make room for Allen.
</P>
<P>
   On draft day, the Patriots had a chance to trade for one of the
best backs in the NFL _ Jamal Anderson, who has brought great
talent and leadership to the Atlanta Falcons _ but cap restrictions
prevented it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Falcons called us twice on draft day,'' said Grier. ``The
first time, we said no. Then they called a second time after the
two backs (Ricky Williams and Edgerrin James) were gone. We got
together and said, `How can we do this?' After discussing how we
could do it, the solution was we'd have to cut six players off of
our team to be able to get Jamal in here and then sign him to a new
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also had a problem with the asking price. They wanted our
two No. 1s, and we figured the market had also been established for
a top running back. We received a first- and a third-rounder for
losing Curtis (Martin), and Marshall Faulk went to St. Louis for a
second- and a fifth-round pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has $1.6 million remaining on the final year of his
current contract, and he would have been looking for a $10 million
signing bonus and an average salary of $6 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 26, is just the kind of rugged runner the Patriots
would love to have, but they said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these teams talk about the salary cap, but they can
find a way to have the players they want to have on their team,''
said a Patriot player.
</P>
<P>
   With what they have, if the attitude is right and the top talent
is healthy, the Patriots should be able to overcome money problems
and compete very well in their division. Judging by the number of
players in their strength and conditioning program, they feel they
are far ahead of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the players who were injured or feel they have something
to prove have decided to take matters into their own hands. One
Patriots executive said that Armstrong, who has lost 25 pounds,
``will be coming to camp with a chip on his shoulder. He wants to
prove a lot of people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungry may be good. Angry may be even better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McGinest and Slade are on the mend after having medical
procedures recently. McGinest, 27, missed seven games with a
groin/abdominal pull last season, the first year of a five-year,
$25 million contract for which he received an $8 million signing
bonus. McGinest, who had 3 1/2 sacks last year, had some tightening
of muscle done in the groin area in an effort to prevent future
damage. He has been attending the strength and conditioning program
consistently since April after spending much of the offseason in
Vancouver, where he worked with a groin specialist on strengthening
muscles. The program was taken to Foxborough, where McGinest has
worked closely with trainer Ron O'Neil and strength and
conditioning coach Johnny Parker. Slade, 28, had a minor
arthroscopic procedure on his knee about three weeks ago and should
begin running again next week. Both players are expected to be at
full strength by the start of training camp in Smithfield, R.I.,
July 30 . . . Funny line by former Patriots coach Dick McPherson on
a recent ``Imus in the Morning'' program: ``Bill Parcells should
thank me every day of his life. Because we went 2-14, he was able
to draft Drew Bledsoe.'' . . . Just asking: With The Wall and the
infield being preserved as part of the new Fenway, will the
Patriots seek to preserve the aluminum seats at Foxboro Stadium? .
. . There is speculation in Dallas that Deion Sanders may get cut,
which would relieve $8.2 million from the salary cap. Sanders had
toe surgery and is expected to be out 3-4 months, which means he
likely wouldn't start the season . . . Michael Bishop and Scott
Mutryn, the two young quarterbacks vying for a spot on the Patriots
roster, have both ``had good days and bad days,'' according to
Grier. Bishop wasn't coming close to a spiral on Thursday.
Meanwhile, North Reading's Jim Murphy, also New England property,
is third string in Barcelona of NFL Europe. The Patriots are hoping
a team in need of a young quarterback comes to them and pays a
price for Murphy . . . As much as the Patriots have tried to get
away from the practices of the Parcells era, they keep inching
back. Assistant coaches are once again off limits to the media,
just as they were during the Parcells reign . . . OK, I give up.
Where is the Boston franchise in the International Football
Federation, a professional spring league due to open in March 2000,
going to play home games? The league supposedly has other
commitments from New York, Fort Lauderdale, Orlando, Orange County
(Calif.), Toronto, Detroit, Cincinnati, Denver, and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans have sold 48,000 personal-seat licenses for
their new stadium in Nashville, less than the 55,000 they had
projected . . . At their meetings Tuesday in Atlanta, owners will
get an electronic presentation on how instant replay will work, in
addition to a glimpse of the Patriots' Massachusetts stadium plan .
. . It might be overstating things, but Randall Cunningham had an
interesting line on Titans QB Steve McNair: ``The guy is as
talented as any quarterback who has ever played the game.'' . . .
Kadar Hamilton, a safety for Barcelona who is the son of Patriots
assistant coach Ray Hamilton and on the New England roster, said
the reason he wasn't drafted in the NFL out of Stanford two years
ago was his 4.8 time in the 40-yard dash at the combines. The
5-foot-11-inch, 204-pounder, who grew up in Sharon and spent many
years accompanying his father to Foxborough for practice, has given
himself two years to make it in the NFL before he pursues a career
as a financial account executive for Merrill Lynch in San
Francisco. ``The 40 time is very important at the combines, and it
determines whether you get drafted or not,'' he said. ``I just had
a terrible day that day, but Ronnie Lott ran a 4.8 toward the end
of his career, and he was still making plays all over the field. I
just need to get out there and get the experience and show what I
can do.'' Hamilton was cut by the St. Louis Rams in training camp
last year . . . Does anyone blame Barry Sanders for not wanting to
play for the Lions? He has endured 10 years of losing, a great
talent wasted. With 15,269 yards rushing, he is 1,458 short of
Walter Payton's all-time record. Would he retire? It wouldn't
surprise a lot of people who think Sanders is one of those players
who will just ride off into the sunset and never be heard from
again. He would look pretty good taking handoffs from Bledsoe . . .
Receiver Herman Moore is about to receive a big deal from the Lions
. . . Speaking of Bledsoe, he has thrown 128 touchdown passes: 64
at home, 64 on the road. Yet his home/away won/lost record is 28-18
at home, 22-22 on the road . . . Bledsoe will stay in Foxborough
until the middle of June, then head to his Montana retreat until
the end of July, when training camp starts. Bledsoe weighed in on
losing friend and confidant Scott Zolak, who signed with the New
York Jets: ``I'm very disappointed to see him go. He's the best
backup I could have asked for. He's been great for me over the
years. John (Friesz) is a good player who has played a lot over the
years, and if I go down _ which I don't anticipate _ he can come in
and win for us.'' Bledsoe said he saw Zolak last weekend and came
away feeling New England was ``his first choice, but I think he's
happy where he is now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
