<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE TEAMS FACE SEA CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mauricio Macri has been described as a ``hincha con
plata,'' a rich fan. In the case of Macri, chief executive of the
industrial conglomerate SOCMA and president of Club Atletico Boca
Juniors, we're talking about the very richest of South Americans.
</P>
<P>
   River Plate is considered ``The Millionaires,'' the club that
took a socioeconomic leap from La Boca barrio and has been the
transcendent club in Argentina sports. But while River Plate is
reloading, Macri has capitalized, and Boca Juniors is leading the
way, not only in the Clausura standings but in other initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   In five years as president, Macri has modernized Boca Juniors'
infrastructure and their famous stadium, La Bombonera. Like a fan
with no experience in soccer, Macri made grand errors in the early
part of his administration. But he has learned. Carlos Bianchi, his
third coach, is the right person for the position. Macri is
enterprising _ instead of setting a rent on executive box seats at
La Bombonera, he auctioned them off, attracting more than $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Boca Juniors entered this weekend with a 37-game unbeaten
streak, two less than the Argentine record set by Racing in 1966.
And after Gimnasia y Escrima de Jujuy upset San Lorenzo, 3-2, last
Sunday, Macri's club holds a 6-point lead with four games
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But soccer is complicated in Argentina, and all is not well. The
sport is inextricably woven into the fabric of society, and many
problems are rooted in social unrest resulting from economic and
political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   There are 80 professional and semi-professional soccer clubs for
greater Buenos Aires's 12 million people. There are six 50,000-plus
capacity stadiums and another 15 with 20,000-plus capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, clubs have produced revenue by selling players.
River Plate, financially the healthiest of the Argentine clubs, has
earned more than $30 million from sales of Ariel Ortega and Chilean
Marcelo Salas to Spain and Italy in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The next big-money exports will be from Boca: Juan Roman
Riquelme, whose free kick gave Boca the lead against Estudiantes,
leading scorer Martin Palermo, and Guillermo Barros Schelotto, who
is being scouted by Bayern Munich's Karl-Heinz Rummenigge.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's president, Carlos Menem, who was booed as he became
an honorary socio of San Lorenzo during the defeat last Sunday, is
urging clubs to become ``commercial organizations or sociedades
anonimas (franchises).'' Indeed, futbol should be recognized as a
business. But it will be difficult to transform clubs that have
evolved from social organizations into bottom-line enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Argentine soccer already displays many traits of an
advanced stage of capitalism: an international revenue stream
through development and exportation of assets (players), a
sophisticated internal shadow economy involving barra bravas
(superfans), and a television rights agreement worth hundreds of
millions of dollars from Torneos y Competencias (TyC). The
conflicts begin when a club's business or on-field fortunes
decline. Probably, there are too many clubs for all to remain
solvent, but eliminating any will leave a vacuum in the community.
</P>
<P>
   As in England, and other developed nations, there is a great
amount of pent-up angst among the populace in Argentina. And the
soccer stadium is where most of it is released. Such anxiety cannot
be repressed by draconian means _ police are omnipresent at games,
and moats, barbed wire, and fences 60 feet high are in use,
contrary to edicts of FIFA and worldwide trends.
</P>
<P>
   Panstadia International magazine's Simon Inglis recommends ``a
firm, national strategy based not on heavy policing or containment
but on modernization and information.''
</P>
<P>
   Stadiums in Argentina simply must be upgraded to minimize the
chances for a large-scale disaster. The conundrum is that clubs are
not profitable enough to make the necessary improvements, and any
talk of reduction of clubs, mergers, or stadium sharing is resisted
by the loyal populace, which instinctively fears the loss of
identity that accompanies a club's demise.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis notes that the clubs have sports halls, all-weather
fields, swimming pools, social clubs, and even schools and
kindergartens; precisely the sort of community facilities the
hard-pressed municipalities struggle to provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than jeopardize this crucial social role, it may
therefore be wiser to separate the running of the stadiums from the
rest of the organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Passion and tradition must be harnessed in a contemporary
context. In November, lower division games were suspended because
of excess violence, and Primera Division A players went on strike
in sympathy. Now, Racing has been declared bankrupt with $50
million in debts. The president of the club has been blamed for the
losses, and Racing has only been allowed to continue playing
because a group within the club went to court and posted a $1.5
million security.
</P>
<P>
   As Menem noted: ``If the clubs are not adapting to the current
times, I am not going to judge the honesty of the directors.
However, what is failing at this time is the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
