<HEADLINE>
UMASS MEETS ITS MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST REGIONAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ The University of Massachusetts softball season
was supposed to end on a high note, led by senior hurler Danielle
Henderson, who has broken every school pitching record in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it ended with red eyes and bitter words as the team was
left with a heart-wrenching 2-0 extra-inning loss against the
University of California Saturday before 910 fans at Totman Field.
The defeat eliminated the Minutewomen (43-10) from the NCAA East
Regional and cost them a third straight trip to the College World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   California (47-10) will now face top-seeded Southwestern
Louisiana (54-9) Sunday at 10 a.m. for the regional title and a
berth in next weekend's World Series. If California wins, the teams
will play again due to the double-elimination format.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UMass and its five seniors have only Sunday's
graduation to look forward to.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was really a devastating loss,'' said coach Elaine
Sortino. She pointed to a pitch made by Henderson in the eighth
inning she believed was a strike. Instead it was ruled a ball, and
California second baseman Lisa Iancin belted the next pitch for a
double that scored Amber Phillips and Maiko Bristow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Henderson) pitched a great game, but I also think
that call was critical on a changeup,'' said Sortino. ``I think
I'll probably remember it the rest of my life, but that's just the
way the game goes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't even trying to strike her out, I was just trying to
get her to put the ball in play so we could make an out,'' added a
teary Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   California freshman Jocelyn Forest (21-6) proceeded to fan the
final three UMass batters on her way to striking out 14 and
collecting her first career no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson (30-4) struck out 10, and looked as if she had the
same stuff that enabled her to toss her own no-hitter and strike
out 14 in a 3-0 win over Long Island University earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth no-hitter of the season for Henderson, the kind
of performance that has made ``Harry,'' as she's known to UMass
fans, the reason that virtually every home game has been packed.
Saturday, a half-dozen fans sat on the roof of a shed past the
bleachers and put up ``K'' cards every time Henderson fanned a
batter. They were busy all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A leadoff double by second baseman Mandy Galas, followed by a
sinlge by center fielder Teri Rooney, resulted in UMass's first
run. Catcher Nikki Faessler blasted a home run to center field in
the fourth to up the lead to 2-0, and UMass added one more in the
top of the seventh when first baseman Cherra Wheeler doubled to
knock in Katie Kenderski.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Saturday's elimination, both the fans who cheered the
team as they walked off the field and Sortino seemed to recognize
the impact that the team had on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you say about five kids that took you to four NCAA
tournaments, won four Atlantic 10 titles, and took you to two World
Series?'' said Sortino. ``No other class has had as great an impact
on the UMass softball program than the class of 1999. I think it's
quite fitting that they close out the century, because the record
books will probably stand for a long, long time with what these
kids have done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
