<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO PACKAGE:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DOCTOR (Jazince, Macedonia) _ There are moments when the
pure exhilaration of being here leads Dr. Jennifer Walser to wish
she did not have to return to New York. But there are also moments
when her efforts to alleviate are dwarfed by the sheer scale of the
tragedy unfolding before her. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The mood in the city. It is
weariness that hangs heavily in the air here, not defeatism. The
citizens of Belgrade, interviewed by the dozen this last week, feel
they are right to be fighting for Kosovo. Some express shame at
what they've heard about the purging of ethnic Albanians; most
express anger at Western support for the secessionist Kosovo
Liberation Army. They're proud of their war, of their brave if
inevitably futile defense against all the might of NATO. They smell
a political settlement that will bring foreign troops into Kosovo,
and they don't know why it's taking so long to write down the
obvious. By Stephen Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Fier, Albania) _ In a place called Fier,
pronounced fear, there is a camp called Hope, and the Americans who
are building the camp hope thousands of Kosovo refugees will come
to safety here until they can return to their homeland. But so far,
the refugees' fear of coming this far south seems to be winning out
over hope. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Blace) _ More refugees cross the border from
Kosovo, in the biggest surge in weeks. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-GANDHI (New Delhi) _ A profile of Sonia Gandhi. By Celia
S. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Making sense of Russia's political
turmoil. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Dateline TK) _ The new prime minister attends a
victory rally and gives his first policy address. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Berlin) _ Johannes Rau, longtime Social
Democrat, becomes president. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   BOUTROS-BOOK (United Nations) _ In a new book, the former
Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali lashes out at Madeleine
Albright and the Clinton administration for denying him a second
term. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE (Newnan, Ga.) _ The members of the Coweta County
Board of Education are not naive enough to think that they
vanquished school violence two weeks ago when they voted to
prohibit students from carrying bookbags unless the bags are
transparent or made of mesh. But at least it is something, they
say. And their attitude is not unique: In the month since the
shootings at Columbine High School, school boards, county
commissions and state legislatures all across the country have
proposed and enacted a broad series of measures aimed at attacking
the youth violence problem at the margins. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Undated) _ After decades of flops, $100 billion
in costs and sharp rises in the political stakes, the Pentagon is
trying again to build a system that can defend America against
missile attack. By William Broad.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SPEECH (Grambling, La.) _ In a commencement address,
Clinton says the Labor Department will review requests from four
states to allow them to spend some unemployment compensation
surpluses on family leave for new parents. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   GUNSHOW-REACT (Fresno, Calif.) _ Talking to gun enthusiasts at a
gun show about the new legislation coming out of Washington. By
Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   EMBRYO-RESEARCH (Undated) _ A presidentially-appointed ethics
panel has decided to recommend that the federal government begin
paying for some research on human embryos. A draft report of the
decision to be announced next month concludes that the moral cost
of destroying embryos in research is outweighed by the social good
that could come from the studies. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   APPEALS-COURT (Washington) _ The Federal Appeals Court based in
Richmond, Va. has, in the view of scholars, lawyers and many of its
own members, quietly but steadily become the boldest conservative
court in the nation, setting remarkable new precedents and adopting
a striking tone on several issues. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-POLITICS (Washington) _ Once reliably Democratic in
congressional races, older Americans have become a critical swing
vote, the object of intense competition on Capitol Hill. Democrats
lost the 60-and-over vote by a 60-40 margin last November, while
breaking even or carrying every other age group. Democrats also
lost that vote in 1996 and 1994. Explanations abound for this
fundamental shift, and what the competition for the vote has meant
on Capitol Hill. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   COX-PROFILE (Washington) _ He is something of a closet
Renaissance man in the House, one who speaks Russian, savors Ayn
Rand and seeks out the latest translation of Omar Khayyam. For a
hobby, he reads book after book on mathematicians. And so Rep.
Christopher Cox may seem the perfect prospect for presiding over
the House's ultra-secret investigation of suspected espionage by
China. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
