A7929 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE-25-COX     05-23 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE-25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IQ to I-Ching, favorite sites brighten the day
 &HT;    CYBERSCENE column
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For people who spend most of their working day and some of their
personal time connected to the Internet, the Web becomes part of
the daily routine.
</P>
<P>
   Just as someone who travels a lot in the real world _ the place
where it rains and the sun shines _ get to know the territory,
those of us who spend half our waking hours in cyberspace get to
know the lay of the land, as well.
</P>
<P>
   We have sites that are part of our practical everyday working
life. For instance, I check the weather by zapping over to the
Weather Channel (weather.com); or for looking up a street address,
e-mail address, or phone number go to Switchboard
(www.switchboard.com), or to find the best way to get to a business
across town use Yahoo!'s excellent mapping service
(/maps.yahoo.com/py/maps.py).
</P>
<P>
   But over time, I've also found some places that just tickle me.
Just as a traveler might urge a friend to someday visit the
Petrified Forest or to plan a long week at the Grand Canyon, there
are some destinations that I like to recommend to my friends. Today
we'll talk about those favorite places.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have no notion in the world of just what our IQ is.
We know that it's an overrated way of measuring intelligence, but
yet there may be moments when you wonder just how smart you really
are. If you'd like a pretty good measuring stick on IQ, there's a
Web site that _ as nearly as I can tell _ produces reasonably
accurate results.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the Self-discovery Workshop and is at www.iqtest
</P>
<P>
   .com/welcometest.html. While at the page you can read a fairly
unbiased account of how IQ tests work.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can take, in just 18 minutes, an online version of the
IQ test. This isn't nearly as accurate as the kind of test you'd
pay hundreds of dollars to take, but _ based on the experiences of
some friends who had their IQ measured professionally _ the results
here are close enough to offer a rough gauge of how you'd test out.
</P>
<P>
   Since part of the test results are based on how much of the test
you complete in 18 minutes, make sure that you carve out at least
that much time for yourself if you decide to try the test. The nice
thing about taking an online test is that you can keep quiet if the
results horrify you. If, on the other hand, you wind up being an
undiscovered Einstein, then you can brag.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop on our tour is a site run by Bell Labs (the folks
who, among other things, brought you the transistor). It's located
at www.bell-labs.com
</P>
<P>
   /project/tts/.
</P>
<P>
   This particular part of the Bell Labs site deals with turning
computer text into synthesized human speech. While the notion of a
talking computer is no longer a novelty, the power of the program
demonstrated on this site is still impressive enough to bring a
smile. You can type in text, and then your computer will repeat it
back as spoken words.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, and this is my favorite of the bunch, there is a site
that uses the ancient fortunetelling technique called I-Ching on
the anything-but-ancient Web. Just go to this site at
www.iching.com/ and follow the directions.
</P>
<P>
   _ While you shouldn't use the advice you find here to start a
new life or decide what car to buy, it's a lot of fun and _
sometimes _ chillingly specific to the question that you ask.
</P>
<P>
   _ The site, by the way, is an advertisement for a program that
uses the same software you'll use online. But the Web version is so
good that you probably won't feel the need to buy the program, even
if you enjoy the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
