r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAC-REPORT25-COX     05-23 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NaturallySpeaking available soon
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some areas, dare I say it, the PC world commands a lead over
Apple Computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more significant is voice-recognition software, a
technology that Apple Computer pioneered.
</P>
<P>
   But Apple Computer is starting to close the gap, much to the
relief of many Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   At the company-sponsored Worldwide Developers conference two
weeks ago, interim chief executive Steve Jobs announced that Dragon
Systems will produce a Mac version of its NaturallySpeaking
software.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon's NaturallySpeaking software is the leading
voice-recognition title in the United States. It enables computers
to translate conversational speech into text.
</P>
<P>
   Until now Dragon produced only a Windows version of
NaturallySpeaking. Now it will release a Mac version later this
year, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   Macs have some limited voice-recognition capabilities through
their PlainTalk technology, which comes installed on most models.
PlainTalk, though, cannot translate conversational speech into
text.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Apple Computer has never had a Mac program that could
translate conversational speech. It hasn't been for a lack of
trying.
</P>
<P>
   The company had been working to enhance its voice technology
with a company called Articulate Systems Inc. But the two companies
couldn't get along, and Articulate pulled the plug on its Mac
offering, PowerSecretary, last year. Dragon Software, by the way,
owned a stake in Articulate.
</P>
<P>
   Before Dragon's Naturally- Speaking, released two years ago,
computers could only translate speech spoken unnaturally slowly and
clearly.
</P>
<P>
   NaturallySpeaking has created whole new uses for computers in
the past two years. Companies use it to take orders over the
telephone and provide automated customer support, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   And NaturallySpeaking is a wonderful alternative to people who
can no longer type because of repetitive stress injuries.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that NaturallySpeaking is perfect. Far from
it.
</P>
<P>
   NaturallySpeaking is a hog in terms of its requirements for disk
space and RAM. But the software is improving all the time with new
versions.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon hasn't announced pricing or a brand name for its Mac
version of NaturallySpeaking. The Windows version, available in
several configurations, sells for between $200 and $700.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon's Mac version of NaturallySpeaking also appears to be a
peace offering. It has battled with Apple Computer through the
years about voice-recognition technology patents. The two
companies, for example, have sued each other over the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7932 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH25-COX     05-23 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web sites can help in tracing ancestors
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week I saw the places where my great-grandfather lived and
worked _ something I would not be able to do without the Web. For
me, the grandchild of Eastern European immigrants, learning about
my family history seemed nearly impossible. Finding bits of
information on the Web was a bit like shining a light in a dark
corner of my attic and finding unexpected treasures I didn't know
existed.
</P>
<P>
   I owe it all to Katie Couric. Well, actually, I owe it to the
entire anchor team of the ``Today'' show, who spent a week tracing
their respective family trees and posting lists of links to help
users get started in the job of researching their own families by
exploring on the MSNBC Web site.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Web sites that MSNBC had recommended were so
swamped by other novice genealogists like myself, it took a lot of
time for each page of requested information to load. Finally, I
just gave up and started looking for Web sites on my own, armed
with some of the links and suggestions that had been provided by
MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   I used to think that it would be impossible to trace my family
tree much past my grandparents, Morris and Fanny Katz, who came to
New York City in the early 1900s. Neither the Russians nor the
Nazis were much into keeping records of the Polish and Latvian
villages they plundered and destroyed in the first half of this
century.
</P>
<P>
   Even if I had the time and resources to travel to Europe to seek
out my family's records, I wouldn't know where to begin, because so
little is known about my great-grandparents. Making things even
worse are my family's many and conflicting oral histories. My
father has nine brothers and sisters who all tell different stories
about my grandparents and great-grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   So, although I am able to call up a wide variety of genealogy
sites and links on the Web, none of this stuff turned out to be of
much use to me, coming as I do from a family that can spend the
better part of a wedding reception _ as mine did once _ debating if
we really did have a Great Uncle Harry who absconded with the
family fortune and went to South Africa to strike it rich in the
diamond rush. The one thing everyone seems to agree on is where my
grandmother was born. It's a place called Slonim, which she said
was in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with just the name of a city in Poland, I began my search.
It was pretty discouraging at first. I tried searching for my
grandmother's maiden name but, since I didn't know quite how to
spell it, I had to rely on a ``sound-alike'' search engine that
couldn't come up with anything even close. After about a month of
searching nearly every genealogy site there I could find, I was
depressed and frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Before giving up entirely, I decided to call up one of the
search engines and type ``Slonim'' in the search field. I nearly
fell over when I found 71 sites. The reason I couldn't find Slonim
was now clear. After World War II,
</P>
<P>
   Slonim became part of the Soviet province of Belarus. More
searching led me to the homepage of a British genealogist whose
family had come from Slonim and who maintained a Web site devoted
to his family history. He included a page called ``The Ledger of
Slonim.''
</P>
<P>
   I discovered my grandmother's hometown had encouraged Jewish
immigrants who were escaping from the Crusades to settle there as
early as 1388. From all indications, it appears that Jews began
their settlement in Slonim that same year. The Web site describes
the prosperity of the city from the Renaissance through the late
1800s. There was also a page of pictures of libraries, synagogues
and other buildings my grandmother and her parents may have
frequented.
</P>
<P>
   The site also describes the anti-Semitic arson attacks on Jewish
homes and businesses. My great-grandfather's comb-and-brush factory
was burnt to the ground in one of these pogroms. That was when my
grandmother was given just enough money to go to America out of
harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   When my grandmother left Slonim in the 1900s, there were about
12,000 Jews living there. After the Germans took Slonim from the
Russians during World War II, the Jewish population dwindled to
zero, where it remains today. Further investigation, all done on
the Web, uncovered first-person accounts of life in Slonim after my
family had left and efforts of the Belarussian government to
restore the libraries and synagogues destroyed by previous
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for my family tree involved using what you could call
``the other Internet.'' So many people think of the Web as a
utility, something used for commercial or practical purposes. Along
with established commercial sites, there is a wealth of information
that will never make a dime or the Media Metrix top 10. But to
scholars, students and family tree-hunters like me, they are every
bit as valuable.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail address: fkatz(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
