<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investment book aimed at the Y2K wary
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you fear the Y2K bug, this may be the book for you. ``Crisis
Investing for the Year 2000'' is a guide on how to protect your
finances if computers _ especially those on Wall Street _ start to
go haywire after midnight on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preparing yourself and your investments for Y2K is not the act
of a fringe survivalist,'' say authors L. Jay Kuo and Edward M. Dua
in the promotion blurb on the jacket of their book. ``Such measures
are the practical precautions of an informed realist.'' Here are
some of the authors' predictions: Y2K will disrupt time-sensitive
industries such as banking and stock trading; Y2K will hurt
companies dependent on computer automation for making products; and
companies dependent on overseas investments will be hurt because
most countries are ill-prepared for the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer is right. The lowly but highly practical floppy
drive is on the way out. Learn about all the new bigger and faster
drives ready to replace it in the June issue of PC World. Among the
contenders is a new drive called the Orb, which stores 2.2
gigabytes _ yes, gigabytes _ of data on a single disk. It retails
for only $200. Another favorite of PC World is the new Iomega drive
based on the USB standard. The magazine says these drives are the
easiest to install and use.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Can you run your household like an office? An affirmative answer
to that question is the idea behind a new computer CD called
FamilyTime. The CD includes six integrated tools designed to help
you plan, control and simplify everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Those tools include a calendar that lets every family member
keep his or her own schedule and then integrates all those
schedules into one master calendar. There's a meal planner that
prints out shopping lists based on the meals you've scheduled and a
record organizer that stores all kinds of information, including
medical and car records. FamilyTime is published by TimeSoft and is
available only for PCs running Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   For kids, Microsoft has released its latest title in the Magic
School Bus series. This one is about animals and features
exploration of seven different geographic zones. There are also
60-plus photographs and 14 games and puzzles. This latest Magic Bus
game is available only for PCs running Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is full of news, and most of it is about itself.
Yes, there's no better place to learn about and keep up with the
Internet than cyberspace itself. One of the best places for news
about the Net is CNET's News.com site. This site not only offers
news but is a daily updated compendium of where to find more
information about the Net. You'll find this site at www.news.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
