<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RadioMouse works, but who needs it?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Ndews Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We gather today to examine a thing called RadioMouse.
</P>
<P>
   RadioMouse is not, as you might think, a mouse with an AM-FM
radio in it, although I'm sure that if one hasn't been marketed it
soon will be.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, RadioMouse is another wireless mouse.
</P>
<P>
   It has this small distinction, at least: It's the first wireless
mouse I've tried.
</P>
<P>
   RadioMouse is a two-button affair of a fairly conventional
humpback style, made rather heavy by the three AAA batteries it
requires. It is smaller than the Microsoft mouse to which I am
accustomed, and I do not find it as comfortable, but that may be a
matter of habit.
</P>
<P>
   The receiver is a small plastic box with a cord that attaches to
the mouse port. It can sit just about anywhere on the desk; it
doesn't seem to require being right in front of the mouse pad.
According to the manual, it can be six to 10 feet from the
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   That, basically, is all there is to RadioMouse. There isn't any
software; it is entirely plug-and-play and in my case, at least,
worked automatically with the Microsoft drivers already installed.
</P>
<P>
   The radio connection appears to work quite well.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately I cannot say the same for the mouse itself. The
buttons are too sensitive, resulting in unwanted right-button
clicks. The ball and rollers have a tendency to lock up, as if
dirty.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the manual warns that ``Mouse ball is easy to attach
dirt and causes malfunction. Clean mouse ball and the two rolling
rolls with tissues.''
</P>
<P>
   From this, you could deduce that RadioMouse is made in China
even if half the manual wasn't printed in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, however, whatever causes the jams isn't related to
attached dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The manual also suggests a novel form of at-your-desk exercise:
``You may discover how easy it is to get comfortable, and enjoy
pointing your PC with freedom and convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, finally, is: Do we need this thing?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is: Probably not, even if it worked smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   It reminds me of a contraption some outfit sent me years ago
that was intended to serve both as a mouse pad and as a kind of
tether for the cord to keep it from fighting you. The modern
Microsoft mouse seems to have a better cord; mine doesn't give me
any trouble at all. I'm perfectly happy with it, and it doesn't
need batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The only real need I can see for a wireless mouse is a situation
in which you're so far from your CPU unit that the mouse cord won't
reach. Then it might be a viable alternative to an extension cable
on the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you feel a wireless mouse would serve you best, you
can learn more about the RadioMouse at:
</P>
<P>
   www.cordlessmouse.com/
</P>
<P>
   It costs $40 _ batteries included.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
