<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHANIE KWOLEK, THE DUPONT CHEMIST BEHIND KEVLAR, IS HONORED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Stephanie Kwolek went to work for the DuPont Co. in 1946,
it was the dawning of a synthetic era. Chemists were turning coal,
castor oil and antifreeze into new plastics and products, many of
which were for the ostensible benefit of womankind.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Tupper was just starting to turn DuPont's polyethylene into
unbreakable kitchen tumblers. Stores were hawking Lucite jewels and
rayon frocks. ``Nylon riots'' were in full swing, with women,
according to press reports of the time, clawing their way through
store crowds for nylon stockings, a scarce commodity in postwar
America.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont marketers understood the promise of women as consumers.
But, alas for Ms. Kwolek, company managers did not think much of
their potential as chemists.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Ms. Kwolek _ who held a college chemistry degree and would
one day invent the technology behind Kevlar, best known as a
bulletproof fabric _ languished for 15 years in the lab without a
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she is one to complain. Ms. Kwolek, now 75, says she is
no ``flag-waving feminist.'' Her approach was to break down
barriers quietly, from the inside. ``If you were ambitious and
applied yourself, you could acquire a great deal of knowledge,''
she said. ``There were a lot of bright, creative men. This made the
atmosphere in which I worked so stimulating and so enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Ms. Kwolek does not want for recognition. She has
been inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame. She has
been awarded a National Medal of Technology. Last month, she
received the Lemelson-MIT Lifetime Achievement Award.
</P>
<P>
   The use of Kevlar has expanded beyond bulletproof vests for
police officers. It is used in firefighters' boots, military
helmets, fiber optic cables, car brakes, skis and racing sails.
Though the original, pioneering patents granted to Ms. Kwolek and
her colleagues have long since expired, the trademarked Kevlar
continues to earn DuPont hundreds of millions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kwolek did not set out to design a bulletproof fabric. At
the time, in the mid-1960s, her goal was merely to create a fiber
strong enough to reinforce radial tires.
</P>
<P>
   The problem she and other chemists faced was that polymers with
rigid, rodlike molecules were difficult to dissolve. But she
succeeded in dissolving a polymer that had rod-like molecules. But
when she held up the solution, she saw that it was not as thick and
clear as it was expected to be, but rather, thin and cloudy. She
decided to try anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But first she had to win over the operator of the spinneret, a
colander-like device through which polymers are extruded to produce
fabric. Such a cloudy solution was sure to gum up his equipment,
the spinneret operator argued. But in the end, he relented.
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Kwolek found was that under specific conditions, these
rod-like molecules arranged themselves into bundles. In each
bundle, the molecules were arranged parallel to one another _ that
is, all the rods in one bundle were oriented all in one direction.
</P>
<P>
   But the bundles themselves were in a jumble and facing different
directions. When forced through the tiny holes in the spinneret,
however, the bundles came out on the other side all facing the same
direction. And this uniform direction made the fiber that was
created very strong and stiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stiffness was absolutely spectacular,'' Ms. Kwolek said.
``That's when I said, `Aha.' I knew then and there it was an
important discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
