<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MATCHMAKER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPINESS FOR A $400 FEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Subtlety is not Irene Nathan's middle name. Her first question
at an encounter is likely to be, ``Are you Jewish?'' The second,
``Do you want to get married?'' Or maybe, ``Would you marry a
goy?'' If so, that client is not for her.
</P>
<P>
   As a partner in Matchmakers, Ms. Nathan claims to have created
almost 300 marriages in 16 years, drawn mostly from Chicago's
Orthodox Jews; only four ended in divorce. Her fee, which she
announces up front, is $400. That certifies a prospect's serious
intentions: ``If you give $400, you want good merchandise.'' She is
candid about her candidates at any given moment: ``We have better,
but this is all the stock I have just now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nathan, a widowed fast-talker in her peppy 60s, is at the
center of Mark Wexler's appealing documentary, ``Me and My
Matchmaker,'' but it turns out that although Wexler hides behind
his camera, he is her prey.
</P>
<P>
   Most of her clients think they know who they are (``I have a
graduate degree'') and whom they are looking for or trying to avoid
(``They have to not be on drugs''). One female client speaks for
many: ``I don't ask for much; I just want happiness.'' Wexler, 39
and presumably still looking, is less forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   The easygoing, hourlong documentary consists mainly of Ms.
Nathan's wooing Wexler with meals while she tries to figure out
whether he really wants a bride and, if so, what kind. ``I've got
to get you married,'' she announces. He becomes her merchandise. Or
does he?
</P>
<P>
   As he tells of the breakup of his mother and father, client and
matchmaker find themselves verging toward intimacy. ``You invaded
my heart,'' she says. When he brings home a woman for chicken soup
with matzoh balls, Ms. Nathan rushes to judgment: ``I didn't like
her. I didn't like anything about her.'' Is her judgment strictly
professional?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to interfere in your life,'' Ms. Nathan
announces. Can you believe her? Can Wexler believe her? Does she
believe herself? After all those dozens of clients and her own
lonely years, she must know better. ``Me and My Matchmaker''
becomes an account of an affair unlike any other in Irene Nathan's
career.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`ME AND MY MATCHMAKER'  &QL; 
At 10 Monday on Channel 13  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and produced by Hajira Majid and Mark Wexler; Wexler,
director and cinematographer; edited by Robert DeMaio; Alan
Robinson, sound. With: Irene Nathan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
