<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-MARKETPLACE-NY     05-23 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: )  
 WALL STREET TAKES A LOOK AT EISNER, THE MAN AND THE MANAGER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The financial feud between the Walt Disney Co.'s chairman,
Michael D. Eisner, and his former lieutenant, Jeffrey Katzenberg,
may have made headlines. But few of the customers examining Mickey
Mouse backpacks or Disney T-shirts, at the Disney Store in Times
Square on Friday even knew a dispute was going on.
</P>
<P>
   The one shopper in an informal survey who did, Chad Coleman, a
Canadian tourist, said the courtroom battle made ``absolutely no
difference'' in his perception of Disney.
</P>
<P>
   But for its part, Wall Street is not happy watching Disney air
its dirty linen in public. The company's stock has been depressed
for months, primarily because its earnings have been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Some media industry analysts believe the lawsuit has been a
factor, raising questions about Eisner's judgment in letting a
private battle go public at a time when Disney needs all his
attention. Disney stock closed at $29.50 on Friday, up from its
52-week low of $22.50, but far from its July 15 high of $40.625.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Eisner's failure to resolve his dispute with
Katzenberg makes a number of analysts nervous, though they are
generally reluctant to criticize the Disney management in public.
</P>
<P>
   Some have even become concerned about Eisner's management
skills. ``The fight highlights not managing well, and it has to be
distracting on a management basis,'' one longtime Disney analyst
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But Laura Martin, a media industry analyst at CS First Boston,
disagrees. ``I do not think that losing the lawsuit reflects poorly
on Eisner's management skills at all,'' she said. ``The fight was
personal and people are human. I do not think it is indicative of
his judgments in operating the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg, Disney's former film studio chief, and now a partner
at Dreamworks SKG, contended that Disney owed him $250 million
because his contract guaranteed him a percentage of the profits
from films produced during his tenure. Disney had initially
countered that when Katzenberg left the company in 1994 for
Dreamworks SKG, he forfeited those profits. Eisner was adamant
about not settling.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides reached a partial settlement in November 1997 in
which Disney conceded that Katzenberg was owed something, and
Disney has paid Katzenberg $117 million. But there was no agreement
about the exact amount of that ``something,'' leading to last
week's hearings. Several people close to Disney said Katzenberg had
nearly doubled his demands from his initial asking price of $250
million, making negotiations difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Although Paul Breckenridge Jr., the retired Los Angeles Superior
Court judge who is acting as referee in the current hearings, ruled
on Tuesday that Katzenberg was entitled to some payment, he has yet
to quantify the amount.
</P>
<P>
   A Disney spokesman said the company did not comment on its stock
price. But a person close to Disney noted: ``If there were a
reasonable amount of new money that Katzenberg were asking for, it
would have been settled. But Disney considers it has a fiduciary
responsibility to shareholders to pay him a reasonable amount and
not the excessive amount he is still seeking.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, where image is all-important, the image-trashing
that has characterized the public fight is unusual. The name
calling reached its peak in court last week when the plaintiffs
introduced notes to Eisner's autobiography, published last year, in
which the Disney chairman said, referring to Katzenberg, ``I think
I hate the little midget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is embarrassing on both sides,'' said another analyst who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``This is the kind of thing that
should have been compromised somewhere along the line. I don't know
if Eisner's behavior has been responsible for a decline. How can
you measure it? There are seven good reasons for the stock to be
down. But it has to have tarnished his image.''
</P>
<P>
   That depends on whom you ask. Abraham Zalesnik, the Konosuke
Matsushita professor emeritus of leadership at Harvard Business
School, said the dispute raised questions about Eisner's ability to
continue running Disney successfully. He said he thought Eisner
expected too much from both Katzenberg, and Michael Ovitz, whom
Eisner brought in as his second in command in 1995 and who left the
company in 1996, with a cash and stock settlement valued at $120
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether Eisner attaches magical significance
to these people he brings in and then gets disenchanted and
therefore lashes out,'' Zalesnik said. ``At this stage, his
judgment of people is really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Zalesnik says Eisner is responsible for protecting shareholder
value and should not simply agree to pay Katzenberg the $250
million he is seeking. But he adds that Eisner made a serious
mistake in letting a personal battle erupt into a courtroom drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could not work it out with this man who is gifted, but his
job is to make it work out so that it does not become a public
spectacle,'' Zalesnik said. The dispute, he said, reflects on
Eisner's ability to retain top managers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Professor John Coffe of Columbia University
Law School is dismissive of the court case, saying it does nothing
to discredit Eisner. ``This is not the kind of episode that has
recurring significance, that says Eisner is functionally incapable
of being a successful manager,'' Coffe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think institutional shareholders want Eisner to be
generous with shareholder funds,'' he continued. ``They want Eisner
to get the cheapest settlement possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one analyst cautioned that Wall Street often indulges
in overkill in its propensity to criticize executives when their
companies are doing badly.
</P>
<P>
   This person recalled that when Time Warner Inc. was doing
poorly, its chairman, Gerald A. Levin, was widely criticized. But
as Time Warner stock has soared, Levin is being widely heralded as
a visionary leader.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Levin never had the mystique that Eisner had. After
taking over Disney in 1984, Eisner produced an impressive record
until 1998. Certainly, Eisner would be less vulnerable to criticism
if the company were continuing to do well.
</P>
<P>
   But not only is the company's ABC broadcast network facing
problems, as Ms. Martin of CS First Boston noted, there are also
cost problems driven by escalating sports rights fees at both ABC
and its ESPN cable network. In addition, there is concern that
``the company is spending too much money on theme parks, which
potentially depresses long-term returns on capital,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   These problem unfortunately come at just the moment when Disney
needs its investors to feel confident that Eisner can himself focus
on Disney's problems and rally a strong management team to help
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
