A7947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEW-SEASON-NYT &LR;      05-23 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEW-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACES ON TV GET YOUNGER AND COMEDY IS NOT KING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The main impressions from the unveiling of new shows for the
fall television season: The new shows in September will be filled
with teen-agers, sex, gay characters and glamorous white people;
they will not be filled with comedy, adults over 40, rural
characters and African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Shows about teen-agers and model-quality folk under age 25
dominated the 38 new series as the smoke cleared from a week of
program presentations. The smoke was being blown by a succession of
network executives selling the notion that they were faring
brilliantly, despite ratings evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Because advertisers pay more for younger viewers, most networks
(except CBS) have built shows around young characters for years.
But the target age is moving lower, edging nearer to the level of
those not yet eating solid food.
</P>
<P>
   Shows are also moving away from one of the most firmly
established genres in the history of the medium, the sitcom. The
half-hour comedy, if not in retreat, is losing ground. Only 14 of
the new shows are sitcoms, an unusually low number. Most seasons,
there are as many comedies as dramas, and in some recent seasons
there have been more comedies than dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new shows are hourlong comedies: ``Get Real,'' about
the tribulations of a contemporary family on Fox; ``Popular,''
about the forced union by their parents' marriage of a girl from
the in crowd with a girl from the out crowd, and two NBC entries,
``Freaks and Geeks,'' about more out-crowd woes, and ``Cold Feet,''
about the interaction of three couples.
</P>
<P>
   This is partly a reaction to the success of ``Ally McBeal,'' the
hit hourlong comedy on Fox. Paradoxically, the creator of that
series, David E. Kelley, decided to remix it into half-hour
segments for a new series called ``Ally,'' on Fox this coming
season. Kelley wants to improve his series' chances of selling as a
half-hour show in syndication, where the money is.
</P>
<P>
   The move away from the sitcom is most noticeable at NBC. Only a
few seasons ago NBC emphasized its ``must-see'' comedies as the
core of its schedule. At a high point there were 18 sitcoms on NBC.
Next season that will drop to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wright, the president of NBC, said: ``The writing talent is
spread so thin. It just seems like the genre has run out of gas for
the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, every network has complained about the
comedy writing talent, with one main charge being that the young
comedy writers favored by studios and networks have little life
experience and no frame of reference beyond other television shows.
Those limitations may be reflected in the crop of three new
comedies at ABC, for example, which deal virtually exclusively with
relationships, dating and sex.
</P>
<P>
   One agent who represents some of television's biggest comedy
clients said another problem affecting the amount of comedies was
the movement by producers to push their comedies as far toward the
edge of subject matter and taste as possible. Most of these efforts
were judged either too wild or too unfunny. One show that pushed
limits and won is ``Action,'' a new Fox comedy as aggressively
outrageous as any recent show. ``Action'' is about a driven
Hollywood film producer who uses language never tried on network
television before (and always bleeped here, though it is clear what
the character is saying). The show also depends heavily on
anatomical jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Anatomy plays a role in many new entries, even on staid CBS.
This is true of some of the teen-age shows. One, ``Manchester
Prep'' on Fox, has a scene of a stepsister eyeing her stepbrother
after he emerges from the shower.
</P>
<P>
   But teen-agers will be everywhere doing everything next season.
As networks are more befuddled than ever about the future and
emphasize more than ever the need to create new hit shows, one main
trend is discernible: a mania to imitate a network whose audience
is among the smallest, the soon-to-be-six-night network, WB.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the success of several of WB's youth-oriented shows,
especially ``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Felicity,'' with success
defined almost solely by the network's ability to attract female
viewers ages 12 to 25, television will be filled next fall with
shows set in high schools and prep schools or among twentysomething
singles looking for love in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Every network but CBS and UPN has one or another of this type of
show, and many have both. CBS does not, mainly because it seems to
be as aggressively running away from young viewers as the other
networks are chasing them. CBS continues to be the only network
featuring unglamorous actors, grandparents and assertively nonhip
story lines.
</P>
<P>
   UPN does not because, as it struggles to find some niche for
survival, it has changed direction yet again and is now seeking
what might be called the un-``Dawson'' audience: young males moved
by wrestling, not nestling. UPN will have two hours of wrestling
every Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   That is evidence of one clear trend of the new season: for the
first time in years competitors are going after the network leader,
NBC, on its stronghold night, Thursday. The competition detects
vulnerability in NBC on that night, especially with younger viewers
and male viewers. That is why Fox, which hopes to mount a serious
challenge to NBC for overall network leadership, has reconstructed
its Thursday night around its hit animated show, ``Family Guy,''
teamed up with ``Action.'' ABC wants to out-WB the WB with
``Wasteland,'' one of the new shows about dating in Manhattan. Even
CBS sees an opportunity and has moved its revamped ``Chicago Hope''
(again to be written by the ubiquitous Kelley) there.
</P>
<P>
   WB, meanwhile, sees a chance to go in a direction NBC seems to
have no interest in _ toward black viewers. This is not a statement
of principle by that network. WB has essentially ghettoized its
lineup of black comedies on a single night for several years. Now
it will be Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from UPN, which has two new shows aimed at black
audiences, and CBS, which in midseason will have a Steven Bochco
show about black doctors, no other network seems much interested in
blacks as viewers or cast members.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has an ambitious drama set in the White House, ``The West
Wing,'' and there are no African-Americans among members of the
president's staff. Fox, once a network with a large black audience
base, does not have a single significant black cast member in any
of its eight new series for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   It does have a regular gay character in ``Action,'' a studio
executive who surrounds himself with gay studs. Other gay
characters are less outrageous. One on ``Wasteland'' is a gay man
terrified of being ``outed.'' On ABC's comedy ``Oh Grow Up'' a gay
man leaves his wife and moves in with a straight friend, though the
wife is always around to insult him for ``going Nancy'' on her.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the new season has teen-agers. It has
teen-age aliens in the WB show ``Roswell.'' It has a teen-age boy
surrounded by a houseful of females in ABC's ``Odd Man Out.'' It
has four male teen-agers living with their widowed father in ``Safe
Harbor'' on WB. It has mean-spirited teen-agers in ``Manchester
Prep,'' nerdy teen-agers in ``Freaks and Geeks'' and teen-agers who
talk to the camera in ``Get Real'' and ``Malcolm in the Middle'' on
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   What has yet to be determined is whether the new season will
have enough teen-age viewers to go around to prevent it from
driving away even more viewers than the 7 percent who defected from
network television this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
