<SLUG> BC-FINALE-HOME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Improvement: Show grew as families did
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Tuesday night, there'll be no place like ``Home.''
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Home Improvement,'' a broad-appeal TV situation comedy
an entire family could watch. Kids could laugh at it, and parents
not only got it, they could trust that they wouldn't be blind-sided
by dirty innuendo snuck in under the guise of being hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement'' was never really hip; the only edge it ever
cut was lumber with a bandsaw. But it was funny, well-executed, as
dependable as duct tape and wildly popular in ``flyover land,''
that huge stretch of America that TV network execs look down on as
they jet between L.A. and N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   It portrayed a loving married couple (strong but with plenty of
stress points) raising good sons (although never easily). It won
People's Choice Awards, but no major Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's 90-minute finale, there will be nothing else on
TV quite like it, which is sad.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's a strong No. 14 in the Nielsen rankings this
season, its eighth, ``Home'' is no longer the powerhouse it once
was for ABC. Back in its third season, it was the No. 1 show in all
television, and at various points, it clobbered both ``Seinfeld''
and ``Frasier'' in head-to-head competition. It's also made $800
million from syndicated reruns, and is expected to hit $1 billion.
That's power.
</P>
<P>
   In January, I had the chance to wander around the ``Home
Improvement'' set in Burbank, and surprised myself by getting a bit
wistful. Standing in the Taylors' adjoining kitchen and family
room, I was taken back to when ``Home'' debuted in 1991, and my
daughter was eight years old, and we'd watch it together. Now's she
16, and into ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   My family's growth paralleled the Taylors', as their three sons
grew from cute little tykes into teenagers, and rather hulking
young lads at that. The show grew, too, from a fairly simple
spinoff of Tim Allen's chest-thumping, pig-grunting stand-up act to
one that dealt with the arcs of family life. (``Home'' was almost
always more real with the family stuff than the ``Tool Time''
segments.)
</P>
<P>
   It was time for ``Home '' to call it a day, but that doesn't
mean one can't miss a show that children and parents could watch
together. These days _ and it's not just my family, it's a wide
swath of demographics _ many families are fragmented, watching
separate TVs in separate rooms. ``Home Improvement'' didn't change,
we did.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
