<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINALE-MAD-COX     05-23 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINALE-MAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mad About You: Lovable couple never able to wow us
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've rarely been mad about it, but we have liked it quite a
lot. It's been a kind of ``Seinfeld'' for married people. It mined
humor from commitment rather than from ducking commitment _ an
out-of-favor concept in an era when sitcoms began to blur into
doomed herds of city-living single people shuffling between coffee
shops.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Mad About You'' would not have worked the last seven
seasons without the remarkable chemistry between Paul Reiser and
Helen Hunt. As the Buchmans, they played out the trivia and trauma
of married life with an almost balletic comic timing. It's not a
stretch to compare them to such memorable TV couples as Lucy and
Desi, Rob and Laura, Burns and Allen. Paul and Jamie really have
been that good, if not quite that emblematic of their times. As
much as they tried _ the lesbian sister, the almost-affair, the
baby _ they never quite pricked the zeitgeist that would have made
them all the talk in offices the next day. It was as if this was a
show that would be a smash in any era _ except its own.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes tonight's hour-long finale a disappointment.
Rather than be itself, it yearns to be something else _ hipper,
darker, profounder ... memorabler.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane Garofalo narrates the time-shifting episode as the
Buchman's all-grown-up daughter Mabel. She's a loving mess: engaged
four times to three men, still unmarried, she's upped her therapy
to three times a week. She blames her parents.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are a series of remembered scenes _ some in the
present, some in the near future, some way, way ahead _ that rarely
celebrate Paul and Jamie, or even just make light of them. Instead,
tonight's finale, despite a few classic moments, manages to make us
like Paul and Jamie less.
</P>
<P>
   A tragic drama beats in the heart of every sitcom. Too bad this
one didn't keep it to itself.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
