<HEADER>
A7950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINALE-MELROSE-COX     05-23 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINALE-MELROSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Melrose Place: When it was bad, it was sooo good
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Eileen Drennen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, Monday nights at 8 meant ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   In a cozy Los Angeles apartment complex with a pool, you got to
watch beautiful people do so many interesting things. Like scheme
and lust, plot and seduce in the kind of clothes you only dreamed
of walking around in. Blonde, brunette or redhead; male, female or
undecided, they married and divorced, lied and cheated,
double-crossed and triple-crossed and punched, burned, cut, crashed
and exploded their way right into our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a cross between an older ``90210'' and an L.A.
``thirtysomething'' soon became a much kinkier cousin of neither,
with a distinctive soapy hysteria all its own. But it did spin
around the same kind of self-contained cast (who never befriended
others, unless it turned out to be next week's Villain, who'd
kiss-and-tell for a couple episodes then disappear) who battled
Recurring Problems in their own fabulous way. A hipper Peyton Place
where women with names like Amanda, Sydney, Kimberly and Taylor
wore the tightest clothes, lowest necklines, shortest skirts and
the men wore ... who cares?
</P>
<P>
   No one did a stitch of work, even while they were at work _
considering the size of L.A., a tiny world made up of cutthroat D&AMP;D
Advertising, neighborhood bar Shooter's and Wilshire Memorial
Hospital. No, the action was all in what they said, and didn't say.
How they misunderstood, lied, seduced, betrayed and made up in the
most delicious ways.
</P>
<P>
   Sample classic dialogue: ``Listen to me you zipper-headed
mutant. You tried to kill me twice _ then you blew up an entire
building because your imaginary playmate told you that naughty
people lived there.''
</P>
<P>
   The action was all walking into and out of rooms and beds and
cars and kisses. Walking down the aisle then getting hit by a car
outside the church. Hearing voices in the mirror that tell you to
kill them all. Going through more careers (secretary, stripper,
madam, designer) in a season than most of us do in a lifetime.
Thinking vodka could help the pain only to find it sent you on
rip-snorting dish-crashing rampages. Rigging promotions by digging
up dirt on your bosses _ and getting away with it.
</P>
<P>
   In Melrose's heyday, roughly 1993-1995, Heather Locklear and
company made inspired TV not just by going over the top. They
out-soaped all the competition with a psychotic beauty that was the
guiltiest of guilty pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping tonight's series finale, titled ``Asses to
Ashes,'' does them proud.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
