</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVFINALES-WRAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big finales: Well-loved series given last hurrahs
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most TV series just drift away into the atmosphere. Somewhere,
their signals headed away from Earth and our consciousness, are
``L.A. Doctors'' and ``Brimstone'' and so many forgettable others,
canceled without so much as a burp of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Others get the big send-off, out of longevity, network loyalty,
star clout. And the biggest of these attain a combination of hype
and viewer interest that surpasses Super Bowls _ the finales of
``MASH,'' ``Mary Tyler Moore,'' ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing this season can match those farewells, but three
long-running series over the next two days take their final bows
with splashy goodbyes: ``Mad About You'' (9 tonight on NBC
(43786)), ``Melrose Place'' (8 tonight on Fox (77704)) and ``Home
Improvement'' (8 p.m. Tuesday on ABC (47800)).
</P>
<P>
   All three series are well past their prime as hits, yet each
was, in its day and in its way, quite a favorite. ``Home
Improvement'' was once No. 1, a family-friendly show that parents
could trust. ``Mad About You'' got bounced around the schedule but
people kept watching. ``Melrose Place,'' after Heather Locklear
joined the cast and it turned from earnest Yuppie drama into
unabashed soap, had fans gathered in bars on Monday nights to watch
and hoot.
</P>
<P>
   They're not the only series getting a network-noted exit this
month. ``The Nanny'' got all misty-water-colored-memoried two weeks
ago; NBC let ``Homicide'' have a sense of closure on Friday, and
two WB series, ``Unhappily Ever After'' and ``Sister, Sister,'' had
finale episodes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The series finale dates to 1967 and ``The Fugitive,'' when
Richard Kimball finally caught that one-armed man. Over the years,
we've seen finales in which ``St. Elsewhere'' was turned upside
down as merely the long-running fantasy of an autistic child, and
``Newhart'' was exposed as just a dream dreamed by Bob Newhart on
his previous series.
</P>
<P>
   Not every series can, or should, have a finale with that level
of twistedness. In the brutal, get-the-hook world of network TV,
just getting a finale is accomplishment enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melrose Place''
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Jack Wagner and Heather Locklear among many others.
</P>
<P>
   Final episode: 8 tonight on Fox
</P>
<P>
   Seasons running: 7
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad About You''
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Helen Hunt and Paul Reiser
</P>
<P>
   Final episode: 9 tonight on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Seasons running: 7
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement''
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Tim Allen and Patricia Richardson
</P>
<P>
   Final episode: 8 p.m. Tuesday on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Seasons running: 8
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
