<P>
   &UR; HOW TO HELP YOURSELF IN EVERY WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jonathan Bines &LR;  and  &UR; Gary Greenberg &LR; 's new ``Self Helpless''
(Career; $12.95) describes a range of non- &LR; existent self-help books
that includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Book of Rhetorical Questions,'' endorsed by the author
of ``The Pope Is Catholic; Answers to Rhetorical Questions.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``The Stella Stein Prophesy,'' in which Mrs. Stein predicts
what may happen to you, for example, if you don't have a good
reading light or don't sit far enough away from the TV.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Attention Deficit Disorder: Help is.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Reviving Ophelia; the Royal Shakespeare Company's Emergency
Preparedness Handbook,'' which tells what to do, for example, when
``the wind machine blows  &UR; King Lear &LR;  into the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WORD'S THE THING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - There's a problem with the location of that huge ``Re-Elect
Mayor  &UR; Willie Brown &LR; '' sign on the plumbers' union headquarters on
Market Street, notes  &UR; Paul Spiegel &LR; . The building is at the foot of
Franklin, visible all the way up the street. But traffic on
Franklin is one-way north, so the sign is visible mainly in
rear-view mirrors, and so it appears backward. Too bad the building
isn't at the bottom of Gough Street, suggests Spiegel, ``where
drivers in traffic on the way to the freeway and Market Street
could take a long and thoughtful look.''
</P>
<P>
   - That San Francisco bus shelter ad picturing a urine specimen
bottle with the simple words, ``Your boyfriend. 43 seconds. Taking
the STD test even quicker,'' wasis &LR;  posted by St. James Infirmary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Barbara Fritz &LR;  is impressed at the Martin Windows' catalog
quoting the classics _ ``They can do all because they think they
can'' _ but thinks the company's erudition ought to extend to the
spelling of the author's name, which ain't Vergil.
</P>
<P>
   - A fine year for squash in Chico:  &UR; Morgan Omaha &LR; , 5, inspected
his family's vegetable patch and ran inside exclaiming ``There's an
enormous Lamborghini in the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Sharon Stone &LR;  has turned over to Beverly Hills police one
shotgun and three handguns she said she kept for protection. She
issued a statement saying she'd been motivated by the Littleton
shootings, &LR;  to do her part to ``change our world into a safer, more
loving, more thoughtful environment for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Kate Moss &LR; , recently out of rehab, is reported to have fallen
off the wagon at the Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   - Two thousand members of the American Psychiatric Association,
convening at Constitution Hall in Washington last week, were heard
singing, ``Getting to Know You,'' ``The Impossible Dream'' and ``I
Gotta Be Me.'' A San Diego psychiatrist who arranged the sing-along
told the Washington Post that his colleagues ``really need music to
come together.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Reese Ehrlich &LR; , just back from Caracas, Venezuela, reports
wistfully that public transportation there, clean and efficient,
costs the equivalent of 40 cents a ride.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Edwin Heaven &LR;  sends advance word that Starship, nee Jefferson
Airplane nee the band that once commanded motherandsoforth to
``tear down the walls,'' will appear on ``The Donnie and Marie
Show'' on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   - National Accordion Awareness Month being June,  &UR; Tom Torriglia &LR; 
certifies that the instrument ``has just been certified as being
Y2K compliant. ... Can you say that with absolute certainty about
any other musical instrument?''
</P>
<P>
   - New York writer  &UR; David Margolick &LR; , who's doing a book on
 &UR; Billie Holiday  &LR; and the political implications of ``Strange
Fruit,'' says she sang it often in repeated club gigs in San
Francisco in the '40s and '50s. ``Strange Fruit'' was written by
 &UR; Abel Mirapol, &LR;  a left-wing schoolteacher who is the adoptive father
of the sons of  &UR; Ethel &LR;  and  &UR; Julius Rosenberg &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Margolick wants to interview people who heard her perform the
song live, or were influenced by her recording of it. He's at 315
West 86 Street, No. 14F, New York, N.Y. 10024; or at
damarg &LR; aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Debbie Reynolds was indeed the girl next door, if you lived
next door to a self-centered, totally driven, insecure, untruthful
phony.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Eddie Fisher  &LR; in his forthcoming memoir, ``Been There, Done
That,'' to be published by St. Martin's in September. The book is
his second autobiography, the first of which didn't tell all. The
passage was quoted by MSNBC.
</P>
