A7965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATIN-MUSIC-BOOM-2TAK     05-23 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-MUSIC-BOOM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN MUSICIANS DISCOVER NEW WORLD'S TO CONQUER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ricky Martin, Ricky Martin, Ricky Martin. The name has become
some sort of Gertrude Stein exercise since Martin put a match to
the tinder of the pop-music world with his performance at the
Grammy Awards in February. He has not dropped out of sight since,
riding his hit ``Livin' La Vida Loca.'' He has become a symbol on
two sexy feet of Latin culture's new mainstream status in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's Latino credentials are in order: he is originally from
Puerto Rico and had a stint in the Spanish-language teeny-bop
supergroup Menudo. But his album ``Ricky Martin,'' which hit the
No. 1 spot on Billboard's pop chart in its first week, is in
English and features Madonna. Martin is a U.S. citizen, speaks
English, acted in the soap opera ``General Hospital'' and dyes his
hair blond.
</P>
<P>
   While it is tempting to see in his success the mainstream
rushing to embrace Latin culture, Martin, who has been a Latin and
international idol for at least five years, became acceptable to
the English-speaking audience only recently, when he recorded in
English.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony, Martin is talented,
photogenic and bilingual; they have all decided to sing in English.
But to understand the inroads that Latin music is making in the
United States, one also must listen to Elvis Crespo sing in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The energetic, black-haired Crespo released his second album,
``Pintame,'' last week; it hit the Billboard pop charts at No. 49.
``Pintame'' is in Spanish. It has no guests from the
English-speaking world. It uses no deracinated international pop
styles, as do the majority of the Spanish-speaking pop stars, from
Julio Iglesias to Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Crespo's album was not created to infiltrate the
English-speaking market, though a few concessions have been made
and it will surely cross over. Most important, it is hard,
danceable tropical music. It is unapologetic merengue, a form from
the Dominican Republic that in the hands of Crespo is becoming one
of the biggest international dance styles since the mambo traveled
around the world from Havana in the mid-1950's.
</P>
<P>
   That English speakers are buying the album tells an important
story, especially to English speakers who are only now becoming
aware of the extraordinary amount of talent and variety that Latin
music offers. But it is hardly the only story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to say it, really, but in some senses we don't
need the English-speaking market,'' said Oscar Llord, the president
of Crespo's label, Sony Discos, the Latin branch of Columbia
Records. ``Remember, we've sold half a million copies of Elvis'
first album, `Suavemente,' in Europe, and we still haven't really
started the campaign there on his behalf. The European market is
humongous, enormous, as is the Latin-speaking market here and in
Latin America. Really, when you speak about the Latin market now,
you're talking universally.''
</P>
<P>
   The album ``Suavemente'' rode a hit of the same name, using the
tough, repetitious rhythms of merengue. Crespo, like Martin, grew
up in Puerto Rico; he was born in New York and traveled between the
two.
</P>
<P>
   He started professionally as an older teen-ager, singing chorus
in famous merengue bands in Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic,
including Tono Rosario's band and Grupo Mania, whose bigger hits
featured Crespo as a lead singer. A year and a half ago he started
on his own. He had no idea what was going to happen to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have changed so much for Latin artists in the last two
years,'' said Crespo, who was in New York to perform at a concert
put on by an English-language radio station. ``When I started out,
Latin music, regional music, wasn't part of America. We were off to
the side. But look at the success that so many Latinos have had,
even if they're working in English, whether it be Ricky or Jennifer
Lopez. They've all helped open the door. If I had started my career
two years earlier, I wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Crespo, who is taking English lessons to polish up a language he
had been forgetting, is right, for several reasons. One important
reason is that Sound-scan, a service that counts album sales, has
over the last several years begun to move into Latin record stores,
especially in Puerto Rico, to report on sales there. Two years ago,
before that effort began, Crespo's ``Pintame'' would not have
registered as highly on the Billboard charts as it has, even if the
sales had been the same. Soundscan was literally blind to Latin
sales.
</P>
<P>
   A result of increased accuracy on the part of Soundscan has been
that the Latin sections of record stores are expanding across the
country, and chains that never had a Latin section are now carrying
Spanish- language albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``As record stores see the increased Soundscan numbers, they
respond by expanding the sections,'' Llord said. ``When you expand
a section, you sell more.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps English-speaking fans are changing their tastes a bit,
venturing out of linguistic limitations and into a broader vision
of Americana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids go for beats first,'' Llord said. ``Then they think about
language, and what Elvis is offering is some of the best beats
around. It's music that makes you feel good, regardless of the
language.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important reason of all is simple: the demographic. The
Latin population of the United States now numbers some 30 million
(most under age 30), and the Census Bureau expects it to overtake
the country's black population in a few years. The No. 1 FM radio
stations in New York, Los Angeles and Chicago are Spanish-language
stations.
</P>
<P>
   But the Latin population is not one monolithic entity, and the
Latin music world is split into different markets, including
Mexican pop, Mexican regional, salsa, merengue, cumbia from
Colombia, rock in Spanish and more. The reason for the success of
the biggest Latin pop singers is that they usually resort to a
bland international pop style to bridge the various communities. A
Mexican usually listens to Mexican music, a Cuban to Cuban music.
When all the different Spanish-speaking populations come together
to buy one type of music, all the movement creates a hit.
</P>
<P>
   In Crespo's case he tapped into a type of music that has become
the international dance style of choice, without losing its
regional wrinkles. Merengue is heard at poolside in Havana and at
clubs in New York. It is heard in Paris and all over the rest of
Europe. At the Copacabana in New York, a Honduran woman will dance
merengue with a Puerto Rican man; Dominicans dance it, and Mexicans
and so do French tourists. It is easy to dance to, and fun, and
every tourist who has spent time in the Caribbean has heard it.
</P>
<P>
   Crespo, 27, sold somewhere between 30,000 and 90,000 copies of
``Pintame'' two weeks ago. ``Pintame'' may have reached the highest
chart position for regional records to date, and its success is far
from over.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Pintame' is selling much faster than `Suavemente' did,''
Llord said. ``We've already sold 1.5 million copies of
`Suavemente,' and the record isn't finished yet.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But Crespo made some concessions. Merengue is close to being the
fastest music man has ever played. He slowed it down, put some
groove back into it and plied the songs with obvious melodies. He
accentuated the bass, making it closer in depth and volume to
hip-hop. Then there were the remixes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar Llord wanted me to do a Spanglish remix of
`Suavemente,''' Crespo said. ``So I did it. It came out in the
movie `Dance With Me,' and then all of a sudden it became an
English pop hit. It was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Llord said: ``Merengue is great because everybody understands
it. It's great for remixes because it has a solid, four-four beat;
it's not complicated. You can play remixes of it on English pop
stations here, and in clubs in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a Spanglish version because that's the way kids
are today. I have two teen-age daughters, and that's the way they
speak. Our parents were ashamed of being immigrants, but our kids
aren't. They aren't afraid to say, `I love Ricky Martin, and I also
love Tom Cruise.'''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Crespo is being courted by the English-language media,
even if he is singing, at best, in Spanglish _ the Spanglish
version of the song ``Pintame'' comes out in a week _ and has not
dyed his hair blond, though an English-language album is probably
inevitable. He performed on ``Late Night With David Letterman''
several weeks ago; other shows are lining up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a tropical artist, and so I started doing research on
Latin music,'' said Sheila Rogers, a music producer for the
Letterman show. ``People had seen him at the Billboard Latin award,
and said he blew everybody away, and so we booked him and at the
show people were dancing in the aisles, which doesn't happen very
much. So the response was fantastic, and we plan to do it more. I
want to get Marc Anthony, and Shakira.''
</P>
<P>
   But the English-speaking world is not the target. Llord and
Crespo have not fully conquered Latin America and Spain yet, and
the first thing on their agenda is to tour there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good moment for us Latinos, lots of happiness,'' Crespo
said. ``We're going to be going lots of places where we weren't
seen before. I used to be something tropical, local. Now I'm the
taste everybody wants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
