<HEADER>
A7967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSWEEK-MEACHAM-MEDI     05-23 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSWEEK-MEACHAM-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 30 AND CLIMBING THE MASTHEAD, NEWSWEEK EDITOR EARNS BEGRUDGING
RESPECT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jon Meacham, a stolid fellow known in the Newsweek offices for
his neatly combed hair and carefully chosen words, has a bust of
George Bush on the shelf next to his desk. An authority on
civil-rights history and World War II arcana, Meacham drinks Jack
Daniels, loves to talk about his wife _ ``she's a real Mississippi
Delta girl,'' he said _ and goes to church on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Meacham has also been part of the team supervising coverage of
dozens of national news stories, from the 1996 presidential
campaign to Monica Lewinsky for the magazine owned by the
Washington Post Co. Last November, he was named managing editor, a
title he shares with Ann McDaniel, Newsweek's longtime Washington
bureau chief.
</P>
<P>
   If Meacham sounds like _ let's be blunt _ a vastly experienced
old fogey ticking off the days to retirement, read on: Meacham,
arguably one of the most influential editors in the news magazine
business, was still in his 20s last week. On May 20, he finally
passed over the epic chronological cusp of 30, an age when most
newsweekly journalists are still grinding out articles, not
overseeing a magazine staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my age is an issue,'' Meacham said in an
interview on his birthday (Thursday) in his Manhattan office (the
size of a studio apartment, which is what most of his college
classmates are probably still living in) overlooking Central Park.
Meacham pointed out that Richard M. Smith, Newsweek's editor in
chief and chairman, doesn't care either. ``He believes in `Throw
them in the deep end of the pool and see if they can swim.'''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Isikoff, the Newsweek correspondent whose reporting
helped to uncover the Lewinsky affair, refers tartly to Meacham in
his book ``Uncovering Clinton: A Reporter's Story'' as ``the `Boy
Wonder' nation editor.'' Around the Newsweek offices, Meacham's
reputation is that of a man so methodical _ although his youth and
relative inexperience have rankled some staff members _ that
colleagues often referred to his age by reversing the numerals,
said one editor; when Meacham was 27, for example, they considered
him 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that we all thought, when we learned he was going
to be the nation editor, well, gosh, he's awfully young,'' Isikoff
said. ``But he certainly filled the role pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Meacham is a bit of an anomaly, although there is historical
precedent. After all, Briton Hadden and Henry R. Luce founded Time
magazine when they were in their early 20s. But the standard
trajectory in the newsweekly business has been to rise through the
reporting ranks _ as Whitaker and Ms. McDaniel did _ before
assuming the authority of senior editorial roles. At 29, for
example, Ms. McDaniel was covering the Supreme Court and the
Justice Department for Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess I was no slouch,'' Ms. McDaniel said. ``But it
did take me until I was 42 to be named managing editor.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Chattanooga, Tenn., Meacham spent most of his childhood
at the knee of his grandfather, a prominent Chattanooga judge.
``Every morning at ten, he had this group of old guys at the
Downtown Hotel who would meet for coffee, five days a week, every
day except for Christmas,'' Meacham said. ``I remember that the
governor would stop by, and Al Gore would stop by,'' he said,
referring to the father of the vice president. ``So my earliest
memories are talk of politics and personalities, from what was
going on in Watergate to who was going to become the new county
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Meacham said that because Chattanooga was a relatively isolated
city, in terms of news, in the 1970s and 1980s, newsweekly
magazines were cherished objects. ``It was before the national
edition of newspapers and before CNN, and so Time and Newsweek
played a huge cultural role,'' he said. Tuesdays, the day Time and
Newsweek arrived, ``were a big day in my house.''
</P>
<P>
   He majored in English at the University of the South in Sewanee,
Tenn., purposefully skipped journalism school, going to work as a
reporter at The Chattanooga Times instead. After a year, he went to
work for The Washington Monthly, which _ for the annual salary of
$10,000 _ he was put through what he referred to as ``journalism
boot camp'' and caught the eye of Newsweek's editor, Maynard
Parker, who died last year.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's Time, Newsweek and U.S. News &AMP; World Report have
watched their readers age during the last decade; to thrive they
must attract younger readers with ever-younger editors. Stephen A.
Douglas, the general partner at the Douglas Jones Group, a research
firm for the advertising industry, said that aging readership is a
special concern for the newsweeklies, and pointed out that in 1985
the median age of Newsweek's readership was 37, and in 1998, it was
43.2.
</P>
<P>
   ``A news magazine has a bunch of old editors, and sometimes
having a young editor brings a different perspective the readers
can sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that ``no one has ever asked or considered how old
someone was around here.'' He added: ``Jon's a wonderful writer. He
sees stories whole and he sees packages of stories whole. He has a
great sense about how to make the words and the pictures and the
organization of cover packages accessible, entertaining and
informative for the readers. That's not an age-specific thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But does Meacham risk cultivating too stodgy an image with his
old-fashioned demeanor, his bourbon habits and his membership in
the Council on Foreign Relations? ``No,'' Meacham said, explaining
that he was a ``term member'' of the Council. ``That means I'm
junior league. Just a pledge. That means I run around getting them
drinks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
