<HEADER>
A7970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-950(2     05-23 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAMP OF HOPE AND FEAR FOR KOSOVO REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FIER, Albania _ In a place called Fier, pronounced fear, there
is a camp called Hope, and the Americans who are building the camp
hope that thousands of Kosovo refugees will come to safety here
until they can return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the refugees' fear of coming this far south seems to
be winning out over hope.
</P>
<P>
   The first 2,500 of an estimated 20,000 refugees who are supposed
to resettle in Camp Hope have moved into large green military tents
erected by an American company under a contract with the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them are not the refugees who have clustered near the
Kosovo border in northern Albania and whom relief agencies had
encouraged to relocate here. Rather, most are like Bali Muza, who
moved here last week from an old chicken farm nearby, where he had
been living in squalid conditions for several weeks since fleeing
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions there were horrible, and gangsters come over
every day to start trouble,'' said Muza, 66, who comes from the
village of Jashanica in western Kosovo. ``When they told me I could
come here, I said yes right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees to persuade
people who settled in and around the northern Albanian city of
Kukes to relocate for their own safety have by and large failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been very successful,'' said Ray Wilkinson, an
agency spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Kukes was supposed to be a temporary transit point for refugees.
About 300,000 refugees have passed through the city on their way to
more secure destinations farther from the often-tense border with
Yugoslavia, just over 10 miles from Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   But more than 100,000 refugees have put down roots in Kukes and
remain there in increasingly desperate conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Many are reluctant to leave the border area either because they
expect _ unrealistically _ to return to Kosovo soon, or because
they continue to wait for family members to cross. Others say they
will not leave because they have not been given enough information
about where they will be taken.
</P>
<P>
   The area is dangerous, in part, because Kosovo rebels have set
up operations there, and several Serbian rockets have already
landed nearby. And the longer the refugees remain in Kukes, the
more determined local Albanian officials become to force them out.
Water is getting scarce, and the decrepit city of 20,000 residents
is unable to cope with the burden of caring for so many refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Albanian special policemen armed with automatic weapons
have gone through one camp frightening the refugees and ordering
them to move.
</P>
<P>
   After that episode, the U.N. refugee agency persuaded the
government to suspend such aggressive actions and to give the
agency time to encourage the refugees to leave on their own.
</P>
<P>
   But after several information campaigns, and a day spent flying
refugee leaders to new destinations and then bringing them back to
Kukes to brief others, few refugees who are already in camps in
Kukes have voluntarily agreed to uproot themselves again.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. policy is not to force refugees to leave, and they do
not want to close the camps at Kukes because the flow of refugees
continues. At the same time, the U.N. policy is not to keep
refugees within 50 miles of a contentious border. And, the flow
continues, including 1,000 men who came over on Saturday and Sunday
after being released from Serbian prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only want to be here. We don't even want to look at any
other camps,'' a refugee leader named Rahim Ymeri said at a news
conference that the refugees organized in Kukes recently.
</P>
<P>
   With estimates that it may take as long as two years before all
refugees can return safely to Kosovo, the relief agencies are
forced to confront the reality of long-term stays. Unlike the
northern camps, most of Camp Hope has been designed as an
all-weather, year-round camp, although the bulk of the tents will
not be erected for several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance of the refugees to move again underscores some of
the problems that have plagued relief organizations _ and in
particular the United Nations _ since NATO began bombing Yugoslavia
in March.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee agency ``has not taken the leadership role that it
normally would have taken in a situation like this,'' said Barbara
Shenstone, a program manager with CARE International, which is
running Camp Hope. ``It seems like they've always been behind the
wave, never in front.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that they want the United Nations to lead
relief efforts, CARE and other agencies have said the scale of the
crisis here appears to have overwhelmed the High Commissioner for
Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not been as strong on the ground as they should have
been,'' said John Sargent, a spokesman for Oxfam, an international
aid agency. In part, he said, ``The U.N. appears to have been
sidelined by individual agencies setting up operations outside of
their control.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other refugee crises, like those in Africa, this one
has been very visible. Because it has taken place right in Europe,
it was much easier, and much more politically rewarding, for nearby
governments and agencies to come in on their own, said Wilkinson,
the refugee agency spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Italian government established its own camp at a
prominent spot on the only road leading from the border crossing at
Morina to Kukes. It is a first-class camp, with tents, water and a
clinic, and the refugees who settled there have been reluctant to
leave it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the camps are almost too good,'' Sargent said. ``They
use too many resources, and if everyone did the same, it all would
collapse.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Greek government also established a well-organized camp near
Kukes, and the United Arab Emirates has built a large camp that
includes a field hospital and a mosque, in a show of Muslim
brotherhood with the largely Muslim Albanian-speaking refugees from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After about a month, the Italian and Greek governments pulled
out and left the operation of the camps to relief agencies. CARE
International now runs one of two Italian camps and tries to
encourage refugees there to move to Camp Hope.
</P>
<P>
   Individual agencies, including Doctors Without Borders, have
established their own camps in Kukes. In many cases, negotiations
were conducted directly with the government of Albania and local
landowners, and not through the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Relief efforts have been hampered by land-ownership problems in
Albania. When the Communist government collapsed in 1990-91, all
land was in state hands. But since then, conflicting land claims
have made negotiating leases a nightmare. Camp Hope is situated in
an isolated salt marsh near the Adriatic Sea because it is one of
the few large parcels with clear title: The Albanian government
still owns it.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee agency concedes that it did not bring in enough
people at the beginning of the crisis to coordinate the activities
of all the camps and the more than 100 individual relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Money has been a problem. For weeks, the United Nations has been
saying the costs of moving refugees and feeding them have exhausted
all of its reserves, while only half of a $140 million emergency
appeal for additional funds has been met. Raising money has been
difficult in this crisis because traditional U.N. donors are also
being solicited by the other aid agencies working in Albania,
Macedonia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the presence of NATO has presented yet more
challenges in terms of communicating needs and coordinating relief
efforts. NATO trucks have at times gone back to Tirana with
supplies, planning to bring refugees back south, but have returned
empty because the relief agencies were unable to gather refugees at
the time or place NATO needed them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the delays, Chris Sykes, a CARE coordinator, is certain
that refugees will come to Camp Hope. ``One way or another,'' he
said, ``this camp will be filled.''
</P>
<P>
   Agron Lama moved into the camp a few days ago after having lived
in five previous camps across Albania, most recently in the city of
Fier.
</P>
<P>
   Lama speaks some English, and one of the first things he did
after arriving here was to use smooth river stones to spell out the
camp's name, Hope, in English at the entrance to the tent where he
now lives with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stands for the camp,'' he said, ``and also our hope for a
better future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
