<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENCE-TURNER-COX     05-23 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-TURNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ted Turner feels partly responsible for school violence
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Maybe it's time to find a new nickname for Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ''Captain Outrageous'' actually was something closer to
courageous here Saturday night, refusing to follow the example of
so many others in the entertainment and media business by dodging
questions about the recent spate of school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Turner brought up the subject himself in accepting the
Denver Press Club's fifth annual Damon Runyon Award. Days after the
shootings at Columbine High School near Denver, Turner said, CNN
and Time Magazine asked 500 teenagers about possible causes. While
availability of guns ranked No. 1, the amount of violence in
television, movies, music and the news followed close behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to feel partly responsible for that,'' said Turner,
the founder of CNN and now vice chairman of the Time Warner
multimedia empire of which CNN is a part. ''I've never made any
gratuitously violent movies, but I'm certainly in the news
business, and we show a lot of violent stuff on the news,'' Turner
said.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke two days after the shootings at Heritage High School
outside Atlanta _ ``my hometown,'' he sighed _ and 10 hours after
Columbine's graduation ceremony was carried live on CNN. The Damon
Runyon dinner was originally scheduled just three days after the
Columbine shooting but was postponed largely at Turner's
suggestion, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been extraordinarily generous with his time,'' Denver
Post columnist Chuck Green said of Turner, who flew in just before
a hailstorm raked Denver on Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Denver Mayor Wellington Webb declared Saturday ``Ted
Turner Day'' in that city, despite Turner's ``tearing the baseball
heart out'' of the region last year by making Atlanta Braves of
popular Colorado Rockies players Andres Galarraga and Walt Weiss. A
local a capella quintet performed ''Sailing,'' in honor of Turner's
1977 America's Cup victory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the press club bent its own rules in giving Turner
the Runyon Award, which usually goes to newspaper writers such as
Jimmy Breslin and the late Mike Royko and which is named for the
long-ago Denver journalist whose fiction about a lovable group of
gamblers spawned ``Guys and Dolls.'' The press club began in 1884
as a floating poker game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Turner is a writer, but not in the traditional sense,''
said Green. ''He writes the course of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's colorful speech traced his own roll-the-dice news
broadcasting career, from the early days at TBS when an announcer
simply read newspaper headlines aloud at 3 a.m. to the glory days
of CNN. But he frequently touched on current events, as when he
called for NATO to stop bombing Yugoslavia. Among his many reasons:
the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``People watch CNN all over the world,'' Turner pointed out as
his audience roared with laughter. ''So when they bomb 'em, they're
bombing my customers!''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rocky Mountain News reporter and dinner organizer John
Ensslin: ``He's definitely the most Runyonesque character around
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
