u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-2TAKE     05-23 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS YELTSIN GOES ON VACATION, RUSSIANS WONDER WHERE THE POWER
RESIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Having fired a government, squelched an impeachment
drive and installed a colorless but loyal police commander as prime
minister and potential successor, Russian President Boris Yeltsin
headed south Friday for what his aides described as a well-deserved
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   As for ordinary Russians, they were left _ once again _ out in
the cold, and in the dark. If the extraordinary events of the last
11 days proved anything, it was that Russia's fledgling democracy
is as secretive, and arcane, as the Communist regime it replaced
seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinion of the silent majority _ that is at least 77
percent of the population which does not want to see upheavals _ is
ignored,'' said Vyacheslav Nikonov, head of the Poliika Foundation,
a political think-tank. ``The authorities and public opinion have
in the past week been acting totally at cross purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the name of stopping a purported Communist comeback,
spearheaded by former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's popular if
inactive government, the Kremlin has reverted to form. Now it's
back to the days of `cadres' (an old Soviet term for personnel) and
clans, of backroom deals and hidden agendas, of rumors and oblique
hints.
</P>
<P>
   Russian politics have never been free of intrigue, but the
eight-month tenure of Primakov, whose coalition Cabinet included
Communist ministers and was backed by Yeltsin's Communist
opposition, did mark the first attempt by the Yeltsin
administration to rule not by confrontation, but consensus.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't last. ``The consensus model of government suited an
overwhelming majority of the population, and an overwhelming
majority of the elite,'' said Nikonov. ``But it sidelined the
president's administration, and reduced its ability to play the
decisive role in deciding who would be Yeltsin's successor.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Kremlin's view, Primakov's coalition government had
overshot its role as a guarantor of stability, and was rapidly
becoming a launching pad for the Communist party's long-term
ambitions _ first as a source of financial support for coming
parliamentary elections and for Primakov's own anticipated
candidacy in the June 2000 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to Primakov's firing, Yeltsin's advisers
took pains to depict the power struggle in Manichean terms. On the
eve of the government shake-up, one top Kremlin official described
the prime minister as ``strategically dangerous,'' a man who if
allowed to govern Russia until 2000, would emerge as a ``cross
between (Communist party leader Gennadi) Zyuganov and Stalin.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Primakov out of power, some Kremlin advisers are
talking about grooming his successor, Sergei Stepashin, a
47-year-old veteran of Russia's security services, as Yeltsin's
latest heir, an alternative not only to the Communists but also to
Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, a leading presidential aspirant.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Luzhkov was in good favor with Yeltsin. Now, after
failing a number of loyalty tests, he is again feeling a cold wind
blowing from the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin's success hinges on his ability to survive the coming
year, until the eve of presidential elections scheduled for June
2000. In that time, he must negotiate the passage of tough fiscal
legislation required to ward off Russia's default on foreign loans,
and navigate parliamentary elections due in December.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, he must survive the whims of an emotional and jealous
president who could at any moment overturn the best of strategies.
Among the wild cards now said to be under consideration is a
popular referendum to unite Russia with Belarus, its western Slavic
neighbor, in a union that would throw Russia's political calendar
wide open because it would create a new entity in need of a new _
or old _ president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Stepashin manages to stay and be the last premier before
the elections, he has a very good chance to become a presidential
candidate supported not only by the Kremlin _ which is important,
but not that important _ and the regional elite which is more
important, and key political forces,'' said Alexander Shokhin, a
former minister and centrist Duma deputy. ``So far, he has a
chance, provided he is not fired in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin's credentials for his new role are still obscure. His
record as head of Russia's domestic intelligence service was
blotted by a disastrous performance in the early days of Moscow's
conflict with the breakaway republic of Chechnya. His views on
economics are pretty much a blank but his loyalty to Yeltsin _ with
whom he began his national career _ is absolute.
</P>
<P>
   As one recent poll indicated, many Russians are ready for a
law-and-order candidate, and Stepashin holds the rank of colonel
general in Russia's interior forces. Others look to Stepashin, son
of a naval officer from St. Petersburg, as an example of a new
generation of more mild-mannered, urbane politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we voting for Sergei Stepashin?'' asked Vladimir
Zhironovsky, Russia's most virulently anti-Communist nationalist,
during the debate that ended last Wednesday with Stepashin's
overwhelming confirmation as prime minister on first try. ``Simply
because we are sick and tired of people from the sticks. For the
first time in the past 100 years, someone from St. Petersburg will
head the government.''
</P>
<P>
   As Stepashin learns the ropes, who is running the country these
days?
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious answer is Yeltsin himself. After a winter of
hibernation, the 68-year-old president roared back to center stage
in the spring, despite an apparent _ but officially unconfirmed _
physical relapse. In recent appearances, his step has been
unsteady, his speech labored, and even slurred, and his
off-the-cuff comments confused.
</P>
<P>
   Behind him, stands a tiny group of Kremlin insiders who include
top members of his administration as well as his daughter Tatyana
Dyachenko.
</P>
<P>
   This group, known here simply as the ``Family,'' has became the
conduit for a remarkable comeback by two of Russia's most
politically unpopular figures _ Anatoly Chubais, a liberal reformer
and former privatization czar, and if press reports are to be
believed, Boris Berezovsky, a multibillionaire financier with
irrepressible political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais has all but openly admitted his role in the decision,
made late on May 11 at the Kremlin , to fire Primakov and replace
him with Stepashin. Interviewed by Newsweek magazine, Chubais, now
head of the national electric utility company, called the
appointment of Stepashin ``a strategic and reasonable step by
Yeltsin.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Kremlin strategies are not always smoothly executed, as
became embarrassingly apparent on May 12, the day that Primakov's
firing was announced.
</P>
<P>
   First, Gennadi Seleznyov, the Communist speaker of the
parliament's lower house, told deputies that he had had a call from
the president, informing him that the next prime minister would be
Nikolai Aksyonenko, a little-known railways minister (since
promoted to become Stepashin's first deputy prime minister).
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, Seleznyov again interrupted the proceedings with
the news that a letter from the Kremlin had arrived, nominating
Stepashin as prime minister. Seleznyov smiled, and shrugged. ``I
came to work today with clean ears, and my telephone is working,''
he said, as the deputies roared with laughter. ``The president told
me Aksyonenko, which is what I told you.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Russian politicians, journalists and analysts are convinced
that the president's confusion may not have been accidental. As the
haggling over Stepashin's Cabinet appointments moves into full
swing, the newspapers have been full of reports of a struggle
between Chubais, and Berezovsky, who reportedly backed the
Aksyonenko nomination.
</P>
<P>
   How much real influence is wielded by Berezovsky is difficult to
gauge since his Kremlin access reportedly goes directly through
Mrs. Dyachenko, the youngest of the president's two daughters and
his political counselor since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin Yumashev and Alexander Voloshin, the Kremlin's former
and current chief of staff respectively, each have ties to
Berezovsky. A master of intrigue who is said to have taken care of
the Yeltsin family finances, Berezovsky is also a master of
illusion, and of the well-planted leak designed to suggest _
without proof _ that his political comeback is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky is the most notorious of the so-called oligarchs who
made fortunes in the early days of Russia's chaotic privatization.
As long as Primakov was in power, Berezovsky was on the defensive,
targeted by a series of well-publicized corruption probes that
threatened to creep into the Kremlin itself.
</P>
<P>
   When Primakov was fired, Berezovsky _ then in France _ lept back
into the limelight with a statement that portrayed the decision as
a triumph of good over evil. ``Primakov's dismissal is not just a
replacement of one person to the post of prime minister for
another, it is ``an abortion of an attempt for a Communist and KGB
revenge in Russia,'' Berezovsky told the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   As for Stepashin, the financier's praise was lukewarm.
``Stepashin doubtless shares the president's ideology and will
doubtless follow the course of reforms,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
