</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTOPHER COX: THE RENAISSANCE CONGRESSMAN WHO PRESIDED OVER SPY
INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(ms) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He is something of a closet Renaissance man in the
House, one who speaks Russian, savors Ayn Rand and seeks out the
latest translation of Omar Khayyam. For a hobby, he reads book
after book on mathematicians. And so Rep. Christopher Cox may seem
the perfect prospect for presiding over the House's arcane and
ultra-secret investigation of suspected espionage by China.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a man who raced through three years of college at the
University of Southern California, then pursued twin degrees in law
and business in the next four years at Harvard ought to be able to
manage one of the most complex and technical, not to mention most
intensely reviewed, redacted and rewritten reports of recent
congressional vintage: the House's tome detailing China's years of
relentless espionage, which will be released to the public Tuesday
morning in its unclassified version.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Ground Hog Day will be over,'' Cox exulted in his office,
saying that after repetitiously renegotiating every jot and tittle
of the report with the administration, he felt like the Bill Murray
character who had to relive a day in Punxsutawney, Pa., over and
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two months we were nowhere,'' said Cox, a California
Republican who headed the House's eight-member select committee
that completed its full Top Secret China report last January, only
to find the task compounded in the negotiations with the White
House over the declassified version. The struggle was
understandable, for the panel's mandate was to delve into President
Clinton's controversial decision to waive export controls over
advanced space technology to China. Beyond missile technology, the
highly sensitive inquiry had subtexts of political fund raising
abuses and global economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially the guts of the report were blacked out,'' said
Cox of White House vettings that required numerous rewritings by
the committee until some acceptable public ground was laboriously
reached.
</P>
<P>
   For all that success, the real achievement by the 46-year-old
chairman may be that his committee conducted its job with
absolutely none of the partisan bombast and political firefights
that have marked five years of congressional investigations of
Clinton by the Capitol's Republican majority. Almost eerily, the
Cox committee stands brickbat free as it quietly moves off stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our report was unanimous because we stuck to the facts,'' said
Cox, carefully praising the committee's minority Democrats, led by
Norman D. Dicks of Washington. ``Things about which we disagreed we
simply left on the cutting room floor because there was so much
that was incontrovertible fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Dicks still sounds amazed. ``There we were, Republicans and
Democrats functioning together in the middle of impeachment,'' he
said. ``Chris Cox has been a man of his word: There were no leaks
during the election. Chris played it straight.'' The Democrat said
that the panel's unusual creation of a joint investigating staff
and even a unified press office set a precedent for cooperation
that will be dearly needed when legislation is proposed to remedy
the security lapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report was worth the wait,'' concluded Cox, exuding a
quiet satisfaction that, whatever public furor may ensue, critics
will be hard pressed to dismiss the report as merely another
partisan salvo. It was as if Cox, a politician ambitious enough to
have vied unsuccessfully for the speakership during last fall's
Republican meltdown, understood that the clever way to stand out in
his China task was to buck the noisy, partisan routine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he says his only real escape from the job lately is
sinking into books about mathematicians. ``It takes me completely
away from work,'' he explained, smiling apologetically at his
six-year binge of math reading. ``A crime novel would only get me
thinking about the crime bill.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an off-handedness to Cox's manner that is belied by his
resume. He sped through the U.S.C., shifting his major to English
after cramming on math. At Harvard he edited the law review. He
eventually was hired as a counsel by the Reagan Administration as a
kind of aberrant whiz kid _ an openly pro-Reagan Harvard man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I actually ever discovered an appetite for
politics,'' said Cox, who was elected to the House in 1988 after he
suddenly decided to enter a primary that already included 13 other
Republicans. ``It was merely impulsive,'' he explained. ``The
Reagan Administration was ending and I needed a job.'' He proved to
be no slouch as a candidate, enlisting the conservative heroes
Robert Bork and Oliver L. North to campaign for him.
</P>
<P>
   His earliest ambition was to be a sports car racer like his
father, a printing executive who competed on the national auto
circuit with his adoring son in tow. ``Eventually it dawned on me
that an abnormal number of my boyhood heroes were deceased because
of that sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox had his own brush with mortality as a law clerk when he
broke his back in a (non-competitive) auto accident. He was
paralyzed for three weeks, an experience that he finds has left him
ever appreciating how wayward life can be in its risks but also its
blessings.
</P>
<P>
   For the latter, he and his wife, Rebecca, who is a vice
president of Continental Airlines, have three children. The
lawmaker celebrated the Cox clan in the Congressional Record last
year, saluting his parents, Marilyn and Charles, on their 50th
wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Twain once remarked that he spent $25 to research his
family tree, and then he had to spend $50 to cover it up,'' the
congressman orated happily, taking time out from the China inquiry.
``Not so the Cox family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
