</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY ELECTS RAU, LONGTIME SOCIAL DEMOCRAT, AS PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Johannes Rau, a moderate Social Democrat, was elected
Sunday to be Germany's eighth postwar president, a largely
ceremonial post whose chief significance lies in its influence on
the nation's conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Rau, 68, won on the second round of voting in the Federal
Convention, a body of 1,338 members made up representatives from
the parliament and regional assemblies in Germany's 16 states. He
will replace Roman Herzog, a conservative from the opposition
Christian Democratic Party, on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in the federal republic's 50-year history,
the election took place in the Reichstag, whose reopening last
month heralded the government's move to Berlin later this year. The
setting of the vote reflected the historic shifts taking place in
Germany that may give Rau a more important role than his
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, presidents have spoken out at times of intense
national questioning to calm spirits and encourage reconciliation.
For example, Herzog has done much to promote understanding between
Germans of the east and west, and his predecessor, Richard von
Weiszaecker, pressed Germans to deal openly with the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the major issues in the country include how to
revive the model of the ``social-market'' economy that served
Germany well in the postwar years but has proved unable to create
jobs in the 1990s, what role Germany should play in a Europe at
war, and how to reconcile an onerous past and ambitious aspirations
in the new capital Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   In an opening speech, Wolfgang Thierse, the speaker of the
parliament, thanked Herzog for his five years of service and said
the presidency expresses ``what binds us as Germans and also how we
will be seen in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rau's qualities as a conciliator are widely recognized. He ran
Germany's most populous state, North Rhine-Westphalia, for 21
years, doing much to turn the area into the country's economic
powerhouse and earning the title of ``the patriarch.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Protestant pastor, he is deeply religious and is
sometimes referred to in the press as ``Brother Johannes.'' He has
a penchant for speaking in deferential riddles rather than forceful
terms, a style that has insured he has few enemies but that could
prove inadequate if Germany's economy falters further and the
national mood turns sour.
</P>
<P>
   Asked before the election _ whose outcome was clear because of
the large Social Democratic majority _ whether he would run for a
second term in 2004, he said, ``We must never say tomorrow I will
do this or that, but accept God's will.''
</P>
<P>
   The liberal weekly Die Zeit suggested that Rau might be too much
of a middle-of-the-road president for a country in need of new
ideas. The paper said he was not the man to push Germans toward
``the uncomfortable reforms that the country needs.''
</P>
<P>
   After the trauma of World War II, Germany's postwar development
was heavily based on an economic model that encouraged solidarity
and provided extensive social insurance. This model has safeguarded
the country from the extremes of social tension that were the
backdrop to Hitler's rise, but has of late appeared rigid, tired
and costly.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder came to power
seven months ago promising to revive an economy that has left more
than four million Germans _ or over 10 percent of the workforce _
unemployed, but has so far been unable to come up with effective
new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from economic issues, Rau may be called upon to give some
guidance on the increasingly disputed and embarrassing question of
a large Holocaust memorial in Berlin that has been planned for a
decade without a decision being made on what should be built.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Rau has expressed skepticism over the current
plan, which calls for a conference center, a museum, a wall of
books and a field of over 2,000 stone columns to be built on a vast
site next to the Brandenburg gate. The Reichstag is to vote on the
project, which is backed by Schroeder, later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rau, who will become Germany's eighth postwar president and only
the second Social Democrat to occupy the post, defeated Dagmar
Schipanski, 55, from the opposition Christian Democratic party and
Uta Ranke-Heinemann, 71, a theologian whose candidacy was backed by
the leftist Party of Democratic Socialism. He won a clear majority
of 690 votes in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his role as moral arbiter, the president's functions
include representing Germany abroad, pardoning convicted criminals,
naming senior officials and magistrates, and approving the
nomination of the chancellor and government ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The new president is married to Christina Delius, the
granddaughter of Germany's third postwar president, Gustav
Heinemann, the only other Social Democrat to have held the office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
