<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, May 24. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ As NATO enters its third month of air
attacks, the Serbian military is sending fresh troops into Kosovo
to shore up its positions near the border with Albania, NATO
officials said Sunday. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The mood in the city. It is
weariness that hangs heavily in the air here, not defeatism. The
citizens of Belgrade, interviewed by the dozen this last week, feel
they are right to be fighting for Kosovo. Some express shame at
what they've heard about the purging of ethnic Albanians; most
express anger at Western support for the secessionist Kosovo
Liberation Army. They're proud of their war, of their brave if
inevitably futile defense against all the might of NATO. They smell
a political settlement that will bring foreign troops into Kosovo,
and they don't know why it's taking so long to write down the
obvious. By Stephen Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Making sense of Russia's political
turmoil. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE (Newnan, Ga.) _ The members of the Coweta County
Board of Education are not naive enough to think that they
vanquished school violence two weeks ago when they voted to
prohibit students from carrying bookbags unless the bags are
transparent or made of mesh. But at least it is something, they
say. And their attitude is not unique: In the month since the
shootings at Columbine High School, school boards, county
commissions and state legislatures all across the country have
proposed and enacted a broad series of measures aimed at attacking
the youth violence problem at the margins. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Undated) _ After decades of flops, $100 billion
in costs and sharp rises in the political stakes, the Pentagon is
trying again to build a system that can defend America against
missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   EMBRYO-RESEARCH (Undated) _ A presidentially-appointed ethics
panel has decided to recommend that the federal government begin
paying for some research on human embryos. A draft report of the
decision to be announced next month concludes that the moral cost
of destroying embryos in research is outweighed by the social good
that could come from the studies. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   APPEALS-COURT (Washington) _ The Federal Appeals Court based in
Richmond, Va. has, in the view of scholars, lawyers and many of its
own members, quietly but steadily become the boldest conservative
court in the nation, setting remarkable new precedents and adopting
a striking tone on several issues. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
</TEXT>
