<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-TEXAS-0524-COX     05-23 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXAS-0524-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE HEADED TO TEXAS, WITH FAITH-VALUES STOPOVER IN ATLANTA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) political categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore makes his first fund-raising
foray into Texas this week as part of a three-day swing through the
Bible Belt in which the one-time divinity student will speak of
religious faith in ways seldom heard from Democratic politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Texas, politically, is indisputably a Republican
state, as well as the home of George W. Bush, the state's popular
governor and overwhelming front-runner for the Republican 2000
presidential nomination, Gore is undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be competitive everywhere,'' Gore spokesman Roger
Salazar said Sunday. ``We're not taking anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians go where the money is. And while it is nearly
impossible to subtract Texas from the Republican column in the
mathematics of presidential politics, it is as important a source
of campaign funds for both parties as is California, New York or
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on Tuesday, while Gore's wife, Tipper, will be hosting
a Gore 2000 fund-raising luncheon in Austin, former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, the vice president's sole opponent for the
Democratic 2000 presidential nomination, will be raising campaign
funds in El Paso and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gore himself will appear at campaign fund-raisers in Dallas and
Houston on Wednesday. The success of those events will indicate how
important Texas is going to be in the vice president's future
fund-raising efforts. ``We'll know soon enough,'' said Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also will lead a conference on empowerment zones in McAllen
on Tuesday, and, with his wife, discuss school safety in Dallas on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the top-billed event of Gore's three-day trip through
Florida, Georgia and Texas is a speech on faith and values the vice
president plans to deliver Monday afternoon at a Salvation Army
cafeteria in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   (Upon his arrival in Atlanta, Gore will be greeted by fire
fighter Matt Mosely, whose daring crane rescue made international
headlines last month.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the only one of the 13 presidential candidates who has
attended divinity school, is expected to call for partnerships
between the federal government and faith-based organizations to
address problems of juvenile crime, poverty, violence, drug
addiction and health care.
</P>
<P>
   The speech appears, in part, to be an attempt to build the
momentum resulting from Gore's dramatic tie-breaking vote to pass
gun control legislation in the Senate last week.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's camp, however, denies the connection.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's vote ``was not about politics _ it was about protecting
America's kids,'' said Gore spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation came in response to the killing of high
school students in Littleton, Colo., a month ago, and was passed
within hours of the wounding of six students at a high school some
25 miles east of the Salvation Army cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a divinity student at Vanderbilt University in 1971, has
occasionally invoked Biblical passages in speaking of the Littleton
tragedy. He also has spoken openly of his own religious faith,
something few Democratic politicians do.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party has ``a large, secular constituency of
nonreligious people who don't react particularly well to religious
language,'' said John C. Green, a political science professor at
the University of Akron who studies the relationship between
politics and religion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gore's interest in getting the government working with
faith-based groups to address social ills has raised some concerns
in organizations that have come into existence to oppose
initiatives of the Christian Coalition and other religious
conservatives with close ties to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic Leadership Council (DLC), the organization
from which many of Gore's ideas come, contends that turning to
faith-based organizations to provide social services will be more
efficient than the bureaucratic, one-size-fits-all approach.
</P>
<P>
   Local institutions and charities ``are a true hope'' for people
in need, said David Kuo, a DLC associate.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
