</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Just one of those days
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When our oldest son was 5, he had to undergo
surgery. A dear friend brought him a book in the hospital, Judith
Viorst's ``Alexander and the Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad
Day.'' It's been one of my favorites ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's day begins badly when he gets out of bed and gum is
stuck in his hair. It only gets worse. His teacher doesn't like his
picture of an invisible castle. His mother forgets to put dessert
in his lunchbox. He goes to the dentist with siblings and he's the
only one with a cavity. His mom makes lima beans for supper and he
hates lima beans. In every respect, it was a terrible, horrible, no
good, very bad day. Alexander wants to move to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   We've had a few of those days through the years. Take a recent
Friday, for example. We returned home from a day trip to find a
crew of workers finishing up our new roof. This was good _ until
the crew boss informed us the skylight we ordered was too small.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can it be too small?'' we asked incredulously. ``We
ordered the size you told us to get.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry. It's too small. You need a larger one.''
</P>
<P>
   We stood there helplessly, looking up at the 4-foot by 4-foot
hole in our newly shingled roof as storm clouds gathered ominously
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we can put a piece of plastic over it for you,'' the
crew boss said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, thank you so much.
</P>
<P>
   As the roofers strung the equivalent of a big trash bag over the
hole, we jumped into our van to go to the building supply store to
look for a larger skylight. My husband turned the ignition key and
. . . click, click, click. We looked at each other. We had just
traveled some 200 miles in this car. What could possibly be wrong
with it?
</P>
<P>
   Click, click, click.
</P>
<P>
   I dropped my head into my hands as my husband went to get
another of our vehicles to try to jump-start the engine. Click,
click, click. Nothing. We went to our last hope, the old Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   With jumper cables draped haphazardly from one car to the other,
I watched as the engine did nothing more than click, click, click.
It didn't work. Maybe it wasn't the battery. Maybe it was something
major that would cost thousands of dollars. Maybe I would just go
to bed at 4 in the afternoon and not get up until the next day.
Maybe I would move to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   We got in the Toyota and went to the store to ask about the
skylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What size?'' the clerk asked with amazement. ``Well, I don't
think they make them that size, but I can call the wholesaler on
Monday and try to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you so very much.
</P>
<P>
   We went home and stretched the heaviest tarp we could find over
our gaping syklight hole, anchoring it with our son's barbell
weights. That was the weekend, of course, when we had several
sudden downpours. Each time, we scaled our kitchen table and gently
poked the tarp upward with a broom handle so that water wouldn't
collect and come cascading into our kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   This day was not over yet. My husband went out to change the
bulb in one of our porch lights, and the side glass panels slipped
from their tracks and crashed to the porch.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing the noise, I went out to see what had happened. There we
stood, shards of glass around our feet, a loose end of the tarp
flapping above our heads and two of our vehicles sitting useless in
the rain. ``I never wanted to own a home, or a car,'' my husband
muttered under his breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' I said. ``They own us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrible, horrible, no good, very bad day. But, as
Alexander's mom reminded him, some days are just like that. Even in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
