<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8021 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN25-COX     05-23 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Trading apartment din for yard noise
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Sometimes at night, I still find myself
listening for the tumbler.
</P>
<P>
   The tumbler lived in the apartment above mine. She was 10 or so
and took gymnastic classes. A good somersault, from the point of
view of someone living beneath it, begins with a thud of initial
impact followed by a short string of lighter taps as the
somersaulter wheels the length of the room, and ends up, I assume,
in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   THUMP-thud-thed-thed-thed-bom. Ta-dah!
</P>
<P>
   After a few weeks, I hardly thought twice about it. A budding
young gymnast, on the scale of apartment noise-sources, is far
superior to a metal-head, a dissolving romantic relationship or any
high-strung dog.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, I traded the communal existence of an apartment
dweller for the open spaces of house life. I like doing laundry
without going outside. I miss the Coke machine, though. People told
me I was moving to a quieter existence, but mainly I traded one set
of sounds for another.
</P>
<P>
   I am not a temperamental neighbor. I am skilled at the art of
ignoring. Civilized society, after all, rests on our ability to
tune each other out. I'm doing my part for civilization, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished sleeper, I have blissfully snoozed through
nearby parties, motorcycle tune-ups and criminal disorder. My
greatest moment of oblivious tenancy came many years ago when I
slept through an attempted murder in an upstairs apartment, which
had been followed by ambulance and police sirens, scampering
paramedics and shouting police.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow tenants pitied me for missing the drama and
excitement. Each resident was happy to fill me in on all the
ghastly details.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was a fight between roommates, that much was the same
in everyone's account. The two young men pounded each other with
objects they found around their home until one of them was
unconscious and the other hauled away by police.
</P>
<P>
   ``In handcuffs, like on TV,'' said the woman the next floor up.
</P>
<P>
   As The Guy Who Missed the Attempted Murder in Apt. 102, I became
something of a celebrity in the building. I was welcomed by all and
sought after by those who wanted to give their account of the
battle without fear of being contradicted by other witnesses.
Nothing cramps a storyteller's style like competing versions of
reality. And a story this strong must be told.
</P>
<P>
   Not having my own version to peddle, then, I was much in demand.
I was the only disinterested audience in the building. In filling
this role, I got to chat with people whom I would not otherwise
have met. People fed me. They handed me beers.
</P>
<P>
   I have been a good listener ever since. There is no better
training for journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Now I live in a house with a yard. It's a whole different group
of sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone within an earshot is so quiet I hardly notice them. I
haven't seen many of them since the time the guy down the street
cut down a tree and ended up knocking down a power line. (The
lights went out for half a block. Everyone came out to stare. It
was almost a block party.)
</P>
<P>
   I also haven't heard an attempted murder for ages. Any nearby
metal-heads must be in hiding. My ceiling stays silent, even though
I half-expect the small gymnast to reappear on my roof.
(THUMP-thud-thed-thed-thed-bom. Ta-dah!)
</P>
<P>
   In their place, I am awakened by leaf-blowers, lawn mowers,
edgers and small, two-stroke engines powering lawn-and-garden tools
beyond my understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I can hear easy-listening music played loudly
somewhere. Playing mellow music at high volume is an act that
strikes me as deeply, maybe pathologically, contradictory. But,
hey, no metal-heads are powering their speakers near my plumbing,
so I wouldn't dream of complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Not about the music, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'd gladly pick a second-floor gymnast over a leaf-blower
if I could choose my wake-up sound. Leaf-blowers are evil. They are
often operated by early risers.
</P>
<P>
   Late sleepers are the sure sign of an advanced and civilized
people. We are persecuted both in house and apartment. It's hard to
say where it's worse. Regardless, though, we still follow our
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
