A8022 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX     05-23 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Laws alone can't solve problems of our violent
society
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The following is an excerpt from an NRA ad:
``The gun came to America on the Mayflower. The right to own it
didn't. That right came with the blood and bravery of countless
patriots, whose valor now bestows it at birth upon every U.S.
citizen.'' It reminds us that weapons played an important part in
man's ``rise to freedom from oppression, and the sweet victory of
liberty over tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   True. All of it.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred years ago our forefathers also needed guns to hunt
for food and keep wild animals at bay. Today the wild animals are
carrying the guns and the rest of us feel like ducks in a shooting
gallery. Is this what happens to an armed society when there are no
longer any common causes to rally around? We shoot each other?
</P>
<P>
   There were no guns in my parents' home. The first gun I ever saw
was the one my new husband, the airline pilot, brought with him
when we married and moved into an apartment on the west side of
Chicago. Although I can't quote caliber and make, I do remember it
was big, heavy, and lived in the night table drawer.
</P>
<P>
   The ``big gun'' and I were never on intimate terms. I watched my
husband clean it a few times but the only occasion I ever had to
handle it was during the weekly dusting.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot and I had been married less than a year. He was on a
three-day trip to somewhere, and I was home alone. The night was
dark and creepy, and so was our cavernous old apartment. The
bedroom was a long, dim hallway away from the front door. I was
propped up in bed, wearing a pair of my husband's pajamas, and
reading one of the spy novels he collected, when I heard someone
tampering with the front door lock. It was decision time.
</P>
<P>
   In silent slow motion, I threw back the covers and slid open the
night table drawer. The gun felt cold in my hand. As I slipped
soundlessly out of bed, I heard the front door squeak open. My
right hand awkwardly held the gun - while the left one clutched at
the waist of the too-big pajama bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   As I tiptoed down the hall an ugly idea occurred to me - what if
there was no shell in the chamber? What if in the next fraction of
a second I was going to be facing down an armed breaker-and-enterer
with an unloaded gun? I transferred the gun to my left hand and
reached for the slide with my right. And then it happened. My pants
fell down.
</P>
<P>
   Epiphany. Suddenly I knew that if I were going to shoot this bad
guy, I would have to do it with pajama bottoms around my ankles.
Helluva choice.
</P>
<P>
   But at that moment, the hall light clicked on. Not ten feet away
stood a handsome (but at that moment rather pale) guy in a uniform.
His trip had cancelled.
</P>
<P>
   Gently, he pried my fingers off the gun and laid it on the
telephone table, grinning as he eyeballed the heap around my feet
his pajama pants had become. ``Jeez, lady,'' he said, ``you almost
widowed yourself.'' I made a joke about collecting big on the
insurance - and then threw up all over his shiny shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost 40 years later, my emotions are still mixed. I truly
wish guns had never been invented - EVER - but I can't believe that
legislation and regulation will make the whole bad scene go away.
The trouble with our violent society runs much deeper than a
problem that can be solved by registration and waiting periods.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Charlton Heston needs to give up moonlighting as president
of the NRA, and go back to his day job as Moses. Maybe he needs to
haul those stone tablets back up the mountain and speak to us one
more time about all of those ``Thou shalt nots'' we've become so
careless with lately - particularly that fifth one - the one that
reads, ``Thou shalt not kill.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
