<SLUG> BC-GEN-CYBER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECTING THE PUBLIC TRUST WITH WEB CAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Perhaps just as likely to encourage vandalism as
it does to protect against it, the latest thing that teams or
cities like to do on their Web sites is point a camera at a
ballpark, stadium or arena under construction and let fans with
computers watch in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, you become the security guards.
</P>
<P>
   The site's intent is to promote the new building and somehow
have people get excited as they watch it progress. But, in
actuality, how much is going to happen in a week, let alone a day?
The only time these kind of things make news is when a fire breaks
out, as it has in a new Miami arena and one recently at the Staples
Center in Downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Of the half-dozen Major League Baseball ballparks going up as we
speak _ with more in the planning stages _ the San Francisco Giants
and Seattle Mariners have come up with what amounts to the two best
hard-hat sites.
</P>
<P>
   On the Giants' site (http://www.sfgiants.com/
PACBELL(underdash)PARK/LIVECAM/livecam.html), there's an Internet
video system in place that updates the picture so fast, it's as if
you're watching a live shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' site (http://www.mariners.org/), after directing
you to Microsoft's Seattle Sidewalk (http://seattle.sidewalk.com/
safecofieldwebcam), doesn't update the picture quite as quickly,
but the up-to-the-minute updates are still turning over faster than
most.
</P>
<P>
   Of the others, Web cameras on the sites for Milwaukee
(http://www.milwaukeebrewers.com/news/millcam.html), Detroit
(http://www.detroittigers.com/) and Houston
(http://houston.sidewalk.com/ballpark) are pretty standard fare.
But they do allow for mischief to be spotted and, if the clicker is
so inclined, notify the team that their project is going up in
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's site (http://piratesball.com/PNCPark/index.html)
doesn't have its camera up yet. And San Diego's site
(http://padres.com/) has only a model of the proposed new ballpark.
So you can watch to see if the glue comes loose.
</P>
<P>
   _Online voting for the July 13 Major League Baseball All-Star
Game in Boston can be found at several places, but most easiest at
baseball's site (http://allstarvote. majorleaguebaseball.com),
which is specifically designed for this event.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, online balloting accounted for more than a
half-million votes. This year's online balloting ends June 27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
