</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA SENDING FRESH TROOPS TO ALBANIAN BORDER
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ As NATO enters its third month of air
attacks, the Yugoslav military is sending fresh troops into Kosovo
to reinforce positions near the border with Albania, alliance
officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The move suggests that the Yugoslav military is still able and
determined to maintain its hold on Kosovo and to continue its
battle to drive armed ethnic Albanian rebels from the province.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Serbs are being battered by round-the-clock air
strikes, which NATO leaders insist are disabling the Yugoslav
military, the dispatch of reinforcements apparently reflects a
decision by President Slobodan Milosevic to try to ride out the
bombing in hopes of negotiating better terms.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic still seems bent on being able to get a diplomatic
deal that enables him to declare victory to his people rather than
yielding directly to NATO's demands and withdrawing his forces from
Kosovo, where more than 1 million ethnic Albanians have been driven
from home since NATO began bombing on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no sign of withdrawal,'' said NATO's military
spokesman, Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz of Germany. ``The contrary is
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   The border region where NATO officials have observed
reinforcements has been the scene of intense fighting between the
Serbian military and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the force of
ethnic Albanian partisans.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces have been trying to seal the border with
minefields and troops to prevent the rebels from sending men and
supplies into Kosovo from their bases in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   There are between 6,000 and 10,000 Albanian partisans inside
Kosovo, according to allied intelligence. The rebel fighters hide
out in mountainous regions in north-central and south-central
Kosovo. Recently, they took the village of Produc near the town
Podujevo in northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Serbs' campaign of driving ethnic Albanians from their
homes and then burning hundreds of villages has deprived the Kosovo
Liberation Army of its base of popular support and left them short
of supplies, including food.
</P>
<P>
   That has made it all the more important for the Kosovo
Liberation Army to keep open supply lines into Kosovo from Albania.
Aside from an incident in which allied warplanes on Friday bombed a
Yugoslav army border post captured by the rebels weeks earlier,
NATO's air strikes appear to have helped the rebels keep those
vital lines working.
</P>
<P>
   There is no official relationship between NATO and the Albanian
partisans, but rebel leaders have said their men provide NATO with
information on Serbian positions. Allied air strikes against
Serbian armor, artillery and troops have worn down the Serbs'
ability to strike against the rebels, and forced them to dodge air
strikes by hiding hardware, and thus eased the pressure on the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the alliance plans a series of meetings to decide
whether to prepare a force totaling some 50,000 troops to go into
Kosovo to keep a negotiated peace. Within three weeks, alliance
officials have said, NATO will face a decision about whether to
prepare a ground force powerful enough to invade the province and
return the hundreds of thousands of Albanian refugees to Kosovo
before the onset of the harsh Balkan winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-BOXOFFICE-NY     05-23 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-BOXOFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' FANS GIVE `MENACE' A LITTLE LESS FORCE THAN EXPECTED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ That George Lucas film, in its first five days,
broke a box office record or two and performed just fine. But
expectations were dashed that what is perhaps the most eagerly
awaited movie ever made would somehow turn into a bonanza that
would crush every previous blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' has turned into,
pardon the expression, just another successful movie.
</P>
<P>
   In its opening days the long-awaited Lucas prequel, which has
become a cultural and media happening, took in a five-day record
$102.7 million at the box office, according to 20th Century Fox,
the distributor. But the movie failed to top the three-day weekend
record set by ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park,'' which reached
$72.2 million over the Memorial Day weekend in 1997. ``The Phantom
Menace'' grossed an estimated $61.8 million over this past weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But there were expectations among rival studio executives that
Lucas' 130-minute, $115 million science fiction epic could reach
$120 million or $130 million in its first five days and start
zooming toward breaking the box office record for James Cameron's
``Titanic'' (1997). That film, which has grossed $600 million
domestically and $1.8 billion around the world, is not, based on
the early evidence, expected to be surpassed by ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dergarabedian, president of the Exhibitor Relations Co.,
which monitors box office performance, said, ``Despite expectations
that had hugely inflated numbers, the numbers that came in are
quite amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Tom Sherak, chairman of the 20th Century Fox Domestic
Film Group, which released the movie, said Sunday: ``This was never
about setting records. It was about getting fans in first, followed
by families. It was planned that way. And that's what's
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he in any way disappointed? ``Absolutely, positively,
unequivocally no,'' Sherak said. ``People are crazy who say it's a
disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before the film opened, studio executives said its
box office success was review-proof. But the negative reviews of
many critics may have hurt the box office figures a bit, even in
the film's opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the dazzling critical response to the first
``Star Wars,'' which opened almost 22 years to the day before
``Menace,'' many reviewers of the current film praised the action
sequences and special effects, but found the acting wooden and the
plot confusing and said there was a lack of emotional involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A disappointment,'' David Ansen said in Newsweek. ``A big
one.'' In The Los Angeles Times, Kenneth Turan called the film ``a
considerable letdown,'' and Todd McCarthy in Variety said it was
``easily consumable eye candy, but it contains no nutrients for the
heart and mind.'' Anthony Lane in The New Yorker called it
``childishly unknowing and rotten with cynicism.'' But Janet Maslin
in The New York Times said it ``offers a happy surprise: it's up to
snuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Radley, president of Lucas Film, discounted the general
impact of critics. ``The wonderful thing about movies is it's a
people's medium,'' he said. ``The only critic that counts is the
individual moviegoer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherak said: ``People say the movie is review-proof. I say:
`Hey, it's ``Star Wars.'' It's only a movie. Have fun.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas will, by all accounts, have the most fun. As the creator
and financier of the film, he could earn as much as $2 billion of
profit as a result of his royalties from not only the movie but
also the toys, books, video games, plastic figurines, toothbrushes
and whatnot. ``Phantom Menace'' is only the first part of a
trilogy. Lucas has already begun working on ``Episode II,'' set for
2002. ``Episode III'' is scheduled for 2005. Twentieth Century Fox,
in releasing ``Menace,'' expects to earn about $100 million as its
distributor.
</P>
<P>
   One Hollywood executive, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said the huge sum assured to Lucas was dismaying because
the studio system would not benefit from it. With blockbusters like
``Titanic'' or ``Jurassic Park,'' the hundreds of millions of
dollars earned were plowed back into their studios for more films.
By contrast, Lucas takes his fortune to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Radley, the Lucas Film president, insisted that no one at the
company was consumed with setting box office records. Nonetheless,
the promotion machinery for the film has accelerated nonstop in
recent weeks, and the normally reticent Lucas has gone out of his
way to discuss the film on television and in newspapers and
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives said the studio had actually spent less promoting
``Phantom Menace'' up to its opening day than other recent
blockbusters like ``Independence Day'' and ``Titanic.'' The reason?
Newspapers, magazines and, mostly, television provided
extraordinary coverage.
</P>
<P>
   It cost about $30 million to open a blockbuster like
``Titanic.'' Fox executives said the promotion of the new ``Star
Wars'' had cost about $15 million so far. There was surprisingly
little paid advertising in large newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The hoopla around the movie may have hurt it a bit, Fox
executives said. Some adults seem to have stayed away from theaters
showing ``Phantom Menace'' because of all the news reports about
large crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Radley said he was not especially disappointed that Loews
Cineplex Entertainment had decided not to play the film at its
theaters in Manhattan because of a longstanding dispute over not
paying a ``floor,'' or minimum percentage of the box office, to the
studio. A result was that ``Phantom Menace'' failed to appear at
some of Manhattan's choice theaters, including Sony's Lincoln
Square, the nation's top-grossing movie house.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Phantom' opened on a nonholiday weekend,'' Radley said,
``and we didn't put it in every possible theater we could. It was
about presentation and ultimately creating an experience that
people could enjoy together.''
</P>
<P>
   What was Lucas' reaction? He is taking a vacation with his
children and writing the sequel to ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
