<HEADER>
A8026 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBRYO-RESEARCH-700&AMP;A     05-23 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRYO-RESEARCH-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL COMMISSION EXPECTED TO ENDORSE ONE FORM OF RESEARCH
USING EMBRYOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mary., Wis.) (rk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After six months of deliberation, a presidential commission is
close to recommending that scientists supported by federal grants
should be allowed to conduct a specific kind of research on
abandoned human embryos.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is also likely to urge that Congress not block
such research, as it has done for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The research would be limited to deriving from the embryos the
primordial cells, known as embryonic stem cells, from which all the
tissues and organs of the body develop. The embryos, which consist
of a tiny blob of cells a few hours after fertilization, are
created in a fertility clinic procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, known as the National Bioethics Advisory
Commission, is stepping into a turbulent side issue of the abortion
debate. Researchers and patients' advocacy groups have argued that
the study of these cells will lead to substantial medical benefits,
possibly including the direct implantation of the cells to replace
the tissues lost in Parkinson's and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of abortion, including many members of Congress,
object to the federal financing of any research that requires the
destruction of a human embryo. The commission's decision, likely to
be made at a meeting next month, was first reported Sunday in The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Human embryonic stem cells were first isolated from embryos last
November by James Thomson of the University of Wisconsin. Thomson's
research was legal because he used private funds. Congress,
however, has barred the use of federal funds for any research in
which an embryo is destroyed, and most biomedical researchers
receive all or much of their support from the National Institutes
of Health, a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   The question then arose as to whether federally financed
researchers could make use of Thomson's cells even though they are
prohibited from deriving them. President Clinton, prompted by
Thomson's advance and the creation of a human-cow hybrid cell,
asked the commission to review the use of embryonic stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Harriet Rabb, general counsel of the Department of
Health and Human Services, issued an opinion that it would be
permissible for researchers to work on human embryonic stem cells,
although not to derive them. She said that because the cells could
not by themselves develop into a human being, they could not be
considered embryos and so did not fall under the congressional ban.
</P>
<P>
   That position did not sit well with opponents of abortion.
Members of the House Pro-Life Caucus declared that the general
counsel's decision ``would violate both the letter and spirit of
the federal law.''
</P>
<P>
   The President's bioethics commission also seems to have been
uncomfortable with the idea that using the cells could be
acceptable if deriving them was not. Eric Meslin, the commission's
executive director, said Sunday that the commission ``has
considered the ethical arguments that would distinguish use from
derivation, and my sense is that they are not yet fully persuaded
that an ethical distinction can be drawn.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission is therefore likely to recommend that federally
supported researchers be allowed both to derive and to use the
embryonic stem cells, even though it ``has not taken a position on
the specifics of what any recommendation would be,'' Meslin said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission discussed only the derivation of stem cells and
has not considered other possible kinds of research on human
embryos, Meslin said.
</P>
<P>
   Background documents prepared by the commission's staff, but not
yet endorsed by the commission itself, suggest that in their
discussions members have seen an irreconcilable difference between
the holders of two ethical views: those who regard an embryo as
having moral rights equivalent to those of a person, and those who
respect the medical values of health, prevention and research.
</P>
<P>
   Though consensus may be impossible, the commission's background
documents argue that a reasonable compromise would be to let
stem-cell research proceed under safeguards that embody respect for
the embryo. The documents argue that the congressional ban has
discouraged the development of a coherent public policy on embryo
research.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the commission decides at its June meeting to permit the
derivation of stem cells from embryos, opponents seem likely to
pursue their case in Congress, which must approve the ban each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Doerflinger, associate director for policy development
at the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, said that the
probable decision ``is hardly unexpected, since I don't think there
is any member of the commission that shares the Catholic
conference's view about the moral status of the embryo.'' But, he
added, ``There are people in Congress who do.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health is preparing guidelines
covering the use of Thomson's cells and of similar cells derived
from fetal tissue by John Gearhart of Johns Hopkins University.
Federally supported researchers cannot use either until the
guidelines are approved.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear if the National Institutes of Health will
proceed to issue its guidelines if Congress should again attach its
ban to the agency's annual appropriations bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
