<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Teens, teachers and the last days of school
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ This column is for readers without any
teenagers of their own. So that no one feels left out of the annual
``school's almost out'' frenzy, I shall generously share my kids
with you. I have 60 of them and they're all in the 8th grade. I
teach English. It's not a pretty job, but somebody's gotta' do it.
</P>
<P>
   It's Monday morning. My partner and I are working the day watch
out of . . . . Sorry. Scratch the Dragnet scenario. It happens
every year at this time when teachers and reality threaten to part
company. I'll try again.
</P>
<P>
   It's Monday morning. My colleagues and I are working the 'shorts
watch' here in Gibsonburg Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   The handbook insists no shorts will be worn before their time,
May 1st, and when they are, they will be mid-thigh. This is tricky
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bitsy, you and your too-short shorts are excused to the
office.'' That's me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh?'' That's Bitsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mid-thigh is the rule, and unless your thighs have risen
during the night, you're out of compliance. Go see the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   She will not go quietly into the hall. Instead she huffs and
whines, ``How come teachers never send any guys to the office? Why
don't they ever get
</P>
<P>
   picked on?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at these guys,'' I explain. ``Can anyone spot a thigh?
Heck, for all we know, they don't even have knees.'' Denny, a
squarely-constructed brute of a lineman on the middle school
football team, breaks into a big grin. I use him as an example
because he can take it. ``Look at Denny. Check out those shorts.
They're pup tent size with a drawstring waist. Could I send
something that pitiful looking to the office?''
</P>
<P>
   Denny and his ``cool'' buddies think that's pretty funny, but
Bitsy shall not be assuaged. She mutters something about dress
codes being dumb and she doesn't understand why we have to have
them anyway. I'm tempted to tell her the truth (to ensure kids
without good sense don't gross us out by coming to school with
various, and possibly pierced, body parts blowing in the wind).
Instead I give her the same answer I gave last week, and the week
before that. ``Teachers love the raw power of being able to bust
kids for absolutely no reason at all.'' Bitsy flounces out.
</P>
<P>
   As I linger a moment over attendance sheets, Bobby who has been
kicked-back on the old plaid sofa comes to life. ``Can't we just
have a fun day today, Ms. Schuett?'' One of his seat-mates chimes
in explaining that since there are only 12 days of school left,
kids should be allowed to stop work now so they can rest up for
summer vacation. Says he thinks he read it somewhere in the
handbook.
</P>
<P>
   I tell them they can rest when they're old but in the meantime
they have essays due. Groans all around and Danny accuses me of
being the meanest teacher in the building. I remind him it was my
major in college.
</P>
<P>
   So, in spite of balmy breezes and sunny skies, it's business as
usual. Rough drafts are pulled out of folders and propped up next
to humming computers. Soon the clack of the old keyboards assures
me learning is taking place. I slip a Mozart disk into the CD
player and for a brief moment, I feel like the conductor of a
finely tuned symphony orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's wail snaps me back to reality: ``Ms. Schuett, my mouse
has no ball. I can''t write.'' I remind him there's always pen and
paper. Miraculously, the mouse ball re-appears. Probably from his
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Bitsy's back wearing baggy sweats and an attitude. She's made a
decision. She's not going to finish her essay, and as soon as she
turns 16 she's going to quit school and become a professional beach
volleyball player. I tell her that's a great idea and ask if she's
made plans for when she outgrows her bikini. She glowers.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, I double-check my desk calendar. It's still 12
days.
</P>
<P>
   It's Monday. My partner and I are on day watch out of....
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
