<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, May 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms will erupt over portions of the Northeast
Monday as an unusually strong low pressure system forges eastward
across southeast Canada. Initially, a round of steady rain with
embedded thunderstorms will sweep through the central and northern
Appalachian Monday morning, reaching the New England coast by
midday.
</P>
<P>
   After the rain ends, intervals of sunshine will develop over the
eastern Middle Atlantic states. As the sun heats the ground, and
overlying moist air, the stage will be set for severe thunderstorms
to form Ascending currents of air, enhanced by a jet stream
disturbance will cause a narrow line of strong thunderstorms to
ignite during the middle and late afternoon. Some of the storms
will produce damaging winds and hail. The region at highest risk
for severe weather will stretch from North Carolina to eastern
Virginia and southeastern Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, blustery and unseasonably cool weather will
plague the central and western Great Lakes Monday. Residual
moisture in the lowest 10,000 feet of the atmosphere will promote
plenty of clouds and spotty sprinkles across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Offshore breezes will cause unseasonably warm and sunny
conditions to persist in the Pacific Northwest Monday, though much
cooler air will arrive Tuesday behind a cold front. Meanwhile, a
pocket of cold air aloft near 15,000 feet will cross the
southwestern states, renewing the risk for spotty mountain
thunderstorms. Elsewhere, low clouds will obscure portions of the
California coast early Monday morning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Rare Thunder
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday, peals of thunder echoed across portions of
southern California, a very unusual occurrence during the month of
May. On average, May thunderstorms are observed at Los Angeles once
every 10 years. Thunderstorms are sustained from the instability
that results when air temperature decreases rapidly from near the
ground to high altitudes. Cold low pressure in the middle
atmosphere set the stage for the thunderstorms on Sunday. Monday,
the same low pressure system will progress slowly east, bringing
the threat for additional thunderstorms to Arizona and Nevada.
</P>
</TEXT>
