<SLUG> BC-GEN-YESTERDAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY'S GREATEST GETS KINGS TO FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some of the
anniversaries that will occur this week in Los Angeles sports
history (followed by the ranking of the event from the book
``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles Sports
History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   May 24, 1913: USC's baseball team is disbanded as the school
wants springtime athletic pursuits to be focused on the track and
field team.
</P>
<P>
   May 25, 1984: USC's Mark McGwire hits his final home run of the
season against Cal State Fullerton. It sets the school's
single-season (32) and career (54) record for homers.
</P>
<P>
   May 25, 1992: UCLA claims its eighth national softball
championship with a 2-0 win over Arizona in Oklahoma City. Junior
Lisa Fernandez pitched a four-hitter. The Bruins finished the
season 54-2. (83).
</P>
<P>
   May 26, 1928: After leaving Los Angeles 573 hours earlier,
Andrew Payne of Claremore, Okla., arrives in New York on foot and
is declared the winner in the first coast-to-coast walking race. He
beat 273 others over the 3,422-mile route.
</P>
<P>
   May 27, 1985: The Memorial Day Massacre _ Boston beats the
Lakers 148-114 in Game 1 of the NBA Finals at the Boston Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   May 27, 1978: USC's relay team of Joel Andrews, James Sanford,
Billy Mullins and Clancy Edwards sets a world record in the 800
meter relay in 1:20.3 at the Sun Devil Relays in Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   May 28, 1957: National League club owners approve the move to
the West Coast of the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   May 29, 1993: The Kings' 5-4 victory at Toronto clinches the
Campbell Conference title and puts them into the Stanley Cup Finals
for the first time in franchise history. Wayne Gretzky, in what
he'd later call his greatest individual game, scores his eighth
career playoff hat trick. (12)
</P>
<P>
   May 29, 1979: The Dodgers hit a team-record seven home runs in a
17-6 win over Cincinnati at Dodger Stadium. The magnificent seven:
Dusty Baker, Steve Garvey, Joe Ferguson, Gary Thomasson, Davey
Lopes, Derrel Thomas and Rick Sutcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Today: Former Lakers forward and current GM Mitch
Kupchak (45). Tuesday: Former Lakers coach Bill Sharman (73).
Thursday: Angels manager Terry Collins (50) and Dodgers catcher
Todd Hundley (30). Friday: Former Lakers great and current VP Jerry
West (61), Lakers forward Glen Rice (32) and former Dodgers
outfielder Kirk Gibson (42). Saturday: Former Dodgers outfielder
and L.A. native Eric Davis (37) and Toluca Lake golfer Bob Hope
(96).
</P>
</TEXT>
