<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAUDI-SUCCESSION-2TAK     05-23 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-SUCCESSION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SAUDIS PUSH FOR A NEW GENERATION OF LEADERS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia _ The king of Saudi Arabia, long ailing, is
78 years old. His designated successor, the crown prince, is 76.
The defense minister, seen as next in line for the throne, is 75.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when leadership is changing and passing to a younger
generation elsewhere in the Middle East, the prospect of a
continuing gerontocracy is beginning to provoke open concern among
businessmen, politicians and even members of the royal family and
Saudi Arabia's allies.
</P>
<P>
   They fear that the monarchy's unusual system of fraternal
succession _ adopted by King Abdelaziz al-Saud before his death in
1953 to avoid violence among his 44 sons _ could weaken the kingdom
in what are sure to be difficult years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Abdelaziz unified the kingdom in the early part of the century,
and power to date has remained among his sons, with Saud, Faisal,
Khalid, and now Fahd taking their turns in order of age.
</P>
<P>
   Many more brothers still await their turns. But age is catching
up with them, prompting many people in this secretively ruled,
male-dominated kingdom _ including even members of the royal family
itself _ to ponder whether Saudi Arabia needs to adopt a different
rule of succession in which power would pass vertically, from this
generation to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is consensus among the sons of Abdelaziz,''
Prince Talal bin Abdelaziz, 68, one of those sons, said in a rare
interview here. ``The real problem will come among our sons _ the
next generation _ if matters are not arranged now.''
</P>
<P>
   As things stand, Saudi Arabia could be ruled by a rapid
succession of septuagenarians at a time when oil prices have
foundered and the prosperity that has served to cushion political
dissent since the 1970s has shriveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you'd have is a bunch of leaders who, even if they had
lots of determination and heart, would just be plain old,'' said a
Western diplomat, showing that the succession worries the Saudis'
allies, too.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that more Saudis have begun to talk about succession
is a widening recognition that the era of King Fahd, who became
king in 1982 at age 61, has essentially passed. Since November
1995, he has survived several strokes and major surgery and now
moves about in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   People who have met with him recently say that he is in better
health than he was a year ago, when he underwent emergency gall
bladder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not stood up for more than a year, according to
Western diplomats, who say that his crippled knees can no longer
bear his considerable weight. They say he still responds politely
to conversation, but that some recent visitors have come away with
the impression that he is not fully engaged.
</P>
<P>
   And though Fahd still receives important foreign visitors, the
diplomats say most meetings are nothing more than courtesy calls
and that the real business is conducted with Crown Prince Abdullah,
who they say has been Saudi Arabia's effective decision maker since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Attention on succession has also intensified following the death
in March of Fahd's eldest wife, Princess al-Anoud, after a long
illness, and the recent deaths of King Hussein of Jordan and Sheik
Isa bin Salman al-Khalifa, the emir of Bahrain. Both of those Arab
leaders have been succeeded by their sons, in an example of the
generational change for which many Saudis seem to yearn.
</P>
<P>
   In recent conversations, at least six Saudi businessmen in four
cities independently compared the situation that their country
might face to that of the Soviet Union of the early 1980s, when
power was passed from one aging, infirm leader to another, and the
country was left with almost no direction.
</P>
<P>
   Across Saudi Arabia, people spoke guardedly, at first, about the
power sweepstakes that seem to lie ahead. Many noted that the
succession is the preserve of a royal family that acts prudently,
on the basis of consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Once assured of anonymity, some Saudis launched seamlessly into
analysis of the pros and cons of potential future kings, drawing on
the mixture of fact and rumor that swirls through informal personal
networks, rather than on the fawning and tightly controlled state
media.
</P>
<P>
   Even within the royal family, some senior princes are saying
this may be the moment for the family to agree on when and how
power should pass to the next generation. ``In the final analysis,
it will be practicality and realism that determines decision
making,'' said one such royal.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone in Saudi Arabia now seems to believe Crown
Prince Abdullah, still in good health, will be the next to take
power.
</P>
<P>
   And though he is not obliged to do so, Abdullah is widely
expected to name as his heir Prince Sultan bin Abdelaziz, the
75-year-old defense minister who has held that post since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   A full brother of Fahd, Sultan is said by associates to want
very much to become king. He has two elder brothers, Musaid and
Bandar, but neither holds government office and neither is seen as
a viable candidate. Since 1982, Sultan has held the title of second
deputy prime minister, ranking him behind Abdullah in the
governmental hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   What might happen next is far less clear.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five of Abdelaziz's sons are still alive. Some are seen
as having removed themselves from the path of succession, but
others, including some not much younger than Abdullah and Sultan,
are believed to see themselves as contenders, still entitled to the
throne.
</P>
<P>
   They include Prince Abdel Rahman, 68, the deputy minister of
defense, and Prince Nayef, 66, the minister of interior, although
neither man reportedly commands much popular support.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the names listed by prominent Saudis and Westerners
as attractive future kings tend to be those of younger men, who are
seen as better equipped to guide the country through what could be
difficult economic times.
</P>
<P>
   Those most often mentioned are Prince Salman, 62, a son of
Abdelaziz who has been governor of Riyadh since 1962; Prince Saud
bin Faisal, 58, a grandson of Abdelaziz and son of the late King
Faisal who has been foreign minister since 1975; and his brother,
Prince Turki bin Faisal, 54, who has been head of the Department of
General Intelligence since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Others seen by some as viable candidates in coming years are two
other grandsons of Abdelaziz: Prince Khalid bin Faisal, 68,
governor of Asir since 1977, and Prince Bandar bin Sultan, 49,
ambassador to the United States since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   But Saudi culture places a premium on seniority. And in the
history of Saudi succession, it is only when elder brothers have
stood aside _ as one of them did in 1975, for example, to allow
Fahd to become crown prince _ that exceptions have been made.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles in the way of the grandsons, who number in the
hundreds, are even more complex. As made explicit in a basic law of
government issued by Fahd in 1992, a Saudi king has the unilateral
right to designate and dismiss his heir, with the only criteria
being that he be a son or grandson of Abdelaziz, and that the
future king be ``the most upright'' among the candidates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That means that Fahd could, conceivably, designate one of his
own sons as heir, just as King Hussein did in Jordan earlier this
year, less than two weeks before his death.
</P>
<P>
   But in practice, Saudis say, every member of the royal family
knows that such rash action could lead to bitter, even violent
division within the family, whose power is widely spread, with
various members controlling different provinces, armies and the
internal security service.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The prospect of passing the monarchy to the grandsons of
Abdelaziz raises questions of who should have preference.
</P>
<P>
   Should it be the sons of King Saud _ who was Abdelaziz's eldest
son, became Saudi Arabia's second king in 1953 and was formally
deposed in 1964 by his brother Faisal? Saud died in exile in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Or should the first choice be among the heirs of King Faisal,
who was assassinated in 1975 by a deranged nephew and whose sons
are held in particularly high regard?
</P>
<P>
   Should the chosen be the sons of King Khalid, who died in 1982,
after a relatively brief seven-year reign? Should they be those of
Fahd, who, after Abdelaziz, is now the longest-serving of the Saudi
leaders? Or should they be those of whichever future king decides
to reach to a new generation?
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is not clear enough,'' said Prince Walid bin
Talal, the billionaire Saudi businessman, whose father, Prince
Talal, is not seen as a candidate to become king, in part because
his open calls for limited democratization in Saudi Arabia have
long made him a dissenting voice in the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Prince Walid also said he had no political
aspirations. But he was also among a handful of members of the
royal family willing to say publicly that the system of succession
should be made more clear.
</P>
<P>
   He said of a future King Abdullah: ``I think he should
institutionalize and formalize the process of the transfer of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Without political and economic reform, many prominent Saudis and
Westerners fear, dissatisfaction with the royal family will grow.
</P>
<P>
   Since his debut as a leader, when Fahd temporarily transferred
full powers to him, the crown prince has earned admiration from
Western diplomats, who say that early worries that he may be less
friendly to the West than his brother appear to have been
overwrought.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Abdullah made a low-profile world tour that included
stops in France, the United States and China. At home, he has
enhanced a reputation of probity, in part by ordering other members
of the family to pay their utility bills, a first step toward
reining in chronic overspending.
</P>
<P>
   Many Saudis and Westerners regard Prince Sultan as an able,
experienced leader, but others complain that he has demonstrated no
capacity for financial discipline.
</P>
<P>
   When promised anonymity, many Saudi businessmen say their choice
to succeed Abdullah would be Prince Salman, the 62-year-old Riyadh
governor, whose hard-working habits are legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Abdullah or Sultan, they say, a King Salman could
reasonably hope to rule for a decade or more in good health,
providing the kind of continuity they believe necessary to guide
the country through difficult times. By age alone, however, Salman
ranks just 16th in seniority among Abdelaziz's surviving sons, and
most people say he will almost certainly have to wait some years
for his turn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
