<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8048 &Cx1f; tth-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-23 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUESTS WILL JUMP FOR JOY WHEN SERVED FROGMORE STEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are no frogs in Frogmore Stew. Good thing, too, or this
one-dish meal would create more of a mess than a mud-rassling match
atop Martha Stewart's coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, if Martha Stewart decided to serve Frogmore
Stew, she might have to saw a hole in the table and install a
bucket underneath. That's what they do in some restaurants in the
Gullah district of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   A retired Navy officer, Al Wood, lives near St. Helena Island,
which was dubbed Frogmore by early inhabitants. We met Wood far
from his South Carolina home, on a cross-country skiing trail at
Jasper, Alberta. He seemed to sense that the author of a cookbook
called ``Gluttony Without Guilt'' would be a candidate for the
Frogmore Stew Appreciation Society.
</P>
<P>
   Essential equipment at a Frogmore Stew feast includes at least
two rolls of paper towels as napkins, a galvanized bucket and a
large appetite. Here is Wood's recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Frogmore Stew
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds unshelled medium shrimp (40 to 50 per pound)
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter pound of butter
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds of mild Hillshire Farm sausage cut in slices
</P>
<P>
   5 ears of corn, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds of medium new red potatoes, diced in large pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, diced in large pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons Old Bay seasoning
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   You could probably substitute any good brand of kielbasa or
other precooked sausage in the recipe. One bag of crab boil might
also be substituted for the Old Bay seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   What you do is to half-fill your largest cooking pot with water.
Add the butter, salt, crab boil, the pieces of sausage and the
onion. Bring this mess to a boil, then add the corn and potatoes.
Continue to boil for four minutes, then add the unpeeled shrimp and
stir-cook four to six minutes, or until the shrimp rise to the top
of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Turn stove off and let the ingredients sit for four minutes, or
as long as it takes you to hum two choruses of ``Carolina Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   With a perforated serving spoon, transfer the ingredients of the
pot into a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Furnish five guests with melted butter or seafood sauce as a
dip. Then let everybody attack the contents of the bowl. The shrimp
shells and corncobs go into the bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Wood says the above recipe is widely circulated in his part of
the country. The same is true of the following gut-busting dessert.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I encountered it, the dessert was described as
``Bear Bryant's favorite mud pie,'' in reference to the late, great
Southern football coach.
</P>
<P>
   The same recipe, with different names, has appeared in two or
three community cookbooks we have acquired. Like Frogmore Stew,
this dish is awfully easy and awfully good. So don't put away those
paper towels quite yet. We can make a meal out of Frogmore Stew
and:
</P>
<P>
   Pudding Cake for a Bear
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   one-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   two-thirds cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   one-half cup milk
</P>
<P>
   one-half cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons melted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Pudding topping (recipe below)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Sift the flour with the baking powder, salt and cocoa. Stir in
the sugar. Add the milk, walnuts, butter and vanilla. Mix
thoroughly, then plop this sludge into an ungreased, 8-inch-square
glass baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the topping over the cake mixture. Pour 1 cup boiling
water over all, and DO NOT STIR!
</P>
<P>
   Shove the dish into a preheated 350-degree oven for about 40
minutes, or until the pudding cake is slightly crusty on top. Let
sit for a while, then serve warm with whipped cream on top. Feeds
four to six.
</P>
<P>
   For the topping
</P>
<P>
   Mix together:
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter cup white sugar
</P>
<P>
   half cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   You can also throw any leftover pudding cake into the galvanized
bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Except there won't be any leftovers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
