<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8049 &Cx1f; tth-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-MELTING-POT-SPI &LR;      05-23 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MELTING-POT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S FASCINATION WITH INTERNATIONAL FOODS RESULTED IN A
COOKBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY ROBERTS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In northeast Seattle, Georgia Lord Watanabe discovered
the Mexican cactus specialty nopales on a store shelf on Lake City
Way.
</P>
<P>
   She found the Philippine fish sauce bagoong on 125th Street, and
on 80th Street, sweet slices of the Middle Eastern snack halvah.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's South End, she browsed through Southeast Asian
produce marts stocking fresh, 20-pound jackfruit and malodorous
durian the size of footballs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Beacon Hill neighborhood, she checked out lamb's tongue
and chicken feet.
</P>
<P>
   She spotted the Salvadoran herb lorocco in a refrigerator case
in Bellevue, the Lebanese flatbread lavash in a shop huddling next
to an Exxon station in Edmonds, Wash., and sheets of seaweed _ for
wrapping norimaki sushi _ in a big, Korean-Japanese grocery in
Federal Way, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized, after visiting 100 stores or so, it really did
become an obsession,'' Watanabe said. ``It still is.''
</P>
<P>
   Watanabe has turned her fascination with international foods
into a book, ``Puget Sound Culinaria _ A Cook's Guide to Ethnic
Markets.'' The paperback, self-published from White Paw Publishing
in 1998, sells for $17.95 in area kitchen-supply shops and
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   In its 269 pages, ``Puget Sound Culinaria'' lists 92 ethnic food
markets in and around Seattle, from big, modern stores like
Uwajimaya in the International District, to its tiny, time-warped
neighbor, Yick Fung &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Listings are grouped by location, from Edmonds to Tacoma and on
both sides of Lake Washington, and each entry includes a brief
description of the appearance and inventory of the store.
</P>
<P>
   With her husband, Louis, a former software developer who now
manages the Northwest Asian American Theatre in Seattle, Watanabe
scoured the region for ethnic food stores.
</P>
<P>
   Her market compilation includes African, Mexican, Italian,
Scandinavian, Russian, Middle Eastern, Latin American and all
manner of Asian markets, from Pakistani to Filipino, Chinese to
Japanese to Korean and on through the cultures of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to find out how diverse our community, in markets,
is,'' Watanabe said. ``I wanted to make sure I included as many
peoples as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   There are kosher markets, which observe Jewish dietary
regulations, and there are halal markets, which sell meats
slaughtered under Islamic law. For good measure, Watanabe included
37 ethnic bakeries, a dozen cooking-supply stores and some 30
recipes gleaned from cookbooks and family members.
</P>
<P>
   The most direct genesis of the book was a 1995 free-lance
writing assignment to cover a cooking class. Watanabe wondered
where the instructor bought some of the exotic ingredients. She
researched the sources and ultimately wrote an article about ethnic
markets in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting the focus to Seattle, where she lives, and expanding
the concept to a book were logical extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the roots of ``Puget Sound Culinaria'' go back much further.
Watanabe's father, Bill Lord, spent his career in the Army, and the
family lived in France, Germany and different cities in the United
States. Everywhere they moved, the Lords explored the local culture
and, most memorably for Georgia, its food.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers shopping with her mother in a French village,
bargaining for green beans, baguettes, cheese and fish. On Sundays,
the Lords would sightsee in Paris, where her father would treat the
kids to jambons, sandwiches of thin-sliced ham on crusty bread.
</P>
<P>
   Food acquired a significance for Watanabe. After earning a
degree in home economics from Cal State-Northridge, she worked in
research and development for food-processing companies in
California. She has taught cooking classes for children and now
demonstrates kitchen appliances part time at malls and department
stores in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always curious about what I haven't seen or smelled yet,
or cooked,'' she said. ``I'm intrigued by how the ingredients are
combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get really excited just walking up Jackson Street (in the
International District) and seeing all that fresh produce. I want
to start grabbing it and squeezing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is very sensual. The sights and shapes and aromas are
irresistible to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Watanabe, 50, and her husband moved to Seattle five years ago
when Louis was transferred here by the computer company he worked
for. Although Louis grew up in Southern California, his father was
raised in a Japanese American farm family in Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Louis, too, is an accomplished cook, his wife said, and together
they turn out an array of ethnic dishes: gnocchi pasta, pot
stickers, enchiladas, pancit and adobo from the Philippines,
Japanese shabu-shabu and teriyaki chicken, samosas from India,
couscous and tabbouleh from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The frequent relocations of Watanabe's childhood meant more, she
said, than simple exposure to diverse cultures and cooking styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you grow up in the Army, you're always one of the new
kids,'' she said. ``I spent my childhood being a newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always want to know about people: where they came from, how
they came, how they adjust,'' she said. ``I feel a little affinity
with people who come from another place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of ritual around food, and how it's prepared,
and how it's served,'' Watanabe said. ``When people come here, they
bring that with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry that that's going to be lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
