A8052 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS24-COX     05-23 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves clubbed by Cubs again 5-1
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Change all the locks. The Cubs just left.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves completed a brief but excruciating season series with
Chicago Sunday, again falling behind immediately in an eventual 5-1
loss that gave the Cubs three of four weekend games at Turner
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with a 1-2 series at Wrigley Field last weekend, the
Braves wound up 2-5 against Chicago for the year, the first time
since the franchise relocated in Atlanta that the Braves haven't
won at least three from the Cubs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played us great, I guess,'' Atlanta manager Bobby Cox
said, before the club embarked for Wisconsin and a four-game set
with Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Chose any part of the Braves' anatomy and the Cubs kicked it
over the previous 10 days, when Chicago out-hit (65-54),
out-homered (12-7) and outscored (40-23) them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were taking advantage of every time they got runners on
base, when they would execute,'' said Gerald Williams, who played
right field for Brian Jordan, sidelined with a mild ankle sprain.
``They had timely hitting and played solid defense. That's how you
play winning baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Mulholland out-pitched Atlanta too, allowing just five
singles and just two runners past first base before leaving with
two outs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it look easy,'' said Cox. ``That's the way we normally
do it, but we haven't been doing that lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Odalis Perez (2-2, 5.54) did nothing to improve his
portfolio, giving up back-to-back home runs to Jose Hernandez and
Sammy Sosa (his 14th) in the first inning and then a two-run shot
to Henry Rodriguez in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he was hurt again in the first inning, putting the
Braves behind 2-0 before they ever got to the plate. Of the 25 runs
Perez has allowed this year, nine have come across in the
opponents' first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got down five again today and that's hard to bounce back
from every day,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have followed up on a dreary 3-9 road trip with a
disappointing 4-3 homestand. Moreover, they lost five of seven to
the Cubs, who are just two games over .500 against the rest of the
National League. Mulholland faced three over the minimum through
the seventh and a crowd of 48,782 spent more time exhorting the
visiting team than the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happened to us last season too,'' said Andruw Jones,
recalling a 3-6 record against the Cubs in 1998. ``In the playoffs,
we beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   But not by performing like this.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S GAME
</P>
<P>
   Opponent: Brewers
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 8:05 p.m.; County Stadium in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitchers: LHP Tom Glavine (3-4) vs. RHP Steve Woodard
(3-4).
</P>
<P>
   TV; radio: Fox Sports Net; WSB (98.5 FM).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
