</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRAVES NOTEBOOK: Jordan sits out, may play tonight
 &HT;    
 &HT;    THOMAS STINSON
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brian Jordan hopes to be back in the lineup in Milwaukee tonight
after sitting out Sunday with a tender right ankle. He chased a
ball deep into the right-field corner Saturday night, came out of
it lame and only therapy will tell if the Braves' most productive
hitter will miss more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks pretty good,'' club trainer Dave Pursley said. ``We
expect to get him back out there. It's not swollen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan told manager Bobby Cox he was available to pinch-hit
Sunday but was moving slowly with a high ankle sprain and a sore
left Achilles' tendon. He was injured in the third inning of
Saturday night's game, when the Cubs' Lance Johnson sent a liner
into the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan set up to field it off the wall, but when it kicked to
the right, his left ankle collapsed. He remained in the game for
four more innings, until the leg tightened and he asked to come
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball bounced off the wall, I rolled my ankle and it
popped back real quick,'' Jordan said. ``I kind of kick-saved the
ball and as the game went on, it felt like my Achilles' started
tightening up on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday marked the second game Jordan has missed with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Cat sighting?
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez, who has kept in close contact with Andres
Galarraga, said the club's wayward first baseman hopes to visit the
team in two weeks and may even accompanying the Braves to Boston on
June 4-6 for their first interleague series of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's feeling good, sounds good, the same Big Cat,'' Perez
said. ``He'll be here before the Boston trip and then wants to go
to Boston, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga is over halfway through chemotherapy treatments for
lymphoma in his hometown of West Palm Beach, Fla. Other than two
visits during spring training and a brief encounter at the Florida
Marlins, the Braves have not seen Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   Re-arming
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz threw for the first time Sunday since being placed
on the disabled list last Monday. The half-hour session was really
an elaborate game of catch in the bullpen, interspersed with
conversation with pitching coach Leo Mazzone. Smoltz reported no
discomfort in his right elbow but was only throwing at 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing fell off,'' Smoltz said. ``My brain's still intact.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step comes Tuesday, when he will attempt to throw hard
in a full side session. Smoltz also hopes to test his arm with a
session of live batting practice, before the decision is finalized
to bring him off the DL for his next scheduled turn May 31 against
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a super-complicated thing, but it's not an easy thing
either,'' he said. ``You don't throw for seven days and then you go
out there and try to regain your form.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker is quietly putting together a strong second month as
he evolves as the club's closer. Despite Cox's first inclination
that the would finish games by committee, Rocker has found steady
work in the ninth inning in May, recording five saves in six
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 appearances this month, he has been charged with one
earned run and four hits in 10 1/3 innings, while striking out 13.
He lost a May 7 game in San Diego by giving up three consecutive
hits, but otherwise has been spending his time well as an
apprentice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I produce over a long, long stretch,'' Rocker said,
``I'm still getting comfortable with my ability to get in the ninth
inning and get three guys out. But until I save games for a long
stretch, that's what really matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker enters the Milwaukee series at 2-2 with a 2.55 ERA with
six saves and two blown saves.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
