<SLUG> BC-MACRO-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACROMEDIA PLANNING A NEW INTERNET STRATEGY
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The multimedia software publisher Macromedia
plans to introduce an Internet entertainment strategy on Monday
based on a ``media player'' program, similar to player software
developed by Real Networks, Microsoft and Apple Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia has already popularized Shockwave and Flash as
multimedia formats that are widely used by a variety of commercial
World Wide Web sites for adding animation and sound to graphics.
Now the company plans to introduce a free Shockwave ``remote''
version that will enable individual computer users to locate and
play games, view animation and otherwise make use of various
multimedia material on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also developed a $19.99 Shockmachine player
software program with more features, including a larger format
display. Starting next month, both the remote and the player
versions will be available for downloading from a new Macromedia
site, shockwave.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the next natural step for Macromedia,'' Robert K.
Burgess, the company's chairman and chief executive, said.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess said that the Shockwave.com Web site would offer
original cartoons, comics, music and games, as well as material
from movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans on Monday to announce a number of content
partners including Time Warner's Comedy Central cable channel and
Warner Brothers studio; the Fox Interactive unit of the News Corp.;
Hasbro Interactive; Marvel Enterprises, and Mplayer.com, an online
gambling company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the potential to step up what entertainment on the
Web can be,'' Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   The Shockmachine player will use the Shockwave and Flash formats
for playing cartoons and interactive comics that can be downloaded
from the site. For video clips, though, the player will employ
Apple's Quicktime multimedia format.
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of the company's existing multimedia tools,
Macromedia has grown significantly in the last year. Revenue for
the fiscal year, which ended March 31, rose 33 percent, to $149.8
million, from a year earlier, and profits grew to $19.8 million
from a loss of $6.2 million in the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which was trading at less than $13 a share in August,
reached a 52-week high of $50 in mid-April. On Friday, the stock
closed at $49.50, up $4.1875 for the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
