<HEADER>
A8060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-CHURCH-COX     05-23 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-CHURCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shooting victim's mom tells Satan to back off
 &HT;    By Leon Stafford
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The mother of a victim of last week's shootings at
Heritage High School told Satan on Sunday to back off because he
can't win against her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is mad at us and he is after our children, but I just want
to say that he is a lie and he is not going to get them,'' Felecia
Cullins said to a rousing standing ovation at the Church in the Now
in Rockdale County. Her daughter, Cania, shot in the knee during
the Thursday incident, sat in a wheelchair at her side and nodded
enthusiastically as the room exploded in clapping.
</P>
<P>
   The Heritage shootings were the topic of church sermons and
after-service discussions throughout Rockdale on Sunday. Residents
used the time to thank God that the injuries were not more serious,
and to pray that no additional harm will come to their children as
they return to classes today for the first time since the incident.
</P>
<P>
   At a ``service of comfort'' Sunday at Ebenezer United Methodist
Church, clergy suggested the congregation tie red and white ribbons
around their car antennas today to show support for the students.
The service, which was attended by more than 200 residents of
different denominations, initially was planned to offer spiritual
support for residents trying to understand the war in Kosovo, the
shootings at Columbine High School and the recent spate of
tornadoes in the Mid-West.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear by their sniffles, tightly held hands and
comforting hugs that the incident in their own backyard was of more
concern to those congregated at Ebenezer.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Martha Wright, Ebenzer's minister of pastoral care,
said at first she wondered where God was during the shootings. But
then she realized he was with Heritage Assistant Principal Cecil
Brinkley, who disarmed the alleged 15-year-old gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Father John Keiran, pastor St. Pius X Church of which the gunman
was a member, told his congregation that now was the time for
residents to reach out and help one another.
</P>
<P>
   Around metro Atlanta, one minister took the occassion to discuss
school shootings for the second time in less than a month.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Randy Mickler, pastor of the 5,400-member Mt. Bethel
United Methodist Church, told church members trying to make sense
of the Heritage students that they must ask if they share part of
the blame. Church members across the nation, he said, haven't
reached out to people with problems and emphasized Bible-based
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children are searching for affirmation, a sense of purpose
and direction,'' Mickler said. ``Who best to do that but church
people? (But) our witness is weak because of who we have become _
fat, lazy pew-sitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
