<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-AD-COLUMN-NYT     05-23 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: COCA-COLA'S FORMER AD PHILOSOPHER NOTES
MARKETING CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumers might not have guessed, but the death of Diana,
Princess of Wales, had a profound effect on the marketing of
Coca-Cola in the days that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, New Coke was not the total disaster it has been
made out to be.
</P>
<P>
   And another thing: if the goal is to get people observing
Ramadan to drink their share of Coca-Cola, even though they are
fasting during the day, try marketing to them at night.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the kinds of insights offered up by Sergio Zyman, the
frenzied former marketing chief at Coke, the man both respected and
feared across the advertising industry as the ``Aya-Cola'' and
``Attila the Hun,'' in a newly published book, ``The End of
Marketing As We Know It'' (HarperCollins, $26).
</P>
<P>
   Zyman was one of the highest-paid executives at Coca-Cola and
was credited with revitalizing the company's formerly fusty image
when he left the company in March 1998 after a four-and-a-half-year
stint, his second with Coke. (The first ended in 1987, shortly
after New Coke was taken off the market.) At the time, he said he
would work as a consultant to Coke, write a marketing textbook, and
spend more time with his daughters, who are in their early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the book is a fait accompli. Zyman is a consultant
or director for more than half a dozen companies, including Cemex,
a large Mexican cement company, the Newspaper Association of
America and the American Tennis Professionals tour. Other clients
are Internet-based recent phenomena like Computerjobs.com and
Deja.com. (He yearns to become a consultant to the French
government, he added.) And the family life component _ well, ``The
End of Marketing As We Know It'' is dedicated to his wife and
daughters, ``for hanging in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone hoping to find the secret formula for Coca-Cola, either
the syrup or the stock performance, embedded in the book's 247
pages is in for a letdown. But Zyman does take the reader on a
whirlwind tour of his own marketing philosophy, which seems to be
an amalgam of the corporate and profit-oriented _ ``Never forget
that marketing is about selling stuff'' _ and the practically
devil-may-care, as in ``I'll try anything once.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an ego book; it's not a telltale book,'' Zyman said
last week, between bites of a Cobb salad in the restaurant at the
Four Seasons Hotel in Manhattan. He seemed much more relaxed than
in the Coca-Cola days, and politely batted away questions about
Coke, which, arguably, has had some marketing issues of its own
since he left last year. Zyman really wanted to talk about the
book, which he hopes will come to be regarded as a textbook, in the
tradition of David Ogilvy's ``Ogilvy on Advertising,'' for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   The basic message centers on Zyman's belief that marketing is
the name of the game, whether the game is tennis or selling soft
drinks. ``The conventional view of looking at marketing today is
gone,'' he said. ``It is too important to be left to the
marketers.'' The book includes a discussion of how he wrested
control of Coca-Cola's marketing away from its principal
advertising agency, McCann-Erickson, because he thought Coke
executives ``need to be the ones driving the strategy and making
the decisions.'' He hired different agencies to handle various
campaigns, and insisted on paying them fees, rather than the
commissions that were the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing requires hard work, not alchemy, Zyman writes.
Marketers have become too absorbed with what he calls ``the glitz,
the award presentations, the jetting off to `do a shoot' on some
tropical isle, and they have forgotten that their job is to sell
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   To hide their failings, they make marketing into a mysterious
enterprise, when all it is, Zyman writes, is a science, with a
strategy. ``Spending on marketing is an investment that pays
returns,'' he writes. ``If you think that marketing is just making
eye-catching commercials and occasionally goosing up volume with
rebates and promotions, you're fried. You will never succeed.'`
</P>
<P>
   He looks to politicians for inspiration _ ``They are the
ultimate marketers'' _ and thinks children, as marketing targets,
are both highly impressionable and unreliable. ``They are the most
disloyal consumers we have today,'' he said. ``They will abandon
you in a nanosecond.''
</P>
<P>
   And he offers a spirited defense of New Coke, widely considered
the biggest new-product flop in modern business history. ``It
turned out to be a roaring success for Coca-Cola, because it
rekindled the relationship between the American public and Classic
Coke,'' he writes in the book.
</P>
<P>
   And he adds that he did not leave Coke after the New Coke
debacle because he was fired. Rather, he sensed the environment was
not going to permit more experimentation. ``I rejoined Coke in 1993
because Roberto C. Goizueta and M. Doug Ivester, who were then
running the company, decided they were ready to start moving ahead
again,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Good marketing includes keeping track of a market's mood _ at
election time, during holidays, and in times of upheaval or grief,
he believes. To wit, when Diana died in a car crash in Paris in
1997, he commissioned some quick research to find out what it was
that caused the outpouring of sorrow in Britain and elsewhere.
``She was the ultimate example of balance,'' he said, recalling his
conclusions. ``She was the jet setter who cared about the land
mines, and the adulteress who cared about her kids. She had the yin
and the yang.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to that research, he writes, ``We didn't run big ads
that said, `Drown your sorrows in Coca-Cola.''' Instead, ``we
adjusted our mix of ads to send a balance of basic messages, ones
that celebrated life and ones that suggested comfort and
dependability. The changes we made were subtle, but the important
thing was that we were looking, and listening, and learning, and
acting. And it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
