BC-FINBUDGET-FINANCE _ BUDGET _ SFCHRON  

</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON  Here are the finance stories the San Francisco Chronicle plans to
move for AMs and PMs of Monday, May 23. For questions, please call
Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; XOOM  &LR; _ No. 1 TV network NBC is joining forces with two top Web
sites, Xoom.com and Snap, to create an Internet juggernaut called
NBCi. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE _  &LR; When it comes to getting on the Information
Superhighway, the phone company may provide a faster on-ramp than
the cable company. In an independent test performed by an Internet
consulting firm, Pacific Bell's digital subscriber lines provided a
slightly faster pipeline to the Internet &UR;  &LR; than a cable connection
from AtHome Corp. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Y2KWATCH  &LR; _ There is a legal quagmire surrounding the Y2K
problem, which is why Congress is debating legislation designed to
stop frivolous Y2K lawsuits from clogging the courts. By Benny
Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VIRUS  &LR; _ Serves me right for being a sadistic slob, for
reveling as a computerized blender churned an animated frog into a
disgusting, screaming swirl of green and red. That frog, sent via
e-mail, also was the likely carrier of the dreadful Chernobyl
computer virus that melted down my home PC on April 26. By Benny
Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIOSCOPE  &LR; _ Around the corner from the biotech trade show I
attended last week in Seattle, counterculture activists staged
their own tiny gathering, ``Biodevastation.'' Guys with Rastafarian
hair and women in hemp skirts gathered in a church to proselytize
against bioengineered crops. The short walk between those two shows
encapsulated the yawning gulf between the believers and naysayers
in agricultural biotechnology. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NET FILES  &LR; _  &LR;   &LR; Bookmark last week's price-slashing of
best-seller books by online merchants as another sad chapter in the
plight of independent booksellers during the digital age. By Jon
Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FARALLON &LR;  _ Farallon Communications is neither the first nor
the largest company to offer home-networking products, but it has a
unique twist: Farallon is first to market with a solution that
works with Apple Macs as well as Windows PCs. By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MACROMEDIA &LR;  _ San Francisco's Macromedia Inc., which makes
software widely used by Web and multimedia designers, now wants to
become a household word with average Internet consumers. By Benny
Evangelista
</P>
