A8074 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XOOM-FINBUDGET_XOOM &LR;      05-23 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XOOM-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ XOOM  
 Xoom Helps to Hatch the Peacock Portal  &HT;     By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Sometimes, Internet mergers can be stranger than fiction.
<P>
   Chris Kitze, chairman of San Francisco's Xoom.com, was hunched
over a conference table in midtown Manhattan late May 8, hammering
out a top-secret deal with NBC executives to create the mother of
all Web portal sites. One floor down, another hush-hush event was
in progress: Monica Lewinsky was rehearsing for her surprise guest
appearance on that night's ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Suddenly during the marathon negotiations, overhead TV
monitors flashed images of Lewinsky with a President Clinton
look-alike in a white robe. It is a common ritual at NBC to
broadcast dress rehearsals of the venerable comedy show throughout
Rockefeller Center on the evening of a performance.
</P>
<P>
   While some slack-jawed suits gave the boob tube a double take
and others chortled, Kitze _ undeterred by the negotiations and
history's most infamous intern _ plowed ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the going gets weird, the weird turn pro,'' Kitze says a
few days later in his San Francisco office, borrowing the words of
one of his influences, gonzo journalist Hunter S. Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was hallucinating,'' chimes in Xoom.com spokesman
Roger Maes, shaking his head. ``The whole scene was otherworldly,
surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   But not bizarre enough to stop Kitze, NBC executives Tom Rogers
and Marty Yudkovitz and a herd of financiers from forging an online
juggernaut by 5 a.m. the following Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Internet (NBCi) _ to be based in San Francisco and headed by
Kitze _ is an amalgam of news and entertainment content from NBC;
Xoom.com, an e-commerce and community site; and Snap.com, an
NBC-Cnet virtual venture for searches and directories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; By combining all three services under the Snap.com name, NBCi
hopes to convert TV viewers into online users. It will offer them
everything from digital video clips of ``Seinfeld'' and other
``Must See TV'' shows to breaking financial news reports and free
e-mail and chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, the venture is the first to meld a major
broadcast network and a popular Internet site, a powerful
combination. An estimated 92 million American homes tune into NBC
at some point each week. America Online, the world's most popular
online service, reaches 18 million paid subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Xoom.com has quickly built its own database of nearly 8 million
users because it was one of the first sites to offer an appealing
mix of free e-mail, Web-building tools, chat rooms and online
shopping. NBC would dearly like to tap into those subscribers and
millions of other Internet users to sell them NBC merchandise and
garner additional advertising revenue. Think of it as the Peacock
Portal, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xoom.com has done an amazing job of building a huge database
of users without extensive marketing. Now with a huge TV ad
campaign and NBC's name, they'll be in people's living rooms
regularly,'' said Catherine Skelly, Internet analyst at BlueStone
Capital Partners in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first example of convergence of TV and the
Internet,'' she added. ``It will turn Snap.com and Xoom.com into
household names.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds of Lewinsky cavorting with an ersatz President Clinton
seemed as unlikely a few months ago as say, little Xoom.com
becoming a linchpin in No.1 TV network NBC's Internet strategy.
Industry watchers peg the value of the new company _ which will be
the seventh-largest on the Internet _ at upward of $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in my wildest imagination did I believe that NBC would
be our partner,'' the 40-year-old Kitze said.
</P>
<P>
   Xoom.com, one of the few popular commercial Web sites not yet
acquired, had spent the previous few months talking with a long
list of corporate heavyweights _ CBS, Microsoft, Amazon.com, AtHome
and AOL _ about a merger or partnership, according to Kitze.
</P>
<P>
   NBC was a late entry after Cnet co-founder Halsey Minor
suggested to Kitze that Xoom talk to the peacock network.
</P>
<P>
   Xoom.com, formed in late 1996, quickly grew into one of the
Web's most visited sites as a so-called people portal. Its nearly 8
million members use a variety of free services, such as Web-page
building tools, chat rooms and digital greeting cards. Consumers
also can buy goods off the site, ranging from Beanie Babies to DVDs
and software. Xoom.com went public in December 1998 and now has a
market capitalization of $901.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But you couldn't tell by touring Xoom.com's pedestrian
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Kitze's spartan office typifies his corporate mantra: ``Make
money, don't spend money.'' There is a sizable tear in the shag
carpet near his $100 metal desk and a lovely view of some vents and
steam pipes outside his third-floor window.
</P>
<P>
   The only concessions to materialism are the lime-tinted iMac and
Lava lamp perched on his desk. His office's mostly bare walls are
undisturbed _ save for a pair of paintings of movie stills. Robert
Mitchum glowers over Kitze's right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the Seaside Hotel,'' Kitze cracks. ``I have good
taste; I just don't want to spend it here. This is not the Taj
Mahal.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Need further proof? Then saunter down the hallway of the
converted Bank of America offices to what used to be an executive
washroom. There, you'll find a row of video arcade games on the
marble floor. Half-filled soda cans and bottles are the only
evidence of a sugar-addled, late-night gaming session by Xoom.com's
engineers. Almost all of Xoom.com's 136 workers are shoehorned into
tiny cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, NBCi doesn't share Kitze's frugal disposition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The new venture plans to pour $380 million into TV ads (all
on its parent network, of course) promoting its Internet service
during the next four years, including a marketing blitz during the
network's coverage of the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney,
Australia. Pepsi, by comparison, spent $150 million on TV ads last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC's strategy is to do everything to have a major position in
the Internet,'' NBC chief executive Bob Wright said the day of the
deal. ``This (new venture) is a great way to pull (broadcast and
online services) together and hopefully get a great service
position in the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitze is more direct. ``This  &LR; is  &LR; NBC's Internet strategy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   NBCi, which will employ 350 to 400 people in San Francisco,
marks Kitze's largest venture to date.
</P>
<P>
   The serial entrepreneur has started and sold three interactive
companies: Point Communications, a reviewer of Web sites; Aris
Entertainment, a publisher of interactive CD-ROM titles based in
Marina del Rey (Los Angeles County); and Creative Multimedia,
another CD-ROM-maker in Portland, Ore. Kitze also was vice
president of marketing at portal company Lycos, which acquired
Point Communications in a stock deal in late 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Xoom.com's association with NBCi that will touch most
Americans, according to Kitze.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, the winners on the Internet will be the
ones with the strongest brand-name recognition,'' Kitze said.
``There are billions of dollars in brand equity tied into the NBC
name. You'll see a peacock at the bottom of every Web page on our
site.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
