r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2KWATCH-Y2KWATCH_SFC     05-23 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KWATCH-Y2KWATCH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Lawmakers Ponder Limits On Y2K Suits  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
When Andersen Consulting designed a computerized inventory control
system for Boston clothing retailer J. Baker Inc. 10 years ago,
both companies knew it might have a potential Y2K problem but
didn't think it was urgent.
<P>
   So J. Baker, which operates the Casual Male Big &AMP; Tall retail
chain, gave Andersen the contract to install the system and each
side dotted the I's and crossed the T's.
</P>
<P>
   But in June 1998, lawyers representing J. Baker threatened to
sue Andersen if the management consulting giant didn't pay the $3
million that it cost to fix the system's Y2K problem. Andersen
called in its own legal team and sued J. Baker.
</P>
<P>
   That case, said Andersen Consulting's Eric S. Jackson,
epitomizes the legal quagmire surrounding the Y2K problem. It also
illustrates why Congress is debating legislation designed to stop
frivolous Y2K lawsuits from clogging the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House of Representatives on May 12 approved the Year
2000 Readiness and Responsibility Act. Backed by the computer
industry and business groups, the legislation would limit punitive
damage awards to $250,000, make plaintiffs wait 90 days after a Y2K
failure before they can file a suit, encourage mediation instead of
litigation and limit the ability of lawyers to file broad,
class-action suits.
</P>
<P>
   Watchdog groups like Consumers Union, Public Citizen and the
U.S. Public Interest Research Group are protesting the bill, saying
it would harm consumers who have legitimate Y2K claims.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was supposed to consider a similar bill last week,
but the debate was delayed by the more heated gun control issue.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said legislation is needed to prevent the court system
from being overwhelmed by Y2K cases like Andersen vs. J. Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some organizations that absolutely should be held
accountable for what they didn't do, but this should not be a
windfall for lawyers,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen and J. Baker agreed to drop their claims in December
after an independent mediator found Andersen had met its
contractual obligations. Still, Andersen racked up thousands of
dollars in legal bills and hours of staff time on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Although Andersen is not directly involved in Y2K consulting
work, the company is using the case as a warning for its clients to
make sure they do everything possible to prevent Y2K foul-ups. That
includes fixing internal computer systems and determining which
vendors and suppliers may not be ready so that contingency plans
can be in place.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Reed Kathrein, a San Francisco attorney who
helped defeat two bills in Sacramento that also would have limited
Y2K-related lawsuits, said if companies follow those simple
guidelines, existing civil tort laws are enough to protect them
from frivolous Y2K suits.
</P>
<P>
   Kathrein, a partner with the law firm Milberg Weiss Bershad
Hynes &AMP; Lerach, said companies should spend less time worrying
about their potential legal liabilities and more time trying to
solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh  &LR; Help for Small Business
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute of Standards and Technology has a ``Y2K
jump-start kit'' designed to help small businesses. The package is
available through the agency's Y2K Center for Small Business at
(800) Y2K-7557 or at  &LR; www.y2khelp.nist.gov. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are other Y2K-related Web sites for small business owners:
</P>
<P>
   _Small Business Administration,  &LR; www.sba.gov/y2k &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _Telecommunications Industry Association's Year 2000 (Y2K)
Resource Page,  &LR; www.tiaonline.org/y2k &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _Information Technology Association of America's Year 2000 Home
Page, &LR;  www.itaa.org &LR;   &LR; /year2000. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _Federal Government Gateway for Year 2000 Information
Directories,  &LR; www.itpolicy.gsa.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FALLING BEHIND
</P>
<P>
   A new survey last week showed America's biggest companies were
falling behind on their Y2K work. About 74 percent of large
companies surveyed by Cap Gemini America LLC said they expected to
have more than half their software codes tested and Y2K compliant
by January 1, yet only 55 percent had actually met that goal.
</P>
<P>
   About 72 percent of the companies had already experienced a Y2K
problem, mostly due to software programs that miscalculated
financial data for 2000 or beyond, according to Cap Gemini, which
specializes in technology and management consulting. And 85 percent
were planning to build Y2K command or crisis centers.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate Gallup poll, eight out of 10 consumers were
confident that they will be able to use their ATM and debit cards
after the New Year, while 79 percent expected Y2K to have little or
no impact on their personal finances.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE LOW GROUND
</P>
<P>
   A company called HighGround Systems Inc. of Marlboro, Mass., has
launched a Y2K marketing campaign for software that manages data
backup storage. The company's public relations PR agency sent
journalists an official HighGround condom, along with a printed ad
with a picture of one that has sprung a leak.
</P>
<P>
   Among HighGround's list of Y2K clients: Siemens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
