r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRUS-VIRUS_SFCHRON &LR;      05-23 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-VIRUS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 ON TECHNOLOGY/BENNY EVANGELISTA  &HT;     How a Frog in a Blender Made My Computer Croak 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Serves me right for being a sadistic slob, for reveling as a
computerized blender churned an animated frog into a disgusting,
screaming swirl of green and red.
<P>
   That frog, sent via e-mail, also was the likely carrier of the
dreadful Chernobyl computer virus that melted down my home PC on
April 26.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, computer experts said the virus hardly caused a sneeze
in the United States. Chernobyl inflicted far more damage in other
countries, hitting about 300,000 computers in China alone.
</P>
<P>
   But antivirus software-maker Network Associates Inc. estimated
that 11,000 U.S. computer users were Chernobyled, 80 percent of
whom were home computer users like me. So for us, the frustration
and anger of wasting precious hours and spending sleep-deprived
nights fixing the damage was all too real.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a chance that strains of the virus, which can delete
some or all data on a hard drive, could strike again this Wednesday
or on the 26th of every month following.
</P>
<P>
   Chernobyl is ``one of those viruses that sits around and you
don't know you got it until the date arrives,'' said Yogesh Gupta,
a senior vice president for Computer Associates International Inc.,
which makes corporate-strength antivirus software.
</P>
<P>
   I feel especially foolish because four days before Chernobyl,
officially known as the CIH virus, was programmed to strike, I
received fair warning from Gupta's company and other computer
security experts that everybody needed to keep their antivirus
software updated.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was the nasty work of Chen Ing-hau, a 24-year-old
Taiwan resident who told authorities that he was trying to exact
revenge on what he called incompetent antivirus software-makers.
</P>
<P>
   Chen currently is serving in that country's military.
Personally, I hope he pulls latrine duty for the duration of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was timed to hit on April 26, the 13th anniversary of
the Chernobyl nuclear plant meltdown in the former Soviet Union.
Strains of the CIH virus are triggered on the 26th of every month,
but experts say those versions pose a lesser threat to the public
because they had less time to spread.
</P>
<P>
   CIH affects Microsoft Windows operating systems and is passed by
executable files from floppy disks, e-mail attachments, internal
network servers and the Internet, according to the Computer
Emergency Response Team at Carnegie Mellon University in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the virus overwrites the computer's system BIOS,
an expensive problem for laptop owners who have to replace internal
circuit boards, said CERT spokesman Bill Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   He said the most common file that spread the CIH virus was
frog.exe, known as the ``frog in a blender'' joke. The animated
program allows you to select various blender levels for an
obnoxious frog, all the way up to frog puree.
</P>
<P>
   I received the frog joke from a family member, so I didn't even
consider that it could be infected. I had antivirus software on my
computer but didn't keep it up to date because the free-upgrade
period for the software had expired.
</P>
<P>
   And part of me believed that those same software-makers who were
the object of Chen's ire were using another scare tactic to sell
their wares.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Melissa virus, which automatically sent itself
out to 50 e-mail addresses found in a PC user's files, was
contained fairly quickly after it was identified in March. A few
folks I know, including my boss, sent me Melissa-infected files
here at work, but The Chronicle's antivirus software stopped the
virus each time.
</P>
<P>
   So, lulled into a false sense of security, I forgot all about
Chernobyl until about 10 minutes after midnight on April 26, when
my PC crashed and would not reboot. A wave of panic splashed over
me like a tsunami.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a tech head, and to me, my computer is like my car. I
can add oil to the engine but don't ask me to change the timing
belt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, during the next few days, I tried remedies suggested by
friends and colleagues, including an off-the-shelf crash-recovery
program. Nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   I eventually had to wipe everything off the hard drive and start
fresh, including the time-consuming task of rebuilding the
operating system version by version, starting with the ancient DOS
6.2.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, important files like bank records were on a second hard
drive, which wasn't wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Even Computer Associates' Gupta, whose company now is offering a
free consumer version of its corporate antivirus software, once was
bitten by a computer virus.
</P>
<P>
   To recover, he said, ``it took us a whole weekend. I was working
until the wee hours of the morning. It's one of those things that
until it hits you, you don't really think about, and once it hits,
it's much harder to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that I have my computer running again, I will try to keep my
antivirus program fine-tuned to hunt down any future bugs.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe one of these days, I'll get around to checking to see
if my computer is Year 2000 compliant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
