<P>
   GUNS-SHOW (LAKEWOOD, Wash.) _ The single-shot pistols and rifles
are neatly aligned on the Asian rug covering the folding table.
Some of the metal on the old German guns have subtle, marble
coloring and multiple triggers that designate which barrel fires.
Across the aisle a collector has a hodge-podge of handguns and
pre-ban semiautomatic rifles and a few patches and buttons from the
Civil War for sale. Welcome to the all-American gun show, touted by
some as a celebration of U.S. history and the weapons that made it;
to others it's a Tupperware party for criminals.
</P>
<P>
   By Lise Olsen. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TERN-SALMON (RICE ISLAND, Wash.) _ The tern's feeding, so
natural and ordinary, has become a menace to Columbia River salmon
recovery. Caspian terns have built one of the world's largest tern
colonies here, about 20 miles east of where the river empties into
the Pacific Ocean, and are thought to be gobbling as much as
one-quarter of the Columbia Basin's dwindling salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Taylor. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-MULTIRACIAL (Seattle) _ When Matt Kelley reads media
accounts about interracial people, he often feels as if he has
entered ``The Twilight Zone.'' `` `Hi, My name is Matt. My mother
is Korean. My father is white. .. I'm sooooo proud,' '' he says,
mocking the tone of quotes in those articles. ``There is more to
us, to our experience, than that!'' But rather than knock the media
_ for using lame quotes or portraying multiracial people as exotic
or hip _ he has become the media. Kelley has created Mavin, a new
magazine that gives voice to young people from multiracial
backgrounds. as well as children who are adopted by parents of a
different ethnic background than their own.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert L. Jamieson Jr. (Story will move in the ``e''
category.)
