<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-735(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA SENDING FRESH TROOPS TO ALBANIAN BORDER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Adds sixth graph giving Yugoslav troop strength and 600-word
addend regarding effects of bombing, involvement of Montenegro,
mobilization efforts and the surge in refugee numbers.)  (jw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ As NATO enters its third month of air
attacks, the Yugoslav military is sending fresh troops into Kosovo
to reinforce positions near the border with Albania, alliance
officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The move suggests that the Yugoslav military is still determined
to maintain its hold on Kosovo and to continue its battle to drive
armed ethnic Albanian rebels from the province.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Serbs are being battered by round-the-clock air
strikes, which NATO leaders insist are disabling the Yugoslav
military, the dispatch of the troops appears to reflect a decision
by President Slobodan Milosevic to try to ride out the bombing in
hopes of negotiating better terms.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic still seems bent on being able to get a diplomatic
deal that enables him to declare victory to his people rather than
yield directly to NATO's demands and withdraw his forces from
Kosovo, where more than a million Albanians have been driven from
home since NATO began bombing on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no sign of withdrawal,'' said NATO's military
spokesman, Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz of Germany. ``The contrary is
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO says there are about 40,000 Yugoslav soldiers and Interior
Ministry police officers in Kosovo. Jertz said he was not able to
estimate the precise number of fresh troops being sent in, but he
suggested that they were being used to replace soldiers killed in
allied air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The border region where NATO officials have observed
reinforcements has been the scene of intense fighting between the
Yugoslav military and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the Kosovar
Albanian rebel group fighting for independence for their province.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces have been trying to seal the border with
minefields and troops to prevent the rebels from sending men and
supplies into Kosovo from their bases in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   There are 6,000 to 10,000 Albanian partisans inside Kosovo,
allied intelligence officials estimate. The rebels hide in
mountainous regions in north-central and south-central Kosovo.
Recently they took the village of Produc near the town Podujevo in
northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Serbs' campaign of driving Albanians from their homes
and then burning hundreds of villages has deprived the rebels of
their base of popular support and left them short of supplies,
including food.
</P>
<P>
   That has made it all the more important for the Kosovo
Liberation Army to keep open its supply lines from Albania. Aside
from an incident on Friday in which allied warplanes bombed a
Yugoslav Army border post captured by the rebels weeks earlier,
NATO's air strikes have helped the rebel effort to keep those vital
lines working.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has no official relationship with the Albanian partisans,
but rebel leaders have said their men provide NATO with information
on Yugoslav positions. Allied air strikes against Yugoslav armor,
artillery and troops have worn down the Serbs' ability to strike
against the rebels and forced the Serbs to dodge air strikes by
hiding hardware, thus easing the pressure on the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the alliance plans a series of meetings to decide
whether to prepare a force totaling some 50,000 troops to go into
Kosovo to keep a negotiated peace. Within three weeks, alliance
officials have said, NATO will have to decide whether to prepare a
ground force powerful enough to invade the province and return the
hundreds of thousands of Albanian refugees to Kosovo before the
onset of harsh Balkan winter.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, NATO has relied on air power alone, and allied
officials continue to insist that that approach is working. Touting
their two months of bombing raids, officials said Sunday that NATO
planes had directed 14,000 missiles and bombs, 10,000 of which were
precision guided, against targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO says the attacks have destroyed one-third of the Serbs'
heavy military equipment in Kosovo: more than 550 tanks, artillery
pieces and trucks. The bombing raids, NATO said, have also
destroyed half of the Serbs' ammunition storage sites in Kosovo and
11 command posts.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from targeting the Yugoslav military in Kosovo, the
alliance says it has destroyed more than 100 Yugoslav combat
aircraft in raids across the country. It has also pounded and
destroyed many of Serbia's bridges, rail lines and roads,
repeatedly assailed its oil refineries and often interrupted power
and water supplies to large parts of the republic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to send in fresh recruits indicates that the
Serbs are not yet ready to give up. The move contrasts with the
reports of desertions, which allied officials cited last week as a
sign of weakening Serbian morale.
</P>
<P>
   The new recruits, from Montenegro, are stationed near Pec, a
town close to the northern part of the the Albanian-Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has been careful to limit its bombing strikes against
Montenegro, Serbia's sole remaining partner in the Yugoslav
federation, a much smaller republic whose leader has distanced
himself from the Kosovo campaign waged by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav military, which has several important installations
in Montenegro, has sought to take advantage of this restraint, not
only by sending troops in from that republic, but by stationing
aircraft and radar equipment there.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Yugoslav recruits arrived in Pec without their
armored vehicles and heavy military equipment, an indication of the
difficulty that convoys have experienced in moving along Kosovo
roads in the face of allied air attacks, allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The recruits are not the only troops that have been sent, allied
officials said. The Yugoslav military has also dispatched elements
of a special operations unit to near the western Kosovo town of
Junik _ a Kosovo Liberation Army stronghold fiercely contested
since last year _ to replace soldiers killed in allied bombing
raids, Western officials say.
</P>
<P>
   To organize additional forces, President Milosevic has been
mobilizing reservists, a move that has led to some scattered
political protests and demonstrations in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of people coming back home, everybody is being called
up,'' said Jamie Shea, NATO's chief spokesman. ``The Yugoslav Army
is now trying to mobilize an increasing number of reservists who
don't want to be mobilized.''
</P>
<P>
   As the war drags on, the Serbs have also continued their
campaign against Albanian civilians. There has been a dramatic
surge in recent days in the number of civilians who have been
forced out of Kosovo or who have fled because of fear and hunger.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, some 14,000 refugees crossed into Macedonia, the
largest exodus since early May.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been a sharp increase in flow of refugees to
Albania: 3,650 arrived on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They included 583 men who had been imprisoned near the northern
Kosovo town of Mitrovica. NATO said the men were not members of the
Kosovo Liberation Army but had been mistreated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all handcuffed,'' Shea said, ``until shortly before
they reached the border.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
