<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8087 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-NETFILES_SFC     05-23 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-NET </SLUG>
 FILES _ SF CHRON  
 THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ  &HT;     Online Cuts Burn Indie Booksellers 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Bookmark last week's price-slashing of best-seller books by online
merchants as another sad chapter in the plight of independent
booksellers during the digital age.
<P>
   Amazon.com, Barnesandnoble.com, Borders.com and
Booksamillion.com said they will offer discounts of 50 to 55
percent on best-sellers on the New York Times list to consumers.
The moves should increase online traffic at each site and, more to
the point, drive up their already inflated market capitalizations.
Amazon.com, which has yet to turn a profit in its four-year
history, is valued at $21.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In their dogged pursuit of market share and sales at the expense
of profits, the online merchants have made it clear that they are
willing _ almost eager _ to hemorrhage millions of dollars in the
short term to woo consumers to their Web sites. The theory is that
with a broad audience, online retailers will be able to set premium
advertising rates, auction items and sell commodities besides
books, such as videos and CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Calculated? Perhaps. Brazenly insensitive to the financial
health of indie booksellers? You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a lot of book clubs around the country will begin to
order their books online while they are still on the (best-seller)
list rather than wait for them to come out in paper,'' said Jeremy
Potash, a founding member of the 26-year-old Oakland Women's
Literary Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commercial Web sites constantly preach community, but what
they're really pushing is sacrificing good business sense for
market share,'' said Charlotte Cook, co-owner of Sunrise Bookshop
in Berkeley. ``Why don't they just send books to consumers along
with $10?''
</P>
<P>
   Although shoppers may love this novel giveaway, their enthusiasm
could be short-lived. Membership in the American Booksellers
Association has dwindled to 3,300 from 5,200 in 1992, leaving
consumers with fewer choices _ save for chain stores at the local
mall. That's hardly encouraging news for generations of readers
reared on quaint bookstores with quirky titles.
</P>
<P>
   For those stubborningly seeking solace in dirt-cheap prices,
consider this: As online book merchants grow in influence, don't
expect them to continue to offer steep discounts. If anything,
expect price increases.
</P>
<P>
   In the Internet age, a billboard in Mill Valley best sums up the
sentiments of book lovers everywhere: ``Think globally, shop
locally.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CLARK'S LAW: Net entrepreneur Jim Clark is almost the human
embodiment of Moore's Law. That's the theory in which Intel
co-founder Gordon Moore predicted that the number of transistors
the industry would be able to place on a computer chip would double
every 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   With each successive venture, Clark has established a shorter
time period between starting a company and building it into an
enterprise worth billions of dollars. The cycle took 10 years at
Silicon Graphics, almost three years at Netscape Communications and
two years at Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   At this pace, we expect Clark's latest brainchild, MyCFO, to be
a billion-dollar enterprise before the clock strikes midnight this
New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Historical note: In 1995, Moore amended his prediction to once
every two years. He probably didn't have Clark in mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHERE IMAC CUSTOMERS SHOP: A few years ago, Macintoshes were
second-class citizens at most computer retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our products were displayed horrendously,'' said Mitch
Mandich, Apple senior vice president of worldwide sales. ``They
were dusty, buried in the darkest corner of a store's PC section.
It made you sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the surging computer pioneer inked a deal with Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. to further remedy its distribution blahs: Starting
Memorial Day weekend, the largest U.S. department store chain will
carry the rainbow-hued iMacs at 825 locations.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, the news was far more bitter. Apple concentrated
its retail efforts on CompUSA _ the nation's largest PC retailer _
and deep-sixed agreements with Sears, Circuit City Stores Inc.,
Best Buy Co., Computer City and Office Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the high-water mark of the company's revenues, in the
mid-1990s, Apple tried to saturate the market by offering Macs in
every conceivable place,'' said Stephen Baker, senior hardware
analyst at PC Data Inc. in Reston, Va. &UR;  &LR; ``Unfortunately, they
didn't have compelling consumer products to sell and their models
were overpriced. That seems to have changed with iMacs.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot-selling iMacs have helped polish Apple's brand name
among the coveted Generation Y crowd and computer novices. Nearly
half of the 1.15 million units sold so far were purchased by
first-time buyers or Windows converts. Apple's pact with Sears
should make the Internet machines a lot more accessible to the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sears is an optimum distribution network in nonmetropolitan
areas, and half of its PC shoppers are first-time buyers,'' Mandich
said. ``They fit our retail profile perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being relegated to the dustbin of computer stores,
Apple now is picking and choosing its distribution partners,
according to Mandich.
</P>
<P>
   Apple scotched a potential deal with Best Buy last month because
the Minneapolis chain insisted on carrying only the top-seller
``blueberry'' iMac flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DOT.COM MERGER MANIA: Northern California is ground zero for
virtual king making in the United States, accounting for a fourth
of all Internet mergers and acquisitions since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 43 deals, worth a whopping $11.5 billion, were
inked in the Bay Area, including 17 in San Francisco, according to
Web Merger Watch in San Francisco ( &LR; www.webmergers.com &LR; ). The
report covered 178 transactions valued at $19 billion during the
past 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend will continue _ indeed, accelerate _ as long as
stock valuations, or overvaluations, of Internet companies
persist,'' said Tim Miller, president of New Media Resources in San
Francisco, which published the quarterly report.
</P>
<P>
   Putting their paper currency to use, Web companies spent nearly
twice as much on mergers during January 1999 ($11.5 billion) as
they did in 1998 ($6 billion). A pair of monster deals _ At Home's
$6.7 billion purchase of Excite, and Yahoo's $4.6 billion buyout of
GeoCities _ ignited the steep rise in spending.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Healtheon and WebMD confirmed that they are tying the
knot in a stock deal worth about $9.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that by using their overinflated stocks to buy
other companies, firms like Yahoo and AtHome further inflate the
value of their own stocks,'' Miller said. ``Eventually, this
self-perpetuating cycle has to end.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's investor-frenzied climate? Don't hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Leery of online quackery? Then  &LR; www.healthfinder.gov &LR;  may be your
prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, death is as inevitable as taxes. Determine your date
with the grim reaper at  &LR; www.deathclock.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for those sick of the hype:  &LR; www.ihatestarwars.com &LR; .
</P>
