<HEADLINE>
FRESNO GUN SHOW DRAWS A QUIET SUNDAY CROWD
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. _ It was a perfect day for rifle shopping. A
lazy, hazy Sunday, when the gun show inside a building at the
County Fairgrounds would be cool and dark and inviting.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Barber and his 9-year-old son, Billy, made it to the gates
of the fairgrounds at 9 a.m. sharp. They knew that by noon the
crowds could make the gun show feel like a Christmas season mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy is already a great shot,'' said Barber, a farm supplies
salesman, mussing his son's blond bowl haircut into a frenzy. ``We
shoot skeet and he can pretty much shoot wherever he aims.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few fathers and sons made it to the Fresno Gun Show
Sunday. So did quite a few mothers and sons, fathers and daughters,
brothers and sisters, husbands and wives. Hunting buddies came in
threes and fours, families in three generations, dates holding
hands and new parents holding babies.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to see the wares of 90 dealers selling everything from
antique ammo to Winchester rifles was $7 for adults, with children
under 13 free. And anyone who would ask why on earth anyone would
bring children to a festival of arms and ammunition would be
immediately branded as one of The Other Kind. To people in and at
this show, it was pretty clear that there are two kinds of people
in this world: gun people, and the other kind, who just do not get
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see any gun nuts here, do you?'' said Charlie Brady,
a carpenter and lifelong backyard target shooter. His T-shirt,
stretched over his belly, read, ``I Get Enough Exercise Pushing My
Luck,'' which was about the zaniest thing anyone here wore. One or
two people came in camouflage, or with rifles slung over their
shoulders. But at a time when gun shows have become a major target
of lawmakers in Washington pushing for new restrictions, the most
striking thing about this one is how benign it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   This could be because California already has strict laws
governing gun sales at these events. In a way, the Fresno Gun Show
could be the future of gun shows everywhere. The laws here are as
strict as those proposed in the Senate bill that passed last week,
in some ways stricter. Buyers must be 21 years old. They must take
a safety test. And guns purchased are held for 10 days, for a
background check. Armed security guards stand at the doors and long
laundry lists of rules are posted on the doors. (No trading
firearms, for example.)
</P>
<P>
   No one was going to walk out of the Fresno Gun Show with a
handgun, unless they brought it with them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these are testy times for gun dealers here, same as
everywhere else. A lot of them spend a lot of time going up and
down the state to these shows, hauling their arms and children and
dogs in motor homes with mini-satellite dishes. They sounded tired
of defending themselves against criticisms that their livelihood is
at least indirectly responsible for most of the mayhem in society.
Several dealers declined to be interviewed, and one, who dealt
mostly in handguns, was openly hostile, continually telling other
dealers that they should not grant interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Padgett, who runs the Fresno show and others in eight
cities throughout California, said dealers blame the media for many
of their problems. When California passed its strict gun show laws
in 1992, at a time of random shootings and a crack epidemic, the
shows were blamed for those maladies. Now, he said, he thinks gun
shows and dealers are becoming scapegoats for all of society's
failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've raised three children and have four grandchildren and
they've all been around guns,'' Padgett said. ``I always watched my
kids, taught them about the seriousness of guns, and I never had
any problem. Evidently, my kids are doing the same with their kids.
I think it all starts at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Richards, a retired landscape surveyor who was selling decoy
ducks he had carved himself, along with some ammunition and a gun
or two, was one of several dealers who echoed the sentiment. ``When
I was a kid,'' Richards said, ``I was taught how to use a gun. Our
guns were kept in a corner. I knew the guns were always in the
corner, and I knew I was not supposed to take a gun unless I had
permission. We never had an incident, never had anyone shoot
anyone. Of course, we didn't have TV or movies like we do now,
either. I, at 78 years old, turn off my TV because of what's on.''
</P>
<P>
   Half of the two dozen people interviewed said they were not gun
fanatics; the show was just something to do. Fresno, (population:
about 350,000) is a sleepy city, though the almond and berry farms
collide with sprawling housing developments. True, the city has an
urban center, but even a casino smack in the middle of it has not
brought back the life that fled downtown for highway strip malls.
The gun show and the swap meet right across the street were a way
to round out a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark and Mary Trujillo brought their three children, 9-year-old
twin girls and a 6-year-old boy. While Trujillo looked at rifles,
Mrs. Trujillo and the children looked over stuffed toy animals made
with real animal fur.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to see too many vegetarians at these shows,''
Mrs. Trujillo said with a laugh. She watched her son, his eyes as
big as plates, find his dad aiming a rifle. ``I want my children to
know how to use guns,'' she said, ``because I learned how to use a
gun when I was a kid. It's more American than apple pie.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
