A8090 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACROMEDIA-MACROMEDIA     05-23 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACROMEDIA-MACROMEDIA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Macromedia Will Unveil a Shocker  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Macromedia Inc., which makes software widely used by Web and
multimedia designers, now wants to become a household word with
average Internet consumers.
<P>
   A pioneer of San Francisco's Multimedia Gulch, Macromedia today
cq monday  &LR;  will launch a new company called shockwave.com,cq on
lower case s &LR;  part of a shift to a consumer-oriented strategy
marketing ``online entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   The new company, headed by former Disney Interactive executive
Stephen Fields, will offer software that can be downloaded from the
Internet onto a computer to play and organize games like Frogger
and Centipede.
</P>
<P>
   The free ``shockmachine'' player also will play back online
versions of cartoons like the edgy ``South Park,'' along with music
and interactive comics created with Macromedia's Flash and
Shockwave software. The player also can be used to create animated
e-mail greetings and to play MP3-encoded files.
</P>
<P>
   An expanded version of the shockmachine with more storage will
sell for $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia has lined up several well-known entertainment
companies to provide content, including Comedy Central, Fox
Interactive, Hasbro Interactive, GT Interactive Software, Warner
Bros. Online, Mplayer and ZDNet.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia chief executive Rob Burgess called the new venture
the ``logical next big step'' in the evolution of Macromedia, which
has shifted from making multimedia software for CD-ROMs to tools
for Web publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the company's ShockRave, an interactive gaming
site started as a showcase for Macromedia products, ``showed us
people were ready for an entertainment experience on the Web,''
Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts favored the move and said the new company has potential
to become another hot ``dot com'' Internet stock. Burgess said an
IPO is a possibility down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a clever strategy,'' said Seamus McAteer, director of Web
technology strategies for Jupiter Communications. Macromedia
``would be leaving competitors such as Adobe in their wake.''
</P>
<P>
   In shockwave.com, Macromedia is borrowing a page from the
playbook of RealNetworks Inc., the Seattle company that sells
streaming audio and video software. As RealNetworks has done with
RealPlayer, Macromedia wants to distribute shockmachines as widely
as possible, which would, in turn, help increase sales of
Macromedia's Web authoring programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them, this is a real departure,'' said Harley Manning,
research director for Forrester Research Inc. ``It leverages their
core strengths in a way they've never done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia's Flash and Shockwave players reach about 77 percent
of all Web users. Flash has been included with Microsoft and Apple
operating systems, Netscape's Navigator and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done a fabulous job of seeding the market over the
last year or so,'' Manning said. ``Having seeded the market,
they're ready to harvest something. They're trying to see what can
be a cash crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're thinking like a consumer products company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new shockwave.com will start as a wholly owned subsidiary of
Macromedia and will have about 80 workers by the end of the year, a
mixture of new hires and existing Macromedia employees. The
headquarters will be down the street from Macromedia's Townsend
Street building.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia closed at $49.50 on Friday, up $4.19.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
