<SLUG> BC-FARALLON-FARALLON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Farallon Gives Wing to Home Networking  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Farallon Communications is neither the first nor the largest
company to offer home-networking products, but it has a unique
twist: Farallon is first to market with a solution that works with
Apple Macs as well as Windows PCs.
<P>
   The San Leandro company's new HomeLINE products will let family
members on two or more computers participate in multiplayer games,
share files and printers and get online simultaneously via the same
Internet account and modem.
</P>
<P>
   Because HomeLINE uses existing phone wiring and jacks to connect
the computers _ without interfering with voice traffic _ no new
wires are needed.
</P>
<P>
   All this also is true of phone-line networking products already
available from Intel, Diamond Multimedia and several smaller
players. But those offerings work only on PCs, while Farallon's can
create networks of multiple Macs, multiple PCs or a mixture of the
two.
</P>
<P>
   A HomeLINE Starter Kit for connecting two machines will cost
$139, while a Single Pack for adding another system will be $79.
Both packages include PC and Mac software, plus circuit boards that
have to be plugged into a PCI slot inside the computer. Most
desktop PCs and Macs manufactured in recent years have such slots.
</P>
<P>
   But the iMac, the all-in-one model that's helped Apple grab back
a growing share of the consumer-computer market, doesn't have any
slots. Farallon said it plans to release an external HomeLINE
connection device for iMacs this summer. That product also will
work with at least some of Apple's PowerBook laptops.
</P>
<P>
   PC notebooks also lack PCI slots, but according to Farallon,
they can be connected to a HomeLINE network by using an Intel
product called AnyPoint, one version of which attaches to PC
printer ports. Both Farallon and Intel, as well as other vendors,
have based their products on a new standard developed by a trade
consortium called the Home Phoneline Networking Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Farallon said, its PCI cards are manufactured by Intel
and its Windows software is based on Intel's.
</P>
<P>
   The software enabling HomeLINE users to share files and printers
between Mac and PCs works for only three hours per session. Users
who want an unlimited version can upgrade for about $100.
</P>
<P>
   As of a year ago, more than 18 million U.S. households had more
than one personal computer, according to Dataquest research cited
by Farallon. Between 3 million and 4 million of those had both Macs
and PCs, even though the survey was conducted before the
hot-selling iMac was released.
</P>
<P>
   Farallon was founded in 1986 to market local-area networking
products developed by Mac enthusiasts at the University of
California at Berkeley. The original company gradually shifted its
focus to Internet hardware and software, and in 1987, it changed
its name to Netopia Inc. But last year, Netopia spun off a separate
company, under the old Farallon name, to market and develop some of
its local-area products.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
