<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEAFS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES, WITHOUT HASEK, TAKE A 1-0 LEAD ON THE MAPLE LEAFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A much-discussed feature of the new Air Canada Center
is the corridor by the locker rooms, where fans from the rink-level
seats can gather to see players walk to and from the ice. When
visiting players are angry or fans are heckling, it creates some
tension. And when a star player is out of uniform, unexpectedly, it
generates a buzz of gossip that shoots like an electric current
from the ground floor to the highest seat in the arena.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case Sunday in the hour before the Buffalo Sabres
took the ice to defeat the Toronto Maple Leafs by 5-4 in Game 1 of
the four-of-seven game Eastern Conference finals of the Stanley Cup
playoffs. The Sabres played without Dominik Hasek, generally
considered the best goalie in hockey in the 1990s. Hasek had
re-injured his groin during the previous series against Boston and
he said it got worse during the five days off before Sunday. The
Sabres kept the secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I didn't want to expose,'' said Sabres Coach
Lindy Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's backup, Dwayne Roloson, stopped 28 of 32 Toronto shots
to earn the victory. Hasek said he would return to Buffalo tonight
while his teammates remained in Toronto for Tuesday's Game 2. There
will be more tests and treatment, but Hasek seemed discouraged when
asked about his health and state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very worried,'' said Hasek, 34, who won both the Hart and
Vezina trophies in both 1997 and 1998 as the most valuable player
and the best goalie in the National Hockey League. Again this
season, he is one of three finalists for both awards. ``I'm not
able to make a butterfly,'' he said, referring to a shot-blocking
technique that involves dropping to the knees and spreading the leg
pads. ``I cannot go up and down. It never healed. Unfortunately, it
did not get better. It got even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's absence, if prolonged, could have a significant effect
on the series. Roloson, although 29 years old, never started a
playoff game before Sunday. He appeared in 18 regular-season games
this season and in one in the post-season, when Hasek was hurt.
Although he is from nearby Simcoe, Ontario, Roloson said he did not
call his family on Saturday night to let them know he was playing.
His relatives were on vacation, at their cottage, for the long
Victoria Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to call them, wreck their weekend,'' Roloson
said. ``I wanted them to relax and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Toronto goal, Curtis Joseph gave up five goals on the
first 19 Buffalo shots. Also a finalist for the Vezina, Joseph was
not at his sharpest Sunday, but few players for either team were.
Although the game had many exciting moments, it was loosely played,
filled with the turnovers and other mistakes that could have been a
sign of opening-game nervousness, bad ice conditions or of new foes
trying to figure out each other's styles.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto scored three of its four goals on power plays and held a
3-2 lead, briefly, during the second period. Buffalo pulled ahead
for good in the third period, going up by 5-3 before Steve Thomas
scored for the Maple Leafs to cut the final deficit to one goal.
Vaclav Varada, Dixon Ward, Stu Barnes, Curtis Brown and Geoff
Sanderson scored for Buffalo. Barnes' goal, on the power play, was
his first as a Sabre in 28 games since being traded from
Pittsburgh. Mats Sundin scored twice for the Leafs and Bryan Berard
got the other. Sundin's first was at even strength, 9 seconds after
Varada had opened the scoring at 4 minutes 23 seconds of the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Hasek has been injured in the
playoffs. In 1997, he played only three games before sitting out
with a knee injury. There was much debate then about the
seriousness of the injury and about its connection to Hasek's
deteriorating relationship with Sabres Coach Ted Nolan, who was
fired after the season. This time, there seems to be no doubt about
the injury. Hasek missed 12 games during the season because of the
groin injury and traveled to Germany for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said after the game: ``Don't say he doesn't want to play.
Because of the pain, he can't. It's possible that the area has
become inflamed. We'll approach it on a day-to-day basis.''
Roloson's teammates seemed to take it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, one of the goal-scorers, said: ``I was excited for Rolie.
He got an opportunity he deserved and wanted and he was waiting
for.''
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs did not seem too discouraged. They also lost the
opening games of the first two rounds, against Philadelphia and
Pittsburgh. The winner of this series will play Dallas or Colorado
in the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't go the way I wanted it to,'' Joseph said.
``We've lost the first game in the last two rounds and overcame it.
We're looking to do the same thing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
