<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PETERPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERKENS, MASTER OF UPSETS, HAS MOUNT IN BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Allen Jerkens, a trainer with a history of
springing upsets, reared his head again Sunday at Belmont Park when
his colt Best of Luck won the Peter Pan Stakes in the mud and
thrust himself into the Triple Crown path of Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Best of Luck is a 3-year-old son of Broad Brush who ran second
in the Wood Memorial in April and second in the Withers in May
while Charismatic was winning the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness.
Jerkens has kept him clear of the Triple Crown wars _ until now.
But Best of Luck is a long-striding horse who runs from far back
and then makes his move late and long in the homestretch, a style
well suited for the rigors of the Belmont Stakes and its distance
of a mile and a half.
</P>
<P>
   And he gave a perfect performance in the Peter Pan, trailing by
15 lengths before cranking up his power in the final quarter of a
mile and winning by one length over Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he acts OK, we'll take a shot at the Belmont,'' Jerkens
said. ``He seems to really be coming into his own. His style of
running, coming from far behind, isn't conducive to winning a lot
of races. But it looks like it will be a slower pace in the big
one. And he should be able to go the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Going the distance was no problem Sunday. Best of Luck, running
on a muddy track for the first time, went the mile and one-eighth
in 1:47 4/5, just one-fifth of a second slower than Adonis ran
while winning the Wood Memorial on a fast track. But in the
homestretch he gathered momentum on the outside, flew past the
leaders and crossed the finish line a length in front of Treasure
Island, who had a length and a half on Lemon Drop Kid.
</P>
<P>
   Farther back in the pack came several other colts with somewhat
equal betting appeal: Unbridled Jet, fifth; Successful Appeal,
winner of the Withers, seventh, and The Groom is Red, an
acknowledged mud-runner from Nick Zito's barn, eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But if Best of Luck took some long strides on his road to the
Belmont Stakes, which is June 5, several of his rivals came to the
end of their Triple Crown hopes. Shug McGaughey said that Treasure
Island might run in the Dwyer on July 11 or the Ohio Derby on July
24, but not in the Belmont. Bill Mott, the trainer of Unbridled
Jet, said that he was not certain where his colt would run next but
that it would not be in the Belmont. And Zito said The Groom Is Red
``looked great and trained great, but he didn't run great,'' and
added that he had no agenda right now for his horse.
</P>
<P>
   Best of Luck ran his usual suspenseful race, breaking eighth in
a field of nine and hanging ninth after half a mile while Barry
Schwartz's colt David set the pace.
</P>
<P>
   As they passed three-quarters of a mile, Best of Luck was
eighth. David was starting to soften up in the stretch, but
Treasure Island was right at his heels in second place, where he
had been running from the start.
</P>
<P>
   But Best of Luck followed the Jerkens script faithfully. With
Jean-Luc Samyn riding, he turned for home five-wide, shot forward
from the outside and ran past the herd, buying himself a ticket to
the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Best of Luck, in earning $90,000 with his third victory in eight
starts, returned $9.20, $4.60 and $3 for a $2 bet. Treasure Island
paid $10.80 and $5.80 and Lemon Drop Kid was $3.30 to show.
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Schulhofer, who trains Lemon Drop Kid, said later that he
was still planning to run in the Belmont, but added, ``He ran good,
but a better horse beat him.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
