</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS IS PREPARING FOR THE RED-CLAY WARS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Never say never. That's the mantra Pete Sampras takes
into the only Grand Slam event to defy him. Sampras' aversion to
the French Open's red clay is reminiscent of Ivan Lendl's terminal
allergy to Wimbledon's grass, and it's an aversion Sampras shares
with a couple of unlikely soul mates, top-ranked Martina Hingis and
13th-seeded Andre Agassi. Like him, they have found Slam
gratification every place but here at the clay-court marathon that
represents the missing link in their Grand Slam biographies.
</P>
<P>
   On this, his 10th attempt to solve Roland Garros, a feat fellow
Americans and former No. 1s John McEnroe and Jimmy Connors never
did master, Sampras can catch Roy Emerson's career record by
capturing his 12th career Grand Slam title on June 6. But that
seems a tall order. If the French Open, which begins Monday, were
played in hermetically sealed conditions, Sampras, a fuss-budget
and perfectionist, no doubt would have won it years ago. But the
French is anything but climate controlled, and the second-seeded
Sampras is anything but in his heyday.
</P>
<P>
   As the defending champion, Carlos Moya of Spain, pointed out
Sunday, every day at the French ``is going to be like war.''
According to Moya, Sampras may be ``the greatest player ever,'' but
not for these two weeks. Moya listed the 1997 champion Gustavo
Kuerten, Chile's Marcelo Rios, and anybody with a Spanish passport
as his 1999 French Open sure shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a whole 'nother animal,'' Sampras said about his
struggles here, where he is 22-9 and his best effort remains a
semifinal finish during an uncommon balmy spell in 1996. ``I'm a
bit of a dark horse,'' he said of his attempts to cope with the
ever-changing temperament of the French.
</P>
<P>
   On picturesque sunny days, trekking through a match is a bit
like a forced march across the Sahara: grit gets in the eyes and
mouth and paints tennis whites brick red, and unless a player has
some grit in the back of his mind, he probably won't survive for
future rounds.
</P>
<P>
   On cold and clammy days, players slog away on a surface that
resembles red quicksand. Rain or shine, there are no cakewalks
here, and nobody buys a free pass to the final on the strength of a
bullying serve and whiz-bang volley.
</P>
<P>
   Better to own a sly drop shot, a ton of topspin, and a physique
that understands the hidden meaning of go-with-the-flow: anybody
too tense to slide and glide gets blisters instead of results.
</P>
<P>
   The French Open is the dirtiest Slam event to win, but there is
an elusive art to negotiating it. In the recent past it has
thwarted the likes of McEnroe, Connors, and Stefan Edberg,
versatile stars who managed to master all three other Slam events
before closing the curtain on their careers. Sampras is not the
obsessive sort, but he knows that selective greatness, like his
five Wimbledons, won't put him on equal footing in the record book
with the icons Don Budge and Rod Laver: it's going to take a French
Open victory to round out the resume.
</P>
<P>
   After being hissed off the court two weeks ago at the Italian
Open, where he fell to Fernando Meligeni, 6-3, 6-1 in the second
round, Sampras, who skipped the Australian Open and had played just
10 matches through the first four months of 1999, described himself
as ``rusty'' and ready to ``go back to the drawing board.''
</P>
<P>
   The most formidable player on clay of late has been Kuerten, the
Brazilian who seemed to be airlifted off a surfboard and out of
anonymity and dropped into the 1997 finale. Patient, resilient, and
seemingly tireless, he is the consummate clay-court animal. A
``monster,'' Moya observed.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 French Open was Kuerten's first career title, and since
then he has collected three more on clay, two this spring while
compiling an 18-3 clay-court record (second only to Rios' 20-4)
with victories at Monte Carlo and the Italian Open. At Rome,
Kuerten defeated Patrick Rafter in a final that denied the
Australian the chance to become his country's first No. 1 since
John Newcombe in 1974. In Paris, no fewer than five men _ Sampras,
Rafter, Kuerten, Richard Krajicek and Tim Henman _ have a chance to
snatch the No. 1 ranking from the 1996 French Open champion,
Yevgeny Kafelnikov, who plays the 1989 Roland Garros champion,
Michael Chang, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, the 18-year-old Hingis, who commandeered
every Grand Slam tournament but the French in 1997 and has never
forgiven herself that lapse, has serious designs on the only major
missing from her trophy case. Hingis hit Paris on the heels of a
title at the German Open, where she sent the French Open's
defending champion, Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, a 6-4, 6-0 tennis-gram
in the semifinals. Sanchez Vicario, who contemplated wrist surgery
in December, has admitted she will be relying on adrenaline, not
fitness, as she begins her title defense Monday against Mirjana
Lucic. Hingis, in contrast, claims all systems are go to make
restitution for last year's semifinal loss to Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about my game and my fitness level right now; the
past few years I've always lost in Berlin and then lost at Roland
Garros, so I hope that this year will be a good omen for me,''
Hingis said. Her 13-1 clay-court record, and two titles on clay,
are the envy of everyone except archrival Venus Williams, who
compiled a 9-1 record courtesy of titles at the Italian Open and
Hamburg. If the draw unfolds to form, Hingis and Williams will find
themselves in a quarterfinal collision.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said: ``I feel much more intelligent on the court this
year; I understand the game more, and I'm going into the French
with the ability to take the title.'' Williams, who joined the
circuit at age 14, turns 19 next month, and needs to hurry if she
wants to gild her phenom label with a Grand Slam championship
before she ceases to be a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 28-year-old Sampras and the 29-year-old Agassi, they
simply want to complete their Slam laurels with a Roland Garros
title before they cease to be players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to go after it and do it,'' said Agassi, who
hasn't won a Grand Slam title since the 1995 Australian Open. He
faces a harsh first-round test Monday from Argentina's 39th-ranked
Franco Squillari, who upset Moya in Rome and won Munich. Agassi
admits to feeling like a starving man at this time of year, ``When
it's the one you've never won, it always makes you hungrier,'' he
said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
