<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MAD-ABOUT-YOU-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAUGHS FOR `MAD ABOUT YOU' WERE FEWER AS THE YEARS WENT ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In assessing the sociological implications of the seven-season
run of ``Mad About You,'' let's remember two key points. One, it
was no ``Seinfeld.'' Two, it never tried to be, which is why the
media hubbub that accompanied the denouement of ``Seinfeld'' a year
ago isn't reaching similar heights of dizziness for ``Mad About
You.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the swan song of ``Mad About You'' on Monday
night is virtually free of hubbubbery. Some say it's because the
show should have bowed out last season, and that it stuck around
for another year only because NBC paid big money to keep from
losing it and ``Seinfeld'' at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't uncommon for a series to depart a year or two or three
past its prime. But no series in recent memory went from must-see
to musty as dramatically as ``Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   In its early years, ``Mad About You'' was as lively a romantic
comedy as there was on network TV. It was funny, fresh and full of
promise. Like about 20 million other American males, I was in love
with Helen Hunt. So was my wife, and at least one of my sisters.
Hunt has a universal appeal that made Paul Reiser's mannered
performance style tolerable. She was attractive to men,
non-threatening to women _ a killer combination on and off the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   And even though NBC treated the series as warmly as a contagion,
changing its time slot as often as Reiser would say ``I'm just
saying,'' it often was as well-written as ``Frasier'' (which
started a season later) and as smart as ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   But ask a group of TV-watching friends if they've seen ``Mad
About You'' recently, and the most prevalent answer will be
something like: ``You know, I used to watch it, but I stopped a few
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Me too.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it changed. And even though change is supposed to
be good for us in the same way as fiber, greens and humble pie, we
really don't like change. When the boss announces that paychecks
will be issued every other week instead of weekly, we hate it. And
then when the boss says the company is going back to the old way of
distributing paychecks, we hate it. The only time we want change is
when we have to feed a parking meter or we're face to face with a
soft-drink machine that doesn't take dollar bills.
</P>
<P>
   The change in ``Mad About You'' can be traced to 1996. In the
fourth-season finale, Paul and Jamie Buchman came close to
splitting up after each flirted with a dangerous liaison. Neither
succumbed to temptation, and their rapprochement was sealed by the
news that Jamie was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, Jamie got her third set of parents, played this
time by Carol Burnett and Carroll O'Connor, and despite promises
from Reiser that Jamie's pregnancy wouldn't be the focal point of
the season, Jamie's pregnancy was the focal point of the season,
culminating in maternity in that season's finale in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the season that Reiser and Hunt got more involved in
the creative process, and the reason I started to lose interest.
The one-time romantic comedy had become an aimless ensemble piece
featuring an array of big-name guest stars who won a trunkful of
Emmys but did little to fulfill the show's early promise. It was
like a bad marriage: The dynamic of Paul and Jamie's relationship
ceased to be interesting, and their lives were defined not by what
they brought to the union but by what was happening to them and
around them.
</P>
<P>
   This is painfully evident in Monday night's one-hour series
finale. Hunt directed it, and at times it is charming, poignant,
even instructive. But it's not very funny. It also moves too
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane Garofalo stars as Paul and Jamie's daughter, Mabel,
speaking to us as an adult. Through her narration we learn what
happened to Paul and Jamie after 1999. For instance, they
discovered they were never legally married because the city utility
worker (Lyle Lovett) who officiated at their ceremony wasn't an
ordained minister, as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out to be an unfortunate metaphor for the series. What
was advertised in 1992 _ a smart romantic comedy _ ended up not so
smart and not so funny.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with the latter. A show like ``Sports Night,''
though cloaked as a traditional comedy, is intentionally unfunny
much of the time. Its fans expect it to be trenchant and
occasionally caustic. But ``Mad About You'' changed channels
halfway through the program, expecting viewers to follow along as
if nothing had happened.
</P>
<P>
   But something had happened, probably because the people who
worked on the show day in and day out were feeling the creative
paralysis that's almost inevitable in a long-running series. To
avoid the ``been there, done that'' trap, they took a left turn and
changed the show, making it star-driven instead of story-driven.
</P>
<P>
   Bad move. Better to take a lesson from ``Seinfeld,'' which
retained most of its audience because the story was king, no matter
how bizarre or insignificant. Sure, they had the occasional
big-name guest on ``Seinfeld,'' but more often it was the other way
around: An appearance on ``Seinfeld'' was a springboard to stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the changes in ``Mad About You,'' Hunt has always been a
joy to watch. Compare Jamie Buchman with other sitcom characters
and Hunt's enormous talent is something to cherish. But ``Mad About
You'' is not, because it lost direction on the way to syndication
success _ and that's maddening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
