<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labonte gets wheels of fortune
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concord, N.C. _ When Jeff Gordon pulled onto pit road for the
final time Saturday night, crew chief Ray Evernham noticed rookie
Tony Stewart's crew was changing only two tires.
</P>
<P>
   Evernham changed his mind and replaced only right-side tires,
too, but he apparently forgot about Terry Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's crew exchanged all four tires on his No. 5 Chevrolet,
allowing him to blow past Gordon and Stewart in the final 10-lap
shootout of The Winston, NASCAR's annual all-star race at Lowe's
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who finished third in the second 30-lap segment, lost
track position because of the longer pit stop and started the final
dash fifth. But he caught Gordon for second in only three laps, and
then passed Stewart three laps later for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The correct pit decision gave Labonte his second victory in The
Winston, joining Gordon, the late Davey Allison and Dale Earnhardt
as the event's only multiple winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys had to work on the car on pit road,'' Labonte said.
`` We were lucky right there. Some of the guys just got two tires
and we got four and gave up some track position, but it paid off
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who started the race 21st after winning the Winston
Open earlier Saturday, finished second. Gordon was third, followed
by Earnhardt and Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably should have taken four tires,'' Gordon said. ``The
car wouldn't turn in the corners at all. It really, really shoved
the nose. We've won this thing on four tires before, and this time
we got beat by somebody who took four.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR ruled that Gordon jumped the start for the final segment,
so the first restart was waved off. When the green flag finally
flew, Stewart blew by Gordon on the high side of the 1.5-mile oval,
but Labonte passed him on the backstretch three laps later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gamble (changing only two tires),'' Stewart said.
``Everybody is rolling the dice. It's a 10-lap dash and this is the
only place you do it. I still am not disappointed. I think we did
the right thing. We just got caught out by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second was all we could do. I could have told you the two-tire
stop wasn't the right move as soon as I saw Terry in my mirror.
When the guy's coming that hard, it's an obvious tell-tale sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stewart and Gordon were around a lot longer than Dale
Jarrett, Jeff Burton, Bobby Labonte and Mark Martin, who all were
eliminated in two pileups during the first 12 laps.
</P>
<P>
   On the 12th lap, Labonte's No. 18 Pontiac wasn't up to speed
after a restart, and he started falling back in the field. Martin
caught his bumper when Ernie Irvan spun out on the top side of the
track.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan's No. 36 Pontiac collected Labonte and Martin, and seven
other cars were damaged before it was over. Rusty Wallace, the
winner of The Winston in 1989, also was knocked out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the restart, it just wouldn't go,'' Labonte said. ``I got a
little loose coming off turn 2. I kept trying to get out of the
way, but I just kept getting hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Jarrett, Burton and Ricky Rudd were knocked out when
Bobby Hamilton's No. 4 Chevy appeared to tap the rear of Jarrett's
No. 88 Ford. Jarrett spun high and collected Burton's car when it
came back across the track.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
