</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTIAL-RAISE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS TO WEIGH WHAT A PRESIDENT IS WORTH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the job were offered in the help wanted
advertisements, it might not sound very attractive:
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive needed to oversee bureaucracy of millions.
Seeking inspiring leader and practical problem-solver. Long hours
and constant criticism. Fringes include large, well-furnished
house, but no pay raise regardless of performance.
</P>
<P>
   Since the job is president of the United States, there is never
a shortage of applicants, even though the pay has not gone up in 30
years, since Brooks Brothers sold suits for $100 and a spacious
apartment on Manhattan's East Side rented for $250 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Now Congress is weighing whether to make the next president the
first to get a raise since Richard Nixon in 1969. The House
Committee on Government Reform and Oversight will take up a
proposal on Monday to double the president's salary, to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten phone calls already from people objecting,''
Russell George, chief counsel and staff director of the panel's
Subcommittee on Government Management, Information and Technology,
said last week. ``They're really revved up about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the complainers were under the mistaken impression that
President Clinton would get a raise if the House and Senate
approved the proposal and Clinton signed it, George said.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution says a president's pay may not be increased or
lowered in the term for which he was elected, so it would not be
Clinton but whoever replaces him at noon on Jan. 20, 2001, who
would draw a salary of $400,000 _ assuming that Congress acts in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee will hear from several former White House
chiefs of staff and experts on government and management who favor
raising the chief's pay. But at least one witness will take an
opposite view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's salary is adequate as it stands,'' Gary
Ruskin, director of the watchdog Congressional Accountability
Project, said last week in a preview of his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   And no one disputes that the presidential compensation package
includes a lot of fringe benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The president gets an annual travel allowance of $100,000, an
expense allowance of $50,000, round-the-clock security, jet planes
and helicopters and a good-sized house where he does not have to
cook for himself. His retirement benefits are generous. And he
never has to pick up his own dry cleaning or hunt for a parking
space.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential perquisites might be worth $500,000 a year, Lloyd
N. Cutler, chairman of a special panel that studied government
salaries, estimated back in 1989. His commission recommended
increasing the president's salary in 1993 to $350,000, plus a
cost-of-living adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Congress ignored the recommendation. But last week a House
Appropriations Committee panel with jurisdiction over White House
spending included a future presidential pay raise in its
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is the hearing before the Government Reform
subcommittee, headed by Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif. George, the chief
counsel, said the subcommittee would ponder the fact that $200,000
in 1969 would be the equivalent to at least three times that in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the relationship of the president's salary to the
salaries of other high officials. The vice president, the chief
justice of the United States and the speaker of the House get
cost-of-living adjustments, unlike the president. Their salaries
are now $175,400, not quite 88 percent of the president's.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, the vice president, chief justice and speaker made 31
percent of what the president made, the Congressional Research
Service of the Library of Congress has told the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet officers and the majority and minority leaders in
Congress make $151,800, about 76 percent of what the president
makes. In 1969, they made 30 percent of what the president made.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of Congress make $136,700, about 68 percent of
what the president is paid; in 1969, they made 21 percent of what
the president made.
</P>
<P>
   If the president's salary stays at $200,000 and other high
officials get adjustments of, say, 3 percent a year, the chief
justice and the vice president would be paid $3,400 more than the
president in January 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Freezing their pay or giving them only tiny raises could lead to
what the Congressional Research Service calls ``pay compression,''
a situation in which not only the highest government officials, but
subordinates on down the line, would suffer.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is crucial. If Congress does not raise the
president's pay this year, it is unlikely to revisit the issue in
2000, an election year. In that case, the earliest a presidential
raise could take effect would be Jan. 20, 2005.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
