<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8112 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-MULTIRACIAL-     05-23 1775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-MULTIRACIAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG PUBLISHER GIVES VOICE TO THE `YOUNG AND MIXED AND PROUD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When Matt Kelley reads media accounts about
interracial people, he often feels as if he has entered ``The
Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Hi, My name is Matt. My mother is Korean. My father is
white.... I'm sooooo proud,' '' he says, mocking the tone of quotes
in those articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more to us, to our experience, than that!''
</P>
<P>
   But rather than knock the media _ for using lame quotes or
portraying multiracial people as exotic or hip _ he has become the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley has created Mavin, a new magazine that gives voice to a
growing but under-served market of readers: young people from
multiracial backgrounds as well as children who are adopted by
parents of a different ethnic background than their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were so starved for this,'' Kelley says, sipping a
glass of water in the small apartment _ World Headquarters! he
jokes _ where he edits Mavin. The second issue of the glossy comes
out next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This magazine fills a big void,'' he says, his eyes growing
big.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley looks like your run-of-the-mill, 20-year-old publisher
and editor-in-chief. He sports a clean-shaven face and a buzz-cut.
His speech is edgy and whip smart, like a hip-hop rapper who aced
his SAT verbals. When he gets excited, he peppers his sentences
with ``yada, yada, yadas.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley is well-read and can lecture like a grad student on how
Christianity helped to preserve African culture among slaves in
Cuba. A plastic yellow bag he was carrying one recent afternoon had
three magazines: The New Yorker (``I enjoy the writing style'');
XXL (``It's about hip-hop and they've got an interesting layout'');
and Cigar Aficionado (``Well, it's not for the cigars!'')
</P>
<P>
   It would not be a slam to call him a grandmama's boy because,
well, he is; he has dinner with his 82-year-old grandmother up to
five times a week. But when it comes to Mavin, Kelley is
bareknuckled and all business.
</P>
<P>
   As deadlines loom, he spends up to 100 hours a week editing,
assigning stories and calling photographers. ``I just go into
another state of mind,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The number of general-circulation publications for multiracial
people can be counted on one hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, on a few fingers,'' says Candy Mills, who edits and
publishes three of the most widely recognized magazines on
interracial issues _ Interrace Magazine, Raising Black and
Bi-Racial Children, and Interrace Singles.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, who is black and married to a white man, is regarded as a
pioneer. She started Interrace in 1989 while in college, then
created the other two magazines to leave a legacy for her children.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly Interrace reaches 25,000 people, despite facing
hurdles such as skittish advertisers and the long hours it takes to
produce each issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a labor of love,'' Mills explains. ``(Matt) should stick
in there. It is tough. But the rewards will come. There is a
population out there to get at.''
</P>
<P>
   Census numbers point to a vast pool of potential readers.
</P>
<P>
   More than three decades after the U.S. Supreme Court struck down
the nation's last anti-miscegenation laws, the number of
black-white marriages has multiplied sixfold, from an estimated
51,000 in 1960 to more than 330,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account white-Asian couples and other interracial
pairings, the number of mixed-race marriages is estimated to be
more than 1.4 million. And for each interracial couple, there is a
broader extended family of relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, whose mother is Korean and father is white, had seen
publications _ some now defunct _ created by adults in interracial
relationships. Many of those publications, he said, failed to
tackle issues faced by the offspring of those unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have to integrate both experiences in a way their
parents cannot fully understand,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one thing to have enough foresight to see a market
niche among the burgeoning population of biracial youths.
(Estimates put the number of biracial people nationwide at between
2 million and 5 million, though exact figures are hard to come by
because of how people choose to identify themselves.) It is an
entirely different matter to have the moxie to make a magazine for
readers of any race in a nation already flooded by more than 18,000
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Kummerfeld, president of the Magazine Publishers of
America, a New York-based trade group, said he had never heard of a
magazine for multiracial kids. But Mavin does draw his interest.
``I'm the father of multiracial children,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Kummerfeld said Kelley is wise to target young people because
teens and young adults are one of the fastest growing segments of
the $25 billion-a-year magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Mavin can grasp its target audience the way other niche
magazines have, focusing on pig farming or hip-hop music, will be
determined by the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not so hard to launch a magazine,'' Kummerfeld says.
``Launching is the easy part.''
</P>
<P>
   Survival depends on securing a solid subscription base, rallying
good advertisers, getting a printer you can trust and handling
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley says he's up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm young,'' he shrugs. ``And when am I ever going to have
another opportunity like this? Anyway, I always do best when I'm
overextended.''
</P>
<P>
   Other people appreciate his cool confidence and professionalism.
Victoria Namkung, a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer who
contributes to Mavin, said Kelley has ``more going for him at 20
than some magazine publishers twice his age.''
</P>
<P>
   The praise and attention are blossoming. The story of the
magazine _ and the young man behind it _ has drawn the interest of
reporters from local Korean newspapers to national newspapers to
Japanese radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz has not gone to Kelley's head, even though just a few
years ago he was a typical kid on Bainbridge Island, Wash., running
his own gardening consulting business and finishing up at Seattle's
prestigious Lakeside School, where he had an ``A-minus'' average.
</P>
<P>
   During his senior year, however, he had a ``life-transforming''
experience. He and a friend made a prank call to the home of a
classmate who had applied to Brown University. The friend, who used
a phone at Kelley's house, pretended to be a Brown admissions
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Unnerved, the classmate traced the call to Kelley's house. When
Lakeside officials found out, they asked Kelley for his
collaborator's name. He refused, though he says he apologized to
the classmate.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at Brown, where Kelley also had applied, learned
about the misrepresentation. Kelley said the school notified Brown
but Lakeside officials said they learned about it after the
classmate notified Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, Kelley's first-choice school, rejected him. Although no
one knows whether the prank played a role in Brown's decision,
Kelley feels Lakeside nuked his chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very tough,'' he recalls, shaking his head.
``There were incidents much more serious at the school that got
others a slap on the wrist ... I felt as if I was not valued as a
student of color.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung, Kelley went on to another highly regarded school,
Wesleyan University in Connecticut. There, he plunged into creative
arts, edited The Ankh, a literary magazine for students of color,
and organized campus gatherings for multiracial students.
</P>
<P>
   Fate then stepped in. One day Kelley wrote a poem about his
part-time work in Seattle at Childhaven, an agency for abused and
neglected children. The poem, which touched on his bond with the
kids, many of whom were minorities, unleashed deep emotions inside
him _ emotions so powerful he became emboldened to be more
expressive on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Kelley was sitting in front of a computer terminal
at college. His heart still burned over the Brown rejection. But he
resolved to take such negative experiences, tap into positive ones
_ like his work at Childhaven _ and channel it all into a forum for
others to appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I did have a love for journalism, expressing
myself,'' he says. ``I was very excited to create a forum to
write.''
</P>
<P>
   He left Wesleyan after his freshman year to give Mavin its
wings.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's first issue came out in January, touting itself
as a celebration of the mixed-race experience. It featured articles
on ``hapas,'' the Hawaiian term for people of partial Asian
descent; portraits of the mixed-race people; and an essay about
being black and biracial in a world that likes to categorize
people.
</P>
<P>
   The masthead proclaimed: ``We're here and we're intelligent,
creative, talented and beautiful.... we're redefining what it means
to be young and mixed and proud and loud and subtle and smart.''
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming second issue is 64 pages _ 18 pages bigger than the
first. There will be 7,000 copies of the issue which will deal with
a broader array of topics, including Kelley's dispatch from his
visit to Cuba and an interview with Amy Hill, the half-Japanese,
half-Finnish comedian who played the grandmother in the short-lived
sitcom, ``All-American Girl'' in the mid-1990s. For levity, there's
a spoof: ``Mulatto for Dummies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley says he does not see Mavin as a manifesto, though he
realizes some people may perceive the magazine as having a
political agenda. It's not about politics, he says, it's about
people.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine is a family affair. His older sister, Joanna Lee, a
fashion designer in New York City, serves as Mavin's creative and
managing editor. His parents _ mom is an accountant, dad a
stockbroker _ are supportive from the sidelines. And there is an
extended family of photographers and writers who give true meaning
to the free in free-lance. By using volunteers, he is able to keep
Mavin's cover price down to $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   Each issue costs about $15,000 to print. Kelley said he covers
costs with financial support from friends and family, in addition
to subscriptions and ads.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine can be found in Vancouver, B.C., Los Angeles, New
York and several other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley plans to keep Mavin going, but he wants to go back to
school this fall and publish from a house near the Wesleyan campus.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Kelley was invited to Lakeside to speak about his
foray in magazine publishing.
</P>
<P>
   He could not make it _ not for reasons of the past, he says, but
because of the future. He had to take care of baby Mavin, which
means in Hebrew-Aramaic, ``one who understands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
