<HEADLINE>
WATSON ENDS CAREER ON PGA TOUR WITH BIRDIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tom Watson left his final interview at a PGA
Tour event yesterday and walked toward a flock of fans waiting for
an autograph. As he considered his future on the Senior PGA Tour,
he summed up his 29 years as a regular tour player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a nice run,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it has.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who turns 50 in September, only has the major
championships _ the U.S. and British Opens and possibly the PGA
Championship, if he gets an exemption _ left on his schedule. He
came to the MasterCard Colonial to defend his title, and in the
process reminded fans what they were losing.
</P>
<P>
   On his last hole, the 427-yard, par-4 No. 18, the 42-time winner
recorded a birdie, getting him to even-par 280 for the tournament.
Touchingly, Watson, who has won eight major championships and more
than $9 million in career earnings, ended his PGA Tour career the
same way it started. In 1971, he birdied his first hole as a pro,
recording a 4 on No. 1 of the PGA National Golf Course in Palm
Beach Gardens, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started with a birdie,'' Watson said. ``It's nice to end
with a birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty more in between, but one of Watson's most
memorable birdies came at Colonial during last year's final round.
Forced to play from an awkward stance out of the fairway bunker at
the par-4 No. 9, Watson hit it over the water hazard and onto the
green, then made the putt that sparked his victory.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, he had the same shot yesterday, except the ball
was plugged in the bunker. This time, he didn't reach the green,
hitting his ball in the water hazard. But in dramatic fashion, he
took his penalty stroke, dropped behind the hazard and promptly
chipped it in for par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to do it again,'' Watson said. ``I just had a bad
lie in the bunker. But it was a great four!''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether Watson will take his exemption as a
past champion and return to Colonial in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a chance,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   And what would clinch it?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had won, then maybe I could say for sure,'' Watson said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
