<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUIT COMPLICATES OFFERING PLANNED BY JOHN HANCOCK
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock Mutual Insurance has been moving smoothly toward a
reorganization that would allow it to sell shares to the public,
but a Massachusetts appeals court has reinstated a lawsuit by a
policyholder that dredges up an old scandal in which the company
acknowledged that its lobbying violated state law.
</P>
<P>
   The litigation revives questions about the integrity and
management of John Hancock, one of the United States' largest life
insurers, at a time when the company has been doing everything
possible to enhance its attractiveness to potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY FEUD ANNOYS WALL STREET
</P>
<P>
   Although the feud between Walt Disney's chairman, Michael Eisner
and his former lieutenant Jeffrey Katzenberg has had little effect
on the public's perception of the company, Wall Street is not happy
watching Disney air its dirty linen in public. The company's stock
has been depressed for months, primarily because of disappointing
earnings, but some analysts think the lawsuit has also been a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   MACROMEDIA ADDS FUN AND GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia, the multimedia software publisher, plans to
introduce an Internet entertainment strategy on Monday that will be
based on a media-player program similar to software developed by
Real Networks, Microsoft and Apple Computer. The company plans to
set up a Web site and introduce versions of its Shockwave format
that will enable computer users to find and play games, music and
material from movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLESOFT TO NAME NEW PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>
   Peoplesoft, a leading seller of business management software,
plans to announce Monday that Craig Conway, a former Oracle
executive, will become its president and chief operating officer.
He joins a company that has seen its growth slow as big
corporations delay buying software because of possible Year 2000
computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   CANON CHASES LOW-END MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Canon, which has been nipping at the heels of Xerox in the
market for expensive high-speed copiers, is trying to bite chunks
out of Hewlett-Packard, Xerox and Lexmark in the market for slower,
cheaper printers.
</P>
<P>
   TV NEWS SHOWS FORM PERSONALITIES
</P>
<P>
   While skeptics said that the networks had stuffed too many news
magazines into their schedules and that the genre would become
either puffy or stale, all the magazines did reasonably well for
the season, and almost all were renewed for the fall. Producers and
executives say that the news magazines, which cost less to make
than other shows, have developed individual personalities, although
there is some overlap.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH FOR HARPER'S BAZAAR EDITOR
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen Black, the president of Hearst Magazines, caused a
fracas recently after approaching Bonnie Fuller, the editor in
chief of Glamour magazine, to see whether she wanted to run
Harper's Bazaar, which was edited by Liz Tilberis until her death
last month. Ms. Fuller declined, but the commotion has drawn
attention to an important editorial race. Ms. Black's choice of a
new editor will affect the company's cultural direction.
</P>
<P>
   COPYCATS SEEK TO EMULATE EBAY
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming popularity of the online auction giant Ebay _
with a $22 billion market value and millions of daily visitors _
has inspired a convoy of copycat sites hoping to ride on its
success. Whether Ebay's success can be duplicated is anyone's
guess, but it has clearly stumbled onto something that has never
been seen before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
