</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The pride of Zoo Atlanta
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My name is Zulu, and I'm an 8-year-old African lion who lives at
Zoo Atlanta. You might remember my 1 1/2-year-old cub, Kariba, who
was in News For Kids a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever touched the rough tongue of a pet cat? My tongue
is like that _ after all, lions are big cats _ but much bigger,
rougher and
</P>
<P>
   stronger. I use it to clean my fur and to pull meat from bones.
I could take the skin off a human hand with two licks. (Which is
one reason they keep me in a secure pen at the zoo!)
</P>
<P>
   Here's more about me:
</P>
<P>
   My scientific name: Panthera leo.
</P>
<P>
   What I eat: Meat. At Zoo Atlanta, it's fed to me. If I were in
Africa, I'd eat gazelles, zebras, crocodiles and many other
animals. Sometimes lions even eat animals as big as hippopotamuses!
</P>
<P>
   How lions live: In the wild, we live in ``prides,'' or groups of
four to more than 30 lions, sharing food. Female lions usually
catch the animals we eat. They stalk their prey until the last
second, then try to run it down in a sprint. Many times the animal
gets away, and the lioness must try again. Male lions like me don't
hunt very much, but we protect the pride from outsider lions.
</P>
<P>
   How long lions live: In the wild, many lions die as cubs, and
adults often perish by age 10, from attacks by people, other lions
or prey animals. In zoos, where they're protected from such
attacks, they can live to 25 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   A cool thing about me: My roar, which in Africa would help me
communicate with my pride and scare away other lions, can be heard
up to five miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Another cool thing: In captivity, lions have sometimes mated
with tigers. The cub of a male lion and a female tiger is a called
a ``liger.'' The cub of a female lion and male tiger is called a
``tigon.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental note: Lions aren't endangered species, but our
numbers have declined because people have taken over many of the
places where we used to live.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Zoo Atlanta,
</P>
<P>
   Encyclopaedia Britannica Online
</P>
