<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IZZY-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH PITCHING UNSETTLED, METS CALL UP ISRINGHAUSEN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an effort to bolster a starting rotation hit by
injuries, the New York Mets recalled Jason Isringhausen from their
Class AAA farm club Sunday and said he would start Monday night
against the Pirates in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets said that Al Leiter would probably not start again
until next Sunday because his left bicep is still sore as he had
overcompensated for a ligament strain in his left knee. Bobby
Jones, who has had a string of poor outings, will miss at least one
start with shoulder tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen, a 26-year-old right-hander who has not pitched in
the major leagues since undergoing reconstructive elbow surgery
after the 1997 season, is 3-1 with a 2.53 earned run average with
47 strikeouts in 461/3 innings for the Norfolk Tides.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's built up enough of a foundation to come up here and
pitch,'' General Manager Steve Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, one member of the Mets' front office suggested that
Isringhausen might remain with the team instead of going back down
to Norfolk after one start. He would presumably shift to the
bullpen when Leiter and Jones are healthy again. But Jones, who has
allowed 20 earned runs in 132/3 innings over his last three starts,
might be in line for a stint in long relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``That remains to be seen,'' Phillips said. ``Jason will make
one start. Then we'll see how Bobby feels and how Al feels and
we'll piece it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was re-examined by Dr. David Altchek, the team physician,
during Sunday's game at Shea Stadium. He will not pick up a ball
for four or five days to see if the tendinitis in his shoulder
calms down. ``And if it's not better by Thursday, I'll have to
undergo a magnetic resonance imaging test,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine said that Jones probably would not pitch
again for eight or nine days.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, meanwhile, was preparing to toss batting practice
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he thought he had identified something from
videotapes that might be hampering Leiter's velocity. ``We all know
Al is rather violent in his delivery,'' Valentine said as he
demonstrated the difference in Leiter's follow-through with tapes
from last season and from Leiter's start on Thursday. ``But now it
looks like he gets shot, like his delivery is short-circuited.''
</P>
<P>
   The tapes show that Leiter has lost the exaggerated kick of his
back leg on his follow-through, which might be causing Leiter to
overcompensate with his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like his back foot is tied to the pitching rubber
and then it can only go so far before it stops,'' Valentine said.
The Mets feared that could lead to something more serious than the
bicep soreness Leiter has been experiencing since his May 10 start
in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's troubles began on April 28 against San Diego, when he
strained the medial collateral ligament in his left knee. In both
that start and his previous start, he allowed one earned run. But
in the four starts since then, Leiter _ who signed a four-year, $32
million deal during the off season _ has allowed 35 hits and 24
earned runs in 22 innings, an e.r.a. of 9.82.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Leiter is 2-4 with a 6.38 e.r.a. in nine starts,
after going 17-6 with a 2.47 e.r.a. last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was trying to throw where I didn't feel my knee as
much,'' Leiter said. ``But it looks like somebody shot my leg on
the left side and it's just dragging through. I've been using my
upper body to compensate. I want to be able to get that explosive
feeling off the rubber back, without feeling sore the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will have Leiter tape his knee the way a football
player might and then see if he can throw freely in the bullpen
against hitters before he starts again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't put him at risk, and we can't allow Al to put himself
at risk in May because of an `I'm the guy' mentality, an `I've got
to right this wrong' attitude, and `the team needs me' stuff,''
Valentine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
