<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUN-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONCIANO HELPS DAY CATCH ON WITH RAIDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Donnell Day has an NFL contract, and much of the
credit goes to Ron Ponciano, Cal State Northridge's head football
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Day, an All-Big Sky Conference defensive back last season as a
senior, went undrafted in April and hadn't had any free-agent
feelers.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Ponciano acted. He called Bruce Lemmerman, the New
Orleans Saints' director of college scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Lemmerman, a former CSUN player, scanned the rosters of every
NFL team and noticed the Oakland Raiders had a habit of signing
smaller cornerbacks; Day is almost 5-foot-9 and about 180 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano connected Day with the Raiders. Day, who had three
interceptions and 32 tackles last season, signed after an
impressive free-agent minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Raiders) were really pleased,'' Ponciano said.
</P>
<P>
   So is Ponciano. Day is the second CSUN player from the 1998 team
to sign a free-agent contract this spring; wide receiver Mike Ogas
signed with the St. Louis Rams last month.
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely power: Home runs were the story for the softball team
in the first two days of the NCAA regional playoffs at UCLA,
whether the Matadors were hitting them or giving them up.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising shot came from senior second baseman Katrina
Nolletti, who hit a three-run homer Friday in the Matadors' six-run
second inning in their playoff-opening 7-3 win over Missouri. It
was only the second homer of Nolletti's CSUN career, and she didn't
hit any over-the-fence home runs in four years at Fresno's Bullard
High.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Nolletti's parents, Vince and Marianne, said
they could remember Katrina hitting only ``four or five'' homers in
her softball career, including on all-star traveling teams.
</P>
<P>
   Behold the future: CSUN's athletic department may be facing an
$800,000 deficit, but there isn't a lack of talent on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball team re-established itself as the top college
source for local talent; CSUN signed two of the City Section's top
pitchers _ Granada Hills' Kameron Loe and Sylmar's Ivan Hernandez _
as well as a top shortstop, Moorpark's Wes Rasmussen.
</P>
<P>
   Taft High's Marquis Brignac, a football signee, won the
Northwest Valley League title in the 100 meters May 14 and also ran
a leg on the Toreadors' record-setting 400 relay.
</P>
<P>
   Men's basketball recruit Craig Calloway, a senior guard at Long
Beach Jordan High, was a Long Beach Press-Telegram all-star
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a contract: A three-year contract between California
State University administrators and faculty, which was tentatively
agreed upon May 10, was good news for CSUN head baseball coach Mike
Batesole.
</P>
<P>
   Interim athletic director Sam Jankovich indicated two weeks ago
that the faculty labor dispute put his contract negotiations with
Batesole in limbo. Batesole's contract ends in June and he is
seeking a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   The new union contract, which gives professors more control over
merit raises, must be ratified by union membership and Cal State's
Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Kopita leaving: Ron Kopita, CSUN's outgoing vice president of
student affairs who had a rocky run as the overseer of the
university's athletic department, announced May 13 he accepted a
similar job at Wichita State.
</P>
<P>
   Kopita, 55, was a central figure in the cutting of four men's
sports in 1997. He also was criticized when then-women's basketball
coach Michael Abraham was arrested on campus last November on
drug-trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN President Blenda Wilson stripped Kopita of his
responsibilities with the athletic department after Abraham's
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he gets to Phoenix: Danny Phillips, a junior
outfielder who led the Matadors in home runs (16) and RBI (61) this
season, works out for the Arizona Diamondbacks this week in a
pre-draft camp.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who went undrafted last year after playing at Pierce
College, said he's taking a different approach to the pro draft.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he waited by the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking off for a few days,'' he said. ``My sister is going
to be a secretary.''
</P>
<P>
   Other CSUN players anticipating a call for the two-day draft,
which starts June 2, are junior outfielder-pitcher Darryl Grant,
junior catcher Jeremy Sickles, junior first baseman Adrian Mendoza
and senior second baseman Kevin Patrick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
