<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUMS-REVAMP-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LIMITS TO SCIENCE AT MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Ind., Pa.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Yes, its front lawn is newly filled with jumbo
sculptures by Keith Haring. But no, the Museum of Science and
Industry _ Chicago's special hometown blend of Barnum &AMP; Bailey,
Popular Mechanics, Smithsonian Institution, Mr. Wizard and World's
Fair _ has not suddenly gone arty.
</P>
<P>
   Deep inside the museum, baby chicks are still hatching.
</P>
<P>
   The Haring show, which began this month and runs through Sept.
12, is a graphic reminder _ in red, yellow, blue and green _ of how
the institution on the South Side is trying to reinvigorate itself
and compete for hearts and dollars in the pastime world of
information, entertainment and retailing.
</P>
<P>
   But the museum's chick hatchery, a 45-year-old exhibit that has
little to do with science or industry, may be an even more potent
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies a paradox faced by science centers nationwide: some
of their biggest attractions are their oldest and least
sophisticated displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exotic can be pre-industrial,'' said Neil Harris, a
professor of history at the University of Chicago and a student of
American cultural institutions, who allowed that ``watching the
chickens hatch was always my favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Science centers find themselves in a ``constant struggle'' to
balance nostalgia and novelty, said Ellen Griffee, director of
government and public relations for the Association of
Science-Technology Centers in Washington, which counts 324 members
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the Franklin Institute Science Museum in Philadelphia, for
example, couples have been engaged and married in the walk-through
human heart. And when the 707 airliner parked outside had to be
removed in 1987 to accommodate a building expansion, the institute
gave a farewell party in its honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do like the comfort level of something you're familiar
with, yet the mind wants to explore something new,'' Ms. Griffee
said. ``Science centers are not the nation's attic.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to Kevin Ahlgrim of La Porte, Ind., who returned to
the Museum of Science and Industry this month for the first time in
20 years, with an 11-year-old son in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was curious to see if they still had the coal mine,''
Ahlgrim said. ``I was glad they did.'' The exhibit, which opened in
1933, allows visitors to descend a 50-foot hoist and ride a work
train through what appear to be real tunnels carved from sheer
walls of Illinois coal.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, a 14-year-old from Waukegan, Ill., Jason Keeton, took
a moment off from writing a computer program for a robotic
ball-throwing device in the ``Lego Mindstorms'' exhibit to ponder
what he most liked in the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``That big heart,'' he said, meaning a thumping, low-tech,
16-foot-high model through which visitors have been circulating
since 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why she had brought friends from Palm Desert, Calif.,
to watch chicks scramble out of their eggs, Meryl Cohen of Skokie,
Ill., a regular visitor to the museum for more than 30 years, said,
``It's about the struggle for life.''
</P>
<P>
   David R. Mosena, the president and chief executive of the Museum
of Science and Industry, surveyed the crowd around the glass-walled
hatchery. ``The human, emotional draw to this exhibit is
profound,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a collection of icons,'' Mosena said. ``Part of our
audience is coming back with fond memories of things that they want
to show their children and grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosena sees nothing incongruous about 10 Harings frolicking like
anthropomorphic lollipops around the corner from the museum's other
large outdoor artifact: a German submarine captured off French West
Africa in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, congruity has never been a strong suit at the
museum, which was founded by Julius Rosenwald, the president of
Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. It is housed in Art Deco galleries built in
the reconstructed shell of the Palace of Fine Arts from the 1893
World's Columbian Exposition; set like a neoclassical tiara across
one end of Jackson Park, eight miles south of the Loop.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.75 million people visit every year _ all on the same
afternoon, it can sometimes seem, to judge from the button-pushing,
lever-cranking, wheel-turning, knob-spinning commotion.
</P>
<P>
   As the lines blur between information, entertainment and
retailing, the Museum of Science and Industry must vie with tourist
attractions such as Navy Pier, where one can shop or ride a
150-foot-high Ferris wheel, and the DisneyQuest virtual ``theme
park'' that is to open near the Loop this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Museums are in competition for people's leisure time,'' said
Mosena, a Tennessee native who became the museum's president in
1997 after running the Chicago Planning Department, the staff of
Mayor Richard M. Daley, the Aviation Department and the Chicago
Transit Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't attract a crowd, sell them lunch, sell them a
trinket, we're not in business,'' Mosena said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A family of four can expect to pay $26 just to park and walk in
the door, although school groups always get in without charge and
Thursdays are free for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Before admission fees were instituted in 1991, the museum
estimated attendance at up to 4 million visitors annually. With the
fees, it dropped nearly in half, although the 2 million figure
still made it the best-attended museum in Chicago. When parking was
seriously disrupted by the construction of a new 1,500-space
underground garage, attendance fell further, to 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the garage is open, the number of visitors has begun to
grow again, Mosena said. Sixty percent of the museum's $40 million
annual operating budget comes from admission fees, food and retail
sales and special events. The rest comes from a city subsidy,
fund-raising and earnings on its endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the largest corporate backers are United Airlines (one of
its 727 jets is cantilevered from the east balcony), the Ameritech
Corp. (sponsor of the communications hall) and Abbott Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, makers of an antiviral drug, supported ``AIDS: The War
Within,'' an exhibit dealing with a realm in which neither science
nor industry have triumphed. ``The AIDS exhibit is not designed to
sell a product, it's designed to educate,'' Mosena said. ``I don't
think the commercial underwriting is blatant commercialization.
It's understated and enlightened.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking briskly around the 15-acre museum, Mosena makes plain
how eager he is to freshen exhibits like ``Food For Life,'' where
the hatchery sits. The gallery looks like a 1970s rerun with its
mechanical conveyor belt on which plastic facsimiles of servings
from the five food groups rotate endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Mosena plans to turn the hall into a biotechnology exhibit,
focused on DNA, cloning and other advances in genetic engineering.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, on baby chicks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
