<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-KABILA-ART-NYT &LR;      05-23 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-KABILA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO'S WEARY MASSES LOSE FAITH IN ONCE POPULAR REBEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ When Laurent Kabila's army neared this capital
two years ago to topple the country's long-ruling dictatorship,
Bernardin Mungul Diaka urged residents to wear white armbands, wave
white flags and greet the rebel leader as their liberator.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, Diaka, who was a prominent opponent of the former
dictator, Mobutu Sese Seko, describes his call as the ``biggest
mistake'' of his political life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that Kabila's administration is 100 times worse than
Mobutu's,'' said Diaka, a onetime prime minister under Mobutu,
whose 31-year reign is remembered most for its staggering
corruption and brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting someone better, and we were handed someone
worse,'' he said. ``So the worse one makes me regret the lesser of
two evils. In short, in two years, I think Kabila has had only
failures.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years after he seized power and 10 months into a rebel
insurgency that is now aimed at overthrowing him, Kabila's
popularity as president is declining rapidly here.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel groups backed by Congo's neighbors control at least half
the country, Africa's third-largest, dividing it into several
pieces. With the help of other neighboring countries, Kabila was
able to avoid defeat at the hands of the rebels last August, but
now those allies are looking for a way out of an unpopular war that
has drawn in troops from seven regional powers.
</P>
<P>
   In Kinshasa, Kabila's perceived weakness has emboldened
opponents to voice their criticisms aloud, even as the government
has stepped up arrests of critics and journalists. A collapsing
economy, punctuated by skyrocketing food prices, gas shortages and
inflation topping 600 percent last month, seems to have eroded
Kabila's standing even further.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to May 17, the day on which Kabila took
power in 1997, reports swirled around the capital that residents
were buying up whistles to blow a symbolic ``fin de match,'' or end
of game, for the president. Whether the reports were exaggerated or
not, the government, clearly nervous, did not bother to find out,
sending in soldiers the night before to man checkpoints all over La
Cite Indigene, the slums where most of Kinshasa's six million
residents live.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'est l'homme qu'il fallait!'' proclaim billboards showing
Kabila's beaming face at several intersections, most of them near
government buildings. ``It's the man we needed!'' But the billboard
at Rond Point de la Victoire, La Cite's busiest corner, was taken
down. Neighborhood residents said people had been mocking the
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``With time, we hope there will be a change in leadership,
because the current leaders are the same as the ones in the past,''
said Mbiya Kalondji, 40, who sold fake Nike tank tops on a table in
a market in Masina, a district near the international airport.
``The government is not popular because we don't have food or jobs.
Some people even long for the past. At least under Mobutu, there
was no war and we had food.''
</P>
<P>
   The people of Masina jeered at Kabila's passing motorcade last
month. Youths hurled rocks and women bared their bellies to call
attention to food shortages. Even Mobutu loyalists now openly
criticize Kabila. ``Under Mobutu, at least the situation was not as
catastrophic as it is now,'' said Omari Leasisi, a former Governor
in the eastern Kivu region under Mobutu, who died in exile in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is splintered into three or four parts,'' he said,
pointing out that Kabila has paid his allies by giving them access
to Congo's mineral resources. ``To stay in power, does he have to
cede everything to foreigners?''
</P>
<P>
   Berci, the leading polling agency here, showed that Kabila's
popularity spiked in the months after August. But after its monthly
polls showed it has been falling fast since January, government
officials visited the office of its director, Olivier Kamitatu. The
intimidation forced him to cancel his report last month, Kamitatu
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government marked its second year in power this month by
holding a seven-hour parade in a stadium, attended by soldiers and
civilians wearing T-shirts made for the occasion. Kabila did not
address the crowd. But that night, he delivered a televised speech
that played to his people's deep resentment over foreign
intervention in Congo's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer foreigners, big or small, who will, as in the
past three decades, nominate our leaders,'' said Kabila, who was
plucked from obscurity by Rwanda and Uganda to lead a successful
rebellion against Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
   Didier Mumengi, the minister of information, said there was no
evidence pointing to a decline in the government's or Kabila's
popularity. ``If the head of state were not popular,'' Mumengi said
in an interview, `` there would not have been a parade of seven
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kabila took over the former Zaire, he promised that
elections would be held in April 1999. But the government has put
them off because of the war.
</P>
<P>
   In August, rebels backed by Rwanda and Uganda began a campaign
against Kabila in eastern Congo and, after flying troops into
western Congo, almost seized the capital. Rwanda and Uganda both
supported Kabila in his war against Mobutu, but he cut off his ties
to them after the relationship made him unpopular among Congolese.
</P>
<P>
   But at the last minute, Kabila won the support of several
neighbors, including Angola and Zimbabwe, whose troops helped him
defeat the rebels in western Congo. Since then, the rebel forces
are said to have advanced westward, even though they are now split
into at least three factions, each holding on to a slice of Congo.
They are also believed to be approaching the diamond-producing
areas in the south that are the government's main source of
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats here say it is unclear how much longer Kabila's main
allies, the Angolans and Zimbabweans, who entered the conflict for
their own domestic reasons, will support him.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Kabila's weakening position, he has made a series of
what appear to be concessions in recent months. He has agreed to
meet with the Congolese rebels, after vowing never to talk to what
he called puppets of Rwanda and Uganda. But talks held in various
African nations have led nowhere, despite the frequent
announcements of breakthroughs, because the war has drawn in so
many nations and factions.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the government called for a national debate to which
Congolese political parties would be invited. The idea received a
cold response from opposition leaders, whom Kabila has treated with
open contempt since taking power two years ago, accusing them of
having collaborated with Mobutu. The government has allowed
political parties to organize, but because of a long and intricate
process, no party has been recognized yet.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
