<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' 5-RUN NINTH STUNS A HARDY SCHILLING
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Curt Schilling, the major league leader in complete
games, completed another one Sunday. But he did not do it the way
he had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the ninth inning with a 4-0 lead, Schilling allowed the
Mets to bat around and emerge with a stunning 5-4 victory over the
Philadelphia Phillies at a rain-soaked Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The last two runs came on John Olerud's two-out single to left
field, one pitch after Schilling (7-2) had grazed Edgardo Alfonzo
with a 1-ball-2-strike 96-mile-per-hou fastball to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That pitch to Alfonzo ended up burying me,'' Schilling said of
the pitch that nicked Alfonzo's right forearm, the second batter
Schilling hit in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the game,'' said Schilling, who looked crestfallen and
who sat long in the dugout after the game. ``The pitches I had made
up to that point, I had a chance to get him out. And I didn't want
Olerud up in that spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Lopez and Roger Cedeno scored on Olerud's third hit of the
day as he extended his batting streak to 13 games. Cedeno's
right-foot-first slide just beat catcher Mike Lieberthal's tag
after an outstanding one-hop throw from left-fielder Ron Gant.
Cedeno celebrated by pumping his fists upward as he lay on his back
over home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the right guy on second base,'' an ecstatic Manager
Bobby Valentine said after a mad Mets' celebration. ``He's probably
the only guy in the league who could score on that throw. Gant made
a perfect throw. But Roger's a rabbit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are in sole possession of second place in the National
League East after taking two of three games from the Phillies for
the second weekend in a row. Last week, however, they did not face
Schilling in Philadelphia, who Sunday was searching for his
major-league leading eighth victory.
</P>
<P>
   And for eight innings, it looked as if those Mets players who
were grumbling before an almost two-hour rain delay of the start of
the game were right when they said the Mets had the perfect pretext
for calling the game on account of the weather, thereby avoiding
Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets also had ticket sales of 34,950 that they did not
want to lose that gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a weird game,'' said Valentine. ``We sit around for an
hour and some people started saying, `Should we even play this
game? We should issue an executive edict and miss Schilling and
maybe he'll be in the American League the next time we play them.'
There was a lot of that going around. And if we didn't win that
game, there would have probably been a lot of second-guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, all the second-guessing was faced by Philadelphia
Manager Terry Francona, who did not have his closer, Jeff Brantley.
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Curt was in complete control of the game,'' said
Francona, who had Wayne Gomes and Jim Poole warming up.
``Regardless of who was available, that was his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling _ who threw his fifth complete game (and fourth in a
row) with a season-high 138 pitches _ had made 109 pitches through
the first 8 innings. He had scattered seven hits _ all singles _ as
no Mets runner advanced past second base. Heading into the ninth,
Schilling had retired nine in a row. And even though Schilling
allowed a lead-off single in the ninth to Mike Piazza, he had
registered 96 mph on the radar gun during the at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went 1 for 4 off him,'' said Piazza on the first anniversary
of his first game in a Mets' uniform. ``And I feel like I had a
good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura was next. ``I don't want to hear anybody saying he
lost it,'' Ventura said. ``He pitched nine innings and didn't lose
anything off his fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, perhaps, some control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran a fastball in to Ventura that I didn't get in enough,''
Schilling said of Ventura's two-run home run that cut the lead to
4-2. ``And the balls I threw to Lopez and Alfonzo, I got in too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1-2 pitch from Schilling struck Lopez on the back of the right
elbow, following a one-out single by Matt Franco, the first batter
he had hit in 81 and a one-third innings. Jermaine Allensworth then
provided a run-scoring pinch-hit single between third and short,
and it was a 4-3 game.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno was the next batter. He had struck out looking three
times and was 0 for 4 on the day. On an 0-1 pitch, Cedeno lined a
ball back through the box. Schilling knocked it down and his throw
to second forced Allensworth. But shortstop Alex Arias' alert throw
to third was just a tad too late to catch Lopez off the bag. And
when Cedeno took took second base without a throw by the catcher,
the stage was set for Schilling to hit Alfonzo _ and then for
Olerud to come up with the game-winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That particular pitch I had already fouled off on my first
three at-bats,'' said Olerud of the low and away fastball he lined
into left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you should choke and blow a 4-0 lead,'' said
Schilling, still wondering how he had lost. ``I don't care who you
are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
