u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAA-PILOT-FATIGUE-820     05-23 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-PILOT-FATIGUE-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS SAY FAA IGNORES A SAFETY RULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States' second-largest airline pilots union is
accusing the Federal Aviation Administration of refusing to enforce
a safety rule because many airlines find compliance too costly.
</P>
<P>
   The rule requires that pilots get at least eight hours of rest
in the 24 hours before the end of their flight duties. The
controversy mainly affects reserve pilots, who, if they are awake
in the day and then are assigned to an overnight flight, may end up
being awake for close to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The union, the Allied Pilots Association, which represents the
9,500 pilots at American Airlines, has asked Kenneth Mead, the
Department of Transportation's inspector general, to investigate
why the FAA has not enforced the 1985 regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure of the FAA to enforce current regulations
regarding crew rest is an industrywide problem and a major cause of
pilot fatigue that is seriously compromising aviation safety,''
Richard Rubin, a 767 jetliner captain and a member of the union's
national safety committee, wrote to Mead on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has acknowledged on several occasions over the last
decade that airlines have not been complying with the rule and that
the FAA has not been enforcing it. But Margaret Gilligan, the FAA's
deputy associate administrator for regulation and certification,
said in an interview on Friday that it was not clear whether
airlines were in compliance, because the FAA had not conducted a
formal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly some perception that there may be one or
more programs that are not in compliance,'' Ms. Gilligan said.
Nevertheless, she said she was recently directed by the FAA's
administrator, Jane Garvey, to determine how the agency should
enforce the rule.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a turnabout from what Rubin said was Ms.
Gilligan's position in March. He said she told the Allied Pilots
Association's president, Richard Lavoy, that the FAA would not seek
to enforce the regulation, despite its promises to do so. Ms.
Gilligan said she had not meant to give that impression.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of fatigue has become a growing focus of pilots and
safety experts in all modes of transportation in recent years.
Tired pilots have been blamed for a number of crashes, including
the 1993 crash of a DC-8 cargo plane at the U.S. Naval Air Station
in Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   One recent study concluded that being awake continuously for 20
to 25 hours is equivalent to having a blood alcohol level of 0.1,
well over the legal limit for airline pilots.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the National Transportation Safety Board placed
increased rest at the top of its annual list of recommendations for
avoiding transportation accidents. The board, which has no
regulatory authority, also has expressed frustration that the FAA
has chosen not to enforce the rule for airline pilots.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the American pilots union, the Air Line Pilots
Association, which is the industry's largest union, representing
53,000 pilots at 52 airlines, has also raised concerns about the
issue. On May 13, Duane Woerth, the union's president, wrote to Ms.
Garvey asking her to ``expeditiously enforce'' the regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the rule has been simmering for most of
this decade. The Air Transport Association, the lobbying group for
the major airlines, contends that fatigue is not a problem and that
compliance with the rule would cost its members hundreds of
millions of dollars because they would have to hire more pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the major U.S. scheduled airlines give their pilots
ample time off to rest, and none of them has had a fatal accident
attributed to pilot fatigue,'' the association said.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation states that airlines must give pilots at least
eight hours of guaranteed rest in the 24 hours before they finish
their flight duty. The requirement poses no conflict for senior
pilots who fly regular schedules. But thousands of so-called
reserve pilots can spend several days in a row awaiting a call to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current practice at American, United Airlines, Delta
Airlines and other major airlines, a reserve pilot who woke up at 8
a.m. might be called in the late afternoon to fly an evening flight
that would land at 7 a.m. the next day. The pilot would be awake
continuously for 23 hours by the time the flight duty ended.
</P>
<P>
   The few airlines that comply with the regulations, including
Continental Airlines and United Parcel Service, divide their
reserve pilots into groups assigned to rest at different times of
day.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, the American captain who has focused on the fatigue
issue, said Continental and UPS had to increase their pilot ranks
by only 2 percent to make the system work. But he emphasized that
cost was not the point. ``The regulation sets this rule as the
standard for safety,'' he said, ``To operate under the regulations
requires this expense, period.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The FAA proposed amending the rule in 1995, promising at the
time to enforce the 1985 rule if no change was made. But after
soliciting the views of pilots, airlines and other interested
parties, the rule was not amended and the agency did not act.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the FAA again promised to ``rigorously'' enforce the
rule if an industry-pilot task force failed to agree on a new
standard. That initiative ended in failure in February, after which
Rubin, a member of the task force, said Ms. Gilligan of the FAA
indicated that the agency would not keep its promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult for the FAA to go against the ATA because
it is so powerful,'' he said of the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gilligan said that she has now been asked by Ms. Garvey, the
FAA administrator, ``to pursue a vigorous enforcement strategy.''
But she added that the agency first would have to investigate
whether airlines were violating the rule. Then the airlines must be
given time to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we have accepted what they have been doing for so
long,'' she said, ``they need to have an opportunity to make
changes, if that is appropriate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
