<HEADLINE>
HUGE TERN COLONY THREATENS COLUMBIA RIVER'S DWINDLING SALMON RUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB TAYLOR  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICE ISLAND _ The Caspian tern banks and lands on the sand, a
young salmon dangling from its beak.
</P>
<P>
   Guilty as charged.
</P>
<P>
   The tern's feeding, so natural and ordinary, has become a menace
to Columbia River salmon recovery. Caspian terns have built one of
the world's largest tern colonies here, about 20 miles east of
where the river empties into the Pacific Ocean, and are thought to
be gobbling as much as one-quarter of the Columbia Basin's
dwindling salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   Though man is largely responsible for the bird's explosive
growth here, he's finding that hard to change. This spring,
biologists are urging the birds to leave, but most of the ingrates
are refusing to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable how many birds are here,'' biologist Ken
Collis muttered last week, as he watched more than 10,000 of the
seabirds stand, sit, squawk and shuffle around on the west end of
this island.
</P>
<P>
   The Caspian Tern Relocation Project, which Collis advises, aims
to shift the terns downriver to a former nesting spot where they
would eat fewer salmon. The project has wielded bulldozers and farm
equipment, scarecrows and decoys, fencing and guns.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the birds are staying put. Last Friday, about 12,000
terns jammed into a corner of Rice Island, by Collis' estimate.
They loafed, nested, squawked, and feasted on salmon and steelhead
that included threatened and endangered runs. Some even nested next
to a 3-foot-tall wooden scarecrow painted to look like a bald
eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The birds on Rice Island are a lot more determined to nest
there than we thought,'' says Dan Roby, another biologist advising
the relocation project.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is another illustration of the lengths man must go to
correct problems he causes by messing with Mother Nature. The
lesson keeps cropping up here, in one of the most engineered rivers
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers dammed and dredged this river
and its tributaries. When its fish runs started failing, the Corps
put fish ladders on most dams to get adults upriver and built
bypasses and barges to carry young fish downriver.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't enough. Governments threw up hatcheries to produce
fish where dams, farming, logging or development wiped out spawning
streams. They implanted fish with tags, transponders and radios;
spilled more water over dams; counted and studied fish; and offered
bounties for killing fish that prey on young salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago did federal and state agencies focus on the
little-noticed Caspian terns.
</P>
<P>
   Named for the Caspian sea in southern Asia, this largest of the
tern species is found on seacoasts and inland lakes almost
throughout the globe's temperate regions.
</P>
<P>
   The fish-eating birds were first seen nesting in the lower
Columbia River in 1984, on East Sand Island, about five miles from
the sea. In 1986, they also colonized Rice Island, about 20 miles
from the river's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Both islands are artificial creations where the Corps of
Engineers dumped sand dredged from the river. They made excellent
nesting grounds for terns, which prefer bare, open sand near the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Fishery biologists worried as the Rice Island colony grew to an
extraordinary 10,000 nesting pairs. Elswehere a group of 2,000 is
considered a lot. The group on this artificial island became the
largest in North America, researchers said, perhaps the largest in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   After aerial surveys found a lot of salmon radio-tags
broadcasting from Rice Island, a study was commissioned in 1997. To
fish managers' dismay, it concluded that the terns were eating an
extraordinary 6 million to 25 million salmon, steelhead and trout _
or about 6-to-25 percent of the run below Bonneville Dam.
</P>
<P>
   To salmon biologists, the birds could hardly have picked a worse
site. Out-migrating young salmon and steelhead run into their first
salt water near Rice Island, and some linger to adjust. They are
easy marks; especially hatchery fish that are conditioned to feed
on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The terns were feasting on a handful of threatened or endangered
runs whose decline threatened to impose costly fixes from
Washington's Methow Valley to Idaho's Redfish Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of upstream salmon fixes latched on to the tern study
to resist demands on water, barging and cheap, dam-generated
hydroelectric power. Instead, they blamed fishing, Caspian terns,
seals and sea lions for the runs' demise.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies and wildlife groups squabbled over what to do. Some
agencies and fishing groups wanted to rid Rice Island of the birds.
But citing the International Migratory Bird Treaty Act, the Fish
and Wildlife Service and the Audubon Society came to the terns'
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Under a compromise plan launched last February, an interagency
team tried to make most of Rice Island inhospitable to the terns by
planting winter wheat in the sand. It left an acre unplanted so
that as many as 1,000 pairs of terns could stay to be monitored and
to sustain the population if terns couldn't nest elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the team set out to lure the terns to their former
nest site downriver on East Sand Island. Researchers figured the
birds would catch a hefty share of small marine fish there,
reducing their toll on salmon.
</P>
<P>
   With heavy equipment, researchers cleared grass and trees from
part of East Sand Island, which they festooned with tern decoys and
recorded tern calls.
</P>
<P>
   Though cold, wind, rain and coarse sand kept most of the wheat
from sprouting, researchers found another solution. They
criss-crossed the nesting site with 3-foot-high, black-plastic
fencing. It worked. Terns avoided the fences.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as of last week, terns were packing into the one acre of
open ground like Manhattan sun-bathers hitting the Coney Island
beach in a heat wave. As more arrived, terns spilled onto nearby
areas where small plants, disturbed by the project, had failed to
resprout. Hybrid western and glaucous-winged gulls made repeated
forays into the crowd of squawking terns, stealing smolts and
burgling nests.
</P>
<P>
   The Rice Island terns behave strangely, according to Collis.
They fight amongst themselves, spook easily and fail to protect
their nests from attack. Similar problems the past two years have
left them with few young, so dispersing the colony should be good
for the birds as well as the salmon, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Local Audubon Society chapters complain that the terns are being
scapegoated. The birds weren't even present while the basin's
salmon and steelhead runs plummeted, they note.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some Pacific County residents fear that
moving terns to East Sand Island will defeat their habitat
restoration effort for salmon in nearby Chinook Creek.
</P>
<P>
   And some locals question the kid-glove handling of the terns. A
few predators on the island would solve the problem, says Rex Ziak
of Naselle. In fact, researchers have trapped raccoons and other
nest predators that they believe people put on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The project is far from meeting the goal of moving 80 percent to
90 percent of the colony from Rice Island. But Collis says that
goal was unrealistic for a seabird transplant that had never before
been attempted.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the project is a success. It has demonstrated that
the terns can be moved, though not micro-managed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, about 1,000 terns were counted on East Sand Island,
and with a few strategic shots from a .22-caliber rifle,
researchers were keeping predator gulls at bay from the new colony.
As crowding and predation continue on Rice Island, meanwhile,
Collis hopes more terns will take the East Sand Island way out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
