<SLUG> BC-GEPHARDT-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT VOWS SPEEDY HOUSE VOTE ON GUN BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The House minority leader, Richard A. Gephardt, vowed
Sunday to press for a House vote this week on the first major
anti-gun bill to clear one chamber of Congress since the
Republicans won control of Congress in 1994. He predicted that GOP
moderates would be wounded politically if they block it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a lot of pressure'' this week, Gephardt
said in an interview. ``Frankly, these measures are modest.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, 58, a Missouri Democrat who has led his party in the
US House of Representatives since 1995, was in Boston to address
graduates at Suffolk University's Law School and take part in a
forum on women's issues sponsored by the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, hours after gunfire erupted in a Georgia high school,
the Senate approved legislation that would require safety locks on
new handguns, ban juveniles with a history of violence from buying
a firearm, and stop the importation of large ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans have said they will hold hearings this week on
the measure, but have not agreed to a speedy vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt, saying ``the earth is shifting under everybody's
feet on this issue,'' said the Democrats believe the time for
hearings has long since passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people who are really troubled by this are the
moderate Republicans,'' who, Gephardt said, risk appearing ``like
they're part of a group that's dominated by'' the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The House minority leader decided in February that he had a
better chance of becoming the next Democratic House speaker than he
did defeating Vice President Al Gore for their party's presidential
nomination next year. The Democrats need to pick up six House seats
if Gephardt, a House member for 22 years, is to wrest the speaker's
gavel from the GOP when the 107th Congress convenes in January
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said Democrats have ``their hands full'' in their
efforts to retain the White House and take back the House. But he
called the recent spate of stories about troubles within Gore's
campaign exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is the front-runner and the front-runner always gets
knocked at by everybody's who after him. That's normal,'' Gephardt
said. ``I think that at the end of the day he will win the primary
and I think he's going to win the general election. He's a good
candidate. He's smart. He's experienced. He's probably the best
vice president anybody's ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The intense scrutiny now being endured by Gore, said Gephardt,
awaits the Republican presidential front-runner, Texas Governor
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be formidable. But I do think'' Bush ``can be
beaten,'' Gephardt said. ``I think he hasn't been tested at all. He
hasn't been out of Texas. He's going to have his day in the tub.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt ran unsuccessfully for president in 1988 and considered
running again in 1992, but he concluded then that President George
Bush looked unbeatable before an obscure governor from Arkansas,
Bill Clinton, emerged from the Democratic field to unseat an
incumbent president.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has just written a book, ``An Even Better Place:
America in the 21st Century,'' which includes his diagnosis of what
is wrong with the country and his prescription for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of destruction, which I think has infected the
whole system, is driving voters and ordinary citizens away from
politics,'' Gephardt said. ``People hate it. They hate the
confrontation. They hate the attacks. They hate the endless
investigations. So they're disaffected, cynical, and they don't
participate. It is very worrisome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
