<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS SAY FAREWELL TO LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ With precision and ease, the San Antonio
Spurs helped the Los Angeles Lakers turn out the lights at the
Great Western Forum Sunday by flipping the switch on the Lakers'
season.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan scored 31 points in the first three quarters and
Jerome Kersey came off the bench with eight fourth-quarter points
to lead the Spurs to a 118-107 victory and a sweep of the
best-of-7-game Western Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs advanced to the conference finals, where they will
enjoy home-court advantage against the winner of the Portland-Utah
series.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did not go quietly, and Shaquille O'Neal responded to
his big-man challenge with Duncan by scoring a game-high 36 points.
After dominating the series, Duncan seemed to run out of gas and
was held to two free throws in the final period, finishing with 33
points and 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But San Antonio proved the better team, exploiting personnel
mismatches and better using its bench. The Spurs, with a cohesive
defense and balanced offense, also answered every Lakers run.
</P>
<P>
   The backbreaker came after the Lakers had cut the lead to 86-84
with a furious charge at the end of the third quarter, only to have
San Antonio reel off the first 13 points of the fourth quarter. The
Lakers, swept in last year's Western Conference finals by Utah, now
have team issues to deal with, and not just uniformed personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Will Kurt Rambis, who took over for Del Harris after 12 games,
return as head coach? Will Jerry West, shaken by the Dennis Rodman
episode, remain as executive vice president? And there will be the
inevitable speculation about Phil Jackson, the former Chicago Bulls
coach, replacing both of them.
</P>
<P>
   One replacement is definite: the Great Western Forum, the
playing address for West and Elgin Baylor, Wilt Chamberlain, Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and Magic Johnson, will give way to the new Staples
Center in downtown Los Angeles. The Lakers have played at the Forum
since Dec. 31, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The site of six world championships was given a sour farewell.
Game 4 started the way Game 3 had ended, with the Spurs leaning on
Duncan and Avery Johnson and with the Lakers in meltdown mode. San
Antonio led by 11 points midway through the first period.
Desperate, Rambis turned to Tyronn Lue in hopes of shutting down
Johnson, who already had 10 points. Lue, a quick rookie guard from
Nebraska, had not played in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Lue not only made Johnson disappear, he also took charge of the
Los Angeles offense, contributing eight points in his first eight
minutes in the game. But after watching its lead get whittled to
four points midway through the second period, San Antonio used a
pair of 3-point shots by Jaren Jackson to help rebuild the lead to
65-51 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was a foul and free-throw festival. There were 22
fouls called in the first quarter, another 20 in the second. Of 65
first-half points for San Antonio, 27 came on free throws. It was
evidence of the Lakers' futility in trying to stop the Spurs'
offense, most notably Duncan, who led all scorers at the half with
20 points, but was joined in double figures by Johnson (12),
Jackson (11) and Sean Elliott (10).
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, given some room to work when Lue opened up the offense,
led the Lakers with 15 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had their best quarter of the series in the third.
They outscored San Antonio by 12-2 to open the quarter and closed
the gap to 67-63. They did not appear to get discouraged when the
Spurs answered with a run of 10 consecutive points.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 14, the Lakers scored the final 12 points of the period.
O'Neal turned up the physical contact and the Spurs seemed to lose
their composure for the first time in the four games, committing
four turnovers. Los Angeles cashed in each, with Lue hitting a
drive at the buzzer to cut San Antonio's lead to 86-84. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
