<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT     05-23 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 3-0 LEAD ON HAWKS INSPIRES KNICKS TO ACHIEVE A SWEEP AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the middle of the Knicks' showroom floor of
hot-rod players, with Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby all but
painted with racing stripes, there stood Chris Dudley, like a Chevy
straight from the days of sock hops and soda fountains.
</P>
<P>
   He was all bumpers and bulk Sunday. After Coach Jeff Van Gundy
pulled him off the bench to relieve a ragged Patrick Ewing, Dudley
used his size and strength to push the sharp-edged Dikembe Mutombo
out of position to inflict harm and unearthed a surprising display
of offense beneath his cumbersome exterior to the joy of a Madison
Square Garden crowd that stood in applause when he fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   So this is what it has come to for the threadbare Hawks. It was
Dudley, of all players, who brought the Hawks to their knees and
nudged them to the brink of extinction. After 14 years in the
league, Dudley unleashed the playoff game of his life as he scored
14 points and grabbed 12 rebounds and became part of an
overwhelming effort by the Knicks bench that left them with a 90-78
Game 3 victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks were left in a desperate state. No team has ever been
down 3-0 and come back to win a series. With Game 4 on Monday at
the Garden, the Knicks can complete the sweep of the Hawks in their
best-of-seven-game second-round series. With one more win, the once
dysfunctional Knicks will meet the Indiana Pacers in the Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   `'We want the sweep,'' Latrell Sprewell said. `'We have a
beautiful opportunity to close it out in front of our fans. We kind
of let that chance slip away against Miami; so we want to close it
out here at home. There are two big motivating factors for closing
it out. One, we can get some rest. Two, for the fans. They have
been supportive through the ups and down this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, times have never been better. After taking in another
dominating game by the Knicks, who shot 45 percent while holding
the Hawks to 31, the fans rose in unison for the unassuming Dudley.
He had absorbed a whirl of elbows from Mutombo, and at one point,
had outscored the Hawks, 8-6, in the fourth quarter alone in a game
that grew a bit unsightly at the end. Perhaps lulled a bit by the
control the Knicks had of this game, Dudley gave them someone to
focus their energy on.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a guy with a lifelong brain lock at the free-throw
line, yet the fans went bonkers for the 2 of 4 attempts he made.
Here was a player who has been known to get clumsy around the paint
but drew raves for the way he followed up misses with rim-hanging
dunks.
</P>
<P>
   `'Dud was hot, on fire,'' Marcus Camby said. `'I was pumping him
up, like go get `em, Dud. It's been like this for us in the
playoffs. It's always someone who comes up and delivers. Dud came
up big.''
</P>
<P>
   After nudging Mutombo out of range for his crane-like hook
shots, after sealing him off in order to give his teammates room to
wiggle in for layup, Dudley exited upon his sixth foul with 1:06
left in the game. He ambled over to the sideline, and chuckled as
the crowd chanted, `'Dudley, Dudley.''
</P>
<P>
   `'It was a great feeling,'' said Dudley, who helped hold Mutombo
to 2 for 7 from the field. `'More importantly, it was even better
to be up, 3-0.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are in this position because of the unrelenting
effort from role players like Dudley on a bench that has crushed
the spirits of the withering Hawks throughout this series. This
time, the Knicks outscored the Hawks' bench, 46-22, and
outrebounded them, 27-9.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the bench took over with the game tight at the start
of the second quarter. That's when Camby (15 points) and Sprewell
(17 points) stepped off the bench and provided their usual thrills.
Camby swooped in, stole a pass and was off for a dramatic fastbreak
dunk. That was followed up by Sprewell's driving layup on a
fastbreak that was triggered by a Steve Smith miss. One possession
later, it was Larry Johnson who leaked out on another Hawks' miss
and found himself open for a fastbreak layup.
</P>
<P>
   Swiftly, in the span of 64 seconds, the Knicks turned a tie into
a 6-point lead with 8 minutes left in the first half. They never
trailed again. After Smith began the day with uncanny accuracy
around Allan Houston, Johnson switched to defend him and banged him
for awhile. Then it was Sprewell's turn. By game's end, Smith, who
began 5 for 8, finished 7 for 21.
</P>
<P>
   `'They are using a lot of bodies, a lot of fresh bodies in and
out,'' Smith said. `'We were falling and reaching and trying to
make shots. It's frustrating. I mean, we know we can play better
than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Can they? In each game, the Knicks have been able to wear down
the Hawks and build double-digit leads in the fourth quarter. Game
3 was no different. The Knicks held a 14 point-lead four minutes
into the third quarter and a an 18-point lead with 7:26 left in the
game. Most comforting for the Knicks, they accumulated their
cushions with Ewing shooting just 2 for 12 in a 24-minute
performance that was played with his sore Achilles restricting his
movement.
</P>
<P>
   `'Dud was great,'' Ewing said. ``He played a much better game
than I did. I was hurting but we got the win, and that's the bottom
line.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are winning these days as Van Gundy reaches into
every corner of his roster and pulls out just the right body at
just the right time. If Houston isn't working, then maybe Sprewell
will. If Kurt Thomas doesn't have it, perhaps Camby does. If Ewing
is off, maybe Dudley is on. The team on the verge of missing the
playoffs is now one win from their first Eastern Conference Final
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   `'We've just started to play better,'' Van Gundy said.
`'Sometimes, people make it out to be more complex. We have started
to play more unselfish and much better, and let's face it, we have
gotten some great breaks along the way. We wouldn't be talking
about this if that ball rolled out in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   But Houston's miracle shot fell in, and the Knicks' lifespan in
the playoffs was extended. Now, they are one win away from facing
the team that eliminated them last season, the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   `'You don't want to go back down to Atlanta, travel down there,
extend the series and allow Indiana to have that rest while we're
still at war,'' Dudley said. `'We really don't want a letdown. We
can't afford one. We've got to come out and take care of
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
