<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-OLIVETTI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EXECUTIVE WHO CAPTURED TELECOM ITALIA 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ When Roberto Colaninno emerged earlier this year as the
quarterback of Olivetti's plan to buy Telecom Italia, the biggest
hostile takeover ever in Europe, people who follow business in
Italy reacted with surprise, and then, after a quick reassessment
of the man, with total comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise involved Colaninno's record. He had run a midsized
auto parts company and then Olivetti SpA, which was struggling to
master the phone business after failing at computers, and he was
not part of the Italian corporate elite.
</P>
<P>
   The insight that soon followed was that Colaninno was a hard
worker with few of the pretensions that can accompany Italian
corporate leaders and that he had learned the workings of financial
markets early on, both on his own and as an apprentice to Carlo De
Benedetti, one of the great innovators of Italian finance.
</P>
<P>
   Colaninno had worked, until he took on the siege of Telecom
Italia, as chief executive of Olivetti, the company that had
transformed itself from a sleepy maker of typewriters into a
leading European computer company that stumbled over high costs and
low technology.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when De Benedetti was chairman of a badly foundering
Olivetti, he brought Colaninno to the company, having decided that
Olivetti's future lay not in computers but in telephones, and most
notably the mobile phone business, which was exploding in Italy in
the mid-1990s. But the rise of Olivetti's phone business was
dragged down by hemorrhaging in other areas. From 1990 to 1996,
when Colaninno stepped in, losses at Olivetti totaled $2.4 billion
and debt was crushing the company. Colaninno's recipe was
relatively simple: He ruthlessly jettisoned money-losing
operations, focusing instead on businesses that promised profit,
and most notably on phones.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, that meant cajoling institutional investors, who at
the time held the majority of Olivetti shares, into a capital
increase, then dumping Olivetti's unprofitable office machinery and
computer businesses into the hands of international partners and
focusing the remaining resources on the telephone venture, into
which Olivetti brought a strong partner, Mannesmann AG of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was perhaps remarkable for a man whose career had
begun at a small Italian auto parts maker, Fiamm SpA, which was
owned at the time by the Turner &AMP; Newell group of Britain. In 1972,
Colaninno became Fiamm's chief executive at the age of 29. In the
following years, Colaninno met De Benedetti and together they
founded a finance company, Sogefi SpA, that first acquired Fiamm
from Turner &AMP; Newell, then transformed it into one of Europe's most
successful auto parts suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   That combination of managerial talent and financial shrewdness
is vintage Colaninno, say bankers who have worked with him. By the
mid-1980s, Colaninno had become a board member at several regional
banks in heavily industrialized central Italy, where he wove links
to young entrepreneurs in one of the nation's most dynamic regions.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, people who know him say, Colaninno may be the
ideal man to take on Telecom Italia. Like Olivetti, Telecom
Italia's performance is dragged down by marginally profitable
businesses, like the Italtel and Sirti equipment units and real
estate and insurance operations, that could better be sold or run
by specialized partners.
</P>
<P>
   Colaninno sold Olivetti's computer-manufacturing business to
foreign investors, who ultimately closed it down, and found a buyer
for Olivetti's computer services arm in Wang in the United States.
He brought the office machine division into a joint venture with
Xerox. He showed negotiating skill at convincing Italian government
leaders and labor unions that bitter medicine was necessary, even
though it cost Italy jobs and what was left of its domestic
computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some strong differences in Telecom Italia that
will translate into fresh challenges.
</P>
<P>
   A leading critic of the deal has been De Benedetti, who picked
apart the Olivetti takeover last week in a published interview. De
Benedetti said he advised Colaninno that the takeover could only
yield greater value if Olivetti could bring Telecom Italia bigger
market share, new technology or better management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noted to him,'' De Benedetti said, ``that Olivetti did not
have, as it still does not have, anything to offer Telecom Italia,
except to bring it the debt it would have to incur to acquire
Telecom Italia, and some residual management problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Having garnered only 51 percent of Telecom Italia in the bid
that expired Friday, Colaninno, at a news conference on Saturday in
Milan, said that he planned to ``set up a group of shareholders to
support management's projects and plans'' and assert control at
Telecom Italia. Moreover, Olivetti, which acquired its $33 billion
stake in Telecom Italia through a subsidiary called Tecnost, will
be under pressure from minority shareholders to merge the acquiring
company, Tecnost, and the target, Telecom Italia. At the news
conference, Colaninno said he would ``work to shorten the chain of
holdings.'' Yet some analysts fear that could dilute Olivetti's
control further, to perhaps as little as 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A governmental challenge will probably come as early as this
week when the Minister of Industry, Pierluigi Bersani, will meet
Colaninno and labor union leaders to discuss Olivetti's plans for
Telecom Italia, which will most likely include steep job cuts.
Olivetti's takeover still requires the approval of the government,
which retains a 3.4 percent ``golden share'' with veto rights in
Telecom Italia, though approval is considered certain.
</P>
<P>
   Italian government officials were quick to welcome the outcome
of the Olivetti bid. Colaninno had often argued his case by
insisting that a national asset like Telecom Italia had to be
protected by Italian investors from possible predators abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But a curious twist to this appeal to nationalism, some analysts
note, is that Colaninno himself closed down the remnants of Italy's
computer industry, once also considered a national treasure.
Moreover, by selling control of Olivetti's mobile and fixed-line
phone businesses to Mannesmann, he appears to be placing what many
consider the most unencumbered phone franchise in Italy under
German control.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have the spirit of an entrepreneur,'' he said in a
recently published interview, ``you're never finished. You like
new, exciting times. You need it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
