<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-OUTAGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKS ON UTILITIES DARKEN MUCH OF SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ In what Yugoslav civilians say is an
attempt to make their lives miserable, NATO completed two months of
air raids Sunday by stepping up attacks on power plants in Serbia,
plunging much of the country into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the capital was without power Sunday, and power
disruption was common across the country. Officials at Belgrade's
Neonatal Institute said that three newborns died when its backup
generators could not immediately provide enough electricity for its
incubators.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents in Belgrade complained Sunday that they were
without electricity or water. One political party here said that
NATO was carrying out ``collective reprisals'' against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's humiliating, as if we were plunged back into the
primitiveness of the Middle Ages,'' the Associated Press quoted
Branka Nikolic, a doctor and mother of two, as saying.
</P>
<P>
   A day after bombing a power plant in Kolubara, NATO planes
bombed the Nikola Tesla power plant in Obrenovac, about 20 miles
south of Belgrade. Named after a famous Serbian inventor who
emigrated to the United States, the Tesla plant is the biggest
coal-burning plant in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Like the attack the day before on nearby Kolubara, the dawn
attack on the Tesla plant used conventional, high-explosive bombs.
Previous attacks on power plants have used so-called ``soft bombs''
which explode above ground and release graphite filaments which
short-circuit eletrical transformers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do these NATO animals think? They want to crush an entire
nation,'' the AP quoted a pianist, Buco Kovacevic, as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional bombs, however, cause material damage that
requires more extensive repair work. In Brussels, a NATO spokesman
acknowledged that the alliance's warplanes are using ``mixed
munitions'' of soft and conventional bombs.
</P>
<P>
   NATO planes appeared to be flying lower than usual, drawing the
fiercest antiaircraft fire in Belgrade that anyone could remember
in the previous two months.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of NATO planes being downed, and NATO
missiles cut the power lines that run from Obrenovac to the
capital. Priority customers, such as hospitals, bakeries, and water
pumping stations, were receiving power by midafternoon, but many of
Belgrade's apartment blocks, where most of its residents live,
remained without electricity or water.
</P>
<P>
   The Beta news agency reported that NATO bombs had wrecked a
water plant in Sremska Mitrovica, in the northern mostly rural
Vojvodina region, leaving at least 10,000 people without water.
</P>
<P>
   NATO hopes that by racheting up the hardship on ordinary people,
there will be increasing pressure on Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to accept a settlement over Kosovo. But most anger here
right now appears to be aimed at NATO.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes continued to pummel Serb forces in Kosovo,
hitting 10 artillery units and nine armored vehicles, according to
NATO officials in Brussels. NATO said it flew 652 sorties in a
24-hour period overnight, 301 of which made missile strikes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-23 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HAWKS FIND KNICKS ARE TOO FAST TO HACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Sunday's game at Madison Square Garden,
Atlanta Hawks' Coach Lenny Wilkens suggested an ominous antidote to
the new, high-flying Knicks: rock-'em, sock-'em basketball. Wilkens
recalled a play in Game 2 last Thursday in Atlanta, when a Hawks
player reached in on Latrell Sprewell and lightly fouled him.
Sprewell scored anyway; Wilkens was angry because it hadn't been a
hard foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take his arms off _ you know what I mean, where he can't get
the shot up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens pointed to Marcus Camby's riveting slam dunk over
Dikembe Mutombo in the same game. ``He goes through the lane
untouched,'' Wilkens said. ``Hey, if it's me, I take him down. I'm
not going to be dirty, but I'm going to stop you.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Wilkens' Hawks cannot stop the Knicks. For the third
consecutive game, the Knicks, led by Sprewell, sparked by Camby,
raced past Atlanta Sunday to take a 3-0 lead in the
four-of-seven-game series. The Knicks once again moved too fast to
be hacked, and they are on the brink of their first second-round
triumph in five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   What a phenomenal turnabout: a team barely picked to reach the
playoffs is now looking at a sweep and facing the possibility of a
conference championship. But the more drastic transformation,
greater than the Knicks' racing through the second round in
stunning, running style, is the 360-degree turnabout by Garden fans
toward Sprewell and Camby. These new Knicks, blamed at first for
everything from the demise of the franchise to the nation's
crumbling moral infrastructure, have become heroes of the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, you might regard this as a turnabout of
hypocritical proportions. But in this world of arenas and sneakers,
muscle and sinew, winning negates consistency; success dulls
conscience. At the beginning of this mutant season, many Knicks
fans and pious media types said they could never root for a team on
which Sprewell played. By gosh, he nearly strangled his coach! And
Camby? Well, he'll never fill the shoes of our beloved Oakman.
</P>
<P>
   Oak who?
</P>
<P>
   With the Knicks on the verge of a spectacular sweep, Camby and
Sprewell are now Garden fixtures. Children wear their jerseys;
adults chant their names. They are hailed as the answers to the
Knicks' woes, the reason for the Knicks' heady success. You wonder
what the two of them think. Do they feel like cursing the fans for
their fickleness, or do they simply take it in stride?
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell has been reserved. He hasn't embraced the fans as much
as he has respected them and expressed gratitude. ``I appreciate
the response,'' he said. The word that creeps into his answers is
focus. Asked about the drama involving Dave Checketts, Phil Jackson
and Jeff Van Gundy, Sprewell sidestepped, saying that only Georgia
was in his sights: ``Atlanta, man. That's all I've got on my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby, 25, is a bit more effusive, more open and typically
emotional about his and the Knicks' roller coaster ride to respect.
Hurt by the early doubts, he has been buoyed by the support. ``It
was hard for them to see the real me,'' he said. ``In the beginning
there were doubts.'' His teammates have helped him put the fans'
inconsistencies in perspective. ``On the team, we talk about that a
lot,'' he said. ``Especially in the Garden: when it's going bad,
they boo you. We talk about: it's us against the world _ go out
there, please ourselves, go out there and play hard. It feels good
when they're cheering and we're rolling. If they boo, I want to
stay humble and do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Chaney, the Knicks' assistant coach, looks a bit more
cynically at this outpouring of Garden love for Sprewell and Camby.
``At first they said Allan Houston and Latrell can't play
together,'' Chaney said. ``Now they're saying they're a great pair.
They're saying Sprewell's great and he should be mayor, because
he's playing well. Let Sprewell start playing poorly and see what
happens. Same with this team: when we're playing well they cheer
us; when we're playing bad, they boo. What have you done for me
lately?''
</P>
<P>
   In Chaney's view, the cheers have nothing to do with morality or
acceptance of foibles. They're cheers for the moment. ``New York is
about winning,'' he said, ``no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   There is so much at stake right now for so many within the
Knicks' organization, at some level winning may not even matter.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's game, Wilkens made his own contribution to the
Knicks' soap opera when he praised the acquisitions of Sprewell and
Camby, moves made by Ernie Grunfeld, who was since dismissed as
general manager. ``They made some good trades,'' Wilkens said of
the Knicks. ``And they are starting to pay off. Everybody is all
upset, but if you look at Camby, he is a pretty athletic young
player. And he is paying dividends now for them.''
</P>
<P>
   One executive has already lost his job; more losses are likely
to follow. Sprewell may not be here next season. He has become a
highly marketable commodity who might fetch a great prize, or
prizes, on the trade market: a star-caliber forward and a point
guard. Who knows what this team will look like next season?
</P>
<P>
   All the Knicks have to do is look at the dirty dealing in their
front office to know that they work in a place where no one is
safe, conference championship or no. The fans aren't the only
hypocrites: this Knicks organization specializes in fattening frogs
for the snakes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
