<HEADER>
A8170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-DUDLEY-NYT     05-23 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-DUDLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUDLEY AND 30 POINTS MAKE STRANGE BEDFELLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A hobbling Patrick Ewing was figuratively and
literally on ice, playing sparingly and then soaking his tender
left Achilles tendon in a large bucket of ice. Dikembe Mutombo, the
proud and gracious center of the Atlanta Hawks, could do no right
on offense as his team fell into an 0-3 abyss.
</P>
<P>
   This was shaping up to be a lousy afternoon for big men at
Madison Square Garden, the 7-foot veteran series gone terribly
awry. Out West, Tim Duncan and David Robinson were doing the pivot
position proud _ sweeping Shaquille O'Neal and the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, well, the whole story line was getting muddled.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing vs. Mutombo, remember? That Georgetown showdown was
supposed to be the only reason to tune into the Eastern Conference
semifinal between the Hawks and the Knicks, the only decent subplot
until Reggie Miller arrives in the next round.
</P>
<P>
   And what was this, Latrell Sprewell throwing it down with two
hands on the break, his spindly body squaring up and swishing shots
in mid-air? Marcus Camby taking off from the dotted line with the
ball cocked?
</P>
<P>
   Tiny men, skinny men, darting around all those plodding oafs. No
one to bring honor to the position.
</P>
<P>
   Then it happened _ Jeff Van Gundy summoning him from the bench.
The sweats came off in a flash. He started toward midcourt,
shoulders first, that ninth-grade, tough-guy walk announcing his
entrance into Game 3 with 5 minutes 16 seconds left in the first
quarter. ``Chris Dudley replaces Patrick Ewing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clump. Clump. Clump.
</P>
<P>
   Free-throw purists covered their eyes. Grade-school coaches told
their players not to look. Parents ran, children hid. So lightly
regarded was Dudley when it came to putting in points that the
Atlanta Hawks simply left him alone and covered everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley, the defensive specialist (re: hack) flexed his forearms,
rubbed his large hands together and prepared for another afternoon
of combat in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   He would not only give Ewing half the day off, he would do so
much more. Like score.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen points. Six made shots out of seven, a playoff
career-high. Two made free throws. That athletic dunk off a missed
basket over the 7-foot-2-inch Mutombo was not a a
computer-generated image.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates were pounding his chest and high-fiving their once
offensively-inept comrade. Fans rose and applauded, giving him a
standing ovation as if it were his last game at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   When he checked out of the game with 1:06 remaining, the chants
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dud-LEE! Dud-LEE!''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked about the last time people stood and chanted his
name. ``You mean, besides my wife?'' Dudley said.
</P>
<P>
   It's finally become clear that the Knicks made an awful mistake
in signing Dudley to a 4-year, $28-million contract; $68-million,
Ewing's take for four seasons, would have been more appropriate
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, of course, did not think that attempt at humor was funny.
But you got to give up for the Big Fella, who has been resting up
for Rik Smits two of the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duds played a much better game than I did,'' said Ewing, who
played 17 minutes in Game 1 and 24 minutes yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderful game,'' Ewing added. ``Duds off the bench. And both
he and Marcus and Spree gave us a big lift. This is a team game.
That's the only way you are going to win. Everybody is pulling
their own load, and if somebody gets beat, somebody is stepping in
and taking charge or getting a block. We are just doing what we
have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, making the center a viable position in the series
came at one player's expense. Mutombo simply could not find an easy
path to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not tired, but I may be a little bit frustrated,''
Mutombo said. He had finished with seven points and made only two
of four shots. And his main offensive weapon _ that elegant hook
shot in which his entire 7-2 frame is fully extended upon release
of the ball _ was rendered useless.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-11 bruiser, who refused to be backed down into the post,
would not let Mutombo take that shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I am down 0-3, I think that is the way I can
describe the way I am feeling,'' Mutombo said. ``I just have to
find a way to keep my head up and come up with a better answer. I
just can't believe myself losing three in a row. I just have to
find out how to play my own game.''
</P>
<P>
   Down a Garden corridor maybe 30 yards, Ewing's left leg was
numb. ``I was hurting, but we got the win,'' he said. ``That's the
bottom line.'' Asked how he felt, he added, ``Pain is pain.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone had said the Knicks would win a playoff game when
their franchise center scored four points and made two of 12 shots,
you would have laughed that person out of the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is clearly a different team and these are different
times, when a fuel-injected bench puts up points in a hurry and the
best center on the floor on any given day can be from Yale instead
of Georgetown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dud-LEE! Dud-LEE!''
</P>
<P>
   And the madness goes on. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
