<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-MISSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIANCE PREPARING NEXT STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO officials are preparing to meet this week to
determine their next step, amid continuing disagreements over
whether to commit troops for a ground war. A new round of bombing,
meanwhile, destroyed power systems and plunged much of Serbia into
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Sunday that the alliance is united and
that NATO is winning the war in the air. But if Clinton opts to
push the war on the ground, the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott,
said Sunday that the Senate would ``absolutely not'' approve such
an invasion.
</P>
<P>
   US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, asked Sunday
whether the war can be won without a credible threat of committing
ground troops, insisted that such talk is premature because ``we
are winning'' in the air. But she did acknowledge that the United
States on Tuesday would ask NATO for an assessment of a possible
ground war.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying is that we have asked for an update, and the
president has said that all options are on the table,'' Albright
said on CBS's ``Face The Nation.'' ``But we have also said, and I
repeat, that the air campaign is working.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO must decide soon whether to launch a ground invasion
because it would take months to assemble the necessary forces for
an attack, which officials would prefer to launch before winter
weather sets in.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is pushing for 50,000 peacekeeping troops to
be massed at the Kosovo border, which in theory are to be used only
in a ``permissive'' environment when the war is over and the
refugees return to their homes. A full-fledged invasion force,
however, might require three times as many troops and would be much
more complicated to assemble, both in political and logistical
terms. Still, even the assembly of 50,000 peacekeeping troops might
satisfy the British, who want to prepare for a ground war and may
also send a tougher message to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic about NATO's resolve in ending the war.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's supreme commander in Europe, General Wesley K. Clark,
said the alliance had ``submitted documentation to the North
Atlantic Council which calls for an enhancement to the Kosovo
Implementation Force.'' Given the havoc caused by the Yugoslav Army
and the expulsion of refugees, ``not suprisingly it will take
considerably more forces.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, NATO's air campaign continued, as warplanes for the
second straight day pounded power supply stations inside Serbia,
cutting off electricity for millions of people. NATO said its jets
had made 652 sorties, with 301 hitting their targets.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in an opinion article published Sunday in The New York
Times, said that ``Milosevic's strategy has been to outlast us by
dividing the alliance. He has failed. Instead of disunity in
Brussels, there are growing signs as disaffection in Belgrade.''
Clinton wrote that ``while I do not rule out other options,'' the
air campaign ``has broad and deep support in the alliance and
allows us to meet our objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's view was not shared in some of the other NATO
countries. British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said that the air
campaign was not enough and that NATO must prepare for a ground
war.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said he did not see a
quick end to the war and was ``very worried'' by NATO's mistaken
bombing of civilians and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in other countries, including Germany, have asked for a
cessation of the bombing in hopes of moving peace negotiations
forward. The issue is likely to come to a head when the NATO
committee meets in Brussels to assess the air war and contemplate a
ground war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also faced resistance from Lott, the Senate Republican
Leader. Speaking on ``Face The Nation,'' Lott said that the Senate
would not approve the use of US troops for a ground war. ``If
you're in the so-called permissive atmosphere where you taking the
Kosovars back into Kosovo, that would be one thing, but if you're
talking about fighting their way in there, absolutely not,'' Lott
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has repeatedly told the American people that we
would not use ground troops in a combat mode there,'' Lott
continued. ``The American people, I believe overwhelmingly, would
be opposed to that. Now, I hope that the bombing will work.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not share Albright's view that the bombing is
succeeding. ``I worry that the bombing is hurting us and our arms
control activities,'' he said. ``It's hurting our prestige around
the world, and quite frankly, these little boo-boos, where you're
hitting a KLA headquarters, where you're killing innocent citizens,
I think is hurting the image of the military, which is unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   There were these other developments in the Yugoslav conflict:
</P>
<P>
   --About 500 ethnic Albanian men, presumed to have been arrested
by the Yugoslav Army, crossed into Albania and told officials they
have been beaten severely.
</P>
<P>
   --Newsweek magazine reported that the CIA had a plan to train
Kosovar rebels to blow up buildings and cut telephone lines inside
Yugoslavia. The magazine said Clinton had approved a plan for
computer hackers to attack Milosevic's foreign bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   --Serbian deputy premier Vojislav Seselj said foreign troops
would not be allowed on Yugoslav territory, a demand that conflicts
with NATO's proposal for an international peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
   --The president of Montenegro, Milo Djukanovic, accused the
Yugoslav Army of playing into the hands of the ``Belgrade
dictatorship'' as soldiers maintained their stranglehold on the
republic's frontiers, blocking humanitarian aid. Montenegro, like
Serbia, is a republic in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   --Clark, the NATO commander, said Sunday the alliance had
``broadened and deepened'' its target list and airstrikes were not
over yet. ``The array of targets has been broadened and deepened
and so the air campaign is going to continue,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   --Montenegrin television said Sunday Serbian military
authorities had failed to get 2,000 Yugoslav Army reservists to
return to Kosovo after they had left their positions there without
orders five days ago. Reservists from Krusevac in southern Serbia
returned home from Kosovo last week after hearing of antiwar
protests at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
