u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      05-23 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST BOLDLY SEARCHES FOR AN EDITOR  
 TV NETWORKS USING STRONG-ARM TACTICS  
 THE HEAD OF FOX'S TV STUDIO IS ON A ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing's for sure: Bonnie Fuller is a woman with a lot of
chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the last two weeks, Cathleen Black, the
president of Hearst Magazines, approached Ms. Fuller, who is the
editor in chief of Glamour magazine, a Conde Nast publication, to
run Harper's Bazaar, the 132-year-old Hearst fashion monthly. The
magazine was edited by Liz Tilberis until her death last month, and
Ms. Fuller has not been long out of the Hearst fold; she left her
job as editor in chief of Cosmopolitan only last fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Black was undaunted by Ms. Fuller's new status at Conde
Nast, which is owned by Advance Publications. The two seriously
discussed the possibility of Ms. Fuller's running Harper's Bazaar,
said executives at Hearst and Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast executives said that Ms. Fuller had discussed her
possible resignation in a meeting with S.I. Newhouse Jr., the
chairman of Conde Nast, on Wednesday morning. Steven Florio, the
president and chief executive of Conde Nast, visited Ms. Fuller's
office later that day, and Florio's muffled shouts, Glamour staff
members said, could be heard from beyond the closed door of Ms.
Fuller's office.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fuller held a meeting at noon Thursday and made a brief
speech as her staff gathered to eat scones and berries from a local
caterer, Mangia. Arriving late, she compared the Hearst dalliance
to a high school flirtation with a handsome classmate. Speaking at
a cocktail party on Thursday, James Truman, Conde Nast's editorial
director, said, ``But we convinced her to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fracas, some of which was reported in The New York Post
last week, has drawn attention to an important editorial race for
Hearst. Under Ms. Tilberis, Harper's Bazaar won two National
Magazine Awards and featured some major cover models, including
Diana, princess of Wales. But it lags behind Vogue and Elle in
circulation and advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Black's choice of a new editor will affect the cultural
direction of the company at large. Does Hearst want to remodel
Harper's Bazaar as a celebrity magazine akin to In Style, or
continue to focus on fashion? Would it become more profitable if it
more closely resembled Marie Claire, a title for younger women?
</P>
<P>
   Staff members at Harper's Bazaar confirmed that Annemarie
Iverson, the fashion news director, had spoken to Ms. Black about
becoming the magazine's editor. Such a move would signal a
commitment to fashion. Ms. Fuller has also expressed interest in
running a fashion magazine, executives at Conde Nast said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Black has also approached Alexandra Shulman, the editor of
British Vogue, and Tyler Brule, the managing editor of Wallpaper, a
lifestyle and interior design magazine owned by Time Warner Inc.,
who would most likely bring more of a lifestyle slant. But Brule
said he declined.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   TV Networks Using Strong-Arm Tactics
</P>
<P>
   The deal-making became so intense inside the war rooms of the
networks assembling their prime-time lineups last week that studio
executives used terms like ``brutal,'' ``bloody'' and ``vicious''
to describe the action. They made it sound as if the process had
become the television industry's version of Verdun.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, the networks, under pressure to cut costs and
increase profits, sought concessions from program suppliers in
exchange for choice spots on their time schedules. And for the
first time, that meant not only open demands for ownership stakes
in shows, but also demands for rights to broadcast multiple runs of
shows on whatever new windows of distribution, from digital
channels to Internet sites, open up in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for multiple runs of shows came from ABC, which
dangled its best comedy time periods before producers and studio
executives, seeking both an ownership stake and numerous plays of
every episode of the show.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, ABC, which is owned by Walt Disney Co., asked two
comedies, ``Oh Grow Up'' and ``Then Came You,'' to give the network
a 10 percent stake and four plays of every episode in exchange for
the 9:30 p.m. time slot on Wednesdays after ``Drew Carey.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure tactic incensed several studio executives. The Fox
studio, owned by News Corp., flatly refused to comply on ``Then
Came You''; coincidentally or not, the show wound up on Thursday
night instead of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives at several studios, CBS played a similar
game of aggressive leverage with Sony's Columbia studio, insisting
on getting ownership in every new Columbia show that it intended to
use. (It has two.)
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that CBS threatened to hold up renewing
another Columbia show, ``Early Edition,'' if Columbia did not give
in to CBS demands for ownership in the new series. The two new
shows, ``Family Law'' and ``Ladies' Man,'' are now both co-produced
by Columbia and CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS Television, denied using
any undue pressure, saying there had been aggressive posturing on
both sides. But it was well noted in Hollywood that all six new
shows on CBS are co-produced by CBS and studios; Viacom's Paramount
and Seagram's Universal were the others that took on the network as
a partner.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   The Head of Fox's TV Studio Is on a Roll
</P>
<P>
   The big personal winner when the television networks announced
their fall shows last week was Sandy Grushow, the head of the Fox
television production studio, Twentieth Century Fox Television.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is: What does he do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   In the scorecard that television studio executives keep, Grushow
was the clear leader on the fall schedules, with Fox landing 22
shows, the best that studio has ever done. It also among the best
that any studio has ever done.
</P>
<P>
   The buildup at the Fox studio has been accomplished in a short
time. Three seasons ago, when Grushow arrived, the studio had only
six shows on network schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the current successes were already in the works then,
and one particularly important factor has been the seemingly
endless creativity of David Kelley, whose production company is
housed at Fox, a unit of News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For Grushow, the success could hardly come at a better time: He
is in the last year of his contract with the studio.
</P>
<P>
   As for what he does next, a move into the Internet is likely.
Other ideas have come up in recent weeks, including the possibility
of a newly structured position that would keep him at Fox, both
running the television studio and filling some capacity at the Fox
television network.
</P>
<P>
   If that were to happen, it would also be a first: the first time
a studio head also worked directly for a network.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
