<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
  
 REVIVING HOPES FOR MIDEAST PEACE  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, May 24:
</P>
<P>
   The election of Ehud Barak as Israel's next prime minister has
created an encouraging new atmosphere for peace talks with the
Palestinians and Syria. Though Barak's negotiating positions are
not that different from Benjamin Netanyahu's, the new leader's more
positive attitude has drawn favorable notices in much of the Arab
world. Netanyahu saw the Oslo peace agreement as an obligation to
be carried out as grudgingly as possible. Barak views carefully
negotiated treaties as ways to make Israel safer and stronger. The
Clinton administration, whose relations with Netanyahu were always
tense, now has a willing partner in efforts to complete the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's campaign was fought less over issues of peace than of
personality, the role of religion and relations between Sephardic
Jews from the Arab world and Ashkenazi Jews from Europe. Barak won
decisively. His supporters in secular center and left parties won
enough seats for a working parliamentary majority, but one
dependent on parties backed by Israel's Arab voters.
</P>
<P>
   Because any new peace agreements will require a broad consensus,
Barak sensibly seeks support from moderate religious and
conservative groups as well. But he has wisely decided first to set
firm policy guidelines on peace terms and relations between
religious and secular Israelis. Only parties accepting these
guidelines will be invited into the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Once assembled, the new government must fulfill the commitments
Israel made last fall for a further West Bank withdrawal. Then it
must move on to overdue negotiations on Jerusalem, boundaries,
water rights, return of Palestinian refugees and the future of
Jewish settlements. On many of these issues a wide gulf separates
Barak's current positions from those of the Palestinian leader,
Yasser Arafat. The hope is that with improved trust and tradeoffs
on some of the most contentious issues, differences can be
overcome. Responsibility for building that trust falls as much on
Arab leaders as on Barak. Arafat, in particular, must keep his
negotiating positions realistic and his rhetoric calming. Another
helpful gesture would be an early visit to Israel by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, which has remained on the sidelines of peace negotiations
for the past three years, now signals an interest in resuming
discussions. Israel and Syria need to talk about returning Syrian
land in the Golan Heights and assuring Israeli security as Barak
carries out his promised withdrawal from southern Lebanon. In the
past, Syrian President Hafez al-Assad has held out for settling all
issues at once, including a full return of the Golan Heights. But
if he really wants peace, he must be willing to compromise, a point
Washington should stress to Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   Though peace was not the main campaign issue, polls consistently
show that most Israelis favor agreements based on trading land for
security. Barak's government will be measured by the progress it
achieves toward this vital goal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
