<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM'S DEEP BLUE HAS A BUSINESS PLAN  
 GATEWAY'S CONCEPT: THINK PC PETTING ZOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember Deep Blue, the IBM supercomputer that beat the world
chess champion Garry Kasparov?
</P>
<P>
   Well, two years later, IBM is getting ready to give Deep
Blue-style computing a real challenge _ by trying to make a
business of it.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to announce on Monday the formation of the
Deep Computing Institute, which will have a budget of $29 million,
a staff of 120 IBM research scientists and a nine-person advisory
board.
</P>
<P>
   IBM insists that ``deep computing'' is more than a marketing
term. William Pulleyblank, director of the new institute, says
``deep computing'' is meant to describe the use of extensive
computation and sophisticated software algorithms to tackle
problems previously beyond reach.
</P>
<P>
   Deep computing research has been under way for years within
IBM's Watson Labs. ``But we think now is the time to really use
this kind of scientific modeling for business decision-making,''
said Pulleyblank, who heads the mathematical sciences program at
Watson.
</P>
<P>
   He cited precision weather forecasting as a current example of
what deep computing can do. Feeding information from the National
Weather Service, local sensors and topographical databases into
supercomputers has now made it possible to make pinpoint forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of saying there's a 40 percent chance of rain tomorrow
afternoon, you can say it will rain from 2:15 to 3:30 p.m.,''
Pulleyblank said. ``And instead of making forecasts for the
standard 30-kilometer grids, we can narrow them to one kilometer.
The storms will be in Queens, but not the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   Such precision forecasting could be of considerable value to
utilities, for example, as they plan power-plant use and daily
trading strategies in the spot market for electricity.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Deep Computing Institute also plans to announce Monday
that it will give outside software developers free access to the
source code of the company's powerful 3-D visualization software,
called Data Explorer, which is used in supercomputing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing open access to formerly proprietary source code is in
keeping with the so-called open-source movement in the software
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where open source really works is where you build a community
to accelerate innovation,'' Pulleyblank said. ``And we think this
advanced visualization application will attract that kind of
community.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR
</P>
<P>
   Gateway's Concept: Think PC Petting Zoo
</P>
<P>
   The entire personal-computer industry is moving toward the
direct-sales model, which is built on a one-to-one relationship
with customers, build-to-order manufacturing, razor-thin
inventories and higher profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Much as this might allow the manufacturers to escape having to
share profits with middlemen or share customers with the store
chains, however, many consumers still want to look at a PC, even
touch it, before they buy. A recent study conducted by
Infobeads.com, a research concern, showed that 53 percent prefer
hands-on shopping.
</P>
<P>
   What's a PC marketer to do?
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp., which along with Gateway Inc. pioneered the
direct-sales model, made a foray into the retail channel in the
early 1990s but gave up in frustration in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Gateway has also been trying its hand at retail. But
it has taken a hybrid approach, blending retail stores with
direct-marketing methods.
</P>
<P>
   And Gateway opened the doors to its first store in New York last
week, at 4 Columbus Circle, though the ``grand opening'' will be on
June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the Gateway stores as computer petting zoos.
</P>
<P>
   They typically have 15 PCs, all connected to the Internet, that
people can try out.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the machines are loaded with software and hardware
features intended for children. Others are meant for use by adults
at home, and still others are for small-business owners. Gateway
employees are around to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   The stores, called Gateway Country, are designed with a farming
motif _ tractor-style seats at each computer station, a mock grain
silo and murals of Midwestern farm scenery.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a nod to Gateway's roots in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But the stores do not have stockrooms, because they house no
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   A customer can order a computer and pay for it at the store, but
the PC is then built to order at Gateway's factory and shipped to
the customer's home within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Thus has Gateway hewed to the direct-marketing model, even while
building up its own retail chain, with 160 stores in the United
States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have thousands of square feet of warehouse space in
our stores,'' said Joseph Burke, senior vice president for business
development at Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' Burke said, ``we have avoided having the middlemen
mouths to feed that you would in traditional retail stores.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR
</P>
</TEXT>
