<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-HAITIANS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S HAITIAN COMMUNITY AWAITS BRUTALITY CASE RECKONING
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a Pentecostal church in Brooklyn on Sunday,
hundreds of Haitian men and women sang a traditional hymn in Creole
about a clarion trumpet announcing the coming of Judgment Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a dream I heard the trumpet,'' they sang, their voices
rising, their hands reaching upward, their eyes locking on the
heavens.
</P>
<P>
   But up front, in the third pew, near the preacher's squirming
grandsons, one man sat perfectly still. His face was a mask of
calm, his presence unremarkable except for the bullet resistant
vest bulging against the soft, gray fabric of his suit.
</P>
<P>
   Abner Louima clasped his hands before his chin. For him _ and
for other Haitian-Americans throughout New York City _ there is an
earthly significance to a hymn about an approaching day of
reckoning. The federal trial of four police officers accused of
attacking him and one officer accused of covering up the attack is
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Louima is riding a wave of expectation that gains momentum with
each day of damaging testimony against the police officer accused
of sodomizing him with a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes have been raised by reports that the accused officer,
Justin Volpe, is seeking a plea deal with the U.S. attorney's
office in Brooklyn to avoid a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a victorious moment for us,'' said Ketty Fleurimont, who
sat next to Louima for part of Sunday's service. ``It is not every
day that justice is served.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima declined to be interviewed, but he stood and addressed
the church in his native Creole. He asked people to continue
praying for him, and he thanked God for his life and for his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Louima is a familiar figure at the church, Croisade Evangelique
de Pecheurs D'Hommes, or Evangelical Crusade of Fishers of Men, in
East Flatbush. His uncle, the Rev. Philius Nicolas 2d, leads the
church, and his parents are longtime members.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Port-au-Prince and earned a degree in electrical
engineering before coming to the United States in 1990. He lived
unobtrusively, marrying and fathering two children, working as a
security guard. He had never been arrested until August 1997, when
he suddenly became a national symbol for charges of police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, church members have done their best to avoid talking
to him about the specifics of what happened at the 70th Precinct
station house. ``People make a special effort to treat him like you
would anyone else,'' said Ms. Fleurimont.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, again and again church members spoke of Louima in
reverent tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the same as you or me,'' said Jean-Claude Etienne,
47, who is a deacon. ``It is truly a gift from God that he is alive
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The church members said they understood the lies Louima admitted
he told _ most notably his quoting police officers as telling him
``It's Giuliani time'' during the alleged assault. ``For me, it's
such an overwhelming truth,'' said Edwidge Danticat, whose 1988
best seller, ``Breath, Eyes, Memory,'' traces a girl's journey from
Haiti to the United States. ``We're vulnerable to the police, and
in this case you cannot deny overwhelming truth, no matter what
else has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to resume Monday. Regardless of the
verdict, many in this church said they believed their prayers had
already been heard.
</P>
<P>
   They never doubted Louima's account of being attacked. But many
had refused to believe that any officer would back Louima's story
in court, which is why they were surprised to see four officers
offer vivid testimony that supported key aspects of his account.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were praying that the Lord will let them come out and tell
the truth, because you cannot lie in the presence of the Lord,''
said Elmase Archille, 45.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Karl Napoleon, 22, the officers' testimony has challenged
his perceptions of New York police officers in general, and white
New York police officers in particular. Louima is black, and all
five officers charged in the case are white. Yet the four officers
who testified against Officer Volpe are white, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pleasant surprise,'' Napoleon said.
</P>
<P>
   Louima, asked Sunday if he would like to say something to the
officers who testified on his behalf, politely replied, ``At this
time, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the church, his uncle, continued to talk about judgment
day in all its meanings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hand of God preserved the life of Abner that night,'' he
told the congregation. ``This same secret hand is acting now. I
don't think they will be able to do anything against the hand of
God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
