r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MOSS-COLUMN-TEX     05-23 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MOSS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT'S LACK OF A PLAN CONTINUES TO CONFUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will she or won't she? Her trainer will know first, but he isn't
sure yet.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday is a candidate to oppose Charismatic in the June
5 Belmont Stakes. Maybe she will. Maybe she won't. Then again,
maybe she will. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   Her trainer, Bob Baffert, pondered the possibility last week. As
usual, the news media recorded his every utterance and immediately
took them to the headlines and the airwaves. The first reports
indicated the super filly _ a winner of eight consecutive races _
was ``likely'' for the mile-and-a-half Belmont, but that wording
was toned down the next few days when Baffert seemed to waffle
about the idea.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Baffert has been doing more waffling than a
breakfast house. He was sending Excellent Meeting back to
California, and then he ran her in the Preakness. He was running
Silverbulletday in the Preakness, and then he didn't. Prime Timber
was likely for the Preakness and then he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is getting a reputation in some corners as indecisive.
Or maybe not. But actually, that has more to do with training style
than personality.
</P>
<P>
   Some trainers meticulously plot out a schedule for their stakes
horses, months in advance, that is likely to earn the most money
and accolades. These trainers can be determined to make their
horses stick to the agenda no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, on the other hand, flies by the seat of his pants. If
he could fly a plane, he would be a bush pilot with goggles and a
scarf, navigating by the terrain rather than his instruments.
</P>
<P>
   He trains his horses on intuition and feel, not according to a
predetermined schedule. Because of his loquacious nature, he thinks
out loud about races he is considering for his horses. But in the
end, everything depends on the day-to-day physical condition of the
horses, not the other way around. When Silver Charm or Real Quiet
or Silverbulletday show Baffert they are in peak form, he looks for
spots to run them. If they aren't at their best, they stay in the
barn.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert was quoted as considering Silverbulletday for the
Belmont for two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First, of course, she is very fast and could possibly win the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the outcome of the Belmont Stakes could ultimately
determine the horse of the year award.
</P>
<P>
   If Silverbulletday doesn't run, Charismatic could lock up horse
of the year by winning the Belmont and completing the first Triple
Crown sweep in 21 years. But if Charismatic is beaten,
Silverbulletday could stake a claim to the title if she continues
to run well, and especially if she is the one to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday is scheduled for a workout tomorrow at Churchill
Downs, at which time Baffert might decide. Or not. Also on the
workout list tomorrow are Charismatic and Menifee.
</P>
<P>
   Until then and maybe later, Baffert rides the fence. It sounds
as if he is leaning toward not running her, but interpreting his
thoughts can lead to misinterpretations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want her around in the fall,'' he was quoted as saying. ``I
don't want to look back and say, `What the hell was I thinking of?'
''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is in a unique position. Two years ago, he came within a
length of winning the Triple Crown with Silver Charm for owners Bob
and Beverly Lewis. Now the Lewises have another Triple Crown
candidate in Charismatic, only trained by D. Wayne Lukas. And
Baffert could be their biggest obstacle to racing history.
</P>
<P>
   If Silverbulletday runs in the Belmont, she could be the
spoiler, as Touch Gold and Victory Gallop were the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   If she doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just sit back and root for Bob,'' Baffert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
