<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITE MISSES AGAIN IN 26TH COLONIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Kite departed the MasterCard Colonial yesterday never having
won the event in 26 professional starts.
</P>
<P>
   But Kite made all 26 cuts in Fort Worth _ a tournament record _
and now heads to the Senior PGA Tour in January. He leaves Colonial
without the lifetime exemption past winners carry but could return
with a sponsor's exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the schedule is with the Senior Tour and
what tournament is opposite this one next year,'' Kite said. ``We
don't play hardly any golf courses of this caliber. If there's not
anything exceptional on the Senior Tour opposite this, I would like
to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   In 26 years, Kite, an Austin native, has never won a PGA Tour
event in Texas. His last chance comes at the Westin Texas Open in
San Antonio, scheduled for Sept. 23-26.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, Kite's last Colonial round was under par (1 under) to
finish the four days at 281, 1 over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another Colonial, another check,'' he said. ``Not much of one.
I keep finding a way to mess it up a little bit, but at least I got
to play four days.''
No. 18 proves easier
</P>
<P>
   Players completed the 1999 Colonial with a scoring average of
3.979 at the 18th hole, where a signature pecan tree guarding the
left-hand fairway was lost during an October storm. The hole ranked
13th in difficulty during the tournament, down four notches from
its traditional spot among the holes on the Colonial layout.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend scoring averages (3.873 on Saturday, 3.886
yesterday) were among the lowest single-round efforts recorded
during the 1990s. Only twice in the 1990s has Colonial's 18th hole
played easier than it did in 1999, with lower averages recorded in
1998 (3.902) and 1996 (3.974).
Early work stoppage
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended for an hour yesterday morning because of
lightning. Only 11 players were on the course when the horn
sounded, stopping play at 8:20 a.m. The golfers resumed at 9:20
a.m.
Fly like an eagle
</P>
<P>
   Colonial champion Olin Browne's victory could be traced to two
specific holes _ Nos. 1 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   With just two par-5s on Colonial's par-70 layout, taking
advantage and making birdies on those two is imperative. Browne
went one better, recording an eagle on each hole. After starting
the day at 4 under par, he went to 6 under with an eagle on No. 1,
then to 8 under with an eagle at 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two eagles, that doesn't happen to me very often in one
tournament _ much less in one day,'' Browne said.
Maturity prevails
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's victory by Olin Browne marked the 10th consecutive
year that a player over the age of 35 won the tournament. Browne
turned 40 on Saturday. The last under-35 winner of this tournament
was Ian Baker-Finch, who was 29 when he won the 1989 Colonial.
Though Baker-Finch won the 1991 British Open, the Colonial remains
his only PGA Tour victory.
</P>
<P>
   The names and ages for the last 10 Colonial champions: 1990 Ben
Crenshaw 38 1991 Tom Purtzer 39 1992 Bruce Lietzke 40 1993 Fulton
Allem 35 1994 Nick Price 37 1995 Tom Lehman 36 1996 Corey Pavin 36
1997 David Frost 37 1998 Tom Watson 48 1999 Olin Browne 40
Brooks disappointed
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks finish tied for 65th, his lowest
finish out of the 11 cuts he has made at Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play any good,'' Brooks said. ``I hit it pretty
decent maybe two of the days, but not enough to shoot a good score
early in the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was outspoken during the tournament about the course's
hard fairways, which he said produced too much bounce off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of players probably enjoy hitting a lot of short
irons,'' Brooks said. ``You can see a guy hitting only four drivers
for the day. Normally, I'd probably hit about 10 drivers. The
biggest difference is it's so bouncy.''
Cook is cooked
</P>
<P>
   After each of the first three rounds of the tournament, John
Cook was no worse than fourth on the leader board and looked poised
to win his first PGA Tour event since winning the 1998 GTE Byron
Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Early yesterday, Cook was in contention for the lead after a
birdie on the fifth hole put him at 8 under. But the Toledo, Ohio,
native faltered badly down the stretch, bogeying four of the last
nine holes to finish at 1 over for the day and 5 under for the
tournament, three shots behind winner Olin Browne.
</P>
<P>
   The bogeys came on holes Nos. 10, 12, 14 and 18. Those were the
first bogeys he had on those holes all week.
</P>
<P>
   Cook finished in a 10-way tie for 11th and took home $50,680,
bringing his 1999 earnings to $408,548.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
