<SLUG> BC-PEOPLESOFT-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ORACLE EXECUTIVE TO JOIN PEOPLESOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Peoplesoft Inc. plans to announce on Monday that
Craig Conway will become its president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   He will report to David Duffield, Peoplesoft's founder, who
continues as chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Conway, a former executive of Oracle Corp., is joining a company
under pressure. An early leader in applications for managing human
resources and other so-called enterprise resource planning, or ERP,
processes, Peoplesoft has seen its growth slow as big corporations
delay major software deployments because of possible year 2000
computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   Peoplesoft has also come under direct attack from Oracle, which
has gained share in the market in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But Conway, who is 44, said in a telephone interview that he saw
great assets and opportunities at Peoplesoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company that has enormous accumulated assets, a very
loyal customer base, and an almost fanatically loyal employee
base,'' he said. ``This is a company that should be very well
positioned to exploit future options in the e-business area. The
No. 1 challenge is prioritizing the opportunities the company has
available to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peoplesoft's shares closed unchanged on Friday at $16.1875 in
Nasdaq trading, but they are down 69 percent from their 52-week
high of $52.12.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting one-time charges, Peoplesoft reported first-quarter
earnings of $7.6 million, or 3 cents a diluted share, down from
$33.8 million, or 13 cents a share, in the period a year earlier.
Revenue rose 10 percent, to $305.4 million, from $277.7 million in
the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   One-time charges of $176.4 million related to the spin-off of
Momentum Business Applications Inc. and $4.4 million related to
layoffs resulted in a net loss for the quarter of $171.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Duffield, who is 58, said Peoplesoft's problems were part of an
industry-wide phenomenon that had also affected companies like SAP,
Baan and Oracle, but he said he thought the worst had passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect pickup before the year 2000. There is more and
more confidence on the part of CIOs that they're OK, they're going
to be fine,'' he said, referring to chief information officers.
``That opens up the opportunity to bring in the next generation of
software packages.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway was most recently president and chief executive of One
Touch Systems Inc. in San Jose, which was acquired by Hughes
Network Systems and Apollo Group. He was previously president and
chief executive of TGV Software Inc. in Santa Cruz, now part of
Cisco Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He was with Oracle for eight years, ultimately as executive vice
president for marketing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
