u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      05-23 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CONGRESSIONAL BUDGET CHAOS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, May 24:
</P>
<P>
   Congress' recent self-destructive budget maneuvering suggests no
one with a guiding philosophy is in command. Last week the
Republican leadership was pushing a budget blueprint that, if
implemented, would slice tens of billions of dollars from vital
domestic programs. At the same time, Republican lawmakers admitted
that they lacked the votes to get these cuts passed in
appropriation bills. Then, while preaching fiscal discipline, they
passed a bloated emergency spending bill that tapped the surplus
for pork-barrel spending that they say they deplore.
</P>
<P>
   In a burst of candor, Dick Armey, the combative House majority
leader, warned that the Republican budget plan would cause
``sticker shock'' among lawmakers, who apparently had no idea how
big the cuts would be when they voted in broad terms to trim the
budget. In the same vein, Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader,
admitted that many Republicans senators are already saying, ``Oh,
oh, oh, we can't live up to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey and Lott were not trying to get out of making their cuts.
They were simply trying to prepare their troops for what lies
ahead. The plan calls for $26.3 billion in domestic spending cuts,
or 11 percent below the current levels, in such programs as
education aid, housing, job training, health, environmental
protection and basic research. With an expected surplus next year
of more than $100 billion, slashing these programs makes no sense,
except to the right wing of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Hints of an incipient revolt could be seen on Capitol Hill last
week. The two top Republicans on the House and Senate
appropriations committees, Rep. Bill Young of Florida and Sen. Ted
Stevens of Alaska, made it clear they have no intention of living
within the ceilings. They disagree on which spending levels to
exceed.
</P>
<P>
   Few want to admit the obvious, that the Republican budget
strategy is unrealistic. Military spending cannot be raised, taxes
cannot be cut and arbitrary budget ceilings cannot be imposed
without eviscerating domestic programs desired by the public.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone needs to rethink the budget ceilings enacted in 1997.
These caps were put in place when a balanced budget seemed
unattainable. With large surpluses, the caps can be selectively
adjusted without danger of the federal government's plunging back
into red ink. Many lawmakers realize the need, but each party is
hoping the other will jump first.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of legislative hypocrisy is the $15 billion
emergency package to finance the war in Yugoslavia and provide
disaster relief for Central America and American farmers.
Initially, the measure was tightly confined to urgent needs. But
Congress loaded it with pet projects like subsidies for reindeer
ranchers and the Salt Lake City Olympics. The bill also got weighed
down with riders rolling back environmental and wilderness
protections, though the worst of these were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican leaders want to force colleagues to confront the
budget-cutting consequences of their own anti-government rhetoric.
But this is a needlessly damaging way for lawmakers to learn about
the difficulty of translating slogans into laws. It is not too late
for them to take a more sensible course. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
