<SLUG> BC-NJ-ABORT-STRATEGY-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION FOES DRAW NEW ENERGY FROM A STRATEGY OF POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ After years of futile attempts to impose limits
on abortions through protests at clinics and raucous demands for
constitutional changes, abortion opponents in New Jersey have
changed their strategy _ relying as much on petitions, polling and
back-room political negotiations as on blockades and bullhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have definitely gotten smarter about this,'' said Marie
Tasy, the director of public and legislative affairs for New Jersey
Right to Life, the state's largest and oldest anti-abortion
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent victory for abortion opponents came late last
week, when the Assembly Judiciary Committee released legislation
that would require parental notification before a teen-ager could
receive an abortion. Gov. Christie Whitman, in spite of her staunch
support of abortion rights, quickly endorsed the measure, all but
assuring that it would glide through the Republican-controlled
Assembly and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents have played out a similar strategy in
statehouses across the country, confounding their rivals even in
bedrock abortion-rights states like New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a national strategy and it's a state-by-state-by-state
strategy, where they know they can't win on the issue outright so
they hit around the edges and they go after the most vulnerable
first,'' said Chris Korsmo, acting director of government relations
for the Planned Parenthood Federation of America. ``They go after
those who have no voice because they are poor and need public funds
for abortions; they go after minors because they do not have the
vote; they go after those women with dire medical problems who may
need later-term abortions. But by hitting around the edges, they
are able to limit access to a very large number of people.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a well-thought-out strategy that has energized abortion
opponents, focused near-constant public attention on the issue and
helped direct the abortion debate toward common-ground issues, like
parental notification, that attract broad support among the public
and politicians alike. And in many cases it has kept supporters of
abortion rights scrambling for a counterstrategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to turn the tide and advance a proactive agenda and
not be put in the position of having to play defense all the
time,'' Ms. Korsmo said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere has that strategy been more effective in recent years
than in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have consistently shown that most New Jersey residents
back the right of a woman to have a legal abortion, a fact that
until recently had been a political brake on any serious
legislative attempts to limit or reverse abortion rights in the
state. In addition, a succession of recent governors were outspoken
supporters of abortion rights, especially Mrs. Whitman, a moderate
Republican and the state's first female governor.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, she braved the wrath of conservatives and vetoed
legislation banning a late-term procedure that opponents call
partial-birth abortion. The Legislature overrode her veto, but a
state court eventually declared the measure unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But people on both sides of the abortion fight agreed that the
debate over the late-term procedure established a beachhead that
made it easier for the parental notification legislation to advance
after a decade of defeats and made it harder for Mrs. Whitman to
continue to oppose an idea that had become common ground for a
majority of New Jersey residents.
</P>
<P>
   A Quinnipiac College Poll taken in March 1998, at the height of
the debate over the late-term abortion procedure, showed that 71
percent of New Jersey residents supported a requirement that
parental consent be given before a girl under 18 years of age could
have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents have the right to direct the upbringing and education
of their minor children, which includes being involved in any
medical issues regarding these children,'' Liz Tait, legislative
liaison for Concerned Women for America, a conservative public
policy group that opposes abortion, said after last week's
committee vote. ``Let's hope that this bill will pass quickly
through the Assembly and Senate. Being an intelligent and
reasonable person, surely Governor Whitman will have to sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to win broad support for the bill, its proponents,
including anti-abortion activists who testified before the
committee, shaped the debate as a pro-family and parental rights
issue rather than a fight over abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proponents of this bill would like to ban all abortions,''
said Lenora Lapidus, legal director for the American Civil
Liberties Union of New Jersey. ``This is not about family
communications; this is about making abortions more difficult for
whatever population they can target one at a time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of parental notification have worked since 1989 for a
law, and every year legislation has been drafted, only to die
without ever making it to a committee for consideration. That
changed this year when, over the course of several days, the
legislation was put on a fast track by Speaker Jack Collins,
catching opponents and the Whitman administration alike off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was right,'' said Assemblyman John Rooney, who
sponsored the bill with Assemblywoman Marion Crecco, a fellow
Republican. ``We had already done the partial-birth bill and laid
the groundwork.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Mrs. Whitman and her own political
predicament. The governor found herself politically exposed,
unwilling to risk rekindling conservative anger over her veto of
the partial birth legislation as she prepares to run for the U.S.
Senate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ''It has a lot to do with it,'' Rooney said. ``I think she needs
to get closer to the center on social issues, and this could help.
She is very liberal on social issues, but in this one she has moved
a little bit more to the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of abortion rights seemed slow to grasp the changing
political landscape. Even as Rooney was before the committee
introducing amendments that the Whitman administration had insisted
on to soften some of the language in his bill, abortion rights
advocates were still hoping that Mrs. Whitman, who had opposed
previous parental notification bills, would find the legislation
too unpalatable to support, in part because it did not include a
clear-cut exception for abortions in cases in which the woman's
health is at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still no health exception, and she has stood firm on
that issue,'' Ms. Lapidus, the ACLU legal director, said during a
break as she pored over Rooney's revised bill. ``The governor, in
the past, has always required that there be a health exception, and
there's no health exception.''
</P>
</TEXT>
