<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FINALES-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MELROSE PLACE,' `MAD ABOUT YOU' MAKE IT EASY TO SAY GOODBYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Melrose Place'' sadly approaches its series finale Monday
night. TV viewers everywhere shake their heads and say, ``Is (set
ital)that(end ital) still on?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but only long enough to say goodbye with a typically
tasteful installment called ``Asses to Ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   There's talk about a wedding, a funeral and closure for Heather
Locklear. There is no talk about ``MP'' being picked up by PBS for
the fall, though it could mean whole new vistas for ``Masterpiece
Theatre.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox didn't send a preview copy of the series finale for critical
perusal. So after much soul-searching and reflection about the
meaning of this excellent TV series, I've concluded: Screw it,
let's move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad About You'' is also crawling and gasping its way to the
finish line Monday night, and ``Home Improvement'' shoves off
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Don't know about you, but when I think about ``Mad About You,''
I think it's really incredibly generous of NBC to have arranged for
Paul Reiser and Helen Hunt to get $1 million an episode to be in a
dead show.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I would love to perfect a dead show myself, just so
NBC, in another brilliant business decision, could pay me $1
million a week. For $1.99 million a week, I'd eliminate the co-star
and save NBC some bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's finale is an hour long and strives for a
bittersweet mood. It also feels ... very ... weary.
</P>
<P>
   Guest star Janeane Garofalo plays the Buchmans' baby girl,
Mabel, as a young adult in the year 2021. She has just made a film
about the main influences on her life, her parents, and is talking
to us about how wacky they are.
</P>
<P>
   It also turns out that, in that same year 2021, Paul and Jamie
(Reiser and Hunt) split up, in a sort of ``Mad at You'' scenario.
Will they reunite in time for a final smooch? Is Oakland on the
east side of the bay?
</P>
<P>
   Jumping back and forth in the future, the finale in effect shows
us episodes that might have been in seasons to come.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Paul has a vasectomy, but there are second
thoughts. Or, Paul and Jamie keep trying to have the requisite sex
talk with Mabel.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, you'll feel relieved that the show didn't have all those
future seasons. Best to remember them as they were, in 1992, before
constant time slot changes, the passing seasons, overexposure, the
baby and creative fatigue got the best of a once-solid comedy.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Mad About You'' attempts bittersweet, ``Home Improvement''
keeps veering toward maudlin in its own 90-minute series finale
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't enough energy left even to be maudlin. Mainly
it's a clips show _ all those choice comedy bits from seasons past
_ that eventually turns into an outtakes fest. Now that is truly
tired.
</P>
<P>
   The old clips and outtakes are wrapped around a thinly realized
story line involving the end of ``Tool Time,'' the marriage of Al
(Richard Karn) and the Taylors' move from Detroit to a new life in
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   A confession. Back in 1991, I saw little hope for a series based
on Tim Allen's stand-up act. It seemed all simian grunts and power
tools, hardly a foundation for a hit show. What happens in the
third week?
</P>
<P>
   But Allen, Patricia Richardson and the show's producers had
their fingers on something real about humdrum middle American life.
</P>
<P>
   It shows in ``Home Improvement's'' astonishing ratings record.
It was TV's most popular show in the 1993-94 season, when it peaked
with a 20.4 rating average. Through April, its average this season
was exactly half of that, 10.2.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, it also shows in Tuesday night's clips from past
years. Amid the pratfalls and kitchen explosions and sex jokes,
there's something meaty and, yes, even touching about the life of a
family and the bond between a husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, at least, ``Home Improvement'' dies old and still
makes an attractive corpse.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's finale seems to go through several concluding stages
before we see the teary cast members taking their final bows in
front of the show's studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's then, finally, that ``Home Improvement'' dishes out its
final gimmick. That full, unconcealed face belongs to Earl Hindman,
otherwise known as the Taylors' philosophical neighbor, Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
