<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE COMMISSION AIMS TO ENSURE FREE LIBRARY SERVICE FOR
ALL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON STATION, N.Y. _ In recent weeks, a public commission
has been on the road, studying the future of New York's libraries
and looking for ways to ensure that all state residents have free
access to their services.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-member commission, appointed last year, by the Board of
Regents, has held public hearings in Buffalo, where library users
fear that a regionalization plan will shut down their small
community branches; in Syracuse and Brooklyn, where the panel heard
about the shortage of elementary school librarians; and, most
recently, here on Long Island, where the practice of charging fees
for out-of-towners has run afoul of state law.
</P>
<P>
   A common thread at the hearings has been the need to ensure free
access to basic library services, something that 1.3 million New
Yorkers still do not have, education officials say. Nor do most
elementary schools in the state have a librarian, they say, let
alone a complete library.
</P>
<P>
   And while most of the state's 770 public library systems meet
basic standards, many are inadequately prepared for the growing
information needs of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the middle of an information glut, but very few
people have access to it or know how to discern what is viable
information and how to apply it to their daily lives,'' said Martin
Gomez, director of the Brooklyn Public Library and a co-chairman of
the panel, formally known as the New York state Board of Regents
Commission on Library Services.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has until next spring to prepare a report
recommending how to provide a high level of library service to all
New Yorkers. ``Free access to a library, in my view, is an American
right,'' said Frank J. Macchiarola, a commission member from
Brooklyn. ``And it's our job to help make certain this becomes a
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure how much it would cost to meet that goal.
``I know that there is no such thing as a free library, just as
there is no free lunch,'' Macchiarola said at last week's hearing
here at the Huntington Townhouse. ``Such service costs money. But
we should be able to find creative ways to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of free access is of particular concern on Long
Island. Most librarians here agree in principle with the state
librarian, Janet Welch, also a commission member, that all New
Yorkers should have free access. But directors of the 98 public
libraries in Nassau and Suffolk Counties say they cannot afford to
comply.
</P>
<P>
   They told the commission that they were bound by their local
charters to serve only the residents of their districts, who pay
property taxes to support a library. To accommodate residents of
nearby towns, though, they have decided that they must charge a
user fee, in some places as much as $300 a family.
</P>
<P>
   Such fees, however, were banned when the state established
public library guidelines 50 years ago. In December, the Regents
warned libraries throughout the state that they would start
enforcing the ban in January.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Regents create a new plan for libraries based on the
commission's coming report, Ms. Welch said, they have asked that
librarians cut out some of their more expensive services for
nonresidents, like the heavily attended story-telling hours or
borrowing best-selling books and videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Welch said the commission was awaiting results of a survey
of state residents on their library use and priorities and are
studying practices in other states. In Georgia, for example,
revenue from a state lottery is designated for providing all
residents free libraries and an electronic research data base, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's final hearing will be held June 3 at the State
University of New York at Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
