<HEADLINE>
YANKS FIND MAGIC IN THE 9TH AND A VICTORY IN THE 10TH
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Magical. Joe Torre employed the word before Sunday's
game to describe the 1996 season, when the New York Yankees were
not as invincible in winning the World Series as they were during
the phenomenal 1998 season. It was an appropriate day to make the
reference.
</P>
<P>
   Something magical happened at Comiskey Park Sunday as the
Yankees completed an improbable comeback in their 8-7 victory over
the White Sox in 10 innings. It was the type of crazy triumph that
reminded the Yankees of 1996 and 1998 and made them hope that there
is more magic in 1999. Maybe Sunday was the start. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Simas balked in the tying run during a four-run ninth
inning and accused Derek Jeter of shouting ``balk'' from third
base, Chad Curtis' home run off Simas in the 10th vaulted the
Yankees to their third victory in four games. The late-inning magic
did not totally erase the Yankees' earlier sloppiness on a soggy
afternoon, but they headed home for a series with the first-place
Boston Red Sox beginning Monday with the feeling that something was
brewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of win that can get a team going,'' David Cone
said. ``We've been waiting for a win like that all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The most bizarre action unfolded after the Yankees had already
scored three runs in the ninth, two on Bernie Williams' single, to
trim their deficit to 7-6 with one out and runners on first and
third. Jeter crept off third, hoping that the Yankees would find a
way to nudge him 90 feet for the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   They did not have to. The third base umpire, Tim Welke, called a
balk on Simas, infuriating the pitcher. Simas rumbled off the mound
and pointed at Jeter, accusing him of screaming ``balk'' before
Welke did.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter and Welke said Jeter had not yelled anything. Willie
Randolph, the third-base coach, conceded that he called out for a
balk but was not sure if he had done so before Welke. Welke said he
had called the balk first.
</P>
<P>
   It would not have mattered. Jeter can say whatever he wants.
</P>
<P>
   After touching home plate, Jeter snapped at Simas and both teams
streamed onto the field. There was verbal sparring and players
holding each other, but no punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You made me balk,''' Jeter said. ``I didn't
understand how I could make him balk. I wasn't even looking at the
guy. The ump called balk and I clapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Jerry Manuel, the White Sox manager, said Welke had told
him that he called the balk first.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Simas was not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people probably think I'm crazy, but I heard somebody
other than the ump yell,'' Simas said. ``After I broke my hands, I
asked the ump why he called a balk and then he called a balk. That
was a bush play.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how Simas felt, the Yankees were relieved. Cone
had failed to hold a 3-0 lead and Jeff Nelson had been bruised for
three runs in the eighth to give Chicago a 7-3 lead, and it looked
like the Yankees would lose their second straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this was the slap in the face we needed,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Comebacks can make horrible days seem pristine. The ninth began
with walks to Curtis and Shane Spencer before Chuck Knoblauch, who
was 5 for his last 60, punched a single to right to fill the bases.
With Jeter batting, Simas unleashed a wild pitch to slice the
deficit to 7-4. Jeter finished a marvelous 13-pitch at-bat by
taking a 3-2 pitch to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   After Darrin Jackson made a diving catch on Paul O'Neill's fly
ball in left, Williams singled in two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the wackiness with Simas. And in the following inning,
Curtis, who was the first player onto the field to defend Jeter and
who had not homered since April 27, belted a blast to center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the other team is yelling and pointing, winning the game
is the best thing you can do,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   When Cone breezed into the second inning with a 3-0 edge, the
lead seemed safe because he started the game with the best earned
run average in the major leagues at 1.69 and had given up
consecutive hits twice in 531/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   But, by the time an aggravating second inning had ended, the
White Sox had scored four runs on three well-placed singles, one
booming triple, a batter nicked in the folds of his jersey and a
groundout. Chicago had help from Knoblauch, who dived for two
grounders and failed to snare what turned into singles.
</P>
<P>
   Cone fired his glove into the dugout after the second inning and
slammed the ball on the mound after rain delayed the game a second
time in the sixth. Rain had also delayed the start.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Yankees rallied, everything seemed a little
brighter. For two innings and one game, it was magical again in
Yankeeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to see us make a run and I just wanted get that
feeling,'' Cone said. ``Just because we were behind, we weren't
dead.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
