<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOCUSING ON THE GAME, NOT A COACH'S ANXIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The modest office Jeff Van Gundy shares with the
Rangers' coach, John Muckler, has only a television, a telephone
and a desk. There is no nameplate on the door. The room has none of
the warmth of the players' domain across the hall. Its walls are
bare, except for a color photo of Mark Messier scoring in the 1994
hockey finals against the Vancouver Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy's will to win _ man!'' Van Gundy said of Messier,
dodging the obvious question of why he had added no personal
touches, in the manner of a man renting a hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty tough guy,'' Van Gundy said of Messier, firm with his
stonewall. The game, as defined by the ever-stressed Knicks' coach,
is not about ornaments, and certainly not a comfort zone. Forget
Pat Riley. Van Gundy's real mentor was his father, Bill, a grizzled
lifer low on the ladder, at places like Genesee Community College
and Brockport State. ``He's a coach,'' Van Gundy said, embellishing
the statement as if he were sitting at the bar. ``He drove the van,
mopped the floors. He never had a cushy job like I have, where the
biggest worry is the seven steps you take from the bus to the
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that easy, professional coaching, and especially when
the mailing address is Madison Square Garden. That's why Bill Van
Gundy was standing in the runway Sunday, waiting to give his son a
hug, for more than a 90-78 Game 3 victory over Atlanta, and a 3-0
Eastern Conference semifinal series lead over the hopelessly
outmanned Hawks. Even tough little guys like Jeff Van Gundy need
emotional support when tales of taller coaches like Phil Jackson
are being told, even as Van Gundy's team marches on relentlessly
toward Indianapolis and the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   So Van Gundy sat in his spartan space Sunday, offering the bare
minimum on the reports that Dave Checketts, the Garden president,
had weeks ago contacted or met with Jackson about becoming coach of
the Knicks. That is not what Checketts told him, Van Gundy said,
dangling the draw-your-own-conclusion of the corporate white lie,
before insisting that it wouldn't be a distraction toward the
series-ending issue of Monday night's fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   His father had taught him to neglect his troubles; think about
the next game. ``Management owns the team,'' said Bill Van Gundy,
63, a survivor of brain tumors, heart attacks and one job
dismissal. ``It has a right to do what it wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What Checketts apparently wanted to do was find out what Jackson
was thinking, and why wouldn't he? At the time, Checketts was
staring into the bottom-line abyss of not making the playoffs or
likely elimination in the first round. He has those television
moguls to please, his own job to save. And this is the business of
professional sports, sensing the collapse of your house and lining
up another architect to rebuild it.
</P>
<P>
   Even Van Gundy admitted that the Knicks _ from the time
Checketts served Ernie Grunfeld his ``reassignment'' papers along
with his last meal _ had reversed field and qualified for the
post-season ``in the nick of time.'' Then Miami happened. Then
Lenny Wilkens showed up in the second round with his playoff junior
varsity. And here are the Knicks, reinventing themselves in
mid-playoff march, perhaps in the process of making an irrelevancy
of whatever happened three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, Chris Dudley couldn't get off the bench.
Sunday, he pretty much gave the struggling Patrick Ewing the
afternoon off and with one symbolic play brought the conference
semifinal to a screeching and unofficial halt. With about nine
minutes left in the fourth quarter, Dudley ball-faked Dikembe
Mutombo, two-time defensive player of the year, and laid the ball
in, off glass, albeit with the grace of a coin being jammed through
a slot.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a 15-point lead against a team incapable of
catching up. The other point was that Dudley, the Knicks' $28
million all-thumbs backup center, was in the process of outscoring
Mutombo, Atlanta's $55 million franchise foundation, 14-7. The
Knicks' bench again buried Atlanta's, this time by 46-22. There was
a second-quarter span when Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby
accounted for 16 of 18 points. The 18 rebounds and 5 blocked shots
by Dudley and Camby had Wilkens raving about them and mumbling to
himself. Perhaps this all looks very different against the Pacers,
but right now, the Knicks have a bench to match up with Larry
Bird's.
</P>
<P>
   Remember early this season when Van Gundy stubbornly resisted
using his long and athletic reserves who were practically begging
to play? Grunfeld, the doomed general manager, didn't help when he
handed his coach new players for a 50-game sprint and never offered
any assurances to Van Gundy that he wouldn't be a scapegoat if the
chemistry didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy embarked on his own survival course, pushing an
out-of-shape Ewing for too many minutes, riding his trusted horse,
until Big Fella broke down. The irony was that Grunfeld was the
subsequent victim of the resulting chaos of conversion, from the
Knicks as Ewing's team to the one now serving as a tribute to
Grunfeld's vision. The moral of the story is that there is more to
managing a team than picking its players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your boss tells you you're going to be there, is your job
going to be easier?'' Bill Van Gundy said to the question of what
should happen next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's your answer,'' the coach's father said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he slipped into the office where his son was waiting,
mostly for Dave Checketts to come tell him what he deserves to
hear. The room will be half his next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
