</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 A SERGEANT'S TESTIMONY TURNS A TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in the trial of the Abner Louima case, Marvyn Kornberg _
the pugnacious, streetwise defense lawyer _ exuded the brash
confidence of someone who had everything under control. He assured
reporters that his client, Officer Justin Volpe, would be cleared
of charges of torturing Louima. Louima's internal injuries,
Kornberg said, could have been the result of consensual sex with
another man, and DNA tests would show that this was possible. Just
wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Volpe, the officer's father, summed up the defense
attitude when he said with a wink: ``You're at the beginning of the
movie. Let the movie play.''
</P>
<P>
   But the movie had a stunning plot shift last week, after a
witness gave devastating surprise testimony against Volpe. People
who know Kornberg, a veteran lawyer with a reputation for thorough
preparation, were left wondering how he could have been caught by
surprise on something so damaging, or whether the testimony had
really been a surprise to him.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, Sgt. Kenneth Wernick, said in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn that several hours after prosecutors say Volpe tortured
Louima with a stick in a restroom at a Brooklyn police station,
Volpe boasted that he had thrust a stick ``five or six inches''
into a prisoner's rectum. Wernick said that Volpe then showed the
stick to him and to another officer, Michael Schoer.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg declined to cross-examine Wernick, who held the rank of
officer at time of the alleged brutalization. Kornberg later told
reporters: ``We've changed our position; it's that simple. We've
changed the trial tactic in the case. You'll see why when we finish
the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg declined to say when he had first learned that Wernick
would be testifying as he did. But some people close to the case
said Kornberg learned this only last Monday night, when he received
the documents that prosecutors are obliged to turn over to defense
lawyers, documents that contain material like the witnesses'
statements to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   People who have closely followed the case said they did not
expect Wernick's testimony, and lawyers for the three other
officers and a sergeant on trial said they learned of it only a day
or two before.
</P>
<P>
   If Kornberg did indeed learn of Wernick's coming testimony last
Monday, only two days before he testified, then it could mean one
of several things. One is that the sergeant made up the statements
he had attributed to Volpe, and that Schoer also lied when he had
confirmed that Volpe had shown him the stick and had described a
stain on it as human feces. Another possibility is that Volpe lied
to his own lawyer, something defendants have been known to do.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could mean that Volpe, whom another witness described as
having been in an agitated state on the morning that Louima was
reportedly brutalized _ the officer had been punched in the face in
the street melee in which Louima was arrested _ could have simply
forgotten that he had boasted to Wernick of having used the stick
on Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe has rigidly refrained from discussing the case with
reporters, and the usually voluble Kornberg repeated ``no comment''
when asked what his client had told him about Wernick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
