<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-SOFTBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ARE OKLAHOMA BOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA might not want to admit this, but Sunday's
events at the NCAA softball regional at Westwood were supposed to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Only third baseman Julie Adams said anything to that effect:
``We came into this season to do a job, and part of it is done.''
</P>
<P>
   She referred to the Bruins' 12-5 regional final victory over
second-seeded Missouri that sent top-seeded UCLA (59-6) into the
College World Series for the 19th time (three AIAW, 16 NCAA). The
Bruins will seek their ninth national championship when they open
Thursday in Oklahoma City against DePaul.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Adams could speak a bit freely after being named the
tournament's Most Outstanding Player. She homered four times and
drove in 13 runs, best among the six teams competing.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing coaches freely agreed with her. One by one, they
trudged into postgame press conferences and hailed the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri was the last one. In walked Missouri coach Jay Miller,
following the coaches from Alabama, Creighton and Minnesota, and
said basically the same things: UCLA is that good and deserves to
be a favorite to win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, they will win it all,'' Miller declared.
``I'm surprised anyone's given them any trouble. Look at the lineup
they have. They should have no problem. They're just loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   So loaded that:
</P>
<P>
   _Five Bruins made the 12-member All-Regional team.
</P>
<P>
   _The offense outscored the opposition 38-5.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, nine players collected hits, led by Christie
Ambrosi's 3 for 4. Ten different players scored runs and six drove
in runs, led by first baseman Julie Marshall's three. In addition,
all-tournament Stacey Nuveman hit her nation-leading 31st home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be careful I don't slip up,'' said all-tournament
pitcher Missouri pitcher Jennifer Falk (27-13), who gave up 13 hits
and eight earned runs in 62/3 innings. ``They hit the ball, and I
wish them the best of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   _Adams won Most Outstanding Player despite getting all four home
runs and 11 of her 13 RBI in the first two games; she went 0 for 3
Saturday and 2 for 3 with two RBI against the Tigers (41-21).
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they can generate offense, it's tough to beat them,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   _UCLA came within one out of allowing no runs in the tournament
and gave up only one earned run in 28 innings. All-tournament
pitcher Courtney Dale (31-1) won three games. On Sunday, Dale gave
up seven hits with five strikeouts and two hit-batsmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really pleased with the way this UCLA team played this
week,'' coach Sue Enquist said. ``We had lots of tests this
weekend. You want players to experience pressure, and that's going
to help us in the College World Series. We've had pressure. We've
had adversity, and we've done an excellent job of sticking to our
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The only pressure UCLA encountered Sunday came in the later
innings. The Bruins led 9-0 and were one out away from stopping the
game after six when Dale gave up a three-run home run to Erin
Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Towards the end, I got the ball up in the strike zone and it
was making a difference,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So what did UCLA do? It came out in the seventh (the Bruins were
the visitors) and batted around, scoring three more times.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Sunday's outcome wasn't a surprise, because UCLA had
beaten Missouri 9-0 this season in the Fresno State tournament.
Now, the Bruins move on to Oklahoma City, where five Pacific-10
teams await. UCLA won the conference, making them the favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Enquist didn't want to hear about the preordained aspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like (it) at all, and my players don't think that
way,'' she said. ``This UCLA team has too much respect for the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the opposing coaches was happy to say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless they play a bad game and someone plays out of their
heads, they won't have a problem,'' Miller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
