<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENCE-ENTERTAINMEN     05-23 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-ENTERTAINMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
STOPPING VIOLENCE BY SUING THE MEDIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   By KIM COBB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jack Thompson has been spoiling for a fight with the
entertainment industry for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami-area lawyer recalls vividly how he stood before the
Time Warner shareholders meeting in 1992 to rail against the
message in rapper Ice Tea's song Cop Killer. He was acting as
torch-bearer for Oliver North's Freedom Alliance, and he was
clearly in unfriendly territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if Time Warner and the rest of the entertainment
industry does not stop dumping its corrosive, harmful entertainment
into the American culture, then eventually the parents of children
harmed by that would successfully turn around and sue for
damages,'' Thompson said. ``The whole hall was laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ain't laughing now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Littleton, Colo., high school massacre, following several
other horrible instances of school violence, is feeding a clamor
for the courts to put a cork in the stream of violent entertainment
in popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of mostly failed litigation seeking to hold
accountable everyone from rap musicians to movie producers, some
see a possible shift in society that could force changes in the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent appellate court decisions already had entertainment
lawyers worrying about the ``chilling effect'' on the First
Amendment rights which have traditionally protected their industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court refused to block civil actions brought by
surviving family members of crime victims in both a Louisiana
lawsuit against the producers of the movie Natural Born Killers and
in a Maryland suit against publishers of a book titled Hit Man: A
Technical Manual for Independent Contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in both cases are relying on an exception to free
speech protection spelled out by the Supreme Court in 1969. The
court ruled that speech is not protected if it ``incites imminent
lawless activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a week before the April 23 Littleton shootings, the parents
of three children murdered in December 1997 by a classmate in
Paducah, Ky., filed suit against two Internet pornography sites,
the producers of several computer games and the makers and
distributors of the film The Basketball Diaries.
</P>
<P>
   Those forms of entertainment, they argued, made violence
pleasurable and attractive to shooter Michael Carneal, and taught
him to kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd filed it the day of (the Littleton shootings), we'd be
called ambulance chasers,'' said attorney Thompson. ``Now some
people are calling us prophets.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson wasn't alone in finding parallels between the Colorado
and Kentucky shootings. Like the Paducah shooter, the two boys who
fired on their classmates in Littleton and then killed themselves
were described as children who didn't fit in, and who immersed
themselves in computer games such as Doom and Quake, where killing
multiple opponents is a main objective.
</P>
<P>
   From legislated gun control to lawsuits directed against the
entertainment industry, the rush to assign blame for the school
shootings raises constitutional questions.
</P>
<P>
   Is the First Amendment guarantee of free speech at any cost
threatened if society thinks the cost is too high? And will the
courts respond, as they did in tobacco litigation, if legislative
leaders or industry will not?
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugsley, a professor at Los Angeles' Southwestern
University School of Law, said the current climate of fear could
lead to a lawsuit that succeeds in holding a video game or movie
producer liable at some level for a violent incident such as a
school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I do think that's a significant development,'' Pugsley
said. ``If you eventually get a verdict against one of these
defendants and it goes up on appeal, who knows what could happen?
And you could have a further incursion into the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Pugsley said he thinks the First Amendment values that protect
free expression are more important than the immediate problem of
the school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying in any way to diminish the magnitude of loss
these individuals have suffered,'' he said, but, ``there's a lot of
copycatting going on. With the grace of God, somewhere, somehow
this will stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson volunteered himself to the Paducah parents, and said he
hopes to see similar lawsuits. The attorney said he was encouraged
when the Supreme Court allowed the Louisiana Natural Born Killers
case to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Supreme Court really said was ... the entertainment
industry is not the sacred cow of the American enterprise system.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the idea that a video game is First Amendment
speech ``doesn't even pass the giggle test.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a murder simulator. It's a dangerous toy,'' he said.
``Games, when they cause harm ... give rise to damages that are
compensable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Carneal, who had never handled a handgun before, walks in (to
his Paducah high school) and, from a distance, discharges eight of
nine bullets,'' Thompson said. ``All eight hit their mark. They're
all potential kill shots. It's marksmanship off the scale.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney is leaning heavily on the research of
soldier-turned-psychologist David Grossman, a professor of military
science at Arkansas State University who argues that video games
that reward children for shooting faster than they can think are no
different that the reflex training the military uses to get
soldiers past their normal aversion to killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experts tell us that when you discharge a gun, you empty it
into the initial target until your target drops,'' Thompson said.
``What he did was he discharged his gun, moved to the next target
and (immediately) pulled the trigger. Where did he learn that? In
video games where you have X amount of time and X number of shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The video games taught him to be a killer,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney, who refers to himself as a ``culture warrior,''
said the Paducah lawsuit will lean heavily on a psychological
profile of Carneal commissioned by his parents and entered into
evidence in his criminal trial, which spelled out three categories
of entertainment that had profoundly influenced him.
</P>
<P>
   The psychologist cited the movie The Basketball Diaries, in
which a student played by Leonardo DiCaprio fantasizes about
carrying out a classroom massacre, sexually violent pornography he
pulled off the Internet and violent video games such as Doom and
Quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be able to prove that the video game industry
... is addictive,'' Thompson said, echoing some of the strategy
which proved successful in recent litigation against the tobacco
industry . ``We believe we can show they do focus groups, physical
testing on these kids to see how high their heart rates go.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are in a corporate boardroom and you target other
people's children with a program, and you know there are kids at
risk and you know from your own in-house studies you've trained
kids to be killers, you're responsible for that,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   James Hornstein, an entertainment lawyer in Los Angeles who
represents Twentieth Century-Fox Film Corporation and its
affiliated businesses, said there's a big difference between the
tobacco litigation and lawsuits against the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's massive intervening causes between the viewing of a
movie and the killing of innocent victims,'' Hornstein said.
``Before a person has to go out and kill, they have to have a
short-circuit somewhere in the process, and they still have to have
access to a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that somebody sees a movie and as a result of their
upbringing or mental illness, goes out on a crime spree, doesn't
make the movie responsible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the tobacco situation, the cause of lung cancer is the
tobacco being inhaled,'' Hornstein said. ``The tobacco
manufacturers' product is doing the killing, doing the harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornstein predicts that the Paducah suit will not get far once
the defendants challenge the notion that there was intent to harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're claiming only negligence, it's not enough to charge
a free speech defendant with liability,'' Hornstein said. ``And
that's very well settled law, and I see nothing to say that law is
likely to change.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pugsley said that, even as a staunch defender of First
Amendment protections, he's intrigued by the arguments about
physiological responses that can be measured while children watch a
violent movie or play a violent game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the situation where a child voluntarily exposes
himself to a product consumer-tested to arouse the greatest level
of testosterone and desensitizes a person to the effects of what
they're doing, because its only a game? And it's sole content is
battering and maiming virtual human beings? It seems to me there's
the opening wedge of an argument there,'' Pugsley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0248 </DOCNO>
