<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUNNED HAWKS STARING AT SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Atlanta Hawks sat in the visitors' locker room at
Madison Square Garden Sunday looking like Mike Tyson after his
stunning loss to Buster Douglas. There were no bruises or black
eyes, but the lifeless expressions that accompany shock were there
in abundance.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks, after all, entered their second-round series against
the Knicks with unwavering faith. They had won 9 of their last 11
regular-season games to storm into the playoffs as the
fourth-seeded team in the Eastern Conference, while the
eighth-seeded Knicks backed in like shy teen-agers. So confident
were these Hawks that their center, Dikembe Mutombo, guaranteed
victory over the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking was that Michael Jordan was gone, that no team in
the East was dominant, that this was their chance to finally seize
the conference title. Instead, reality smacked Atlanta in the face
like one of Mutombo's elbows, exposing it for what it really is _ a
team that cannot shoot straight.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by three games to none and on the verge of being swept
after Sunday's 90-78 loss, the Hawks attributed their predicament
to their lack of ball movement and inability to make shots. They
know they have missed open 3-pointers, midrange jumpers, floaters
in the lane and layups while shooting 32.2 percent for the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to win a series shooting in the low 30s,'' Hawks
coach Lenny Wilkens said after his team made just 27 of 87 shots
(31 percent) Sunday. ``They're real disappointed because they feel
they are a better team, but when you don't shoot the ball well.
...''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks started Sunday's game shooting 38 percent to trail by
only 52-46 at the half. Steve Smith, the high-scoring shooting
guard, was wiping away the memory of his 2-for-17 performance in
Game 2 by posting 17 points, and Grant Long scored a surprising 14.
But Smith, plagued by foul trouble, went scoreless in the second
half, missing all six of his shots, and Long scored just three more
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started shooting desperation shots instead of being in the
flow, because I was trying to get it back and trying to put it on
my shoulders,'' said Smith, who is shooting 28 percent in the
series. ``I had to take the scoring burden and rush shots
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   It became apparent early in the third quarter, when the Hawks
missed their first nine shots, that they did not have the scoring
punch to challenge. They shot 4 for 20 in the third quarter and 4
for 18 in the fourth in tallying the embarrassing shooting figure
of 21 percent in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Player after player _ from Mutombo, who went 2 for 7, to Mookie
Blaylock, who missed 10 of his 15 attempts _ blamed the Hawks'
imminent elimination on poor shooting and a lack of execution on
offense. They spoke as if they were dumbfounded by their
inaccuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're hurting ourselves more than anything,'' Blaylock
said. ``Our offense wasn't clicking. We'd pass the ball and watch
instead of pass the ball and move. We're in a little funk. It's
like we're going through the motions and the flow isn't there. It's
a frustrating thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth, however, is that Atlanta rarely shoots or moves the
ball well. While 32 percent shooting is exceptionally poor, the
Hawks have never been mistaken for marksmen. In fact, they were
27th in the 29-team league in shooting this season, at 40.9
percent. And that was with the now-injured starters Alan Henderson
and LaPhonso Ellis in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding their lack of ball movement, the Hawks again spoke as
if they have thrown the ball around the horn all year. But the
terribly low total of 10 assists they had Sunday was not that far
out of the ordinary. They had just 13 assists in Game 1 when they
scored 92 points, and only seven in Game 2. On the season, the
Hawks' average of 15.64 assists per game was last in the NBA, more
than five assists below the league average.
</P>
<P>
   Add the Knicks' energized defense to the equation and you get a
lopsided series that has the humbled Hawks wondering what clocked
them. Mutombo cannot believe the Hawks are about to make their
exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really surprised,'' Mutombo said. ``That's why this is so
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo sounded determined to avoid being swept, saying that it
had never happened in his seven-year career. Apparently, he forgot
that San Antonio ousted him and his Denver Nuggets teammates in
three games in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
