<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8222 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THRIFT-EXEC-THREETAKE     05-23 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THRIFT-EXEC-THREETAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRISONED EXECUTIVE BLAMES CONGRESS FOR S&AMP;L CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the untold stories of the savings and loan debacle will
come to a close today when prison doors open and a graying
56-year-old man walks out, free at last.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Ed Morris. He was sentenced to 46 months in prison
for encouraging the public to invest in his St. Louis-area S&AMP;L that
later went kerplunk. Morris says he is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of former S&AMP;L executives _ including Morris _ are convinced
that Congress lost its collective mind a decade ago and unleashed a
reign of terror on the S&AMP;L industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some S&AMP;Ls in the late 1980s and early '90s were infested
with crooks and needed to be weeded out. But while the press was
busy covering the few crooks, many S&AMP;L managers complain, it
overlooked the much bigger story: the annihilation of decent but
struggling S&AMP;Ls.
</P>
<P>
   They say hundreds of legitimate S&AMP;Ls were exterminated, their
owners wiped out and more than a few packed off to prison
undeservedly. Depositors were insured for up to $100,000 each, but
S&AMP;L owners lost their money.
</P>
<P>
   And many in this quiet S&AMP;L underground say their poster child is
Ed Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great admiration for him _ a true hero,'' said Ernest
Fleischer, something of a poster child himself since he has pursued
a multiyear, multipronged legal campaign against the government.
Fleischer wants the government to repay him for Franklin Savings
Association, once Kansas' biggest financial institution, which he
contends was wrongly seized in 1990 and then obliterated by
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, a bookish and bespectacled Wharton School MBA, doesn't
look like an underground leader. But when he was under legal attack
in the early 1990s, he organized ``May Day'' conferences in which
kindred spirits gathered to share horror stories.
</P>
<P>
   And Morris had a sharp pen. He turned out a lively newsletter
called /{Regulatory Watchdog/} that railed against Congress for
tax-code tinkering that undermined real estate and whacked
real-estate lenders such as S&AMP;Ls. The newsletter also skewered
regulators for ``abuse'' when they enforced the new S&AMP;L bailout
rules.
</P>
<P>
   No one accused Morris of stealing money from his S&AMP;L. In fact,
he lost money when it failed, and he had to sell his house to pay
mounting legal bills. Morris' ex-wife, Ann Morris, said, ``Ed is
one of the most honest and good people I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, not all are sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not enough time!'' said Mabel Dickson upon learning
that Morris is to be released from prison. The Cahokia, Ill.,
retiree said her life savings of $229,000 was vaporized in Morris'
S&AMP;L, and Dickson said she had paced the floor at night for more
than 46 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sleep when everything's gone,'' she said. (Dickson
and other investors sued and later recouped more than half their
investment when the government and some of the S&AMP;L's executives
turned over some money.)
</P>
<P>
   And the prosecutor in the main case against Morris, Bruce
Reppert, pointed out that if Morris thought he was innocent, he
could have gotten his side of the story across to the grand jury.
Reppert said he encouraged Morris to testify, have others testify
for him or submit something in writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed declined to do any of the three,'' Reppert said. ``So we
went ahead and indicted him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is evidence to support Morris' argument that the
so-called S&AMP;L bailout wrongly sent some S&AMP;L managers to prison.
Some academics now say that fraud accounted for little _ perhaps 3
percent to 7 percent _ of the $150 billion or so that taxpayers
spent to repay depositors and on other expenses of the S&AMP;L crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A national commission report to the president and Congress said
fraud was significant but accounted for 10 percent to 15 percent of
the $150 billion in losses. Still, it concluded, that the problem
was mainly caused by a series of government missteps and ``fraud
was not the cause of the S&AMP;L debacle.''
</P>
<P>
   If fraud was a small part of the S&AMP;L crisis, why were thousands
of S&AMP;L managers prosecuted? Morris thinks many were accused
unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as simple as this: The people who caused the crisis _ the
U.S. Congress _ decided to take the glare off themselves by making
crooks out of all of us,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Fulwider, spokesman for the Office of Thrift Supervision,
the regulator for thrifts, who was in a similar capacity during the
S&AMP;L bailout, denied that thrift managers were jailed casually and
said that fraud and abuse needed to be cleaned up from the S&AMP;L
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   What Morris knew about savings and loans associations in the
early 1980s wouldn't have filled a passbook.
</P>
<P>
   He had gotten familiar with a suburban St. Louis savings bank
called Germania Bank when Morris, an investment banker in St.
Louis, helped Germania sell stock to the public for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, he was brought aboard Germania as a kind of temporary
chief executive officer. With his investment banking expertise,
Morris could help Germania raise fresh money.
</P>
<P>
   Germania quickly started selling new securities. But Morris saw
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stepped back and said, `I'm real worried about loan-loss
reserves here,' &UR; '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
