<DOCNO> NYT19990523.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THRIFT-EXEC-3RDTAKE-K     05-23 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THRIFT-EXEC-3RDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRISONED EXECUTIVE BLAMES CONGRESS FOR S&AMP;L CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 CHARLES R.T. CRUMPLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... After FIRREA, it had none.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Germania was insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   A so-called friend-of-the-court brief filed by the American
Association of Bank Directors several years later said that FIRREA
``took an honestly and competently managed thrift with adequate
capital and turned it into a prime candidate for the gallows in a
single day: Dec. 7, 1989, when the post-FIRREA S&AMP;L capital rules
took effect.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Friday evening in June 1990, Morris, sitting with friends
on the patio of his St. Louis home, took a call from Germania.
Regulators had seized the thrift.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unpleasant surprise but not a shock. That came the
following morning when he read the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shock was to find out that they had made a criminal
referral,'' Morris said from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Germania's sad saga was tossed to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The 800 or so people who bought the schnotes were stuck with a
dead investment, and some sued. In November 1992, Germania's top
executives were indicted in federal courts in southern Illinois and
in eastern Missouri. Both indictments were similar, essentially
alleging that the executives had misled the schnote buyers by
hiding the September Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Morris argued that he and the other executives had done nothing
wrong. Investors lost their money, he said, because FIRREA killed
Germania.
</P>
<P>
   But his internal fear meter quickly rose. New, Germania's chief
financial officer who had prepared the September Analysis in 1987
that suggested Germania double its loan-loss reserves, pleaded
guilty. Eventually, he became the government's star witness,
testifying that the other Germania executives had ignored his
warnings. New got probation and no prison sentence. He declined to
be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   And Morris' fear leaped again when the judge signed an order
that prevented Morris and the other defendants from using FIRREA as
a defense. The rationale was that the offense occurred when the
schnotes were sold in 1987 and '88. FIRREA, passed in 1989, came
after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Morris and the other defendants were doomed.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Reppert, the prosecutor, argued that would-be
investors in Germania had a right to know about New's September
Analysis. It would have been a red flag about the condition of the
thrift. But Morris and the other executives buried the September
Analysis, the prosecutor said, essentially defrauding the investors
into sinking their money in an ill-fated savings bank.
</P>
<P>
   Morris and the others argued that the September Analysis was
poorly done and so hastily prepared that it was worthy of the trash
bin. Thanks to Morris' insistence on packing away loan-loss
reserves, executives thought they had an ample rainy-day account.
The arguments didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what the jury heard: They had a string of little old
ladies, very sympathetic little old ladies, come to the stand and
talk about how they lost their life savings,'' Morris said. ``I
mean, clearly it was tragic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hear about this scheme to hide the shape of the bank to
induce the little old ladies to invest their money. They don't hear
at all anything about how the bank was healthy in 1988 and 1989 and
that FIRREA ravaged the bank, that the bank was closed because of
new capital standards and that the investors lost their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right up to the last day, we paid monthly interest payments to
all the investors.It wasn't our fault they didn't get their money.
It was because the government came in and changed all the rules and
closed us down. But we couldn't talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the jury room, two jurors held out for one day. The second
day, a sole juror, Michelle Lewis, held out until the end of the
day. She finally agreed to convict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until my dying day, I wish I had never given in,'' Lewis said.
``A great injustice was done to those men.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis thinks that if the jury had known about FIRREA and its
effect on Germania, the verdict could have gone the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The jury convicted Morris and Gardner of two counts of mail
fraud and one count of wire fraud related to marketing efforts to
sell the schnotes. Morris and Gardner were sentenced to 46 months
each.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner did not respond to requests to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Morris appealed the conviction and lost. He was sent to prison
in Springfield, Mo., and was later transferred to Greenville, Ill.,
where he is today.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case in Missouri, Joe Mason, Germania's chairman
and main shareholder, was made a defendant. Having seen what
happened in the earlier case, Mason decided to plead guilty in
return for a lighter sentence of one year and one day. He got out
of prison last May. He not only lost Germania, but he also lost his
homebuilding company in Missouri. Some insiders estimate that Mason
personally lost more than $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial really did miss the point,'' said Victor Simon, who
once owned a trade newspaper that covered the S&AMP;L industry. ``The
thing that caused Ed to go to jail was that they changed all the
accounting standards instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview a year-and-a-half ago, Morris admitted he was
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in jail because of loan-loss reserves, something I still
lose sleep about,'' Morris said back then. ``It kills me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some insiders believe Germania was doomed to fail anyway. It was
loaded down with souring real estate loans. Others dispute that,
saying Germania would have survived and the ample loan-loss
reserves would have taken care of the problem. In either case, it
was academic because FIRREA wiped out Germania's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he prepares to check in to a halfway house, where he
will report until September, Morris said he is no longer bitter.
</P>
<P>
   He's grateful for the support of his family. He's written a
novel. He said he does not regret failing to seek a plea bargain
that would have lessened his sentence because: ``There's nothing
I'm guilty of.
</P>
<P>
   ``My integrity's intact. I feel like I can walk out of here with
my head high and get back to my life. I want to get this lost
decade behind me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
