<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD FEELINGS DIE HARD FOR DEMPSEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers third-base coach Rick Dempsey
wasn't about to let St. Louis Cardinals manager Tony La Russa
disrespect the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers' Devon White cleared St. Louis' Shawon Dunston
from the rest of the pack after Dunston charged pitcher Jamie
Arnold in the ninth inning, Dempsey made sure to get a few barbs in
on La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   Before the teams headed back to their dugouts, Dempsey and La
Russa exchanged heated words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same kind of (stuff) he did before,'' Dempsey said.
``It's why we won the '88 World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey was referring the Dodgers' stunning defeat of the
supposedly mighty Oakland A's, who were managed by La Russa. The
Dodgers upset Oakland in five games to win the World Series.
Dempsey was a catcher on that squad. La Russa has the reputation of
being arrogant and abrasive, repeatedly infuriating other teams
with his managing style.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's more history between La Russa and Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey was a catcher on that squad, as he was with the
Baltimore Orioles in 1983 when that team beat La Russa's Chicago
White Sox team in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw at one of our guys and missed,'' Dempsey said. ``It's
the same thing, and he's complaining about our manager?''
</P>
<P>
   Dunston was upset when he was hit with an Arnold fastball with
two outs in the ninth and the Cardinals ahead 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   Back at sixth: After batting second in the lineup for five games
and leading off in another, Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre
returned to a more familiar spot in the lineup. Beltre batted sixth
after struggling near the top.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre was 5 for 27 (.185) as his average fell from .336 to
.301. After drawing 19 walks in his first 34 games, he walked once
in the week he spent near or at the top of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to do too much because I would like to stay
there,'' Beltre said. ``I was taking a couple pitches so I could
walk and get on base for the next guy. That's what I did to try and
get on base for (Gary) Sheffield.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushed back in the lineup Sunday, Beltre went 2 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen blues: After starting the season in surprising fashion,
the Dodgers' bullpen has been unreliable. It gave up four more runs
in the latest loss and has allowed at least one run in 12 of the
past 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   In the past nine games, in which the Dodgers are 3-6, the
bullpen has a 6.99 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the makeup of my bullpen right now,'' said Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson. ``With (Antonio) Osuna out, there's not a
lot of depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance record: The sellout crowd of 54,514 was the largest
crowd at Dodger Stadium since 54,859 saw the Expos and Dodgers play
July 4, 1994, and it helped set a three-game attendance mark at
Chavez Ravine. The three-game series with the Cardinals drew
162,376. The old mark of 162,122 was established Sept. 5-7, 1966,
against the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Extra bases: Eric Young sat out his second straight game with a
sore ankle and Johnson held Devon White (hip) and Todd
Hollandsworth (back) out of the starting lineup after each were
banged up in Saturday's win. White pinch hit in the sixth and
remained in the game.... Dodgers shortstop Mark Grudzielanek
extended his hitting streak to nine games with a first-inning
single.... The Dodgers are 0-6 on Sundays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
