<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL ISN'T LETTING OVITZ OUT OF SIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They may be billing tonight's NFL meeting in
Atlanta as an update on the expansion effort in Los Angeles, but it
is appearing increasingly like another step in a setup.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL doesn't want to award ownership of the Los Angeles
franchise to Michael Ovitz, it is at least going to great pains to
keep him in their labyrinth expansion game.
</P>
<P>
   One month before the NFL selected the Coliseum as the Los
Angeles area site, commissioner Paul Tagliabue and expansion
committee members toured Ovitz's Carson site and proclaimed him a
``visionary'' and his plans ``compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Then despite selecting the Coliseum site promoted by the rival
Eli Broad-Ed Roski Jr. group for over two years, NFL owners opened
up the stadium design plans and said Ovitz could still emerge as
the downtown team owner.
</P>
<P>
   Now the expansion committee is scheduled to hear an update on
stadium and financing plans from both groups tonight in Atlanta,
and many expect them to line up behind designs Ovitz has scrambled
to put together in less than 40 days.
</P>
<P>
   Whether because they are simply dazzled by his ideas and
Hollywood connections or just want to keep the process competitive
to assure a maximum expansion fee, the NFL is plainly not willing
to let Ovitz slip away.
</P>
<P>
   All these twists and turns, all these minor delays, look like an
effort to allow Ovitz to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't comment on that,'' Broad said. ``That's up to the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   It's uncertain what the NFL will do about the Los Angeles
situation during its three-day meetings. Owners have other serious
issues to resolve _ the sale of the Redskins, the stadium issue in
New England _ but need to move forward on the Los Angeles issue if
its Sept. 15 deadline is realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Owners may select a stadium design plan. They could establish an
expansion fee. They could even select the would-be owner. They
could do nothing. This is the NFL, where anything and nothing is
always possible.
</P>
<P>
   Can you really select Ovitz's stadium design plans, and not pick
Ovitz as the owner?
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot predict what they're going to do,'' Broad said.
``They're going to do it on their timetable, with whatever they're
comfortable with. That's their history, and we respect that.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can say is, if you really want to meet the Sept. 15
date, there is something really ready to go and all the agreements
pretty well signed, you ought to do something now, rather than six
weeks or four weeks or two weeks ahead of that deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand, Roski has been working with the various _ and often
muddled agencies _ involved in the Coliseum area for more than two
years; Ovitz hasn't, and wants to build seven garages for parking.
</P>
<P>
   Are his plans OK with the Coliseum Commission, the city, the
state, the conservancy, USC, the museums? Does the NFL care?
</P>
<P>
   When Tagliabue was here April 13 to name the Coliseum as the
chosen site, he said the league was looking for a ``public-private
partnership.'' The Broad-Roski group clearly has that at the
Coliseum, not Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL can select Ovitz anyway and tell everyone to work it
out. Los Angeles area politicians have a bad history with the NFL
anyway. And if they place stumbling blocks in front of the Ovitz
plan, the NFL can throw its hands up and moan how nothing has
changed in L.A. Carson is still down the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Broad and Roski have been up front with their campaign. They
hired a respected local public relations firm. They put Broad, a
billionaire, on conference calls.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Ovitz works in the shadows. He rarely makes
comments when not in public. There is still much unknown about his
plan. If his parking garages are going to cost $225 million, does
he really expect public funding? Does his group have the estimated
$1 billion it will take to buy the franchise and renovate the
Coliseum?
</P>
<P>
   This much is known: Neither plan shows a new Dodger Stadium, and
both would like former Denver Broncos and Granada Hills High
quarterback John Elway to become a major player in their group.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're Elway, why throw in with either until one is
officially selected?
</P>
<P>
   One will be shortly. Probably not today, but soon. And if the
NFL wants Ovitz, Roski-Broad could be reduced as this pleasant
footnote for having revived interest in the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   This is the NFL, one of the most exclusive boys clubs in the
world, and they are used to getting their way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-23-99 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
