<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEATEN UP BY CARDINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers right-hander Jamie Arnold put
his head down in disappointment after plunking St. Louis' Shawon
Dunston with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   When he looked up Dunston was closing in.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston threw a right hook and slammed Arnold to the ground as
players from both sides streamed onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston's tack was less subtle than what's been happening with
the Dodgers, but the parallel exists. Opponents have been
body-slamming the Dodgers lately.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the emotion of a bench-clearing brawl was another
Dodgers loss, the sixth in nine games. St. Louis beat up the
Dodgers 8-3 Sunday at Dodger Stadium. It's the third time in a
month the Cardinals took two of three games from the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to make heads or tails out of the Dodgers (22-21) seems
impossible these days, much like figuring out why Dunston found it
necessary to charge the mound after being hit in the lower back
with a 1-0 fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He overreacted. That's Dunston,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``(Arnold) is a kid with (18) innings in the big
leagues coming out of Double-A. He's my fifth pitcher of the game.
Anybody that has any baseball sense would know (it wasn't on
purpose). I lost a little bit of respect for (Cardinals manager
Tony) La Russa by accusing him.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa fired back by saying, ``Well, losing respect can go
both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunston was the third Cardinals player to be hit with a pitch in
the game and seventh this season by the Dodgers. Starter Carlos
Perez (52/3 innings, 4 runs) hit Fernando Tatis in the fourth
inning and Arnold hit Joe McEwing to lead off the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing was erased on a double play before Dunston, who was 3
for 5 with an RBI, was hit by the pitch. With both benches and
bullpens emptying onto the field, Dunston was pulled out of the
pack by Dodgers center fielder Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he felt he was thrown at, he did what he felt he had to
do,'' said White, who added he and Dunston are good friends. ``I
can't say we threw at him or not. I'm not in Jamie's head, and I'm
not in Shawon's head. I just tried to stop it before it went any
further.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Dunston said he didn't know why Arnold would throw at
him. Dunston was ejected but Arnold finished pitching the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did he hit me? I don't know,'' Dunston said. ``I have to
take care of Shawon Dunston and not worry about anybody else. I
have to take of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said he could feel tension between the teams. They played
nine times in less than a month, and the Cardinals won six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel he's in the wrong,'' Arnold, 25, said. ``I had no
intention of hitting him. The only reason I knew he was coming was
I heard the crowd reaction. I'm not going to hold anything against
him. I didn't hit him on purpose. I didn't try to hit him or
McEwing. I was trying to pitch on the corners.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams aren't scheduled to meet again this season, which is
good for the Dodgers. The Cardinals hit 18 homers this season
against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' eight runs in the series finale was tied for only
their third highest output against Los Angeles this season. The
Cardinals scored 12 runs _ 11 in one inning _ on April 23, when
Fernando Tatis hit an unprecedented two grand slams in one inning
and opened this three-game series with 10 runs. They scored 60 runs
in nine games and averaged 7.3 runs in six games at Dodger Stadium
and battered Dodgers pitching for 25 runs in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The big blow Sunday came when lefty Onan Masaoka allowed a
pinch-hit, three-run homer to former Dodger Thomas Howard in the
seventh inning to give the Cardinals a 7-3 lead. Johnson decided to
go to Masaoka to make the switch-hitting Howard bat righty.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked our butts two out of three,'' Johnson said. ``I
had Thomas Howard (in Cincinnati). He's not a very good
right-handed hitter. In fact, he quit hitting right-handed for a
while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
