<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLONIAL WINS FALLS TO BROWNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Olin Browne lacks the type of golfing resume
that usually accompanies inclusion on the Wall of Champions at the
MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Browne, who underwent major elbow surgery in October, never
swung a club in earnest until his freshman year in college. He did
not record his first sub-par round until after his 22nd birthday. A
10-time participant in the PGA Tour's annual qualifying school,
Browne arrived at Colonial this week with more top-10 finishes on
the Nike Tour (28) than the PGA Tour (nine) in a 15-year career.
</P>
<P>
   So it may be appropriate that yesterday's surprise winner found
himself in an unusual location when he fired his final shot before
slipping into a plaid jacket. Browne, 40, learned of his triumph on
the putting green beside the ninth fairway while preparing for a
playoff that never came.
</P>
<P>
   After salvaging a par from a greenside bunker on the 18th hole
to complete a final-round 66 and finish at 8 under par, Browne
warmed up with his back to the proceedings for another 30 minutes
because he figured there was ``no way'' he could win without
enduring a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, after countless contenders cratered down the
stretch, Browne found himself reflecting on a weekend in Fort Worth
that included both a 40th birthday and a second career tour
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be at the dock for your ship to come in. But
this one came screaming in and picked me up,'' said Browne, who
defeated five players by one stroke and four others by two. ``My
old man would say, `I backed \Rmyself\S into a tub of butter.' It
doesn't get any better than that. This is awesome. I feel really
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   He should. Browne, who celebrated his milestone birthday on
Saturday, became a poster boy for the ``Life Begins at 40''
campaign during yesterday's final round. He collected eagles on
both of Colonial's par-5 holes, draining a 20-foot putt at No. 1
and a 40-footer at No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   But he never grabbed a share of the lead until bagging his final
birdie, a 2-footer at No. 15, at roughly the same time Greg Kraft
steered his tee shot into the left rough at No. 12. At the time,
Kraft stood at 10 under and was three strokes ahead of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Kraft hacked his way to a double bogey. Browne's
near-simultaneous birdie allowed him to erase a three-shot deficit
and join Kraft, Billy Mayfair and Fred Funk in a four-player knot
at 8 under heading down the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, Colonial's final four contenders dueled down the
stretch with a combined 11 PGA Tour titles to their credit. That's
two fewer than Phil Mickelson, the gallery favorite who opened with
an eagle but backtracked with bogeys at Nos. 7, 11 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   Other marquee names joined Mickelson in slipping off the
Colonial leader board long before the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh, the PGA champ, disappeared with a watery double
bogey at No. 9. Lee Janzen, the U.S. Open champ, collected
back-to-back bogeys at Nos. 7 and 8 to seal his also-ran status.
Davis Love III, the No. 2 player in the world golf rankings, dug
himself an insurmountable deficit with a pair of front-nine bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   That left the title up for grabs between Browne, Funk, Kraft and
Mayfair.
</P>
<P>
   Funk (7 under) blinked first, dropping out with a bogey from a
greenside bunker at No. 16. Mayfair (6 under) followed suit at No.
16, then compounded matters with another bogey after missing the
18th green. Kraft (7 under) coughed up his share of the lead at No.
17, when he flew the green from 141 yards with a pitching wedge and
failed to sink a 4-foot par putt.
</P>
<P>
   When Kraft failed by inches on a bunker blast for birdie at No.
18, the title belonged to Browne, who jumped 136 spots on the money
list _ from No. 171 to No. 35 _ by collecting the $504,000 winner's
check.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a tour journeyman playing in only his second Colonial
was summoned from the putting green to make an acceptance speech.
As he looked at his brightly colored sports shirt, complete with
Tabasco sauce logos, and contrasted it with the plaid jacket he was
about to receive, Browne whispered to a tournament official: ``This
is going to be brutal.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Browne explained, he hadn't dressed in something that
matched a red plaid blazer because he hadn't expected to win. A
half-hour later, he said he was ``still a little numb'' at the
concept of having his name on the same wall that features past
champions Ben Hogan, Jack Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unreal, the way things transpired,'' Browne said.
``The very best players to have ever played have won on this turf.
To add my name to that list is overwhelming. I can't describe the
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's hard to believe you'd want one of these jackets. I
haven't looked at myself in the mirror, but I think anyone who wins
this tournament looks great in plaid. I hope they give me five more
before I'm done.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Browne has to be summoned from the practice green to
make his acceptance speech on each occasion.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
